treasury secretary james a. baker iii may resign his post this summer to oversee vice president george bush's general-election campaign, administration and bush campaign sources are hinting
but the officials, who spoke only on the condition of anonymity, said that such a move is unlikely to occur before the august 15-18 republican convention in new orleans and could depend on the condition of the u.s. economy
meanwhile, president reagan may actively campaign for bush even before the gop convention, according to presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater
fitzwater told reporters on thursday that the president is reconsidering his original vow to remain neutral until after the convention now that bush's only remaining opposition is a token challenge from former television evangelist pat robertson
we could see the president involved in some political activities before the nominating convention _ activities that are directly associated with the nominee,'' fitzwater said
the withdrawal this week of distant rival sen. bob dole gave bush a virtual lock on the gop nomination
bush strategists are now focusing their attention on the fall elections, and baker may play an important role in that campaign
if baker does come aboard, it won't be until around the time of the convention, even though bush is now certain to be the party's nominee, said administration officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity
there long has been talk that the treasury secretary, who managed bush's 1980 presidential bid and was senior advisor to the 1980 reagan-bush campaign, might step aside to help run his longtime friend's campaign
peter teeley, a bush campaign spokesman, said a discussion of what role baker might play in the bush campaign, if any, was only speculative at this time
but, teeley added, ``jim is very close to the vice president and has been for a quarter of a century. there's no secret what their relationship has been.''
in the past, baker has discouraged talk of an early resignation, saying he was happy with his job as treasury secretary, one he has held since 1985
however, on thursday a treasury spokesman, who refused to be identified by name, would only say that there was no truth to reports that baker would quit by aug. 1
baker intends to go ahead with plans to participate in the seven-nation economic summit in toronto in late june, administration officials said
baker, who has built an international reputation in his current post, is an experienced political tactician. the former houston attorney served as reagan's chief of staff for four years before becoming treasury secretary and in 1976 was chairman of president ford's re-election effort
baker's role in the bush campaign, and the timing involved in such a move, could depend on how the economy performs over the next few months
a deterioration in the economy could persuade baker to stay on as treasury secretary to oversee policies designed to head off an election-year recession, some administration sources involved in economic policy-making suggest
however, recent economic data have shown an economy rebounding strongly from last october's stock market plunge
baker could probably have any job in a bush presidency that he wanted, and there have been rumors for some time that he would like to be secretary of state
bush on wednesday told reporters he intended to ``have a new cabinet'' if elected. the answer responded specifically to a query on embattled attorney general edwin meese iii but might also be taken as a signal that there would be a new treasury secretary in a bush presidency
bush, back in town for several days following a three-day swing through wisconsin, met with reagan for their regular weekly working luncheon. fitzwater said he did not know if campaign plans were discussed
the president's spokesman said a decision on any presidential campaign activity by reagan in bush's behalf before the convention ``has not been finally made, although ... the vice president is very close to having the nomination.''
pat robertson is still a candidate, in a declared sense, but he too recognizes the realities of the situation,'' fitzwater said
bush is continuing with plans for campaign appearances in states that have upcoming primaries and that will also be important in the general election _ including new york, new jersey, ohio and pennsylvania
he also is planning fund-raising trips late next week to texas and florida, states where he has already won primaries
a group of 21 senators is writing secretary of state george shultz asking him to refrain from meeting with members of the palestine liberation organization during his upcoming trip to the middle east
the bipartisan group, including presidential hopeful albert gore jr., d-tenn., still was collecting signatures on the petition and planned to send the letter today. a similar letter was planned by house members
shultz left washington on thursday for rome, and will continue sunday to the middle east to lobby for acceptance of a u.s. plan for arab-israeli peace talks
the senators slammed shultz's meeting last saturday in washington with two american university professors who are members of the palestine national council, the plo's parliamentary arm
defending the meeting, shultz said he wanted to hear the views of edward said and ibrahim abu lughod about palestinian representation in mideast talks. he denied his meeting violated u.s. law, which forbids negotiating with the plo, saying that not all members of the council are also members of the plo
we see no distinction between the plo and the pnc,'' the senators wrote. ``we believe your action sets a dangerous precedent.''
congress passed a law in 1985 banning talks with the plo until that organization recognizes israel's right to exist and renounces acts of terror. the law was based on u.s. assurances to israel in 1975 that the united states would not deal with the plo
if u.s. agreements are breached now, how can we expect the government of israel to accept future u.s. assurances concerning an international peace conference?'' the letter said
shultz has proposed giving israel written assurances that an international conference would only serve as an advisory forum for direct israeli-arab talks and would not have the power to impose solutions
the senators who signed the letter were: christopher bond, r-mo.; quentin burdick, d-n.d.; alfonse d'amato, r-n.y.; alan dixon, d-ill.; dennis deconcini, d-ariz.; gore; bob graham, d-fla.; charles grassley, r-iowa; john heinz, r-penn.; gordon humphrey, r-n.h.; daniel inouye, d-hawaii; david karnes, r-neb.; bob kasten, r-wis.; frank lautenberg, d-n.j.; howard metzenbaum, d-ohio; john melcher, d-mont.; larry pressler, r-s.d.; jay rockefeller, d-w.va.; william roth, r-del.; richard shelby, d-ala.; and pete wilson, r-calif. pickup.</note>
