the united states says it will pursue a formal trade complaint against japan after a four-year agreement covering japanese import quotas on beef, oranges and orange juice expired and talks produced no new accord
i am deeply disappointed that the japanese did not come forward with their proposal to liberalize trade on beef and citrus,'' u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter said after three days of talks here with takashi sato, japanese minister of agriculture, forestry and fisheries
thursday was the last day of the agreement. as a result of the failure, the united states will challenge the quotas as illegal under international trading rules, opening the way to possible trade penalties or other sanctions against japan, yeutter said
the united states has requested an emergency meeting of the general agreement on tariffs and trade council next friday in geneva, where it will request ``an independent gatt panel to be formed to review our complaint,'' yeutter said
sato told reporters he and his delegation explained the difficulties of liberalizing beef and citrus imports and ``tried to obtain the understanding of the u.s. side for a more realistic position but our efforts were not successful.''
talks on the issue will continue but no time or place was set, japanese spokesman toshiyuki takano said, and sato plans to leave saturday for japan
under the 1984 quota agreement, japan agreed to admit 141,000 tons of american beef that year, rising to 177,000 tons this year, and to a 1,100-ton annual increase in the 1984 quota on u.s. orange imports of 82,000 tons
the quotas are demanded by citrus and beef farmers who are influential in japan's governing liberal-democratic party. u.s. officials argue that japanese consumers would benefit greatly from cheaper u.s. oranges and meat and that the domestic producers should adjust to imports just as several u.s. industries have had to cope with japanese competition
yeutter said he is confident the japanese quotas will be found in violation of international trading rules because an earlier gatt panel recently ruled japanese quotas on 12 processed foods were gatt-illegal. japan at first ignored the ruling but it was announced during prime minister noboru takeshita's january visit to washington that the country would abide by the decision
officials of takeshita's governing liberal-democratic party said recently japan could not agree to further liberalization of beef and citrus imports because it would threaten producers' livelihood
although japan is the largest purchaser of u.s. farm products, the united states has been arguing that the country's remaining import barriers cost japanese consumers unreasonably high prices, with beefsteak four times the u.s. price and citrus fruit at least double the american cost. move</head>
the owners of eastern airlines are trying to dismantle the financially troubled passenger carrier in an effort to break its unions, the union representing 13,000 eastern workers alleges in a federal lawsuit
the international association of machinists and aerospace workers, afl-cio, filed the lawsuit in u.s. district court here thursday. the 81-page complaint alleges that frank lorenzo's texas air corp. was trying to undermine the union's legal right to represent eastern employees by transferring the airline's assets to other subsidiaries of the parent
the complaint charged that the transfer of some eastern air routes, planes and airport gate rights to other subsidiaries such as continental was part of a scheme to weaken the iam's power to represent eastern employees
such transactions violated the terms of a 1984 agreement that the old eastern airlines management made with the iam under which union members received 20 percent of the company's stock in return for wage concessions, the union said
texas air took over eastern in 1986, but the union contends that the airline's new owner is bound by the collective bargaining agreement that set up the stock ownership plan
the lawsuit also charges a campaign of harassment of iam members as well as ``widespread and blatant'' violations of the labor contract
eastern spokeswoman karen ceremsak said the company would not comment on the lawsuit until officials had a chance to read the complaint
the union last month obtained a contempt citation against eastern for taking steps to sell its northeast shuttle operation to another subsidiary of texas air
the new lawsuit was assigned to u.s. district judge john h. pratt, who last month ruled that the attempt to transfer the shuttle operations flouted an earlier injunction he had issued directing eastern to maintain the working conditions of its unionized employees
the iam and eastern are negotiating changes in the union contract before federal mediators
the company was also ordered this week by another judge here not to lease its planes to an independent cargo carrier to train non-union pilots in the event eastern's unionized pilots honor a possible iam strike this spring
a lot of people will be sleeping late sunday, but not out of a desire for extra rest
it's the day that daylight-saving time returns, meaning that clocks should be shifted an hour forward
the change occurs at 2 a.m. sunday, meaning most people probably will want to set their clocks ahead one hour before retiring saturday night
although known as ``daylight-saving time,'' the annual change doesn't really save any daylight, or time
it simply moves an hour of light from morning to evening by delaying the timing of both sunrise and sunset by an hour
that means that some children wind up waiting for school buses in the dark, for example, in exchange for more time after school to play ball or join the family in backyard cookouts
the idea has been attributed to various people, including benjamin franklin, but it was william willett of england who launched the eventually successful campaign for the idea in 1907
more time for evening recreation, less need for costly artificial lights and a possible reduction of evening crime were cited as major advantages
it was the potential for energy savings that prompted first use of daylight-saving time, in germany in 1916. other countries followed during world war i, returning to standard time afterward and resuming daylight time during world war ii
it was simple confusion that finally led to the adoption of the u.s. uniform time system in 1966. previously, the tradition of allowing local communities to decide for or against daylight time had resulted in a crazy-quilt pattern of time differences
today, daylight time is in effect in all areas of the country except arizona, puerto rico, the virgin islands, american samoa and the part of indiana in the eastern time zone
surveys have found that daylight time is generally more popular in urban areas, where the afternoon and evening leisure time is appreciated
rural areas seem to be the focus of opposition, largely because of the loss of morning light for travel to work and school and adjusting to the change in dealing with livestock, since animals don't observe differences in clocks
residents of a northwestern english town, suckered by an april fools' day gag, deluged local officials with telephone complaints after a newspaper reported they would be made to buy their own streetlight bulbs
in other teasers, a wildlife park in southeastern england said it had launched a campaign to stop fish drowning and a left-wing weekly said labor party leaders had been advised to take assertiveness training
the national circulation newspaper today reported in its april fools' editions that the rail tunnel under construction between britain and france will open next week, a remarkable five years ahead of schedule
a four-page pull-out supplement in the paper bore the headline: ``chunnel opens 5 years early _ exclusive leak on britain's dig to tunnel glory.''
in northwest england the wirral globe's friday edition, issued on thursday before the long easter holiday weekend, said the borough council was planning to make residents buy their own lightbulbs for streetlamps as part of a cost-cutting campaign
the spoof front-page story prompted a flood of calls from worried residents, and a lot of time was wasted calming them, said the council's secretary, john goodacre
in retaliation, the council canceled its advertising with the weekly freesheet, which is delivered to 140,000 homes in the area. the amount of lost advertising revenue was not disclosed
globe editor martin hovden said: ``if we have upset anyone and caused distress obviously i apologize. but we have had at least an equal number of calls from people saying they enjoyed it.''
he said the paper had been running april fools' day gags for 10 years
other cost-cutting measures listed in the globe's spoof report included a ``snatch squad'' to force its way into homes to recover unreturned books from the council's lending library and the closure of local schools mondays and fridays
the national circulation newspaper the independent, normally serious-minded, reported: ``an elusive creature which is new to british mammal records was photographed last week for the first time, our rural affairs correspondent writes.''
the creature has been provisionally nicknamed the bogart by a small group of conservationists, who have formed a society for its preservation,'' it said
the paper printed a photograph of a man with a long pole approaching a creature with a badger's head and a fox's tail against a backdrop of snowy peaks in the cumbrian hills of northwest england
the date, april 1, appeared directly above
the left-wing weekly magazine new statesmen purported to have a leaked memorandum from peter mandelson, labor's director of communications, to charles clarke, a member of the staff of party leader neil kinnock
the spoof had mandelson saying labor should seek a more abrasive image and push its trade and industry spokesman brian gould out of the public spotlight because he was seen as ``soft and cuddly.''
gould, who masterminded labor's sophisticated campaign strategy in last year's general election, is anything but soft
the story said labor should call in a psychologist who had advised soccer teams how to brush up their image and an anthropologist to give key party members assertiveness training
mandelson, in a real-life comment, dismissed the gag as ``light-hearted, clever and amusing _ if a little too clever by half.''
in southeast england, alan breeze, curator of the brambles wildlife park in kent, insisted his rescue campaign to stop fish drowning is an absolutely serious conservation measure to boost the toad population
he said breeding toads will try to mate with almost anything and will often cling to the backs of expensive fish like imported koi carp from japan in ornamental ponds
he said large fish with up to six toads clinging on were known to become exhausted, sink to the bottom of the pond and ``drown.''
he didn't explain how fish can drown but he said the cure was to use a feather to tickle the backs of the clinging toads, which are an endangered species in some parts of the country, to make them release their amorous grip
breeze said he was experiencing difficulty getting people to take the campaign seriously. impeachment trial</head>
a failed effort to reinstate the most serious of three impeachment charges against gov. evan mecham has set the stage for a senate vote next week on whether he should be removed from office
senate democrats on thursday refused to go along with a move by republicans to revive the charge that the first-term gop governor concealed a $350,000 campaign loan _ a decision one senator called ``political roulette.''
if there are not the votes to convict, and governor mecham is back on the ninth floor (the governor's office) on wednesday ... they have dealt themselves a losing hand,'' said sen. tony west, a democrat and mecham critic
the senate has heard five weeks of evidence on the remaining two charges: that mecham tried to thwart investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official and misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
the article of impeachment was dismissed wednesday in a 16-12 vote supported by all 11 democratic senators and five staunch gop supporters of mecham. some of his sharpest critics have been state republican leaders
the senate, in recess for the easter weekend, is to hear closing arguments monday, then vote on the charges later that day or tuesday
although many senators said they had not decided how to vote, gop sen. bill delong said he thought most had made up their minds
there's more than just the guilt or innocence on the charges,'' delong said. he said he expected senators would also be asked to act in the best interests of the state
sen. greg lunn, also a republican, said dismissing the third charge increased the chance of mecham being acquitted because the charge involving the $350,000 loan ``was the most damning.''
the charge was considered the most damaging partly because mecham signed a letter promising the loan would remain confidential
democrats argued that a senate trial on the charge could damage mecham's right to a fair trial in criminal court on similar charges april 21. they also worried that hearing the charge would extend the senate trial past the may 17 date of mecham's recall election
if the senate votes to convict mecham on either article, he would be automatically removed from office. senators also could vote on whether to bar him from holding any future office
an acquittal would immediately return the governor to the office he gave up feb. 5 when he was impeached by the house. secretary of state rose mofford, a democrat, has been acting governor since then
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict
mecham, 63, is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona
a political outsider who took office in january 1987, mecham has insisted that he is innocent of all wrongdoing and that he is being persecuted by the state gop establishment and the media
mecham sparked controversy by canceling a martin luther king holiday for state workers, and has made comments that angered blacks, homosexuals, women, jews and japanese
police used water cannons and clubs to scatter scores of dissidents protesting lack of progress in the investigation of the killing three years ago of three communist activists
reporters and witnesses saw at least 30 protesters being detained during the demonstration thursday
the protesters gathered at a plaza across the street from the government palace in downtown santiago, carrying signs and chanting anti-government slogans. the group included the widows of the three slain communists
jose manuel parada, santiago natino and manuel guerrero were abducted on march 29, 1985. their bodies were found with their throats slit two days later near the santiago airport
four months later, a civilian judge indicted 12 members of the national police, including two colonels, in the kidnappings but not in the killings. the charges eventually were dropped by the supreme court and the case remains open
twenty gunmen attacked an indian reserve in an amazon jungle area claimed by wealthy landowners, killing at least three indians, wounding 20 and leaving 15 missing, the national indian foundation reported
the official report thursday was disputed by the national indigenous council, an indian rights group associated with brazil's national catholic bishop's conference, which set the number of dead at 12, including some children, and 21 injured
the foundation said the attack took place monday on the tikuna indian reserve in benjamin constant, a town 3,700 miles northwest of rio de janeiro near the border with colombia
foundation president romero juca told reporters thursday that the federal police had been called in to investigate the attack
the shootings appeared linked to a dispute between the foundation and landowners for control of the region, which is rich in mineral deposits and timber
according to juca, the foundation marked off 298,870 acres as tikuna territory in 1984, but white landowners have not accepted the compensation paid by the government and stayed in the area
the national indigenous council said about 20,000 tikuna indians live in and around benjamin constant
there are about 220,000 indians in brazil, most of whom live in the amazon jungle
winners of the 1988 pulitzer prizes were:
journalism:
public service _ the charlotte observer
general news reporting _ the alabama journal, montgomery, ala., and lawrence (mass.) eagle-tribune
investigative reporting _ dean baquet, william gaines and ann marie lipinski, chicago tribune
explanatory journalism _ daniel hertzberg and james b. stewart, the wall street journal
specialized reporting _ walt bogdanich, the wall street journal
national reporting _ tim weiner, the philadelphia inquirer
international reporting _ thomas l. friedman, the new york times
feature writing _ jacqui banaszynski, the st. paul pioneer press-dispatch
commentary _ dave barry, the miami herald
criticism _ tom shales, the washington post
editorial writing _ jane healy, the orlando sentinel
editorial cartooning _ doug marlette, the atlanta constitution and the charlotte observer
spot news photography _ scott shaw, the odessa (texas) american
feature photography _ michel ducille, the miami herald
arts:
fiction _ ``beloved,'' by toni morrison
drama _ ``driving miss daisy,'' by alfred uhry
history _ ``the launching of modern american science 1846-1876,'' by robert v. bruce
biography _ ``look homeward: a life of thomas wolfe,'' by david herbert donald
poetry _ ``partial accounts: new and selected poems,'' by william meredith
general non-fiction _ ``the making of the atomic bomb,'' by richard rhodes
music _ ``12 new etudes for piano,'' by william bolcom
a former new york congressman says the uncommitted delegate slate he's part of for the state's april 19 democratic presidential primary hopes ``to persuade the (national) convention to go for mario cuomo.''
we think he would be, by far, the strongest, most inspiring candidate that we could put up,'' democrat richard ottinger said of the new york governor during an interview thursday with wvox and wrtn radio stations
the uncommitted slate of delegates was put together by a group of upstate new york elected democratic county clerks, many of whom hoped cuomo would join the race
albert gore sr. says he almost got the democratic vice presidential nomination more than three decades ago _ and he hopes his son won't settle for the no. 2 spot because it is ``dead-end street.''
gore, 80, said he would not recommend that his son, tennessee sen. albert gore jr., flirt with the vice presidency even if he fails to become the democratic presidential nominee
it's a dead-end street,'' the elder gore, who recalled unsuccessfully seeking the 1956 vice presidential nomination, told the wausau daily herald in an interview wednesday
and i have serious doubts that ... the other contestants for the presidency can win, and who would want to be second on the losing ticket?''
the elder gore also had doubts about the vice presidential job for his son even if the democrats win because it would be ``a do-nothing position.''
married voters tend to vote for republicans in presidential elections, a study by an ohio state university political science professor concludes
the research by herbert weisberg showed that 10 percent to 15 percent more married people than unmarried ones favor republicans, partly because republicans in recent years have emphasized family issues
the republicans have been holding the edge in the marriage gap for some time,'' weisberg said. ``the question will be whether either party finds a way to exploit it.''
married people are in the majority and are more likely to vote than unmarried people because more people vote once they have a bigger stake in the community, weisberg said
former president jimmy carter has praise for the campaign style of jesse jackson, but he isn't saying which candidate he hopes will win the democratic presidential race
carter, speaking thursday with reporters following a conference on south africa, was asked what he thought about jackson's recent strides in the race
i think jesse jackson has run as near a perfect campaign as i have ever seen in this country,'' said carter. he declined to take further questions about politics
former transportation secretary elizabeth dole says the south's super tuesday primaries were won on the ``slick advertising'' of vice president george bush
her husband, sen. bob dole, fell behind in the republican presidential nomination race during those primaries
mrs. dole, in colorado springs to speak at the el paso county lincoln day dinner, told reporters that so many states held primaries on march 8 the candidates were unable to get their messages to voters
the super tuesday idea was not at all a good one,'' she said. ``i don't think we'll ever see that concept again.''
clerks in 17 new jersey counties who claimed an overcrowded slate for the state's june 7 primary would force them to spend $4.1 million for additional voting machines won court approval to change the ballot's design
in my 21 years as county clerk, this is my greatest accomplishment,'' union county clerk walter g. halpin said of the ruling thursday. ``i'm saving my county half a million dollars alone.''
the ruling by superior court judge burrell ives humphreys means that a voter casting a ballot for a candidate seeking the republican nomination for president will select simultaneously those convention delegates pledged to the candidate
sen. max baucus, d-mont., is endorsing massachusetts gov. michael dukakis to be the democratic presidential nominee, citing dukakis' stands on the economy
our nation needs leaders who are committed to rebuilding our economy,'' baucus said thursday. ``creating good, lasting jobs for americans is the key to our future. i believe michael dukakis is best qualified to achieve this goal.''
rep. bill richardson, d-n.m., is endorsing democrat michael dukakis for president, saying he hopes to help the massachusetts governor with a large number of hispanic voters
what is significant here is that there is a perception that minorities in this country are going toward one candidate,'' richardson said thursday, referring to minority support for jesse jackson
the charlotte observer's dogged coverage of the ptl financial scandal, scorned by jim and tammy bakker and many readers, earned the pulitzer prize for public service, journalism's highest honor
in the arts, toni morrison's novel of a former slave, ``beloved,'' won the pulitzer for fiction, a category closely watched after the book failed to win two other prestigious awards for which it was nominated
alfred uhry's first non-musical play, ``driving miss daisy,'' won the drama prize and richard rhodes was awarded the non-fiction prize for his book, ``the making of the atomic bomb.''
the charlotte observer, the wall street journal and the miami herald each won two awards
the knight-ridder newspaper group won six in all, with the observer's two, the herald's two and one each for the philadelphia inquirer and the st. paul pioneer press dispatch. a total of 21 pulitzers were awarded thursday for achievement in the arts and journalism
the observer revealed misuse of funds by the ptl ministry ``through persistent coverage conducted in the face of a massive campaign by ptl to discredit the newspaper,'' the pulitzer board said
the observer's managing editor mark ethridge iii said the real reward was winning over readers who had denounced the newspaper's efforts
the thing that gratifies us the most of all about ptl are the folks who have written us and said, `two years ago, i wrote you and said you all were going to hell. ... now, i want to say i'm wrong and keep up the reporting,''' ethridge said
the paper won the public service award in 1981 for its coverage of ``brown lung'' among textile workers
the miami herald's michel ducille won the feature photography prize for photographs of the decay and rehabilitation of a housing project inundated by the drug crack. he also won a prize for spot news photography two years ago
the herald's humor columnist, dave barry, won the prize for commentary for his ``consistently effective use of humor as a device for presenting fresh insights into serious concerns.''
it's fun to win a pulitzer, everybody should do it,'' barry said
the wall street journal's two prizes came in explanatory journalism and specialized reporting
the paper's daniel hertzberg and james b. stewart won for stories about an investment banker charged with insider trading and about the day after the october stock market crash. walt bogdanich won the specialized reporting prize for a series on faulty testing by medical laboratories
winners generally sounded giddy
several people in the newsroom just took a champagne bath,'' said jacqui banaszynski of the st. paul pioneer press dispatch, who won the prize in feature writing for her series on an aids victim in a farm community
there was a lot of dancing and yelling and singing when the announcement came over the wire _ but that's not unusual for the journal newsroom,'' said jim tharpe, managing editor of the alabama journal in montgomery, which won in general news for its investigation of the state's unusually high infant mortality rate
the lawrence (mass.) eagle-tribune also won in general news for stories that showed flaws in the massachusetts prison furlough system
tom shales of the washington post won the criticism award for his writings on television
ms. morrison acknowledged the controversy surrounding her book after it failed to win the national book award and the national book critics circle award last fall. in january, 48 black writers and critics signed an open letter deploring the lack of national recognition of her book
but the chairman of the pulitzer fiction jury, rutgers university professor julian moynahan, said jurors made their recommendations six weeks before the letter was published and felt no pressure to recommend ms. morrison's book
i am glad that the merits of the book were allowed to surface and be the only consideration of the pulitzer prize committee,'' morrison said
other awards in journalism:
_ national reporting, to tim weiner of the inquirer for a series on a secret pentagon budget used to sponsor defense research and an arms buildup. he was part of a kansas city times and kansas city star team that won a pulitzer in 1982 for general news reporting
_ investigative reporting, to the chicago tribune's dean baquet, william gaines and ann marie lipinski for stories on ``the self-interest and waste that plagued chicago's city council.''
_ international reporting, to thomas l. friedman of the new york times for what the pulitzer board termed ``balanced and informed coverage of israel.'' _ editorial writing, to jane healy of the orlando sentinel for editorials that protested overdevelopment of florida's orange county
_ editorial cartooning, to doug marlette of the atlanta constitution and the charlotte observer
_ spot news photography, to scott shaw of the odessa (texas) american for his pictures of little jessica mcclure being rescued from the well into which she had fallen
other arts awards included:
_ history, ``the launching of modern american science 1846-1876,'' by robert v. bruce
_ biography, ``look homeward: a life of thomas wolfe,'' by david herbert donald
_ poetry, ``partial accounts: new and selected poems,'' by william meredith
_ music, ``12 etudes for piano,'' by william bolcom
winners are selected by the pulitzer board, which is guided by, but not obligated to restrict itself to, a series of finalists submitted by nominating juries in the various categories
except for the award for public service, which brings with it a gold medal, pulitzers carry a cash prize of $3,000. the winners are announced by the president of columbia university, which administers the competition
federal health officials say children infected with the virus that causes aids should receive measles vaccine, since their risk of severe measles is worse than their risk of complications from the vaccine
the immunization practices advisory committee of the u.s. centers for disease control said thursday that children infected with the virus that causes aids should receive the common measles-mumps-rubella vaccine, whether or not they show signs of the devastating symptoms of aids itself
previously, the committee had recommended that children showing aids symptoms should not be vaccinated, because their immune systems might be too severely harmed to tolerate the live-virus measles vaccine
the new cdc recommendation, consistent with recommendations by the world health organization, is an ``approach to protect the hiv-infected child,'' the atlanta-based agency said in its weekly report
complication from measles vaccine in children infected with hiv _ human immunodeficiency virus, the virus that causes aids _ ``hasn't happened,'' said dr. lauri markowitz, a cdc measles specialist
however, she noted, ``we have had several cases of measles in these children, and it's felt that the benefit of getting the vaccine outweighs the risk.''
in 1986 and '87, at least six cases of measles occurred in children infected with aids virus, the cdc reported; two of those children died, in the first u.s. measles deaths reported to cdc since 1985. the other four measles cases were severe
none of the six measles cases was believed linked to measles vaccine. only one of the six children had received measles vaccine, and that was five years before he became ill
it is hoped measles vaccinations will be effective in hiv-infected children, although new studies seem to show that those children, with their weakened immune systems, may not respond to the vaccine as well as healthy children, ms. markowitz said
the cdc has reported 913 cases of aids itself in children under 13. researchers believe that more are infected with the virus that causes aids, but have not yet developed the disease _ and may never
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, cripples the boy's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide spectrum of infections and cancers. the cdc has recorded 57,024 aids cases of the disease since 1981
thumbnail sketches of the 1988 pulitzer prize winners in journalism:
dean baquet, william gaines and ann marie lipinski of the chicago tribune, winners for investigative reporting
baquet, 31, joined the tribune's metropolitan staff as an investigative reporter in december 1984 and was promoted to associate metro editor-chief investigative reporter in 1987. he also worked for the times-picayunem _ the states-item from 1978 to 1984. he attended columbia university
gaines, 54, won a pulitzer prize for investigative reporting in 1976 for his work exposing conditions at two chicago hospitals. he joined the tribune in 1963 after working in radio and television stations in michigan and indiana. he also was a correspondent for the chicago daily news, did news documentaries for the u.s. army in germany and did public relations. he graduated from butler university
lipinski, 32, joined the tribune staff as a summer intern in 1978 after being a summer intern the year before at the miami herald; she stayed at the tribune as a reporter in the features department. she has won the detroit press club award and the 1981 illinois associated press editors association award for public service reporting. she attended the university of michigan
daniel hertzberg and james b. stewart of the wall street journal, winners for explanatory journalism
hertzberg, 42, began his career with the buffalo (n.y.) evening news in 1968 and moved to newsday in 1971. he joined the journal in 1977 and in 1987 was named deputy news editor. also in 1987, he won a gerald loeb deadline-writing award with james b. stewart for coverage of the ivan boesky insider-trading scandal. he received a bachelor's degree from the university of chicago
stewart, 36, who received a bachelor's degree from depauw university and a law degree from harvard, was a lawyer and executive editor of american lawyer magazine before joining the journal in 1983, where he is a special writer. he is the author of ``the partners'' and ``the prosecutors.''
walt bogdanich of the wall street journal, winner for specialized reporting
bogdanich, 37, a reporter, received his bachelor's degree from the university of wisconsin and a master's in journalism from ohio state university. he was a reporter and then managing editor at the compass in hammond, ind. he also reported for the dayton (ohio) daily news, the cleveland (ohio) press and the plain dealer (cleveland, ohio). he joined the journal as an investigative reporter in 1984. he also has won a george polk award and an overseas press club award
tim weiner of the philadelphia inquirer, winner for national reporting
weiner's work for the kansas city times was part of the package that garnered a general news reporting pulitzer in 1982 for the times and the kansas city star. he joined the inquirer in 1982. he also has worked for the associated press, the soho news and fairchild news service. weiner, 31, graduated from columbia college in 1978 and from columbia university's graduate school of journalism in 1979
thomas l. friedman of the new york times, winner for international reporting
friedman, the times' bureau chief in jerusalem, won a pulitzer prize for international reporting in 1983 for his coverage of the israeli invasion of lebanon the year before. friedman, 34, joined the times in 1981 as a business reporter and was named bureau chief in beirut in 1982. before the times, friedman worked for united press international. he graduated summa cum laude from brandeis university in 1975 and was elected to phi beta kappa. he received a master's degree from oxford university in 1978
jacqui banaszynski, of the st. paul pioneer press dispatch, winner for feature writing
banaszynski, 35, is a special projects reporter and feature writer for the newspaper and was a finalist for the 1986 pulitzer prize in foreign reporting. she joined the paper in 1984 after stints with the pulaski news, the janesville (wis.) gazette; the duluth news-tribune & herald; the eugene (ore.) register-guard and the minneapolis star and tribune. she won the minnesota press club's 1986 gene o'brien award for excellence in journalism. she graduated magna cum laude in 1974 from marquette university
dave barry of the miami herald, winner for commentary
barry, 40, a syndicated columnist for the herald since 1983, won the american society of newspaper editors distinguished writing award for commentary in 1986. he was a reporter and editor at the daily local news of west chester, pa., and was a reporter for the associated press. in 1980, he began a nationally syndicated humor column. barry is a graduate of haverford college
tom shales of the washington post, winner for criticism
shales, 44, the chief television critic and television editor of the post, joined the newspaper in 1972 as a writer in the style section. before that, he was entertainment editor of the (washington) d.c. examiner. he has written two books, ``the american film heritage'' and ``on the air!'' he graduated from american university
jane healy of the orlando sentinel, winner for editorial writing
healy, 38, associate editor of the sentinel, was a pulitzer finalist in 1985 for editorial writing. healy, who has been at the sentinel since 1973, has won the sigma delta chi southeast first place award for editorial writing in 1985 and 1986 and the florida society of newspaper editors first place award for editorial writing in 1986. she graduated from the university of maryland
doug marlette of the atlanta constitution and the charlotte observer, winner for editorial cartooning
marlette, 37, joined the constitution in march 1987 after 15 years as editorial cartoonist for the observer. marlette, who has been drawing newspaper cartoons since he was 16, also draws the ``kudzu'' comic strip. he has won the 1986 fischetti award, and has received national headliner, robert f. kennedy and sigma delta chi awards
scott shaw of the odessa (texas) american, winner for spot news photography
shaw, 24, has been a staff photographer at the odessa american since 1986 after working at the paragould (ark.) daily press, the southern illinoisan (carbondale, ill.) and the commercial news in danville, ill. he has a journalism degree from southern illinois university
michel ducille of the miami herald, winner for feature photography
ducille, 32, won a pulitzer for spot news photography in 1986 and won a photojournalism award for his photo essay on the drug crack from the national association of black journalists in 1987. he graduated from indiana university
the pulitzer prize for public service was awarded to the charlotte observer and the pulitzer for general news reporting went to the staffs of the alabama journal and the lawrence (mass.) eagle-tribune. the winners were announced thursday
thumbnail sketches of the 1988 pulitzer prize winners in the arts:
toni morrison, winner in fiction for ``beloved.'' morrison, 57, was born in lorain, ohio, attended howard university and cornell university and lives in rockland county, n.y. an editor at random house, she is the author of four other novels, ``the bluest eye,'' ``sula,'' ``song of solomon,'' which won the 1978 national book critics circle award, and ``tar baby.'' she wrote a play, ``dreaming emmett,'' produced in 1986
alfred uhry, winner in drama for ``driving miss daisy.'' uhry, 51, a native of atlanta, worked previously in the musical theater, writing lyrics for ``here's where i belong'' and lyrics and book for ``the robber bridegroom,'' both collaborations with robert waldman. he and waldman had worked for frank loesser's publishing company as a ``score team,'' and uhry worked for the goodspeed opera house in connecticut restoring early musicals to their original states. ``driving miss daisy'' is the first play he wrote alone
robert v. bruce, winner in history for ``the launching of modern american science 1846-1876.'' bruce, 64, lives in madbury, n.h., and is professor emeritus at boston university, where he has taught since 1955 and still teaches each fall. he is author of three other books: ``lincoln and the tools of war,'' ``1877: year of violence,'' and ``bell: alexander graham bell and the conquest of solitude.''
david herbert donald, winner in biography for ``look homeward: a life of thomas wolfe.'' donald, 67, won the pulitzer prize for biography in 1961 for ``charles sumner and the coming of the civil war.'' educated at millsaps college in jackson, miss., and at the university of illinois, donald has taught at columbia university in new york, oxford, princeton university and johns hopkins, where he founded the institute of southern history. he lives in lincoln, mass
william meredith, winner in poetry for ``partial accounts: new and selected poems.'' meredith, 69, a professor at connecticut college in new london, has published six volumes of poetry. he has been a chancellor of the academy of american poets since 1964 and from 1978 through 1980 was the consultant in poetry to the library of congress. a graduate of princeton, he has also taught there and at the university of hawaii, middlebury college and carnegie-mellon university
richard rhodes, winner in general non-fiction for ``the making of the atomic bomb.'' the 50-year-old rhodes was born in kansas city, kan., and educated at yale university. he has worked as editor at harper's and playboy and is the author of ``the inland ground,'' ``looking for america,'' ``the last safari,'' and ``sons of earth,'' among other books. he has been a guggenheim fellow, a national endowment for the arts fellow and a ford foundation fellow
william bolcom, winner in music for ``12 new etudes for piano.'' bolcom, 49, was born in seattle and now lives in ann arbor, mich., where he is professor of composition at the university of michigan. he attended the university of washington, mills college and stanford university. a solo and concert pianist, his music ranges from ragtime to the theater and from chamber to symphonic works
the pulitzers in arts and journalism were announced thursday
here is a list of non-winning finalists for the 1988 pulitzer prizes. under the rules, pulitzer juries in each category make three recommendations without listing them in order of preference. the pulitzer board, which awards the prizes, can choose a winner from outside the recommendations
arts:
biography _ ``hemingway,'' by kenneth s. lynn; ``george santayana: a biography,'' by john mccormick
drama _ ``boys' life,'' by howard korder; ``talk radio,'' by eric bogosian
fiction _ ``persian nights,'' by diane johnson; ``that night,'' by alice mcdermott
general non-fiction _ ``setting limits: medical goals in an aging society,'' by daniel callahan; ``chaos: making a new science,'' by james gleick
history _ ``the fall of the house of labor,'' by david montgomery; ``the care of strangers: the rise of america's hospital system,'' by charles e. rosenberg
music _ ``concerto for string quartet and orchestra,'' by gunther schuller
poetry _ ``good woman: poems and a memoir 1969-1980'' and ``next: new poems,'' by lucille clifton; ``flesh and blood,'' by c.k. williams
journalism:
commentary _ ira berkow of the new york times for sports commentary; molly ivins of the dallas times herald for columns on social and political issues; and michael kinsley of united features syndicate for political columns
criticism _ michael skube of the news and observer, raleigh, n.c., for book reviews; and allan temko, san francisco chronicle, for architecture criticism
editorial cartooning _ david fitzsimmons of the arizona daily star and don wright of the miami news
editorial writing _ bernard l. stein of the riverdale press, bronx, n.y., for editorials on a variety of issues; and joe dolman of the atlanta journal and constitution for editorials on the rights of jailed cuban refugees
explanatory journalism _ tim weiner of the philadelphia inquirer for his series on a secret pentagon budget; and athelia knight of the washington post for her story on a year in the life of an urban high school
feature photography _ george widman of the associated press for his photo of a homeless man in philadelphia; and barbara j. ries of usa today for a photo taken at the vietnam veterans memorial in washington
feature writing _ lynne duke of the miami herald for her story about a housing project overrun by crack; and john dorschner of the miami herald for stories about a neighborhood feud, police tensions and holocaust survivors
general news reporting _ the atlanta journal and constitution staff for coverage of an 11-day riot by cuban inmates; the charlotte (n.c.) observer staff for misuse of ptl ministry funds; and sam stanton of the arizona republic for his reporting on gov. evan mecham's first year in office
international reporting _ larry olmstead of the detroit free press for reports from south africa about the african national congress; and randall richard of the providence (r.i.) journal-bulletin for his series on americans adopting latin american children
investigative reporting _ larry copeland and tracy thompson of the atlanta journal and constitution for reporting on racial injustice in georgia's toombs judicial circuit; and carlton smith and tomas guillen of the seattle times for their reports on the investigation of the green river murders
national reporting _ the atlanta journal and constitution staff for its series on segregation in schools; george anthan of the des moines (iowa) register for stories about contaminated poultry; and mike masterson, chuck cook and mark trahant of the arizona republic for articles on mismanagement in federal indian programs
public service _ the alabama journal for its investigation of the state's infant-mortality rate; and the courier-journal of louisville, ky., for reporting on vote-buying and influence-peddling in state elections
specialized reporting _ natalie fobes of the seattle times for stories and photos on the pacific salmon's struggle to survive man-made hazards; and the lexington (ky.) herald-leader staff for its report on the rise and fall of a horse-breeding farm
spot news photography _ paul vathis of the associated press for photos of a pennsylvania official who shot himself at a news conference; and carol guzy and brian smith of the miami herald for photos of the turmoil in haiti
residents of this quiet town, where ``everybody knows everybody,'' were stunned and scared after a young woman said a group of men raped her repeatedly while onlookers ignored her pleas
it's something horrible,'' said jesse castanon, owner of the j.c. windmill restaurant on state highway 44, the main road through this south texas county seat about 70 miles west of corpus christi
i don't know how to explain it to you because all of the people are shocked because this never happened here,'' castanon said. he said he knew most of the 11 men arrested in the case
four men were arrested and three surrendered to police thursday, said duval county assistant district attorney rodolfo gutierrez. four others were arrested wednesday. the suspects, 21 to 29 years old, were charged with rape, kidnapping or rape and kidnapping. bonds were set at $20,000 to $50,000
some of them we've brought in have admitted it. some are not talking,'' said ricardo carrillo, another assistant district attorney
there may be more arrests, and the texas rangers will help local authorities in the investigation, according to jerry galvan, an investigator with the district attorney's office
san diego, with a population of about 5,200 people, sits in rolling hills covered with mesquite trees. ranching, oil and uranium mining are major industries in the area, but the biggest employer is the county. like many small south texas towns, the dominant buildings are the courthouse and the roman catholic church
you expect something like this to happen in corpus (christi) or san antonio or dallas, but not in san diego,'' said a woman, who asked not to be identified because ``everybody knows everybody.''
the 19-year-old victim told authorities she was walking home saturday night after visiting a relative when four men forced her into a car and took her to a ranch north of town
she said the four and several others repeatedly raped her for several hours in the back seat of a car while as many as 30 people attending an illegal cockfight either ignored her pleas or joined the attack
some were holding her by the legs and by the arms, and some were covering her eyes and mouth,'' carrillo said
the mother of two said several of the men took her to another remote location and raped her again before releasing her
gutierrez said the woman knew some of her attackers and that others were identified by witnesses, including a 12-year-old boy
the 12-year-old said (the victim) was screaming and crying and told them to take her home,'' gutierrez told the corpus christi caller-times. ``they were just watching ... and she kept calling for help.''
the woman was treated at a corpus christi hospital and released earlier this week
carrillo said the woman's husband, who spent all night looking for her after she disappeared, persuaded her to file charges monday
gutierrez said that people who stood by and did nothing may not have been legally responsible for what happened, but said they were morally obliged to help the woman
schoolteacher johnny salinas said he wasn't surprised that onlookers did nothing to help
these people feel a kinship with each other,'' he told the caller-times. ``i would have tried to stop it, but then again you might be afraid to try because you'd get beat up.''
a 77-year-old woman told the newspaper she was appalled that no one came forward to help
poor girl, no one deserves anything like this,'' said esperanza ibanez. ``what kind of barbarians would have done this to her?''
