hospitals won't be getting bigger medicare payments to help offset the costs to treat heart attack victims with the expensive new anti-clotting drug called tpa
the decision was made public thursday in a letter from medicare chief william l. roper to the american hospital association
there is a question as to whether the circumstances involving tpa are so unique as to justify some special accommodation,'' roper wrote. ``we have concluded that they are not.''
hospitals have been pressing the health care financing administration to take into account the high cost of tpa _ which runs about $2,000 a dose _ in paying for the treatment of heart attack victims
medicare pays hospitals a flat, predetermined amount for treatment of various illnesses rather than reimbursing hospitals for itemized expenses used on a particular patient
the remains of 27 americans missing since the end of the vietnam war will be turned over to u.s. official in hanoi next week and then flown to an army identification laboratory in hawaii, the pentagon says
the planned return of american remains is largest repatriation by the vietnamese government since the end of the war. previously, the largest turnover of remains was 26 on aug. 14, 1985
u.s. officials in hanoi will receive the remains on wednesday. then they will be moved to the army's central identification laboratory in honolulu, hawaii, for identification, pentagon spokesman dan howard said thursday
there are currently 2,404 americans still listed as missing in indochina as a result of the vietnam war, of whom 1,767 are listed as missing in either north or south vietnam. up to now, the remains of 152 americans have been repatriated to the united states and subsequently identified by the laboratory
a racial discrimination complaint filed by more than 100 black agriculture department employees alleges bias in promotions and merit awards and claims top agency officials ignored earlier complaints
the complaint, filed thursday with the department's equal employment officer, involved grievances in the foreign agricultural service, said john franke jr., assistant agriculture secretary for administration
the complaint, signed by a large majority of the foreign service's fulltime black professional and clerical staff, charged top department officials with ignoring earlier complaints regarding placement of whites over blacks in coveted positions. the employees said blacks continue to be denied career advancement, choice overseas assignments and to be underrepresented in merit awards
usda's foreign service promotes agricultural exports through trade development programs and sales
iran launched a missile attack today on kirkuk, iraq's northern oil capital, and said 75 people have been killed and more than 100 wounded in new iraqi chemical bomb attacks on kurdish villages
iran's official islamic republic news agency said iraqi warplanes dropped bombs containing mustard and nerve gases in the qara dagh region of northeastern iraq during the six days that ended saturday
it quoted iranian-backed kurdish guerrilla sources as saying the villages of susiyan, doukan, balakha, jafaran and oliyan were hit
there was no independent confirmation and no comment by baghdad, which has been fighting a brutal mountain war against the kurdish guerrillas, who seek an independent homeland
qara dagh is 15 miles west of the front in a two-week-old iranian offensive into the kurdistan mountains, where iran claims iraqi warplanes dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs march 16-17 on three kurdish towns ``liberated'' in the push. iran claims 5,000 civilians were killed and 5,000 injured
western correspondents who visited one of the towns, halabja, last week reported seeing hundreds of bodies unmarked by bullet or shrapnel wounds. hundreds more iraqi kurds with severe burns and respiratory ailments consistent with exposure to poison gas have been seen in tehran hospitals
irna claimed thursday that iraqi warplanes also dropped chemical bombs on marivan in northwestern iran, killing ``a number'' of civilians
meanwhile, iranian revolutionary guards were reported advancing westward through kurdistan and said they bottled up 5,000 iraqis around a hydroelectric dam on lake darbandikhan, 80 miles east of iraq's big kirkuk oilfields
the iranian missile strike on kirkuk was announced after iraq declared it would halt its missile attacks on iranian cities for three days beginning today as prime minister turgut ozal of turkey visits baghdad
irna said two missiles were fired at a ``military target'' in kirkuk city early today ``in retaliation for iraqi missile attacks on iran's residential areas.''
the official iraqi news agency, also monitored in nicosia, only reported one missile hitting kirkuk, saying it exploded in a residential district, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including women and children.''
the missile struck only a half-hour after the time iraqi said it would stop missile attacks. ozal was to arrive in baghdad this afternoon
iraq sent three long-range missiles thursday into the holy city of qom 100 miles south of tehran and the central city of isfahan
there was no official response from tehran when iraq announced thursday that it would halt its missile attacks at midnight baghdad time. but an iranian embassy spokesman in ankara, turkey's capital, said thursday that his country's attacks on iraqi cities would ``automatically come to an end'' if the iraqis stopped their air and missile strikes
both sides have fired more than 250 missiles into each other's cities since feb. 29, killing hundreds of civilians
on that day that the ``war of the cities'' flared anew, ozal was visiting tehran and several missiles exploded near the downtown hotel where his delegation was staying
iraq said the latest truce would last until ozal's baghdad visit ends. officials in ankara said he would fly home sunday
turkey maintains good relations with both belligerents and has in the past tried to mediate an end to their 7-year-old war
associated press photographer greg english reported from kurdistan that iran's revolutionary guards were pushing westward in the offensive launched march 16
english, among a group of western correspondents flown to the battle zone thursday, reported from the kurdish town of dojaila that artillery rumbled to the west and it was clear ``the iranians have made significant gains.''
the iranians claim their forces occupy the eastern and southern shores of lake darbandikhan and hills overlooking the strategic dam and power station on the lake's southern tip, where they say they have surrounded 5,000 iraqis who apparently still hold the dam
a defiant jimmy swaggart probably will leave the assemblies of god rather than obey the church's one-year banishment from his television ministry, says a member of the denomination's louisiana council
swaggart cited the louisiana district council's recommendation for a more lenient three-month ban when he said through his lawyer wednesday that he would defy the national leadership and return to the pulpit on may 22
the 19-member district council was to meet today at jimmy swaggart world ministries to discuss the case, but swaggart had not been asked to attend and didn't plan to, said his lawyer, bill treeby
one member of the louisiana council said there was little it could do to fight the presbytery's harsher penalty, which includes two years of church-supervised counseling, and swaggart probably would leave the assemblies
the executive presbytery may not have the right to discipline him, but they have the power,'' the rev. ansley orfila of slidell told the springfield (mo.) news-leader. ``i don't think we'll meet to defy them. maybe it will be just to decide how to handle things.''
assemblies general superintendent g. raymond carlson said swaggart probably will be expelled from the denomination if he ignores the national body's sterner penalty
the rev. forrest hall, secretary-treasurer of the louisiana district council, said the state body probably will support the national recommendation
swaggart left the pulpit feb. 21 after tearfully confessing to an undisclosed sin. a prostitute has said swaggart paid her to pose nude for him
treeby said there was a conflict within the assemblies, the nation's largest pentecostal denomination, over whether the national presbytery or the louisiana council has the right to discipline swaggart
he is willing to submit himself to the louisiana district,'' treeby said wednesday. ``he will be considering an appeal to the national presbytery.''
state church officials decided on today's meeting, the news-leader reported, shortly after the church's national officials announced tuesday that they had rejected the three-month ban as too lenient
a storm that whipped up a tornado, hail and wind gusts up to 59 mph in texas and new mexico spread rain and snow today across the great plains
a tornado touched down thursday evening northwest of hobbs, n.m., damaging an unoccupied barn and house trailer
in northwest texas, golfball-size hail fell near woodrow, brownfield, post and denver city. two inches of penny-size hail covered the ground at odonnell late thursday. lubbock recorded a wind gust of 59 mph
the southerly flow of moist air from the gulf of mexico brought heavy rain to some areas. more than 2.5 inches fell late thursday near walnut and cherryvale, kan
forecasters posted flash flood watches for much of southeast kansas, parts of oklahoma and parts of mississippi
the rainfall at wichita falls, texas, brought the total rainfall for march to 5.24 inches, its wettest month on record. the previous record was 4.71 inches set in 1905
omaha, neb., however, had its driest march since 1910 with just .07 inches of rain, but forecasters said substantial rainfall was expected through saturday
snow continued this morning in parts of the southern rockies. albuquerque, n.m., had 4 inches of snow on the ground by midnight and edgewood, n.m., had 7 inches
in colorado, the storm began easing after dropping 20 inches of snow at rye, 15 inches at buelah, 13 inches at silver cliff and 9 inches east of salida. seven inches fell on the denver area. forecasters predicted another 1 to 4 inches of snow in colorado today
a snow advisory was posted for northwestern kansas, and a freeze warning was in effect in southeast arizona above elevations of 4,000 feet
today's forecast called for widespread rain and thunderstorms across kansas, oklahoma, parts of texas and the mississippi and tennessee valleys; showers and a few thundershowers from the ohio valley to the middle atlantic coast and across southern michigan and new york state; thunderstorms from alabama into the western carolinas; snow across colorado, northern new mexico, parts of the texas and oklahoma panhandles and northwest kansas
highs will be in the 50s or 60s in much of the nation; 30s and 40s from the central high plains and the texas panhandle across the central rockies to northern arizona, and michigan to northern minnesota; 70s and low 80s from california to the desert southwest, and from southern and eastern texas across the lower mississippi and tennessee valleys and the southern appalachians to the south atlantic states
the high for the nation thursday was 91 degrees at presidio, texas
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 9 degrees at yellowstone park, wyo., to 75 degrees at key west, fla
