the government foreclosed on his farm, evicted him from the land and burned down his home, but albert schumaker wants to buy back the place
there was just poor judgment on somebody's part'' to burn the house down in january, schumaker said thursday as he asked the farmers home administration to rebuild his home and let him buy back part of the 2,460-acre farm
the 58-year-old farmer, wearing a western hat and accompanied by 10 supporters, made his application at the fmha's burleigh county office here
schumaker said he could raise the $25,000 to $30,000 he estimates he'll need to buy back his farmstead and 10 acres in driscoll, about 30 miles east of bismarck
there (are) people pretty disgusted about the whole thing and will put the money out,'' he said. in addition, a petition is circulating calling for the ouster of some state and local fmha officials, schumaker said
schumaker, a farmer since 1959, said he hopes to eventually buy back all the acerage he lost through foreclosure. ``i have two boys, (ages) 32 and 36, and they were with the operation. my boys might be eligible for a loan.''
the fmha acquired schumaker's farm in march 1986 in a foreclosure, said burleigh county fmha supervisor sterling breuer. schumaker was evicted from his home in december
the home, a corn crib and a garage were burned jan. 30, breuer said. two barns and six steel grain bins were left standing. breuer said the house was destroyed because repairs to bring it in line with agency standards would have cost too much
schumaker said he didn't learn about the fire until three days after it happened. ``that's about the last kick they can give you after you lose a farm,'' he said
schumaker said the kitchen had been remodeled, and new windows, a furnace and water heater had been installed. ``all the neighbors knew it was livable and a good house,'' he said
these days he lives in a mobile home near driscoll, and works for farmers livestock exchange as a cattle consignor
schumaker made his application under the dwelling retention program, part of the agricultural credit act that congress passed in december calling on fmha, the lender of last resort for farmers, to go easier on growers behind in their payments
schumaker claims the agency violated his rights to retain the farmstead when it burned down his home
bob zimmerman, head of fmha farmer programs in north dakota, said the agency would consider schumaker's application, but said he was unsure whether the agency was liable for rebuilding the home
at the time of the burning, one law was being phased out and another was being phased in, zimmerman said
fmha had not received regulations for the dwelling retention program, he said. the agency was told jan. 7 to stop certain foreclosures and liquidations, but received no instructions on situations like schumaker's, where land was already in fmha hands, zimmerman said
however, don vig, vice chairman of the dakota resource council, an advocacy group for farmers and landowners, said fmha should have known about the new law when it burned schumaker's buildings
how is it possible for employees of a federal agency to be totally ignorant of the laws that they are supposed to be implementing?'' asked vig
motorola inc., fined $16.7 million for allegedly overbilling the government on defense contracts, said it is disciplining 59 employees involved in the incident
the company notified the employees last week when the $16.7 million settlement with the government was announced, spokesman mario salvadori said thursday
the company said 20 managers were dismissed or had their salaries frozen or were denied promotions. the other 39 employees were told that if they failed to follow company rules they would be fired
the $16.7 million in civil and criminal penalties and restitution stemmed from charges that the company's government electronics group in scottsdale, ariz., had mischarged the government $2.5 million on three programs in 1983
all of the employees investigated in the case work in arizona. salvadori said he did not know how many of the managers were dismissed. the government has said that criminal charges against individuals are still possible. advisory</note>
in a strategic shift, secretary of state george p. shultz said he is exploring with the soviet union arrangements for continuing u.s. and soviet military aid to rival forces in afghanistan
the proposed compromise on afghan aid would remove the only major roadblock to a negotiated settlement of that country's 8-year-old war and the withdrawal of the red army, which has been propping up the marxist government in kabul
it would be better to have a moratorium,'' shultz said
but, he added, ``to date the soviets have not wanted to do that.``
shultz also said that in meetings this weekend with italian officials he planned to discuss moving dozens of u.s. fighter planes to italy from spain
he heads for the middle east on sunday to continue efforts to spur arab-israeli negotiations
the issue of u.s. aid to afghan guerrillas and soviet aid to the kabul government has become an impediment to improved superpower relations and one of the key regional disputes confronting planners of the planned superpower summit in moscow in late may
shultz made it clear he preferred a suspension of soviet aid to the kabul regime and a matching cut-off of u.s. support for the resistance groups. american weapons have included stinger missiles that have been effective against soviet planes and helicopters
but shultz said the overall goal was ``a balanced outcome.'' he said there was nothing in peace accords being drafted in geneva ``that tells us we cannot support our friends
if the soviets exercise restraint, we are prepared to exercise restraint,'' he said
shultz said he did not know whether the soviets would go along with the equal levels of aid to the two sides. but he stressed the united states was prepared to guarantee a settlement even while weapons keep flowing to the combatants
if we have signed the accords and see a need to support our friends we will be able to do it,'' he said
shultz said he discussed the idea on the telephone wednesday with pakistani foreign minister mohammad khan junejo and that country's president, mohammad zia ul-haq, then called president reagan
so these things are in place,'' shultz said. ``where we will all come out remains to be seen.''
the united states, the soviet union, their clients in afghanistan and the government of neighboring pakistan, have been involved for months in u.n.-sponsored efforts to bring about a withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 soviet troops fighting in afghanistan since the kremlin intervened in december 1979
soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze said in an interview released thursday that he would not be surprised if afghanistan peace talks fail and he accused the united states and pakistan of blocking their success
shevardnadze said that if u.n.-mediated talks in geneva fail, the soviet union will withdraw its troops ``in a way convenient for the government of afghanistan and ourselves.''
he did not indicate whether the soviet union would stick to the nine-month withdrawal timetable already agreed to in geneva
talks aimed at ending the war in afghanistan recessed for the easter holiday. they are scheduled to resume monday, but informal contacts were expected over the weekend
shultz said he would spend the weekend in rome for easter observances and to confer with italian officials. the main topic is finding a new home for 72 u.s. f-16 jet fighter planes spain is evicting in 1991. italy is a prime candidate to take them
shultz did not predict how he would make out in the middle east next week, but he was cautiously upbeat, particularly about king hussein of jordan. his trip last month failed to bring agreement
the jordanians are quite intrigued with this,'' shultz said, ``and i look forward to intensive discussions`` with king hussein
i think we have a chance to see some motion,'' shultz said of his shuttling to israel, jordan, syria, egypt and saudi arabia
the last time foreign correspondent thomas l. friedman won a pulitzer prize he said the moment was marred because he received the news while covering the bombing of the american embassy in beirut
on thursday, though, the second pulitzer for international reporting for the new york times writer was ``unalloyed, untinged by any tragedy,'' friedman said as he and others winners across the country celebrated their honors
in 1983, friedman, then the beirut bureau chief for the times, was told of the award he received for his stories about the israeli invasion of lebanon as he was covering the embassy disaster
it was a moment very much bittersweet for someone living in beirut, with friends in the embassy,'' he said
this time, he received a telephone call from max frankel, the times' executive editor, as he worked on a book at his home in jerusalem
champagne corks popped in newsrooms across the land
if i can win the pulitzer prize, the cleveland indians can win the pennant this summer,'' said the wall street journal's walt bogdanich, who won for specialized reporting. wsj writers daniel hertzberg and james b. stewart also won for explanatory journalism
this place looks like a locker room after a world series victoy,'' said jacqui banaszynski of the st. paul pioneer press dispatch newsroom after she won for feature writing for her series on an aids victim in a farm community
champagne also flowed at the lawrence eagle-tribune, a 60,000 circulation daily in massachusetts that won the general news reporting prize for stories on a furloughed murderer who assaulted a maryland couple
this is pretty big for us. we're just a nice community newspaper,'' said susan forrest, one of the lawrence staffers who worked on the story
tom shales of the washington post, the criticism winner for his writing on television, said he was ``in a state of slack-jawed dumbfoundness.''
it's nice to be in the world almanac permanently,'' said boston university historian robert v. bruce, who won the pulitzer in history for his book, ``the launching of modern science 1846-1876.''
toni morrison, winner of the fiction award for ``beloved,'' said joy was uppermost in her feelings because, ``i really was thinking dark and difficult thoughts about what was available to this book in terms of recognition.''
the book sparked controversy when it did not win two other major literary prizes. ms. morrison said she respected the pulitzer committee for ignoring ``outside matters of speculation and gossip and some slander.''
university of michigan music professor william bolcom said, ``it's better than a kick in the teeth,'' after he won the pulitzer for music for ``12 new etudes for piano,'' a tribute to the late pianist paul jacobs
but bolcom, who said he was disturbed by the ``prize mentality'' of the public, planned a subdued celebration
i put a bottle of champagne in the ice box,'' he said. ``the local paper is coming over to take a picture of me sipping it. we'll have dinner, take baths and go to bed.''
at the miami herald, pulitzers were taken home by humorist dave barry and photographer michel ducille, a second-time winner who this time won for photos of apartments inundated by the drug crack, a potent form of cocaine
i don't want to lessen the pulitzers, but i feel more proud that the photos ... made changes in the community,'' ducille said
barry said he hopes winning the pulitzer ``will make me taller.''
he recalled he once wrote a column making fun of the pulitzer awards, saying that ``horrendously long, complicated'' pulitzer-entry stories should have editor's notes warning readers to avoid them
charlotte observer managing editor mark ethridge iii said he hoped the ptl story that brought the newspaper one of two pulitzer prizes was ``not a story that comes along just once in a lifetime.''
the observer's doug marlette also won a pulitzer for his editorial cartooning in charlotte and at the atlanta constitution, where he now works
scott shaw, a 24-year-old photographer for the odessa (texas) american, said he was surprised to win the spot news award for his coverage of the 58-hour operation that rescued little jessica mcclure and fascinated a nation
i am pretty young. i am just pretty surprised,'' said shaw
a bus filled with holiday travelers plunged 200 yards down a mountainside early today, killing 24 people and injuring 20, police said
the bus began its journey in cape town and was traveling between the towns of ladismith and calitzdorp in southern cape province when it veered off a road through a mountain pass shortly after midnight
police col. herman scheepers said those on board were people of mixed race, except for one white man, believed to be the driver. the white man was killed along with 17 other men, four women and two children, scheepers said
the cause of the accident was under investigation
south africa observes a four-day holiday weekend each easter, and the rate of traffic fatalities during the period is often the highest of the year
the u.n. command rejected north korean claims today that the united states is preparing to launch a nuclear attack from south korea and accused the north of trying to wreck the 1988 olympic games
united nations representatives at a meeting of the military armistice commission ridiculed north korean claims that u.s. forces are using military exercises in south korea to prepare for a nuclear attack against the communist north
u.s. navy rear admiral william pendley, chief u.n. delegate, said north korea was trying to increase tension on the divided korean peninsula to undermine the olympic games in seoul in september
we can understand your need for tension _ it is part of your effort to undermine the olympics,'' said pendley as the two sides traded charges and taunts in panmunjom, a village in the neutral demilitarized zone separating the two koreas
chief north korean delegate maj. gen. li tae ho started the meeting by demanding u.s. and south korean forces halt annual ``team spirit'' exercises in the south involving about 200,000 troops
li claimed the united states was using the exercise as a mask to build up its forces to attack north korea. he asserted u.s. forces introduced a large number of nuclear weapons in recent weeks
your wreckless war promotion has created a serious situation on the korean peninsula and war could break out at any time,'' li said
north korean military forces had been placed on alert to counter a u.s. attack and were in ``a full combat mobilization posture .. . to cope with the extremely dangerous situation created by your reckless military provocations,'' li said
north korea announced the alert last week
pendley said the united states had no intention of attacking north korea and that ``team spirit'' was a legal and reasonable exercise to ensure the defense of south korea. he repeated an offer to let north korean delegates observe the exercises and said the north has always rejected the offer
north korea routinely charges the united states is preparing to launch an attack. it has also placed its forces on alert during the ``team spirit'' exercises in past years
the united states has about 40,000 troops in south korea under a mutual defense pact against the north. u.s. forces are reported to have some nuclear weapons, but washington will neither confirm nor deny the reports
pendley told reporters after the meeting that the u.n. command was making every effort to safeguard the olympic games. but he warned the north may resort to terrorism to frighten other nations into staying away from the games
they may take actions to increase that tension,'' he said
the united states and south korea charge north korea was behind the nov. 29 bombing of a south korean airliner in which all 115 people aboard were killed. a woman who confessed to being a north korean agent said she put a bomb on the plane to wreck the olympics
north korea, which denied it had anything to do with the plane attack, is demanding to co-host the olympics. the international olympic committee and south korea have rejected the demand, but offered to let the north stage some events
the u.n. command, consisting of the united states and 15 nations that aided south korea during the korean war, meets with north korean and chinese delegates to police the cease-fire signed in panmunjom that ended the war in 1953
a former wedtech corp. executive says he plotted with a onetime aide to then-presidential counselor edwin meese iii to cause legal problems for the defense contractor's competitors
under cross-examination by defense attorneys thursday, ex-wedtech vice chairman mario moreno conceded that the now-defunct company used reagan administration connections to have the government investigate rivals for no-bid contracts
however, moreno denied getting wedtech competitors indicted through political connections
moreno testified at the trial of rep. mario biaggi, d-n.y., and six others charged with turning the bronx defense contractor into a racketeering enterprise that paid millions in bribes. the trial was recessed until monday
moreno testified about james jenkins, who was a top aide to attorney general meese when meese was counselor to president reagan
when defense attorney dominic amorosa asked whether jenkins had told him a wedtech competitor ``was also going to run into some serious legal difficulties,'' moreno said he had
in fact, you testified on prior examination here that you and jenkins sat down and agreed to come to limit the competitors to two, to get a particular contract, and whoever the other one was, was going to end up in serious investigative problems, correct?'' asked amorosa
moreno hesitated, then replied, ``yes.''
jenkins, who became a wedtech consultant after leaving the white house, has not been charged with wrongdoing
wedtech grew from a small machine shop into a multimillion-dollar manufacturer through a federal program that set aside non-competitive contracts for companies controlled by minority group members
prosecutors contend that biaggi and others helped wedtech falsely portray itself as a minority concern eligible for the program
defense lawyers are trying to show that wedtech officials corrupted numerous administration officials, and didn't the help of biaggi, a democratic congressman from the bronx, to obtain government contracts
amorosa ticked off a list of politically connected people who got jobs with wedtech: e. robert wallach, meese's former attorney; jenkins; former reagan political adviser lyn nofziger and nofziger's business partner, mark bragg
these people,'' asked amorosa, ``had the ability to get people indicted, didn't they?''
i believe so,'' moreno replied
but he repeatedly denied asking bragg to have wedtech competitors indicted
we asked to have them investigated _ for any skeletons in their closet,'' insisted moreno, one of four ex-wedtech executives who pleaded guilty to state and federal charges and agreed to testify for the prosecution in exchange for leniency
pressed by amorosa, moreno conceded that bragg, while not a member of the justice department, knew a wedtech competitor would be indicted before the indictment was made public
moreno said only one competitor was indicted and that was for matters unrelated to wedtech
nofziger was convicted in february in washington of illegal lobbying for wedtech. bragg was acquitted on related charges
meese has not been charged with any wrongdoing, although a special prosecutor in washington continues to investigate his dealings with wedtech. rebels</head>
rebels claimed they captured three towns in northern ethiopia and state-owned radio quoted president mengistu haile mariam as saying his troops were fighting ``grim battles'' with the insurgents
it was believed to be the first time mengistu has conceded publicly that the secessionist rebels are in any way effective
radio ethiopia on thursday quoted him as saying rebels had launched a ``systematic and highly destructive campaign'' in the tigre and neighboring eritrea provinces, disrupting transport and communications networks
it was the first comment by the marxist government on reports of a new rebel offensive, which also resulted in the capture last week of three soviet military advisers to the ethiopian army
the fighting has aggravated relief efforts in the north, the worst-hit drought region of ethiopia. most of the 6 to 7 million ethiopians threatened with starvation this year live in the north
because of rebel activities, the soviet-backed government often closes roads in the region, cutting off truck convoys
assesa mamo, north american representative of the tigre people's liberation front, claimed the rebels took the towns of axum and adowa on thursday after a three-day battle. he spoke from washington in a telephone interview with the associated press bureau in nairobi, kenya
axum is 110 miles south of asmara, eritrea's provincial capital, and adowa is 30 miles from axum
eritrean rebels said sunday they captured the town of afabet, killing or capturing 18,000 ethiopian troops. the rebels said one soviet officer was killed and three taken prisoner. afabet is 100 miles north of asmara
the rebels claimed to have wiped out three government divisions and captured tanks, weapons and other military equipment worth millions of dollars
there was no way to verify the rebels' claims. but western diplomats in addis ababa said the figure of 18,000 troops, a third of troops stationed in the north, sounded preposterous
the soviet union confirmed three of its advisers were captured, but said nothing of a fourth officer being killed
mengistu made his comments about the rebels in a report to the eighth regular meeting of the central committee of his marxist workers' party of ethiopia
western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said mengistu's statement indicated the fighting must be serious. they said there were reports the ethiopian leader is preparing a huge counteroffensive against rebels of the eritrea people's liberation front and the tigre rebel group
mengistu inherited the insurgencies 13 years ago when, with a group of army officers, he dethroned emperor haile selassie and helped set up a marxist government
eritrean rebels have been fighting for 27 years in africa's oldest civil war
the u.n. world food program reported thursday that a relief convoy reached the town of wukro in tigre province, bringing the first major food delivery to the drought-stricken area since january
the emergency shipment of 1,500 metric tons, enough to feed 100,000 people for a month, arrived march 24, said david morton, the u.n. representative in ethiopia
the american medical association today urged doctors to take a more active role in their communities to ensure fairness in the debate over the use of animals in research
in a commentary in the journal of the ama, the association cautioned that erosion of public support for the use of research animals poses as great a threat as pending legislation or regulatory efforts
when people are given the entire picture, when they're reminded that research animals played a crucial role in the development of vaccines ... and heart transplants and antibiotics, there is clearly backing for this position,'' said william hendee, ama vice president for science and technology
but those opposed to the practice are starting now at the local level, aiming programs at schoolchildren. it's in those situations that we're appealing to doctors and scientists to come forward, to make sure both sides of the debate are presented,'' said hendee, who wrote the commentary with stephen smith, a senior scientist with the association's department of drugs
the congressional office of technology assessment estimates that 17 million to 22 million animals are used annually in biomedical experiments, and that 75 percent to 90 percent of them are rodents: rats, mice, hamsters, guinea pigs and rabbits
dogs, cats and primates make up less than 5 percent of the remainder
primates are obtained from breeders or, in some cases, are bred by research facilities. dogs and cats are obtained from pounds or from special breeders
sixty percent of the experiments each year do not result in any suffering by the animal, and animals receive painkilling drugs or anesthesia in 32 percent of the cases, smith said. pain is inflicted on the experimental animal in 8 percent of the experiments, he added
spokeswoman jeanne roush of people for ethical treatment of animals, a washington-based animal-rights organization, said the appeal shows ``the ama is running scared
they simply realize animal-rights groups are gaining momentum ... that medical students and even doctors are less and less inclined to take part in these experiments,'' ms. roush said
they should begin seriously looking at alternatives (to animals) and phasing this practice out completely,'' she said. ``that's what people want.''
the ama authors said researchers are barred from using pound animals in some places, and that such prohibitions are being considered elsewhere
a complete ban would drive up research costs by $90 million annually, they estimated
most of the millions of animals consigned to pounds are destroyed, he said. less than 3 percent of those are research animals, according to the commentary
a karate student beat, stomped on and threw a man to the sidewalk after the victim questioned his knowledge of the martial art, police said
william roberts, 37, was in critical condition thursday at the university of maryland shock trauma center. a hospital worker who refused to identify herself said she could not release roberts' condition today
the karate student, 28-year-old john mccloskey of suburban pasadena, was held on $250,000 bond, charged with assault with intent to murder, aggravated assault and possession of a deadly weapon
witnesses told police roberts was apparently intoxicated when he staggered up the steps of the order of isshinryu karate school and knocked on the door wednesday
police found him unconscious in a pool of blood and a trail of blood leading into the school
mccloskey told police he had felt threatened
islamabad, pakistan (ap) _ a patron left a bomb in a poultry shop near the afghan border and it exploded, killing seven people and injuring 18, the official government newspaper reported today
also thursday, two other people were killed and two were wounded in another frontier village by incoming afghan artillery rounds, the english-language pakistan times said
the bombing occurred in the northwestern village of sadda when a man purchased a hen then asked the shop owner to keep the bird and a parcel for him while he finished his shopping, the times said
the man has not been apprehended and no group claimed responsibility, the paper said. pakistani officials have blamed a series of terrorist bombings over the past two years on agents of afghanistan's soviet-backed government
pakistan supports the guerrillas fighting that government and shelters about 3.5 million afghan refugees
the shelling occurred in a village identified as ghakh, the times said
cross-border shellings and aerial bombings have been frequent in the 10-year-old afghan war
both of thursday's attacks occurred in semi-autonomous districts ruled by pashtun tribal clans that are normally off limits to pakistani police and military. they are also the main staging areas for afghan guerrillas. stabbed in old city. picks up 5th graf pvs ```we planned... </note>
smaller than normal crowds of christian pilgrims today carried wooden crosses and sang psalms in the old city's via dolorosa to commemorate good friday, the anniversary of jesus' crucifixion
twenty yards away from the street, an arab attacker stabbed an israeli police sergeant in the stomach. the officer was hospitalized in fair condition. police apprehended a suspect and cordoned off the area
arab unrest in the israeli-occupied territories has prompted many pilgrims to stay away this year
the greek orthodox patriarch of jerusalem canceled three pre-easter processions scheduled for today and saturday out of concern for the pilgrims' safety and due to an expected sharp drop in the number of tourists
but the old city was more alive than it has been for weeks and many of the hundreds of tourists visiting the 12th century church of the holy sepulchre said the event was a special one. the church marks the spot where jesus was crucified and, as christians believe, resurrected
we planned to come here for a long time and nothing could stop us, even friends who said we were crazy,'' said david reid of mountain lakes, n.j. ``there are lots of police around and we are as safe here as we are in new york city.''
dozens of israeli riot police stood guard along the route, some munching the unleavened matzoh crackers jews eat during the week of passover, which begins today
the via dolorosa, or way of sorrow, marks the path where jesus, wearing a crown of thorns, was forced to carry the cross on which he was later crucified. the tradition of following the devotional walk was started in the 14th century by the franciscans, a roman catholic order
today, the via is a narrow cobblestone street crowded with shops which passes by several moslem mosques. christians singing and praying walked down the street, along with priests who carried ornate silver and gold crosses and burned incense
the church of the holy sepulchre was built on the site where jesus is believed to have been crucified and buried, and where he is said to have risen from the dead two days later, an event commemorated on easter
the spot of the crucifixion is marked on the church's second floor by an ornate gold table and a figure of jesus, lit only by candles
downstairs, pilgrims kissed and threw water on the rock marking the spot where jesus's body was washed before burial. sixteen choir boys in long black robes sang prayers
arab merchants opened their shops for the three hours permitted by the palestine liberation organization and did brisk business selling solid olive-wood crosses
but christian church officials were predicting the violence in the occupied territories would trigger a sharp decline in tourism
the rev. timoteus margaritis, a spokesman for the greek orthodox christian church, said 1,500 pilgrims were expected to attend his church's april 10 easter service, instead of the usual 10,000
tourism figures, however, have also become part of the arab-israeli conflict, with israeli officials reluctant to acknowledge an adverse impact of the conflict in the territories
tourism ministry officials said more visitors came to israel in january and february as compared with the previous year, but said 13 percent fewer tourists entered the country during the first week in march
we are concerned about the coming months, april, may and june, when we do expect a slight drop,'' said micha dedron, who added that the most serious decline in tourism was among u.s. jews
a high school football coach chose the 50-yard line of capital studium to marry a former cheerleader _ but before the nuptials were over he was called offsides for making a premature pass at the bride
when steve ash, 38, an assistant football coach at rickards high school, asked lora kyle to marry him on valentine's day, he had more than one proposal to make
i'm a coach, she was a cheerleader, we both love sports, and we both think that a marriage should be fun and make you laugh, so why not have a wedding that does the same thing?'' ash said
i never thought it would get this big,'' ms. kyle, 35, said through clenched teeth moments before her wedding
good evening ladies and gentlemen, and welcome to capital stadium,'' jeff duke announced over the public address system. after introducing all the second-stringers who helped, duke gave the starting lineup
direct your attention to the south end zone, where standing tall at 5-feet-9-inches and weighing in at 195, starting at groom from steer creek, w.va., steve ash.''
ash then burst through a paper banner with a pink tuxedo painted on it and ran to the 50-yard line
and now, in the north end zone, a 5-3, 130-pound former cheerleader from smith creek, fla., starting at bride, lora kyle.''
ms. kyle then jumped through a similar banner with a pink hat painted on it
but as the knot was being tied an overzealous ash tried to steal a kiss from his bride and the rev. chuck groover objected
that's offsides. you're supposed to wait,'' groover said. ``you're not supposed to kiss her until i say so.''
a five-second penalty followed after which the real kiss was exchanged as hundreds of blue and white helium balloons were released
pssst, wanna buy a bridge? grays harbor county has one for sale and it's a bargain. it's free
there's just one catch: the purchaser has to take the 120-foot span apart, move it and repair it, according to county records
among other things, the bridge on the olympic peninsula needs new deck planks, the metal truss work needs paint and the new owner should know the wooden stringers have a life expectancy of 10-15 years
the 14-foot-wide bridge, built in 1915, cannot support current legal loads and is to be replaced next year by a two-lane bridge
the span was placed on the national register of historic places in 1980, preventing the county from simply tearing it down without trying to find the bridge a new home
so far, there have been no takers
