it's ridiculous,'' said fraternity president paul kearney. ``why should they be upset if it's a fund-raiser? they do it everywhere else. if they go to the beach, are they going to call that sexist too?''
robert o'brien, chairman of the fraternity's fund-raising committee, said proceeds of the contest were to be used for the fraternity's yearly beer keg roll, a charity event that raised $3,000 for the jimmy fund last year
the jimmy fund, the official charity of the boston red sox, raises money to fight cancer in children
the fraternity circulated fliers last week announcing, ``delta upsilon &amp; the jimmy fund in association with the amherst police dept. present first annual bikini contest.''
but jimmy fund associate director michael rafferty said he knew nothing of the contest and asked the fraternity not to use its name for the event
amherst police chief donald maia had accepted an invitation to be master of ceremonies at the contest but changed his mind over the weekend, saying the contest was no longer a beauty pageant and his presence would be inappropriate
more than 3,000 travelers, many embarking on their easter vacations, were stuck today in a long line of buses, cars and trucks waiting to cross the english channel at the strikebound port of dover
vacationers bound for calais, france, with ferry reservations faced delays of up to 12 hours, and truck drivers could wait even longer, said paul youden, a spokesman for the dover harbor board
the ferry worker's dispute has halted all of p and o european ferries' ships in dover, but other vessels were operating out of the southeastern port
other ports also said they were busy handling some of the traffic from dover
about 2,300 ferry workers have been on strike for eight weeks over p and o's plan to cut 400 jobs and introduce new shifts
