first lady nancy reagan toured the $2.5 million home she and the president will share when the couple leaves the white house
mrs. reagan, her press secretary, elaine crispen, and others in her entourage didn't stop to meet with reporters when they visited the mansion thursday afternoon
mrs. reagan, who arrived in los angeles on wednesday, checked into the beverly wilshire hotel. she was in town to see the house and to take care of ``some business and tasks that she has to perform,'' said wendy toler, the first lady's deputy press secretary
ms. crispen said the first lady had seen the house before but was taking another look while in town
the house has three bedrooms, six baths, guest room, living room, family room, sun room, butler's pantry and three servants' rooms. it's tucked away on a 1\-acre estate in exclusive bel air, 12 miles northwest of downtown los angeles
the reagans' future home sits next door to the kirkeby estate, where the ``beverly hillbillies'' was filmed. television producer jerry perenchio recently bought kirkeby for more than $13 million
the reagans also will be neighbors to such entertainers as elizabeth taylor, joan rivers, zsa zsa gabor, mac davis and burt bacharach
the president and his wife signed a three-year lease on the ranch house within the last two weeks, elaine crispen, the first lady's press secretary, said earlier this week. the house is owned by wall management services, a group of about 20 friends of the reagans who bought it with them in mind, she said
the three-year agreement gives the reagans the option to renew the lease or buy the property. the identity of the wall management individuals and the amount of the lease payments were not disclosed
