president reagan left today for a 10-day easter holiday after ordering new steps to force the ouster of panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega by tightening the economic screws on his government
shortly before departing for his california ranch, reagan also signed a $48 million humanitarian aid bill providing supplies to nicaragua's contra rebels and medical care to war-injured children
the measure received final approval in the senate on thursday on an 87-7 vote. reagan signed the bill in his residence with no fanfare. the signing was announced by a brief executive order delegating responsibilities to various agencies to carry out provisions of the law
reagan, dogged in recent days about his embattled attorney general, edwin meese iii, and resignations at the justice department, did not make any appearance in public thursday and will remain largely out of sight until april 10
his only appearance will be at a fund-raising event monday in newport beach, south of los angeles, for the ronald reagan library. construction on the library is expected to begin this summer at a site in ventura county
as part of the economic pressure against noriega, the internal revenue service said today that american corporations' tax payments to the government of eric arturo delvalle, whom the united states recognizes as president of panama, will qualify for the u.s. foreign tax credit
the announcement cleared the way for u.s. firms that operate in panama to pay taxes into a special account at the federal reserve bank of new york without jeopardizing the tax credit. the credit is designed to avoid taxation of the same dollar of income by the united states and a foreign country
the action cuts off a source of cash to the financially strapped noriega regime. the reagan administration has expressed concern that a recent infusion of cash, some of it from u.s. corporate tax payments, may have temporarily strengthened noriega's hold
delvalle issued a decree on march 25 directing that income taxes due the government of panama be paid only to a new york federal reserve bank
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater, who outlined the series of actions against panama on thursday, said he did know how much money would be involved by the irs step, but estimated it could deprive noriega of ``millions and millions.''
the irs announcement was one of a series of measures to deprive noriega's government of money from american companies and individuals. fitzwater said the administration would consider making the measures mandatory if voluntary action proves insufficient
the action follows the disclosure that some american firms _ including texaco inc. and eastern airlines _ paid taxes and fees owed to panama for doing business there, undercutting the economic sanctions imposed by the united states on panama
announcing the new action, fitzwater said, ``we are giving u.s. companies and persons an incentive and opportunity not to provide financial support to the noriega regime
should these measures prove insufficient, we will review additional legal steps that may be necessary to deny transfer of funds to the noriega regime from u.s. companies and persons,'' fitzwater said
noriega is under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking charges. as chief of the 15,000-member defense forces, he is the power behind panama's civilian government, although the united states recognizes eric arturo delvalle _ who is in hiding _ as the legitimate leader
fitzwater said u.s. government payments owed the government of panama will be deposited in the federal reserve bank in new york. the united states already is withholding canal fees, toll payments and other funds. fitzwater said withholding taxes for u.s. employees in panama and rental payments also will go in the new account
he also said the justice department will take part in legal cases by private parties who owe debts to panama, declaring delvalle the legitimate leader of the country. the u.s. treasury will help establish an account for payments in these cases
the leftist sandinista government and the contra rebels today began a formal 60-day cease-fire in their 6{-year war, but details remain to be negotiated next week
a spokesman for the defense ministry, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there were no initial reports of violations of the truce, which began at midnight
the cease-fire was worked out last week during peace talks between the rebels and government negotiators in sapoa, a post on nicaragua's southern border with costa rica
it was arranged to give both sides time to arrange a permanent truce to bring an end to the fighting that has battered the country since late 1981
the cease-fire is an extension of a temporary truce that began march 21 during the peace talks
in technical discussions earlier this week at sapoa, both sides agreed in general terms on the size and location of five zones where the rebels are to gather in the first 15 days of april
two zones are in the northern part of the country, two on the caribbean coast and one in the south. their exact locations have not been disclosed
the two sides will resume talks next week, apparently to determine details of the cease-fire, including what supplies the rebels may receive and whether they must lay down their weapons
technical discussions are to resume tuesday in sapoa, while high-level negotiations between sandinista and contra leaders are set for wednesday in the capital of managua
under the peace agreement signed march 23, the sandinistas will grant freedom of expression and amnesty to political prisoners and will allow rebel leaders to take part in national talks
the contras, in turn, agreed to gather in the cease-fire zones and accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization, such as the international red cross
in washington, president reagan signed today a $48 million non-lethal aid package for the contras, but it probably will be at least two weeks before the rebels begin receiving supplies under the new legislation
there certainly is an urgent need among the (rebels) for medical supplies, food, clothing, the basic commodities of life,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater. ``this bill is very welcome in that regard and we support it.''
u.s. aid to the contras ended on feb. 29
on thursday, nicaraguan president daniel ortega expressed concern that the measure called for the u.s. agency for international development to deliver the aid to the rebels. he said the organization of american states should determine how the help will be turned over to the contras
government offices and most stores were closed today to mark the long easter weekend. many nicaraguans went to the beaches on the pacific coastal for the holiday
the internal revenue service has ordered its agents to ignore more-restrictive court rulings in determining whether certain stipends paid graduate students are subject to tax
the agency said it will rely instead on a 1975 revenue ruling that allows some stipends to be excluded from taxation
the irs announcement is aimed at clearing up confusion that apparently has resulted in thousands of students being billed for back taxes on their stipends because the district where they filed returns decided the issue on the basis of court rulings
the announcement applies only to stipends earned before 1987. a new law taxes most such post-1986 payments to the extent they exceed the cost of tuition
under the irs announcement, pre-1987 stipend income is not taxed if:
_the student was a candidate for a degree,
_the student performed research or other services for the collge to satisfy requirements for the degree, and
_similar services were required of all degree candidates
students who have been assessed additional taxes and who meet those requirements should apply for a refund, if they have paid, or an abatement, if they have not paid the extra amount, the irs said. any such filing should note that it is being done for reconsideration of whether the stipend is taxable
the agency promised to give quick attention to any such claims. of effects</head>
an attorney for the internal revenue service told a federal appeals court the agency wants to revoke ptl's tax-exempt status even if it means the end of the financially troubled ministry
i don't understand why the irs doesn't take a more practical approach to this,'' judge william wilkins of the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals on thursday told the lawyer, francis allegra
allegra replied, ``the importance here is not just in this case, but it will be felt in other cases.''
wilkins was part of a three-judge panel that heard an appeal from the fort mill-based ministry to an earlier u.s. district judge ruling permitting the irs to revoke the ministry's tax-exempt status. earlier this month, wilkins granted a stay of that ruling pending review by the appeals court, which is expected to make its decision within two weeks
the irs seeks to make the revocation retroactive to may 31, 1981. it contends that contributions funded the lavish lifestyles of ministry founders jim and tammy bakker, who resigned after a scandal over a sexual encounter bakker had with former church secretary jessica hahn, and that much of ptl's heritage village usa operations were commercial in nature
allegra said failure to revoke ptl's tax-exempt status could cost the federal government between $55 million and $82 million in back taxes
ptl attorney r. bradford leggett told the judges that loss of its tax-exempt status would jeopardize the ministry's ability to reorganize itself under federal bankruptcy court protection by a may 1 deadline
wilkins suggested to allegra that the irs could jeopardize its ability to collect back taxes if it succeeds in revoking ptl's status before may 1
allegra acknowleged the agency's action could jeopardize tax payments, but he said to allow ptl a further stay is to invite abuse, adding that the ministry could ask the court for additional stays after may 1
ptl spokesman dave west said the ministry is aware it will have to settle with the irs eventually
but if we do not continue under the protection of the bankruptcy court, then the irs can come in and supersede the work of the bankruptcy court,'' west said
at the very minimum, the irs' actions should be held in abeyance,'' he said
ptl is in the midst of a ``march to victory'' telethon that aims to raise $4.2 million by may 1 to meet the bankruptcy court's reorganization plan. the ministry has debts estimated at $60 million and so far has raised $2.2 million, west said. pvs, meanwhile, justice. trims thruout. mckay's announcement at noon est</note>
independent counsel james mckay today was preparing to issue a statement in the criminal investigation of attorney general edwin meese iii that is somewhat favorable to the attorney general, sources familiar with the probe said
however, mckay, who has been investigating meese's involvement through his longtime friend e. robert wallach with scandal-plagued wedtech corp. and a $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline, will continue his criminal investigation, said the sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity
it wasn't immediately known what the independent counsel's expected one-page statement would say, but one justice department source said that ``on balance'' it is favorable to meese
i'm not concerned about it,'' one of meese's lawyers, james rocap, said when asked if the statement were favorable to meese. rocap said the defense lawyers would have a statement of their own later
meanwhile, justice department sources said that later today meese was likely to announce the names of two, or possibly three, nominees for now-vacant justice department posts
president reagan, asked as he left the white house for an easter vacation in california, ``what about meese. ... should he quit?'' responded, ``i think you'll be hearing from him later today.''
the department's top ranks were decimated tuesday by the protest resignations of deputy attorney general arnold burns and assistant attorney general william weld, head of the criminal division
in addition, the no. 3 justice department official, stephen trott, is leaving to become a federal judge
meese is expected to announce replacements for trott and weld, and possibly burns, said one justice department source, who requested anonymity
the replacement for weld is james i.k. knapp, a deputy in the justice department's tax division who previously worked in the criminal division
the replacement for trott is francis a. keating ii, now the assistant treasury secretary for enforcement, a position that involves overseeing criminal investigations of money laundering and other crimes. keating oversees the customs service, the secret service and the bureau of alcohol, tobacco and firearms
the swift appointments by meese are an attempt to quell mounting calls for his resignation
earlier in the day, the justice department's fourth-ranking official, who reportedly tried but failed to get meese to resign, said he would stay on the job so long as he can work ``with integrity and effectiveness.''
the statement by solicitor general charles fried was devoid of any other expression of support for meese other than to say that the solicitor general would stay on for the time being
in a prepared statement, fried said he had had a private conversation with meese on wednesday ``to tell him clearly what course of action i thought he should follow.''
fried refused to tell reporters what that recommended course was. the new york times, however, said that fried had urged meese to quit but that meese had rejected the suggestion
i have concluded that while i am able to lead the office of the solicitor general with integrity and effectiveness in its special responsibilities to the law, to the united states and to the supreme court, i should continue to do so,'' fried's statement said
fried said pointedly that ``i will not accept any other positions in the department of justice,'' which was rocked tuesday by the resignations of burns and weld
fried's statement referred to the special, almost autonomous nature, of the solicitor general's office in connection with the rest of the justice department. fried's office is responsible for arguing the government's positions before the u.s. supreme court. his statement referred to ``the two departments'' _ his office and the justice department
as course, i serve only at the pleasure of the president,'' said the solicitor general. ``as for the attorney general, i felt it was my duty to him and to the two departments to tell him clearly what course of action i thought he should follow
i did that wednesday in a private conversation.''
retired associate justice of the supreme court lewis f. powell jr. said fried had called him monday evening, ``very upset and concerned, and very perplexed about what he should do,'' according to the times
monday was the day that burns and weld made their decision to quit out of concern that meese's continued tenure as attorney general was hurting the operations of and undermining public confidence in the justice department. the resignations were announced the next day
powell said that fried had indicated to him that ``once he found out what the facts were, he'd have to keep in mind that he had an obligation to the court,'' according to the times
meese has been under criminal investigation for nearly 11 months
meanwhile, meese is facing growing pressure from republicans as well as democrats to resign
meese met thursday with republican sen. strom thurmond, who said a number of people on capitol hill have expressed ``deep concern about the problems at the justice department.''
thurmond is the ranking republican on the senate judiciary committee and the discussion was the strongest sign to date of growing bipartisan concern in congress over whether the attorney general's mounting legal problems are dragging down his department
thurmond said he was not making any judgments, but that he would not ``countenance any corruption in any way, shape or form in the justice department or any other department.''
wallach, a san francisco attorney who is now under indictment in the wedtech scandal, is at the heart of the criminal investigation of meese that began last may 11. the independent counsel has been trying to determine whether wallach or others paid off meese in exchange for his official acts on behalf of wedtech or the pipeline project
in an interview published thursday in the san jose (calif.) mercury news, wallach said he should have been more sensitive to the appearance of impropriety in helping meese set up a financial partnership with investment manager w. franklyn chinn, who later joined wedtech's board. both chinn and wallach have been indicted on racketeering charges related to wedtech
wallach also said in the interview that meese had ``nothing absolutely'' to do with a $150,000 payment wallach received from swiss financier bruce rappaport in connection with the iraqi pipeline plan
rappaport, a partner in the pipeline project, had been scheduled to give a deposition about the case to mckay last month but backed out and has apparently decided not to cooperate with the investigation, the washington post reported today
the newspaper, quoting unidentified sources in washington and abroad, said rappaport changed his mind at the last minute because he was afraid he might not remember everything accurately
rappaport was to have been given immunity from prosecution in the case
the grandson of former university of texas football coach darrell royal has been released after being charged with stealing part of an albert einstein manuscript
samuel royal, 18, who is not a student at the university, was released thursday on his personal recognizance from the travis county jail following his arrest wednesday night
investigators said a telephoned tip led them to the younger royal's apartment tuesday where a page of the manuscript was found in a photo album, along with photographs of his grandfather, the university of texas' football coach from 1957 through 1976
sammy is my grandson, and i love him, but i will not attempt to interfere with the normal process of justice,'' said darrell royal, who now serves as special assistant to the university's president william cunningham
the felony theft charge carries a maximum punishment of 20 years in prison
for about $3,000, japanese tourists can see the great wall, eat peking duck and grow hair with zhao zhangguang's mysterious, magical hair-restoring tonic
a tour bus arrived friday carrying 98 bald and thin-haired japanese for their first treatment with 101 hair liniment, a liquid made from a secret recipe of about 30 medicinal herbs
it is the second japanese group, following 20 who arrived in february, to come to china on a package tour that includes treatment at zhao's clinic at the jinsong hospital in eastern beijing
among the first 20, ``some have already started to grow hair,'' said kenichi morita, president of china-japan treatment headquarters, a private tokyo medical firm sponsoring the tours
most of the japanese said they signed up for the trip after reading in newspapers of the miraculous results of 101, which zhao, a former farmer with only six years of formal education, developed after 10 years of private research
dr. liu qirong, the chief of 12 dermatologists at zhao's clinic, said about 2,700 chinese have been treated in the past year, with 92 percent showing some new growth of hair. for people who have lost hair in patches, the success rate is 100 percent, she said
according to the official news agency xinhua, more than 100,000 people have been treated with 101 since production began a year ago, with an improvement rate of 97.5 percent and a cure rate of 84 percent
zhao's results haven't been independently verified
by comparison, the anti-baldness drug minoxidil, recommended for approval by the u.s. food and drug administration, had a success rate of 26 percent of men in the 40-49 age group. for those under 30, the growth rate was 54 percent, and it was 41 percent to 45 percent in the 31-39 age group
zhao's liniment, liu said, works by stimulating circulation of the blood and cleaning out hair follicles. a second medicine, 102, is available to ensure that the new hair will not fall out
one slightly balding 40-year-old man from osaka, japan, said he read about the cure in a magazine and decided to join the tour because ``it's better to have hair than not to have hair.''
for some, it is more serious. yuji matsuishi, a 6-year-old from fukuoka, lost all his hair 18 months ago, and japanese doctors have had no success in either identifying or solving the problem, said his grandmother, yoshie kuga
we have high hopes. nothing else has worked,'' she said
doctors said the tonic works better on people whose hair loss is fairly recent, and they were optimistic yuji's hair could start coming back after a month or two of treatment
they said treatment generally consists of dabbing the liquid onto the scalp several times a day for about six months or as long as it takes for hair to grow back
the only side-effect, liu said, is that the scalp often turns a brownish color before the hair returns
one bottle of 101, which lasts for about a month, sells for about $12 in china, but morita said the price will soon shoot up to about $30. the chinese government, which has not given official approval to the medicine, has given zhao the go-ahead to cash in on his drug
the treatment is undergoing clinical tests in china and cannot be sold in stores or hospitals here or in any other country. it can, however, be purchased directly from zhao's clinic for personal use
zhao, who once had to sell his only pig to obtain money needed to continue his research, now operates two factories, one in central china's zhengzhou and the other in beijing. the beijing plant earned profits of about $135,000 in its first year, the official china daily reported
liu said people from japan, west germany, hong kong, singapore, the united states and other countries have written about the treatment or come to the clinic, and they hope to begin exporting it once the medicine is approved by various health agencies
we're not in this for profit,'' liu said. ``we're trying to cure people, and when people are cured, it makes us happy.''
most of the nation will spring forward to daylight-saving time on sunday, losing an hour's sleep in return for more evening light during the summer
the official moment comes at 2 a.m., when clocks should be reset to 3 a.m. most people, however, will simply do the job before retiring saturday night
standard time will return on oct. 30
it is the second year that daylight-saving time will begin on the first sunday in april. before congress chamnged the law, the time switch occurred on the last sunday of april. graf pvs bgng ``i want...</note>
democratic presidential candidate michael dukakis said today that corporate greed has left ``the average working men and women of america holding the bag'' while the rich get richer
dukakis, injecting a note of populism into his campaign speech, struck out at corporate greed he said was fostered by the reagan administration
wall street pirates and corporate hit teams aren't the model for a new america,'' dukakis said
if we're serious about winning the battle for our economic future, we've got to get control of the merger and acquisition binge that's gobbling up capital, tearing corporations apart like erector sets, making millions of dollars for a few ... and leaving the average working men and women of america holding the bag,'' he said
on thursday, dukakis said his experience as massachusetts governor would make him a better president than jesse jackson, but he refused to criticize the rival who is running neck-and-neck with him in wisconsin primary polls
i want to win this nomination and unite this party at the same time,'' he said at a news conference
dukakis also called for the resignation of attorney general edwin meese iii, a call made earlier in the day by jackson, who also was campaigning in wisconsin
the justice department is still in turmoil and i guess (that) will continue until we have a new attorney general and it's about time we did,'' dukakis said. ``i would hope at long last the attorney general would resign _ it's long overdue _ and the president would appoint somebody as attorney general we could be proud of.''
dukakis' remarks followed a speech at serb hall, a traditional rallying point for presidential candidates in wisconsin, where dukakis said the reagan administration ``has walked away from the american dream.''
asked why he considered himself more qualified than jackson, dukakis said, ``i think i am going to be a better president because i think i've got the strength, the experience and the values to lead this country; because i'm somebody who not only believes in good jobs and good wages for people, i've helped to create them.''
dukakis also cited his efforts in massachusetts to combat homelessness and drug abuse in schools
that's why i'm running. that's why i think i would be the best nominee and the best president. i respect the other candidates. they have their strengths and weaknesses as all of us do. we all share a lot of common values and goals, but if there is one strength i believe i bring to this campaign it is as a proven chief executive and leader who has done these things.''
dukakis said he is the candidate ``who understands how you take hopes and dreams and transform them into action.''
dukakis' speech, in which he accused the reagan administration of embracing programs for the rich and of excessive military spending at the expense of working men and women, was new
he denied it was a response to criticism that he lacked passion in his campaigning
i just thought it was time. you guys' eyes were glazing over a little bit and i just thought it was time to give you something new,'' dukakis told reporters
president reagan has nominated maj. gen. donald l. cromer for promotion to lieutenant general and assignment as commander of the air force systems command's space division, the pentagon said friday
assuming senate confirmation, cromer, 52, will replace lt. gen. aloysius g. casey, who will retire on july 1 after 34 years' service
cromer, a native of grand junction, colo., now commands the air force's space and missile test organization
in another personnel move, maj. gen. clifford h. rees jr. would be promoted to lieutenant general and named vice commander of the u.s. air forces in europe. rees, 51, would replace lt. gen. thomas g. mcinerney, who was recently nominated to assume command of the alaskan air command
rees, from newport news, va., now heads the tactical air command's air defense weapons center
reagan also nominated rear adm. everette d. stumbaugh to become the judge advocate general of the navy. sumbaugh, 50, a native of clarksville, ark., now is deputy judge advocate general. escaped from four men who held him captive. picks up in 3rd graf, `officers are ...</note>
a town marshal who was believed to have been kidnapped told his family today that he managed to escape from four men who had held him captive in an abandoned house and in a car trunk, officials said
police had launched an intense manhunt for gary stokes after he disappeared early thursday while investigating an apparent burglary in this tiny northeast mississippi town
stokes ``told his father that they let him out of the trunk early today to go to the restoom and, as he walked over some railroad tracks figuring he had a 50-50 chance to live, he ran into the woods,'' said mayor robert p. godwin
stokes was unharmed and resting at his family home, state and tippah county authorities said
about all i can tell you is that he is back and we are investigating,'' said tippah county sheriff leroy meeks said today
officers ``are treating this as a kidnapping,'' said deputy sheriff carl gillard. meeks, however, declined to confirm that stokes had been abducted
stokes disappeared early thursday and authorities feared he may have been taken captive by someone trying to break into a storage room behind a store in blue mountain, a northern mississippi town of about 860 residents
city clerk billie morgan said today her office was told that stokes, the town's only full-time policeman, had walked to a house in the town of myrtle in neighboring union county ``and called in about 3 a.m. i understand he told officers that he was abducted.''
police had used tracking dogs in the rain as they searched for stokes in rural areas around blue mountain all day thursday and well into the night. a helicopter search had been planned today
meeks had said officers from surrounding counties, firemen and civilians had helped deputies in the search
meeks said stokes, 35, radioed the nearby ripley police department for backup while investigating the possible burglary early thursday
when the units arrived, he was nowhere to be found,'' the sheriff said
morgan said officers found stokes' car with the engine still running, the lights on and his radio microphone hanging outside the door
the officers reported they found his police pistol on the ground, with one bullet fired, and his empty billfold nearby,'' morgan said
however, meeks said investigators were uncertain when the bullet was fired. he said no evidence was found that anyone had been wounded at the scene
authorities issued a bulletin for a car with four occupants that apparently was seen in the area about the time stokes radioed in
we are checking every possibility and we don't know if those men had anything to do with all this,'' the sheriff said
a 16-year-old boy died after he shot himself during a game of russian roulette in front of a friend who didn't think the gun was loaded, authorities said
gary l. craig of troy died thursday, a day after he shot himself in the head at his grandparents' home in collinsville, the madison county sheriff's department said
i didn't even know the gun was loaded,'' said richie canada, 16, who witnessed the shooting. ``i was so scared when all of this was going on that i couldn't move.'' graves</head>
john cremens isn't ready to leave this world. but when the time comes, he hopes to settle his bones among famous early americans in one of the city's two 300-year-old cemeteries
during the nation's 1976 bicentennial, the 65-year-old trial lawyer commanded the ancient and honorable artillery company, a now-cermonial militia that marks its 350th anniversary june 1
he hopes to make his last stop with john winthrop, the state's first governor; william dawes, who rode with paul revere; the first woman to get off the mayflower, and the woman some say was nathaniel hawthorne's model for hester prynne, who wore the scarlet letter
cremens wants to be buried in the king's chapel burying ground tomb of capt. robert keayne, the militia's first commander. cremens said thursday he belongs there as the bicentennial commander
an ordinance the city council passed last week permits cremens' burial in the tomb or across tremont street in the granary burying ground, where he would join paul revere, john hancock, samuel adams, and, some say, ``mother goose.''
but the cemeteries are full
and some other militia members say it's not clear cremens belongs there
a real militia established to protect colonists, the ancient and honorable lost its orgininal purpose before the civil war. but it was never disbanded and remains the world's third-oldest surviving militia, exceeded by its english counterpart and the papal swiss guards
nowadays, the group mainly raises money for charity
cremens's request is expected to be discussed monday, at the next militia meeting
member bert caldwell said opening keayne's tomb, already jammed with 36 coffins, would undo two years and $7,500 of restoration
you effectively have to make an archaeological dig. i don't know if it's worth it. ... it's best to let sleeping patriots lie.''
although the city's 16 historic cemeteries are full, title holders to underground tombs can open them for more bodies with the city's permission
ellen lipsey, preservation planner for the city parks department, said a new body is buried every 20 years or so
if cremens doesn't get into the keayne tomb, he must find another tomb and get the titleholders to let him in, then get the park department's permission
parks commissioner william coughlin said if the militia is reluctant to open the tomb it's unlikely the department will approve
cremens said that whatever happens, he's pleased for the opportunity to be buried among heroes of the past
it's a great honor. i'm very happy to be there in that great company, to be part of the history of this country and to be remembered in the prayers of people passing by ... i hope it doesn't happen soon.''
jews celebrated the first night of passover and christians carrying crosses marked good friday under heavy military and police guard that was mobilized to prevent violence after four months of arab protests
fewer tourists than usual filled israel's hotels, normally packed to capacity during passover week. tourism officials blamed it on the fear among foreigners, mainly u.s. jews, because of the fatal riots
police commissioner david kraus told israel army radio extra units of officers patrolled cities and holiday sites
in jerusalem's walled old city, hundreds of christian pilgrims carrying crosses and singing psalms traced the route jesus walked to his crucifixion, but the crowd was thinner than usual
an arab attacker stabbed an israeli police lieutenant in the stomach just 20 yards from the processional route. the soldier was in fair condition
the greek orthodox church canceled two pre-easter processions due to security concerns and an expected drop in tourism. western christians celebrate easter on sunday, while orthodox christians observe it this year on april 10
the original good friday occurred during passover, but the holidays don't usually coincide because the two religions use different calendars
friday also was the moslem sabbath, which in recent months has been a catalyst for violent demonstrations
in jewish west jerusalem, few signs of recent tensions were evident as israeli shoppers jammed stores buying flowers and candy to give relatives, a passover tradition. children, on a two-week school holiday, filled the streets eating ice cream and candy
passover, which commemorates the liberation of jews from slavery in egypt, derives its name from the biblical book of exodus. the book recounts that god ``passed over'' the homes of the israelites when meeting out the worst of 10 plagues, killing the first-born of every egyptian
the plagues finally forced the egyptian pharoah to let the jews leave egypt
the story of the exodus is recounted every year in the seder, the traditional holiday meal. participants take turns reading excerpts from the hagadah, a book of stories, rabbinical sayings and lively songs of thanksgiving
symbolic foods are eaten, including bitter herbs to remind jews of the harshness of their enslavement and haroset, a brick-colored mixture of apples, nuts and wine to recall the bricks laid by jewish slaves
but the best-known symbol is matzo, the unleavened bread eaten during passover week. matzo reminds jews that when they departed egypt, they had no time to let their bread rise and so had to take unleavened bread into the desert
in israel, stores are forbidden to sell leavened bread during passover. but many secular jerusalemites circumvent the restrictions and buy pita, the pocket-shaped middle eastern bread, from arab merchants in east jerusalem
the practice was expected to be more difficult this year with virtually every arab merchant there on a partial strike
life returned to the old city on friday when hundreds of christian pilgrims crowded the via dolorosa, or way of sorrow, tracing jesus' steps to his crucifixion. priests carried ornate silver and gold crosses and burned incense
we planned to come here for a long time and nothing could stop us, even friends who said we were crazy,'' said david reid of mountain lakes, n.j. ``there are lots of police around and we are as safe here as we are in new york city.''
the procession ended at the church of the holy sepulchre, built in the 12th century on the site where the faithful believe jesus was crucified, buried and raised from the dead on easter sunday
pilgrims kissed and threw water on the rock marking the spot where jesus' body was washed before burial, while 16 choir boys in black robes sang prayers
arab merchants opened their shops for the three hours permitted by the palestine liberation organization to sell olive-wood crosses, doing brisk business
tourism officials said more visitors came to israel in january and february as compared with the previous year, but 13 percent fewer tourists entered the country during the first week in march
the rev. timoteus margaritis, a spokesman for the greek orthodox christian church, said 1,500 pilgrims were expected to attend his church's april 10 easter service, instead of the usual 10,000
a former banker who went on a spending spree with funds from his thrift after learning he had aids has pleaded guilty to misappropriating more than $1 million
william patrick debenport, 27, said he gave some of the money to gay charities after being told he had acquired immune deficiency syndrome
debenport pleaded guilty thursday to three counts of misappropriation, admitting he illegally used his position as manager of first texas savings and loan's oak cliff branch to misappropriate $1.1 million from it
documents filed with debenport's plea show he established fake accounts, transferring money to them and then removing the funds by writing cashier's checks
he faces up to 15 years in prison and $3,000 in fines at sentencing may 5
his lawyer, steven cooper, said earlier that debenport used most of the money to buy luxuries for himself and gifts for friends, but also donated some to charities, including $175,000 to a dallas home for aids sufferers
an air force fighter-bomber on a high-altitude training mission crashed friday near the west german border, but the pilot ejected safely, the military said
the mirage iii-e long-range fighter-bomber crashed in a field near bar-le-duc after it developed technical problems, military officials said. the pilot aimed the plane at an uninhabited area before ejecting, and there were no injuries reported
jesse jackson the politician often becomes jesse jackson the history teacher these days, taking his presidential campaign to high schools as often as to union halls or churches
from the inner city school in inkster, mich., to pulaski high in the heart of southside milwaukee, the democratic presidential candidate delivers his sermon of self-respect, a drug-free and violence-free life and the need to achieve
i go to four or five high schools a week in the course of every week, because i love our children, because i care, because their lives are at stake,'' jackson told students in inkster, near detroit. ``you are our energy.''
in the high school speeches there is always a political message _ ``come alive, april 5'' was the chant he taught at pulaski, in advance of the wisconsin primary on tuesday
but jackson has other goals as well, for in 1988 he emphasizes the course of the fight for equal rights for a generation that looks at the 1950s and 1960s as ancient history
jackson tells the story of rosa parks, whose refusal to go to the back of the bus in montgomery, ala., sparked demonstrations that pushed dr. martin luther king jr. to prominence in 1955
jackson, a king protege, talks of the role young people played in the civil rights struggle, saying that king was only 26 when the montgomery bus boycott began and that college students led the lunch counter sit-ins in greensboro, n.c. that inaugurated a new tactic in the fight for desegregated public accommodations
in 1960, four student in greemsboro, n.c. sat at a lunch counter to get hamburgers. they got handcuffs,'' jackson said at pulaski high school. ``they were threatened with expulsion from school. they chose dignity over degrees. they kept fighting to make america better.''
some pulaski students may have had family members who had personal experience with the civil rights movement. it is in the heart of southside milwaukee, an all-white neighborhood that was the scene of ugly, sometimes violent confrontations during open housing marches of the 1960s
jackson also talks in sometimes brutal terms of the price that was paid in the civil rights movement, reading down the list of those who were killed in the fight. often his images are harsh, as in his description of one civil rights marcher's death
her brains were blown out at point-blank range by a shotgun,'' he told students at stevenson high school in sterling heights, mich
after recounting how far the nation has come, jackson turns to the problems of today
each generation must face the challenges of its own time,'' he told pulaski students
at inkster, the message was more direct to an audience of about 1,500 mostly black students
after years of struggle, we have obtained equal protection under the law. you have opportunity. when i went to school, we did not have equal opportunity,'' said jackson, who grew up poor in south carolina
obviously opportunity is not enough. ... what does it matter if you have equal opportunity if your players are drunk on the court? what does it matter if you have a new book or an old book if you never open either?''
this theme jackson uses to launch into his crusade against drugs
the no. 1 threat in your lifetime is not lack of opportunity _ it is concession to the no. 1 killer in the country today _ drugs,'' he said at inkster
then jackson repeats a litany to bring home the pervasiveness of the problems he is attacking. he asks how many students know someone who has died from drugs. usually, a scattering stand up
then he asks how many know someone who is in jail because of drugs. more stand. then the question is, how many know someone who uses drugs. in most schools, everyone stands
he repeats the question and response pattern about knowledge of young people who have brought guns to school and knowledge of contemporaries who contemplated suicide. in each case, a remarkable number of students stand
the preacher-turned-politician is quick to issue a reminder that this is not a limited problem
lest you forget, members of the press, whether we are in the heart of rural iowa or in inkster, mich., or seattle, wash., or pasadena, calif., this is the scene all over america every day,'' he said in the detroit suburb. ``so i reach out to young america today to provide positive and creative energy to keep america strong and to make america better.''
a fugitive arrested recently in florida could shed light on the celebrated but still unsolved ``french connection'' drug theft case, a federal prosecutor says
anthony dominick passero, 53, was arrested feb. 10 in florida on an outstanding money laundering indictment filed in new york in 1984 that named one of his many aliases, anthony paris, u.s. attorney andrew maloney said thursday
it was not until tuesday, when authorities received a report on a fingerprint check, that they realized paris was passero
he ``may be the last living guy who could solve the french connection thefts,'' maloney said
passero was identified by maloney as an alleged partner of the late vincent papa, who was suspected of being the mastermind of the theft of $70 million worth of heroin and cocaine from the property clerk's office in city police headquarters from 1968 to 1972
much of the heroin had been seized in the ``french connection'' drug case, the basis for the movie of the same name starring gene hackman and roy scheider
papa, who had alleged ties to the luchese organized crime family, was stabbed to death in 1977 while in an atlanta prison on other drug charges
maloney said no one had ever been arrested for the drug thefts, allegedly committed by a group of police detectives
in addition to the money laundering charges, passero faces charges from a 1975 heroin trafficking indictment. he also was charged in 1975 with perjury and criminal contempt in connection with the investigation into the french connection thefts, authorities said
passero, focus of an internal revenue service investigation for many years, had been living in a $475,000 home at pompano, fla., under the alias of anthony caruso. five irs agent and two pompano police officers arrested passero and his common-law wife, marie barbieri, 45, at their home feb. 10
both waived extradition
both were named in the money laundering indictment, which alleges they laundered about $750,000 from january 1980 to march 1981. passero told authorities he was a retired truck driver and scrap metal dealer, maloney said
a fraternity organized by homosexual men has been approved by the university of california, which last month approved a lesbian sorority
the 11-member delta lambda phi fraternity was recognized thursday
gay people need a lot of support in their college years,'' said senior jason howe, the group's president. ``they are trying to come to grips with growing up, getting through college and getting a career. but they also have to come to grips with their sexuality.''
the fraternity is a spinoff of a washington-based organization trying to form chapters at campuses around the country
we are trying to encourage socializing outside of the bar environment and its negative emphasis on alcohol and drugs,'' said fraternity adviser chris williamson
official recognition means delta lambda phi can use the school's name, meet on campus and apply for student activities funds, said chris fishburn, ucla's director of fraternity and sorority relations
the fraternity cannot discriminate against heterosexuals, if any apply
technicians will be able to repair a minor insulation problem on a booster rocket without delaying the space shuttle flight planned for august, nasa said friday
during an inspection wednesday, workers found four small areas where insulation had separated from the rocket casing on the bottom edge of one of four segments that make up the right solid fuel rocket. the largest was 1.4 inches
there was concern that if the separation extended deeper into the insulation, the segment would have to be replaced, which could cause a launch delay of several weeks
ultrasound devices were used overnight thursday to thoroughly inspect the segment and no additional separation or ``debonding'' was discovered
there was no evidence the debonding extended beyond the edge,'' said nasa spokeswoman lisa malone. ``it can be repaired here with no impact on the schedule.''
malone said similar debondings had been found on other rocket segments in the past and they were repaired here in parallel with other work. severe debonding could lead to the breakup of a rocket in flight and destroy the shuttle
various technical problems have caused two lengthy delays from the original february 1988 launch date. the target date now is aug. 4
the shuttle fleet has been grounded since challenger exploded jan. 28, 1986, killing the seven crew members. that accident was caused by another booster rocket problem _ a faulty joint between segments that allowed flames to escape and ignite the external fuel tank for the main liquid fuel engines
the joint has been redesigned and has successfully passed several test firings
on the first post-challenger mission, discovery is to carry five crew members who will deploy a communications satellite and conduct experiments during a four-day mission
president reagan signed a $48 million aid for nicaraguan contras and war victims friday and then headed to california for a 10-day easter vacation
reagan signed the legislation in his white house residence, forgoing the ceremonial fanfare that attends some bill-signings
only $17.7 million of the $48 million will go to the nicaraguan rebels, and the aid package contains no provision for weapons and ammunition. the bill could be the last of its kind that reagan signs, given the truce agreement the contras signed march 23 in sapoa, nicaragua, with the ruling sandinista regime
the aid package, which also contains $17.7 million to finance rehabilitation and treatment of children injured on both sides of the 7-year-old conflict, was passed overwhelmingly by both the house and senate earlier this week
besides the money for contra rebels and nicaraguan children, roughly $10 million will be sent to a verification commission to monitor compliance with the cease-fire
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters aboard air force one en route to california that the president had said the aid was ``urgently needed, that he wanted to sign it as soon as possible.''
the president also hoped ``the cease-fire talks on april 5 are productive in getting the sandinistas to bring about democratic reforms.''
fitzwater also noted that a united nations investigative team has returned from central america where it looked into the recent fighting along the nicaraguan-honduran border and the temporary deployment some 3,100 u.s. troops in honduras
although the white house has not yet seen the team's report, fitzwater said press reports have said the u.n. panel's findings ``confirm the nicaraguan invasion of honduras, that they have photographic evidence of the fighting, and that the u.s. exercises were a success. if those reports are right, why, we're very gratified and satisfied.''
reagan's signing of the bill was his last major chore before leaving on the 10-day vacation at his beloved rancho del cielo in the santa ynez mountains near santa barbara
reagan's adopted son, michael reagan, accompanied the president aboard air force one, but remained in private quarters aboard the aircraft and did not speak with reporters
the younger reagan's book detailing his early life, including being a victim of child molestation by a camp counselor, was published recently
the president was to be reunited in california with first lady nancy reagan, who flew to los angeles on wednesday. she paid a visit to the $2.5 million, ranch-style mansion the couple plans to lease when reagan's term ends next january
that wasn't the only looking-ahead note to the couple's spring vacation. the president's only appearance in california will be at a fund-raising event monday in newport beach, south of los angeles, for the ronald reagan library. construction on the library is expected to begin this summer at a site in ventura county
fitzwater also said reagan will address the national association of broadcasters meeting april 10 in las vegas, nev. the spokesman indicated the president's general subject would be foreign affairs and the theme before an expected audience of about 4,000 broadcasters would be ``broadcasting and democracy: a winning ticket.''
financial support to the contras has been shut off since feb. 29, and the house twice last month voted down assistance packages
a state department official said it probably will be be at least two weeks before the contras begin receiving supplies under the new legislation because of the time required to gear up for a new delivery effort
approximately $2.5 million of the $48 million aid package will be given to the department's agency for international development, which will administer the aid program
georgia's 93,000 kindergarten pupils begin taking mandatory tests next week that will partially determine whether they will enter first grade in the fall
some parents and educators oppose the tests
last week, the national association for the education of young children and the national association of early childhood specialists in state departments of education issued policy statements opposed to such mass standardized testing of kindergartners
such indiscriminate testing, the groups said, means ``many kindergartens are now highly structured, `watered down' first grades, emphasizing workbooks and other paper-and-pencil activities that are developmentally inappropriate for 5-year-olds.''
georgia is the first state to make such testing mandatory, although individual school districts such as minneapolis have similar programs
georgia education officials say those who are outraged over standardized tests of 5-year-olds to measure their ability to recognize sounds, letters and basic math concepts are making mountains out of molehills
i think it's more important to focus on the entire process, because there's much more to it than testing,'' said sharon meinhardt, coordinator of the georgia department of education's early childhood education program
ms. meinhardt said if a child does not achieve the required score, education officials will use both the test and the recommendation of the child's teacher in deciding whether the child is ready for first grade
there are a lot of scared parents out there _ i've talked to them,'' ms. meinhardt said. ``when i have had a chance to talk to a lot of the parents and tell them we are going to look at more than the test, there's not a parent who left the conversation without saying `i feel better.'''
the testing policy, approved by the state board of education in february, is mandated by the quality basic education act to identify children in need of special help, and students who are held back will be placed in an alternative kindergarten program
but some educators say assurances from state officials will not make them feel better about testing such young children
our state legislators feel that this test will reduce our relatively high first-grade failure rate by weeding out those children who are not yet ready to attend first grade,'' said marilyn b. gootman, assistant professor of elementary education at the university of georgia. ``instead, the test wastes precious learning time and places unnecessary stress on our children.''
we are very supportive of testing and assessing young children, but we are against one 90-minute assessment in a child's kindergarten year to predict readiness,'' said judy jefferson, gwinnett county's coordinator of primary programs and an official of the metro council for early childhood
atlanta child psychologist asa hilliard said the tests have ``a disproportionate impact on those children who need school the most, the minority children.''
stan berknopf, director of the education department's assessment program, said parental distress over testing kindergarteners will not prompt the state to change the law
their anxiety for the most part is probably misplaced,'' berknopf said. ``we expect over 90 percent of the students to do very well.''
ms. meinhardt said education officials recommend that parents treat the test as they would any other school activity and not pressure their children
there should be no great production made of it,'' she said. ``teachers are feeling a considerable amount of pressure, either from their own minds or from other people in their school system. there is no way some of that pressure is not being transferred to the children.''
the department of education's assessment department estimates that about 90 of the state's 186 school systems will begin testing next week, and the rest will start the following week
beginning friday, drug dealers operating in utah must visit the state tax commission and buy an official drug tax stamp created just for them, or else they'll face additional charges when they're arrested
this is not the case of a state agency or the state legislature condoning the use of illicit drugs,'' said tax commission spokesman lee shaw. ``the drug stamp program is actually a law enforcement tool, not a tax commission initiative. the drug stamps are just another means of applying legal pressure in the prosecution of drug dealers.''
when a dealer is arrested, law enforcement officers will check to see if his drugs have the stamp. if they do not, the dealer faces a third-degree felony in addition to any other charges, shaw said
that could prove helpful in punishing dealers who evade a distribution conviction because of some technicality, said the law's sponsor, state sen. ivan matheson
the law stipulates that if stamps are not attached permanently to drug packages, a dealer could be required to pay the full cost of the tax plus a fine of not more than $10,000
the stamps cost $3.50 for each gram, or portion of a gram, of marijuana; $200 for each gram of a controlled substance sold by weight; and $2,000 for each 50 ``dosage units,'' such as pills, of a controlled substance not sold by weight
i cannot see a major drug dealer going in there to buy a stamp,'' said attorney gilbert d. athay, who has defended a number of alleged drug dealers
but that doesn't mean there won't be a market for the stamps
stamp collectors will buy them. they'll probably be the only people in town who will own them,'' athay said
anyone can buy the stamps. purchasers do not have to identify themselves, shaw said, but must pay with cash or a cashier's check
the tax commission ordered 4,000 stamps from the state printing office
all three stamps are plain. the marijuana stamp doesn't have a picture of a leaf, just the title ``marijuana'' at the top, and several lines printed over the state seal where commission employees can fill in the quantity and their initials
the rev. brice riordan sensed a bargain in the air one day recently while he prepared to celebrate mass
dear friends, it's encouraging to see such a great number of you,'' riordan said, looking out over his congregation. ``there must be a sale at stern's or something.''
the 18-yea-old carmelite chapel in the bergen mall is one of the few in the country to be located in a shopping center. it is billed as the chapel on the mall, devoted to st. therese
the rev. ferdinand schaefer, the chapel's pastor, said the idea for a place to worship amid the materialism of a mall comes from the age-old directive to ``get christ in the marketplace.''
you have to go where the people are, and the people are in the malls,'' schaefer said
the chapel is run by four priests of the carmelite order of the roman catholic church, which helped set up the first known mall chapel more than 25 years ago in peabody, mass
the reason the bergen mall was chosen for a chapel site was a link to the peabody chapel _ allied stores, which in 1970 owned both shopping malls, schaefer said
attendance was poor in the early years but it has gained steadily, and today, especially during lent and on saturdays, it is standing room only in the 150-seat chapel, schaefer said
year round, the chapel attracts about 200 people a day for three masses daily on weekdays and four on saturday, he said. the chapel doesn't offer sunday masses, because the mall is closed
schaefer and steady chapelgoers credit the solid turnout to convenience and the strong sermons of the four carmelite priests
we just love these priests,'' said kathleen tappen of maywood
mrs. tappen and her husband, frank, have been chapel worshipers for eight years
it's like a family,'' added marge wohlrab of rochelle park, a 10-year chapel-goer. ``each (priest) gives a different perspective. we always get another reason for carrying on.''
the priests, ranging in age from 66 to 71 years old, have drawn their wisdom from experience, said schaefer
these guys have 40 to 45 years of priesthood behind them,'' schaefer said. ``they have sort of mellowed. they are not out to do anything except minister the sacraments and be kind to people. that makes a difference.''
the chapel is a no-frills religious experience. there are no baptisms, funerals or weddings. priests hear confessions, celebrate daily mass and provide counseling when needed
schaefer believes its success will continue as long as there are shoppers
you see an awful lot of people going by and stopping and looking and they are amazed,'' schaefer said. ``then, what do you know, another day or two and they will be in.''
the stanford university faculty has voted to replace a western culture requirement, branded racist by black students, with one that includes the study of women and minorities
we're fighting against the white male estabishment that's been here for years,'' said david brown, a member of students united for democratic education
the change is a substantial improvement,'' university president donald kennedy said when the faculty senate voted 39-4 for the change thursday
we feel philosophically that the vote in favor of this was a vote in favor of moving forward and progression,'' black student union chairman bill king said. ``they voted for moving toward ethnic studies, not teaching freshmen lies.''
u.s. secretary of education william bennett charged earlier this year that stanford was bowing to ``curriculum by intimidation,'' and that higher education in general was losing credibility because courses on the classics are being displaced. he is scheduled to speak at stanford on april 18
beginning next fall, freshmen will take classes on ``cultures, ideas and values,'' replacing the western culture program, dubbed racist two years ago by the black student union
students will still be required to study the likes of homer, plato and shakespeare but they also will be exposed to works from at least one non-european culture each quarter
according to a draft of the new course, its objective is to ``provide students with the common intellectual experience of broadening their understanding of ideas and values drawn from different strands of our own culture, and to increase their understanding of cultural diversity and the process of cultural interaction.''
american corporations that owe taxes to panama will be allowed the u.s. foreign tax credit if payments are made to the government of ousted president eric arturo delvalle, the internal revenue service said friday
the announcement was aimed at discouraging u.s. businesses from sending tax payments to the panamanian government controlled by military strongman manuel antonio noriega, which washington does not recognize
some large u.s.-based multinational firms recently made quarterly tax payments just in time to give that government a desperately needed infusion of cash
the foreign tax credit is designed to prevent two national governments from taxing the same dollar of income. in general, the united states will not tax income that an american corporation earns in and pays taxes on to a foreign country
the irs announcement is the latest move in the u.s. effort to squeeze noriega, who has been indicted in the united states on drug-trafficking charges
delvalle, who is in hiding, has directed that all tax payments due his country be paid through the panamanian embassy in washington into a special account at the federal reserve bank of new york
this notice confirms that income taxes due to the government of panama which are paid into such account will be considered paid to the government of panama, and will therefore be creditable foreign taxes if all other requirements'' of the law are met, an irs statement said
the white house, in declaring thursday that such an announcement would be forthcoming, cautioned that u.s. businesses might expect some sanctions if they continue turning over money to noriega
a spokesman for eastern airlines said the company had recently paid the noriega government $178,000 in monthly rentals and landing fees
texaco, inc., routinely paid income, sales and excise taxes for march, said spokesman peter maneri, and sees no conflict with the position of the u.s. government
we do not become involved in any political activity in a host nation; we're just doing business down there,'' maneri said. update with fitzwater quote.</note>
president reagan today signed a $48 million aid package for nicaragua's contras, but it probably will be at least two weeks before the rebels begin receiving supplies under the new legislation
the senate on thursday gave lopsided approval to the bill, sending it to the president on a vote of 87-7. the house had approved the measure 345-70 a day earlier
reagan signed the bill with no fanfare in his residence before departing for a flight to california and a 10-day vacation. the signing was announced in a one-sentence white house statement, which was accompanied by a brief executive order delegating responsibilities to various agencies to carry out provisions of the law
there certainly is an urgent need among the resistance for medical supplies, food, clothing, the basic commodities of life,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said. ``this bill is very welcome in that regard and we support it.''
fitzwater said the president ``just indicated that it's urgently needed ... and that he hopes the cease-fire talks on april 5 are productive in getting the sandinistas to bring about democratic reforms.''
the contras have been shut off from u.s. aid since feb. 29
the state department official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he ``would be very surprised if any aid is delivered within the next two weeks'' because of the time required by the bureaucracy to gear up for a new delivery effort
but the official said even with the delay, delivery will begin more quickly than normal because some of the responsibility for moving supplies will be given to the department's office of foreign disaster assistance, which has experience with such programs
the aid aims at sustaining the rebels as a fighting force while they wait in cease-fire zones for their political leaders and the sandinista government to work out a long-term settlement to their nearly seven-year civil war
aid to the rebels under the bill would total $17.7 over the next six months, including $1.5 million for communications gear if such equipment is deemed to be in accord with a march 23 cease-fire accord between the two sides
another $17.7 million would be spent on a new program of medical and rehabilitation help for war-injured children on both sides of the conflict. the bill offers $10 million to a verification commission that will monitor compliance with the cease-fire, and $2.5 million to pay the state department's agency for international development to administer the aid
the overwhelming and relatively quiet approval of the bill in both houses of congress was an abrupt change in the tenor of a u.s. debate that began with the civil war seven years ago. votes on nicaragua policy have typically been decided by thin margins and with sharp and partisan argument
congress had rejected similar aid packages twice earlier this year, but the march 23 truce reached in sapoa, nicaragua, changed the political climate in congress
one can always hope we may have learned this partisanship is unhealthy,'' said sen. john mccain, r-ariz., after thursday's vote
but let's have no illusions,'' he added. ``future events (in central america) will dictate whether there's maintenance of this bipartisanship.''
sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., noted that the aid bill fell short of the desires of contra supporters, who would have preferred to send weapons to the rebels, and also bothered rebel opponents who oppose sending any aid
this package strikes a balance, and is for the sole purpose of supporting that agreement in sapoa,'' dodd said during a harmonious floor debate on the measure. ``if not for that agreement, we wouldn't be doing this today.''
a contra proponent, sen. david boren, d-okla., said the action would ``send a strong signal that the contras are not being abandoned.''
but boren also said the failure of congress to agree on military support for the rebels would prove to be ``one of the gravest mistakes in american foreign policy ever made.''
the seven senators who voted against the aid package were sens. brock adams, d-wash.; alan cranston, d-calif.; mark hatfield, r-ore.; spark matsunaga, d-hawaii; john melcher, d-mont.; william proxmire, d-wis.; and robert stafford, r-vt
not voting were sens. joseph biden, d-del.; albert gore, d-tenn.; edward m. kennedy, d-mass.; john kerry, d-mass.; warren rudman, r-n.h. and paul simon, d-ill
law enforcement agencies in florida seized more than $4.5 million in property and cash from suspected criminals in the last three months of 1987, according to a state report
state law lets police seize property when authorities believe it was used in a felony. the law has sparked criticism because some agencies confiscate property without making an arrest
while they must return the property to innocent owners, authorities often charge fees to do so. legislation is expected this session to prohibit the fees
metro-dade police seized $1.04 million in cash and $34,000 in property _ mainly older cars _ and earned $55,000 in interest
this is home base on the u.s. side to the major traffickers ... people who will have bags and boxes of money,'' said george aylesworth, commander of the metro-dade legal unit. ``we just bump into them most often.''
a surgeon who died of aids may have contracted the disease while performing surgery in africa and didn't know he had been infected until six days before his death, his superior said friday
the doctor, david collings, performed 338 operations in britain after returning last year from five years in his native zimbabwe. health officials are trying to find the patients to offer them counseling and, if necessary, a free blood test. officials are warning them not to panic
collings, 30, thought he had a bad dose of flu when he became ill on march 16, but his condition dramatically worsened. a blood test on march 21 showed he had aids, and he died six days later at royal devon and exeter hospital in exeter
he just shrugged his shoulders and said, `that is one of the risks of doing surgery in africa,''' said his superior, consultant surgeon bruce campbell
collings, who was trained in edinburgh, scotland, was married and had an 18-month-old child. he worked in mpilo and marondera, zimbabwe, for five years before returning to britain last year, the exeter health authority said
he worked at the alexandra hospital at redditch for a few months before starting a one-year contract in exeter on july 1
collings mainly operated on patients suffering from complaints such as appendicitis, hernias or varicose veins
a list of his patients was drawn up and general practitioners will contact them in the coming days
the officials stressed that they were being contacted to give them reassurance, not because they believe there is any real risk of infection
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a fatal disease that breaks down the body's natural defenses against disease. there is no known cure
construction spending fell for a third consecutive month in february, a 0.3 percent decline which reflected weakness in the housing sector, the government reported friday
the commerce department said that construction spending declined to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $391.5 billion in february following a 2.8 percent drop in january. in addition, the department revised the december figure to show a small decline of $100 million instead of a 0.4 percent increase
the february decline pushed construction spending 2.5 percent below where it was a year earlier. analysts are forecasting further cutbacks in 1988 because of high vacancy rates in apartments and office buildings
michael sumichrast, an economist and editor of a construction newsletter, said that he was predicting a 7 percent decline in private non-residential construction this year following a drop of 8.1 percent in 1987
much of the strength in the past few years was in over-building driven by tax breaks rather than building for the existing market,'' he said. ``as a result, we don't have much strength anywhere.''
residential construction fell by 1.1 percent in february to an annual rate of $188.1 billion. this included declines of 1 percent in construction of single-family homes and a drop of 4.3 percent in construction of multi-family units
non-residential construction posted a 1.2 percent increase to an annual rate of $92 billion. the biggest source of strength came from an 18.8 percent surge in hospital construction which offset drops in office, hotel and shopping center construction
sumichrast said that construction of hospitals and private schools would show increases this year although both sectors represent only a small fraction of the total industry
public construction edged up 0.4 percent in february to an annual rate of $74.7 billion with the biggest category, highway building, posting a 0.4 percent increase
an ap correspondent entered ramallah hours before the israeli army set up roadblocks tuesday and left friday morning, after the curfew was lifted. here is his report:
please! please! a kilo of bread!'' shouted women outside a bakery off ramallah's main square
the flustered bakery owner held out empty hands. ``that's all! i can't sell anymore!'' the stocky man shouted back, locking his shop door to obey the demands of gun-toting israeli soldiers who had confiscated his identity papers
the shop shutters that crashed shut at gunpoint throughout ramallah on tuesday began three days of what residents called a siege by israeli troops determined to crush a 4-month-old arab uprising
but palestinians are hoarding food and launching a grassroots campaign to endure tougher measures some say they expect to come
israeli troops closed off the occupied territories for three days this week, hoping to prevent massive demonstrations on wednesday, a palestinian commemoration of efforts to fight israeli land confiscations. the military ordered all 650,000 arabs in the gaza strip to stay in their homes for three days, and severed telephone links
on the west bank, israel blocked the 850,000 arabs from leaving their towns
journalists were forbidden to enter or travel without military escorts. an associated press reporter entered ramallah, eight miles north of jerusalem, hours before the army set up roadblocks, and he left friday morning, after the curfew was lifted
on the first day, troops in riot gear moved through the hilly streets of ramallah and neighboring el bireh, forcing shops to close. it was punishment for the merchants' nearly universal acceptance of a palestine liberation organization demand they open in mornings and close in afternoons
the shutdowns left the twin cities, home to about 55,000 palestinians, still. men unable to reach jobs hoed their gardens. women chatted while shelling almonds in front of their limestone houses
shrieking children scampered around vacant lots kicking soccer balls or hurling rocks at one another. it was a game they called ``jews and arabs.''
if i see the soldiers, i run,'' said a pushcart vender named bassam, who glanced nervously up a street near ramallah's main business district while cutting off bananas for customers
the conflicting demands of israel and underground arab leaders have imposed similar, longer closures in bethlehem, nablus, jericho and jenin
abded hamouri, co-owner of a fleet of commuter buses, said the israelis ``are talking to the people who do not have the solution in their hands. the solution is not in the hands of the people who own shops.''
i'm not afraid of the military governor. i'm afraid of the guy i don't know who he is or what he is going to do,'' he said, referring to masked young men who tell shopowners when to open or close
israel has tried to mop up those youths since december by arresting more than 4,000 arabs, by government count. palestinian lawyers insist the toll is much higher
yet protests continue, and walls throughout the town carry spray-painted slogans: ``long live the uprising!'' ``up with the plo!''
arabs said jewish settlers were responsible for a grim reply stenciled on a few walls: a hand holding a club over a broken bone, reference to israel's use of beatings to quell disturbances
the three-day closure was israel's broadest effort yet to stifle protests against military occupation. but most palestinians interviewed in ramallah's streets said it was little worse than existing restrictions
to the boys here, it doesn't matter,'' said a young man named suleiman, trying to evade the soldiers who had imposed a curfew on the crowded el amiri refugee camp. he said most young men sleep outside the camp to escape the army's midnight raids
israel earlier severed international telephone connections to the west bank and gaza, blocked deliveries of gasoline and fuel oil to arab dealers, and imposed a tight limit on the west bank's crucial foreign currency imports
it now demands proof of tax payment to obtain a driver's license or exit visa
despite the scramble for bread, arabs throughout the area insisted they were ready for tougher israeli pressure
reporters saw huge bags of flour and stacks of powdered milk cans in two houses. many people said they had stockpiled essentials
we are ready for anything,'' said ramallah chamber of commerce president khader kasis. ``we can exist just on bread and zatar,'' he added, referring to a popular green spice
an el bireh shopowner who spoke on condition he not be identified said his neighborhood this week formed a self-reliance committee
he pointed out vacant land the group planned to fill with crops, and said it had arranged for merchants to sell goods when stores are closed
i think that's happening a lot, especially for security and self-sufficiency,'' said attorney raja shehadeh, a human rights activist. ``people are experiencing a siege.''
authorities have recovered 39 bodies from an avalanche that buried a northern mountain village earlier this week, it was reported friday
another 11 people were still missing in the arundu village high in the remote korakoram mountain range, according to the government-run news agency, the associated press of pakistan
seven people were rescued after the snow slide destroyed the village, the agency said. 12th graf pvs, the saudi deployment.</note>
the united states ambassador to saudi arabia, hume horan, is leaving his post after only six months because of a personality conflict with king fahd, a state department official said today
horan is expected to be replaced by career diplomat walter cutler, a former ambassador to saudi arabia who was succeeded by horan last september, the official said
the official, who asked not to be identified, denied a published report that horan was being withdrawn at saudi request and that his recall was related to u.s. complaints over the saudi purchase of chinese missiles
state department deputy spokeswoman phyllis oakley confirmed that horan was being reassigned but she gave no further details
meanwhile, a group of 32 senators urged the administration in a letter to pressure the saudis to withdraw the missiles
the letter from the senators says the administration should reconsider a $450 million support package of training and maintenance for awacs radar surveillance planes. the administration has not yet asked officially for congressional approval of the package
we strongly believe that our current policy toward arms sales to saudi arabia must be re-examined,'' the letter said
the saudi deployment of the css-2 intermediate-range missiles came to light two weeks ago in news reports and was confirmed by the state department, which said the rockets are not yet operational
shultz will be meeting with saudi leaders in riyadh next week during his shuttle mission to the mideast. he will be lobbying for israeli-arab peace talks, but also is expected to bring up the chinese missiles
shultz already expressed u.s. concern about the sale of the missiles, which have a range of 1,850 miles, when he met in washington earlier this month with chinese foreign minister wu xueqian
saudi arabia, an ally of iraq, says it needed the missiles to protect itself in case of a further escalation in the iran-iraq war, especially in view of iranian threats
but u.s. officials say the saudis bought the missiles in frustration over repeated attempts by congress to block american arms sales
the kingdom began negotiating the deal with the chinese in 1985, after congress blocked the sale of 48 f-15 jet fighters to saudi arabia. congress late last year agreed to sell the saudis 24 f-15s in order to maintain saudi air strength at its current levels
the css-2 rockets also have a nuclear capability, but both china and saudi arabia have assured the united states they do not intend to arm the rockets with nuclear warheads
in another letter, sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., called for a hearing by the senate foreign relations committee to discuss the implications of the new saudi missiles and the reported failure by u.s. intelligence to detect the purchase from china for some two years
we are also deeply concerned that the saudis hid the fact that they possess these weapons,'' the letter said. residues</head>
a national consumer group has lent support to an agriculture department plan for requiring the identification of hogs so that illegally high traces of drugs in their meat can be traced back to the farm
ellen haas, executive director of public voice for food and health policy, said in comments filed with usda this week that the proposal is in the best interests of consumers
improved methods to control and monitor dangerous chemical residues in the swine supply are sorely needed, and this measure will help meet this demand,'' she said
the proposal was announced a month ago as part of a program to strengthen usda's inspection and monitoring of pork for illegally high traces of drugs, particularly sulfamethazine used to treat or prevent swine disease. the drug also has been used as a feed additive for many years in subtherapeutic doses to boost weight gains
a stricter monitoring program already has been put into effect, and the identification proposal is said by usda officials to be on a fast track for approval
the proposed rule would require all swine in interstate commerce to be individually identified by a tag or other approved means, and producers would have to maintain appropriate identification records on each animal for two years
ms. haas cited usda records for 1987 showing that levels of sulfonamides as a group _ which include sulfamethazine _ exceeded food and drug administration maximum levels in 4 percent of the total samples
but in certain states, the problem was dramatically worse: in north carolina, the violation rate was 10.2 percent; in alabama, 8 percent; and in georgia, 7.8 percent,'' she said
according to usda figures cited by ms. haas, violative percentage rates for sulfonamide residues in pork tested in 1987, included these states of origin:
illinois, 4.8; indiana, 6.7; iowa, 2.2; michigan, 3.9; minnesota, 2.1; nebraska, 6.7; ohio, 7.5; and wisconsin, 3.3
virginia, none; and all others (not specified), 2
alabama, 8; florida, none; georgia, 7.8; kentucky, 6.3; mississippi, 2.9; north carolina, 10.2; south carolina, none; and tennessee, 6.9
south dakota, 2.4; and all others (not specified), none
kansas, none; missouri, 4.4; oklahoma, none; texas, none; and all others (not specified), none
hume horan, the u.s. ambassador to saudi arabia, is being reassigned after only six months on the job because of personality differences with king fahd, a state department official said friday
horan is expected to be succeeded by the man he replaced last september, career diplomat walter cutler, the official said
horan, who is fluent in arabic, has been in washington on consultations and will return to saudi arabia shortly for a brief stay to tend to personal matters, according to the official, insisting on anonymity
state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley confirmed that horan is being reassigned but provided no further details except to say that he is being considered for a new post
secretary of state george p. shultz will stop in saudi arabia next week as part of his effort to win acceptance for his middle east peace proposal
both saudi and american officials denied a washington post report that the saudi government had asked that horan be replaced. a u.s. official also denied that horan's reassignment was related to a u.s.-saudi dispute over that country's acquisition of missiles from china
horan had a ``personality conflict'' with king fahd, the official said. ``the decision to recall him was made here, not in saudi arabia. they did not specifically ask us to withdraw him,'' he said
this is the second abrupt departure by an american ambassador to saudi arabia during the reagan administration
former ambassador robert g. neumann was forced out in 1981 by secretary of state alexander m. haig after only two months on the job
cutler, since leaving riyadh last year, has served as diplomat-in-residence at georgetown university here
saudi arabia's purchase of chinese missiles, which have a range of more than 1,000 miles, has been a contentious issue in u.s.-saudi relations
israel is within easy reach of the missiles, which are capable of carrying nuclear warheads. the saudis have said the missiles won't be fitted with such warheads
a group of 32 senators has written a letter to shultz asking that the united states reconsider further arms sales to saudi arabia until the missiles are withdrawn. the administration has been expected notify congress shortly that it intends to sell $450 million worth of support equipment for surveillance aircraft the saudis acquired recently. killed</head>
israel reopened the occupied territories friday at the start of a holy weekend for christians and jews, and soldiers killed two arabs and wounded 13 others hurling firebombs after moslem prayers in the west bank, the army said
a palestinian emerged from a mosque and stabbed a jerusalem policeman in the stomach as he stood guard near the route where good friday pilgrims traced the steps of christ as he carried his cross
police and soldiers were out in force to guard christians as they remembered christ's death and jews celebrated the start of the week-long passover festival
hundreds of pilgrims carried wooden crosses along the via dolorosa _ the route jesus walked to his crucifixion _ in the walled old city, but the crowd was smaller than usual. the greek orthodox church canceled three processions planned before its observance of easter on april 10
an israeli police lieutenant was stabbed in the stomach about 20 yards from the good friday procession, apparently by a worshiper emerging from prayers at the sacred al aqsa mosque. the policeman was reported in fair condition, and a palestinian was arrested
the government lifted an order under which the occupied lands were sealed off for three days, and it ended a round-the-clock curfew in gaza
in addition to the two deaths reported friday, a third palestinian died overnight of a gunshot wound to the head inflicted wednesday. the arab death toll stands at 127 since violence began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, according to u.n. figures, and an israeli soldier also has been killed
army and arab reports differed on what happened in the confrontation between soldiers and palestinians at idna, a village seven miles west of hebron in the west bank
officials at hebron's alia hospital and arab journalists said soldiers stormed the village mosque to subdue palestinians hurling rocks and bottles after prayers
they said jamal tamizi, 20, died after being hit in the head with a tear gas canister and five bullets struck ishak nimr salameh, 18, in the chest and head. the reports said 25 people were wounded
according to the army, soldiers opened fire when they were surrounded by dozens of arab rioters, some flinging bottles filled with flaming gasoline
last week, defense minister yitzhak rabin authorized troops to fire on arabs who throw firebombs
in jerusalem, officials at mukassad hospital said an arab youth from the old city's moslem quarter was wounded in the leg
hundreds of arabs have been wounded since riots began among the 1.5 million palestinians of the west bank and gaza, which israel has occupied since capturing them from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
israel radio said 40 soldiers have been injured, including one who is paralyzed and another in a coma
about 35 women, many of them elderly, emerged from the nasr mosque in the west bank town of el bireh on friday shaking their fists and chanting: ``by our blood and spirit we will redeem palestine!'' soldiers fired tear gas to disperse them
in ramallah, stores and the central vegetable market opened for the first time since the territories were shut down monday night. during the three days, soldiers forced shopkeepers to close during the only hours plo leaflets said they could open
abed hamouri said israeli economic measures, intended to turn middle-class palestinians against the rebellion, had no impact on underground activists. he is co-owner of 24 commuter buses
the solution is not in the hands of the people who own shops,'' hamouri said. ``i'm not afraid of the military governor. i'm afraid of the underground leaders i don't know.''
his reference was to masked men who order shopowners when to open or close and threaten those who do not comply
shmuel goren, government adviser on the occupied territories, contended that israel's methods were working
we have to divide the population,'' he said on israel radio. ``we see a great number of people who certainly feel tired and want very much to stop these things.''
in the gaza strip, the army reimposed 24-hour curfews on the nusseirat and beach refugee camps and on the villages abassan, beit hanoun and bani suheila. a five-hour nightly curfew was restored in the rest of the 6-mile-long coastal strip
army spokesmen said 300 palestinians were arrested while gaza was closed. with number of missiles fired.</note>
ten thousand iranians shook their fists while chanting of death to iraq and the ``great satan'' america at friday prayers, glancing nervously skyward now and then for the vapor trails of incoming missiles
a western diplomat described the weekly ritual at tehran university, where unarmed students defied the imperial army when the late shah mohammad reza pahlavi was deposed in february 1979, as ``the beating heart of the islamic revolution.''
iraq said it would stop firing missiles into tehran and other iranian cities during a three-day visit to baghdad of the turkish prime minister, turgut ozal, beginning at midnight thursday
iran said it launched seven rockets friday into kirkuk, the oil center in northern iraq, and the southern port of basra, but did not report firing any at the iraqi capital. the last report of a missile explosion in baghdad was march 27
turkey maintains good relations with both iran and iraq, which have been at war since september 1980, and has tried to act as mediator
despite the apparent lull in the month-long ``war of the cities,'' in which hundreds of civilians have been killed on both sides, no one in tehran was taking anything for granted on this moslem sabbath
two long-range iraqi missiles landed in the capital during friday prayers in mid-march
we saw the vapor trails, but nobody at the prayers moved,'' said a translator from the islamic guidance ministry who accompanied visiting western correspondents to the university. ``everyone stayed seated when the missiles exploded some distance away.''
weekly prayers on the campus and elsewhere in iran, to western eyes a cross between a revival meeting and political rally, are the main platforms for mobilizing mass opinion and stoking fervor for the war
shiite moslem fundamentalists beat their chests with fists in unison, chant slogans and listen to leaders exhort them to victory, condemn the ``great satan'' america and preach ayatollah ruhollah khomeini's revolution
hashemi rafsanjani, the parliament speaker, is a regular prayer leader at the university but this week it was president ali khamenei
he urged iranians to vote in parliamentary elections april 8 ``even if there are missiles and bombs falling,'' echoing remarks the revolutionary partriarch had made the day before
khamenei praised the current thrust by revolutionary guards into northeastern iraq and said western media had not given enough coverage to alleged chemical warfare in the region
iran claims the iraqis dropped chemical bombs march 16-17 on three kurdish towns in iraq that had been captured by iranian troops, killing 5,000 civilians and wounding an equal number
at prayers, the pattern is the same each week: calls for sacrifice interrupted by such chants from the crowd of ``war, war, until victory!'' and ``death to america!''
death to russia!'' has joined the lexicon since missiles began demolishing homes, schools and hospitals feb. 29. iraq is believed to be using soviet-designed scud-b missiles fitted with boosters so they can reach tehran, which is nearly 300 miles from the border
among the estimated 10,000 people at the campus prayer meeting were about 60 iraqi prisoners of war iranian officials said had volunteered to fight on iran's side
they squatted in an enclosure in front of the covered podium, which bore photographs of khomeini and other religious leaders. all wore white t-shirts emblazoned with the image of imam bakr sadr, a shiite cleric executed by iraq as a subversive in 1980
the imam was a cousin of mohammad bakr al-hakim, leader of the supreme islamic revolutionary council of iraq, a group of dissident iraqi factions supported by iran
another enclosure held men wounded in the war _ without limbs, in wheelchairs _ not far from ranks of teen-aged volunteers for the front wearing red headbands with islamic slogans
security was tight and foreign correspondents were frisked twice before being allowed onto the campus from the surrounding streets, where thousands more people had gathered to hear the sermons through loudspeakers
a bomb exploded on the campus two weeks ago, but no casualty report was given
iranian women, shrouded in the black head-to-toe robes called chadors, were not allowed onto the campus because strict islamic law requires them to be segregated. they sat in an enclosure some distance away
outside the campus, cartoon-like posters explained what to do in case of an iraqi poison gas attack
beside the entrance was a transparent plastic ``war fund'' box into which worshipers stuffed banknotes. officials said one slipped in a check for 400,000 rials, about $5,600. graf pvs, ``an officer...''</note>
sikh gunmen stormed into huts and houses across punjab state on friday and killed 37 people, including seven children, in the bloodiest one-day murder spree this year, police and witnesses said
police in amritsar imposed a night curfew in parts of the region. in new delhi, prime minister rajiv gandhi met government officials and ordered stringent steps to check sikh violence, united news of india reported
gandhi also ordered new police alerts in five states that adjoin punjab
in amritsar, two hindu organizations called for a daylong strike in the district on saturday to protest the killings, uni said. most of the victims were hindus
the attacks began thursday night, hours after an umbrella organization heading the sikh separatist movement called for a halt to the killings of moderate sikhs
the worst attack occured at a hamlet near pangota, 25 miles north of amritsar. twelve gunmen raided the mud huts of a hindu laborer commune and murdered 18 people, said s.s. virk, deputy inspector general of the paramilitary central reserve police force
i heard the killers ordering us to get out of our huts, i hid myself ... and moments later i heard sound of gunfire and screams,'' said tara singh, 45
fifteen people were lined up and shot, and a 23-year-old pregnant woman, a 6-month-old baby girl and an 80-year-old woman were shot and killed in their hut when the killers saw they could not walk, virk said
he said all the victims were related
at shaeed village, six miles west of pangota, another group of militants shot and killed six people, virk said. the victims, all hindus, included a 2-year-old boy. the assailants broke into the homes and shot the victims in their beds
the killers murdered a sikh couple in nearby verowal town after leaving shaeed, the officer said
uni said suspected sikh radicals shot and killed two people in gurdaspur district friday
an officer at the state police control in chandigarh said elsewhere in punjab, nine other people were killed by suspected sikhs late thursday and early friday
an underground organization formed to achieve an independent sikh nation called on militant groups to cease random killings of moderate sikhs
at least 330 of the 618 people killed this year in sikh attacks have been moderates who do not support the militants' demand for an independent homeland in sikh-dominated punjab
sikhs are a religous minority in india, comprising only 2 percent of the total population, and claim they are discriminated against by hindus. militants hae been fighting for a sikh state since 1983
the council of khalistan issued the statement from amritsar's golden temple, the holiest sikh shrine and the center of militant activity. khalistan is the name the militants give to their envisioned homeland
the attacks brought the number of people killed in random attacks this week to more than 80. most of the killings have been near amritsar
the spurt in violence is blamed on differences within militant groups and an attempt to sabotage government moves to reach an accord with the militants
the government last month released 12 sikh leaders jailed for sedition and dissolved the punjab state assembly in what was seen as an attempt to enroll the militants in politics
but sources in the golden temple, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said some militants opposed the plan since it would not give the sikhs total autonomy
punjab gov. s.s. ray said in a recent interview, ``i have seen that whenever a good thing is proposed to be done about punjab ... anti-national terrorists indulge in an orgy of violence thereby trying to prevent anything from being done.'' 3 grafs to update with identity of new owner.</note>
after 24 years as the disc jockey, technician and owner of wvca-fm, simon geller has sold his one-man radio station for $1 million, saying that at age 68 he's ready for a new life
when in a few months he hangs up the earphones for the last time in his two-room apartment-studio, geller plans to walk away from this sleepy fishing community 25 miles north of boston. then he'll finally pop the question to his sweetheart of 32 years
i've had 46 years in this miserable business and it's time to get out,'' he said, when asked about his decision
his 3,000-watt classical music radio station has been on the air every day, except when he shut down to run errands
it's an institution built on the single-minded dedication of a man who won an 11-year battle against the federal communications commission and a powerful business group bent on takeover
it's also a focal point of 90,000 loyal listeners in a 35-mile radius extending into boston and new hampshire, who have contributed more than 90 percent of the money geller needed since wvca-fm went on the air in 1964 as the voice of cape ann
it took a bit of probing before geller, a diabetic with high-blood pressure, talked about his decision to sell
an insulin reaction in 1986 caused him to fall while walking from one room to another in his apartment. he remained conscious, but it took friends five hours to find and help him, while a long-playing tape was unwinding on air
i'm 68 years old, and i don't know how much longer i'll live, so i want to get things straightened out in case i should drop dead next week,'' he said. ``the life expectancy is only 70 in this country.''
also taking its toll is mental fatigue from his battle for license renewal
the challenge was mounted in 1964 by grandbanke corp., a group of new england station owners that wanted to take over his frequency for a folk rock station
while only a few local businesses advertise on wvca-fm, its listening area is considered lucrative. grandbanke argued that the station's format violated fcc requirements that community interest, news and public affairs be a part of programming
an fcc decision against geller was reconsidered in 1984 on orders of a federal appeals court, which pointed out that the station had the support of gloucester community leaders and listeners. his license was renewed a year later
my license was safe until 1991, but i was afraid someone would challenge me in 1991 and i would be in the same mess i was with grandbanke,'' geller said
geller's two cluttered rooms above a coin laundry are crowded with a mixture of antiquated and new equipment, with a maze of extension cords competing for space with unopened mail and cardboard boxes. order is imposed by neat rows of records and tapes on shelves lining the walls
while he said new owner doug tanger, a boston businessman, will likely expand operations, geller declined to discuss details of the sale beyond disclosing that an application was filed with the fcc this week
he said it will probably take three months for the fcc to approve tanger's application, allowing him to take over and allowing geller to walk out the door
tanger owns stations wclz-am and -fm in portland, maine, and with his family has wqrs-fm in detroit
geller said a promise that the station will remain classical permits him to look forward to the future with carol hill
he has publicly talked about proposing to his former bookkeeper for years. but he remains coy about a date
i haven't discussed this with her and until i'm clear here i cannot discuss it,'' he said. ``let's wait until fcc approval.''
georgia, alabama and south carolina are facing their fourth serious drought in eight years, experts said friday
if we don't get a dramatic increase in rainfall, we'll be looking at water restrictions this summer,'' said david word, chief of water resource management for the georgia department of natural resources
lake lanier in north georgia and lakes hartwell and thurmond on the georgia-south carolina border are at lower levels than they were at this point in the drought years of 1981, 1986 and 1987, officials told reporters friday in atlanta
likely effects of the drought include timber loss, reduced water quality, stress on fish and ``water restrictions, if this continues through the summer,'' said pat davis, chief of the technical engineering branch for the u.s. army corps of engineers' mobile district
we're in the third (consecutive) year of greatly reduced rainfall,'' davis said. ``it's been persistently below normal through the decade.''
for the 1980s, much of the area is 12 percent below normal rainfall _ the equivalent of an entire year without rain, he said. some parts of georgia are 70 inches below normal for the decade
the area remains under a ``water shortage alert'' issued by the corps last fall, and that could become a ``drought alert'' later this month, officials said
lake lanier, which supplies water to metro atlanta and is the most visited lake in the corps of engineers system, stood friday at nine feet below its normal level
we have only about a 10 percent chance to fill the lake by june 1,'' said ed burkett, chief of water management for the corps' mobile district. corps officials in november reduced the amount of water flowing from lanier downstream into the chattahoochee river, in an attempt to conserve water in the lake
despite a forecast for above-average rain for april to june, burkett said, the customary summer and fall drops in lake levels would likely leave area lakes below normal levels
the united states announced friday that beginning july 1 it will eliminate duty-free imports on products worth $1.1 billion in 1987, shipped here from 140 third world countries
a u.s. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the decision would add $50 million to $100 million a year to the tariffs collected by the united states. it will also provide additional business to some u.s. producers by discouraging imports
total u.s. imports under this system of ``generalized special preferences,'' the biggest of its kind in the world, reached a record $16.3 billion last year. it is designed to help poor countries improve their production in about 3,000 different products
as developing countries become increasingly competitive, we are removing tariff preferences... for those products where duty-free treatment is no longer warranted,'' said u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter
another $114 million worth of goods, previously cut from the list, was reinstated
and $40 million worth of new products was added, from $17 million worth of fireworks to $3,911 worth of pickled beans. hong kong will be the biggest beneficiary, but only until mid-1988, when it is due to lose its duty-free privilege entirely
none of the exporting countries was removed from the list in this annual review
yeutter said five countries whose labor and human rights situations had been challenged by labor unions and others will remain eligible because of ``improvements in their practices.'' they are taiwan, south korea, indonesia, thailand and turkey
the central african republic is still being reviewed
the trade bill approved thursday by conferees of the senate and house would increase pressure on third world countries on labor issues. it grants the president power to retaliate against exports of countries where the government refuses to give workers internationally recognized rights, such as the right to form unions
supporters of the bill argue that denying such rights gives those countries an unfair trade advantage because it enables them to keep wages down
the reagan administration opposed the provision but rep. donald j. pease d-ohio, its chief sponsor, said in an interview today it has not threatened a presidential veto on that ground
pease said such provisions are intended not to deprive poor countries of trade but to give them an incentive to change their labor laws
it's already happening in country after country,'' he added
yeutter's office gave thailand until dec. 15 to comply with u.s. conditions for protecting patents and copyrights. he has been asked by business groups here to deny duty-free privileges to thailand on this ground
a dog that had been adopted by a convalescent hospital the day it was to have been destroyed was honored for helping a seizure victim by barking to alert others
tori, a 5-year-old sheltie, on thursday was awarded a silver medal in a ceremony attended by actor earl holliman, a member of actors and others for animals, at the astoria convalescent home in sylmar
nancy sue merritt, 50, had been unhappy about the adoption and threatened to move when the dog arrived in january. her opinion changed feb. 7
ms. merritt suffered a seizure, fell and hit her head when no other people were around
but tori barked so loud ``you would have thought there was a pack of dogs,'' said lita joy parker, the director of activities
when she came to, ``i tried to wiggle around,'' ms. merritt said, ``but tori placed a paw on me and wouldn't let me up until help arrived.''
investigators are trying to determine if there was a connection between the crashes of two training helicopters within three days, a spokeswoman said friday
neither the instructor pilot, marine capt. steven andrews, nor his student, navy ensign scott jackson, were hurt when their th-57 helicopter crashed thursday, said airman audry anderson
two days earlier, marine capt. thomas lindblad, an instructor, was slightly injured and his student, marine 2nd lt. bradley eid, was unhurt when another th-57 went down
the helicopters crashed at two outlying practice fields, but photos show each wound up on its left side and with its two-bladed main rotor ripped from the aircraft
the helicopters were assigned to two squadrons in whiting's training air wing 5
a leading cultural figure accused communist party officials of ``upside-down glasnost'' for trying to cover up the truth about a fire that destroyed or damaged millions of literary treasures at a leningrad library
state cultural fund chairman dmitri likhachev said party officials ignored the plight of soviet literature and failed to preserve rare books that their elders managed to protect even from the siege of leningrad during world war ii
the feb. 14-15 blaze struck the library of the u.s.s.r. academy of sciences in leningrad and destroyed or damaged more than 3 million books and periodicals, likhachev said in an interview with the weekly moscow news and in an article he wrote in the weekly publication book review
he said the fire, which raged for 19 hours, was a national disaster made worse by official attempts to conceal it and ``became, truly, a chernobyl of our culture.''
the historian, writer and cultural activist said 400,000 books were destroyed by fire and 2.7 million books and periodicals damaged by water and moisture. a quarter of the library's unique newspaper fund was destroyed, and many of the lost issues were the last in existence, he said
the library, located in a 1920s building on leningrad's vasiliyevsky island, contained about 12 million books, manuscripts and periodicals. its collection was started in 1714, about a decade after peter the great founded the city
it pains me to recall how books were saved during the blockade of leningrad,'' said likhachev, 81, referring to the world war ii occupation when citizens spirited away rare books and other art treasures to protect them from the nazis. ``now, in these peaceful and happy times, books are dying. incredible.''
likhachev said the fire could have been prevented if party and government officials had heeded warnings about the dilapidated condition of the nation's most prestigious book collections
warnings of impending disaster had been published in the state-run press, and party officials responded with promises that crumbling libraries and museums will be taken care of
there grew up splendid buildings of district party committees and regional executive committees ... in which those who had signed those official replies discussed the problems of leisure, deliberated on the declining thirst for books and the crisis of moral integrity,'' likhachev said
this upside-down glasnost is worse than keeping silent, for it creates the illusion that things are being done and enables people to make believe that the train is picking up speed when in fact it is standing stock-still,'' he said, referring to soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's policy of openness
the losses could have been minimized, he claimed, if the fire had been properly extinguished instead of by the ``antediluvian method'' of having 25 fire engines flood the building for 19 hours
he accused library management of trying to hide the extent of the damage and the mishandling of the fire and said administrator v.a. filov and his assistant, v.p. leonov, should be fired
filov originally estimated damage at about $4,800, and promised the library would reopen within a few days
the march 8 edition of the party newspaper pravda said damage was at least $480,000, but added that the figure was based on 1956 values and that some of the lost material was priceless
filov and leonov ``both acted, in the first days, according to the `model' programmed by the mistakes of the chernobyl catastrophe _ they tried to belittle the cultural loss in the grossest manner,'' likhachev claimed
he was referring to soviet authorities' initial attempts to hush up the world's worst nuclear disaster, an april 1986 explosion at the chernobyl nuclear plant in which at least 31 people died and millions were exposed to increased levels of radioactivity
a bulldozer was called, and huge piles of burned, dampened and undamaged books were destroyed,'' likhachev wrote. ``library workers were prohibited from saving books from this heap of ruins. all this was in order to hide more quickly from the eyes of society the size of the catastrophe.''
mold started growing on the water-damaged books within a week, and only through the efforts of literature students and other volunteers has serious work begun to salvage the water-logged books, he said
special driers have been brought in, absorbent paper has been painstakingly applied between the pages of soaked books and great stores of other damaged materials that rescuers could not get to immediately have been frozen to preserve them during the interim
he criticized officials for failing to seek foreign help in salvaging damaged books
