the overseas winner in the mixed dancing competition for 13- to 16-year-olds was the mcging school in chicago
after arrests for art smuggling and ticket scalping, the rev. lorenzo zorza claimed he was only trying to help his friends. these days the ex-vatican diplomat has new friends, federal officials say _ and they operate an international drug ring
zorza, 46, was identified thursday as one of 39 people in the new york area involved in swapping cocaine for heroin with the sicilian mafia in what u.s. authorities described as the biggest international drug bust ever. for the italian-born fugitive priest, it was just another twist in what was apparently a strange double life
known to his friends as father lorenzo, zorza handled an assortment of church duties since arriving here in 1969: at the consolata fathers home for runaway girls, as fourth ranking vatican diplomat to the united nations, as assistant pastor at a manhattan church
authorities provided a different resume: art smuggler, ticket scalper (although charges were eventually dropped), heroin smuggler
among other criminal activities, zorza carries money derived from illegal sources back and forth between the u.s. and italy,'' the heroin complaint against the priest charged. the priest also is heard in several wiretapped conversations allegedly talking about the ring
zorza remained at large friday after failing to get off a flight from italy at kennedy international airport on thursday, as authorities expected
his first encounter with federal authorities came in 1982, when zorza was arrested for using his clerical garb and diplomatic status to smuggle two 16th- century oil paintings worth more than $100,000 from italy into the united states for an $8,000 fee
zorza, who was at the united nations at the time, was placed on probation for three years after pleading guilty to charges in the case
i did it sincerely to help somebody,'' zorza told the judge, asserting he did not know the paintings were stolen. ``i'm terribly sorry.''
and after charges of scalping $40,000 worth of tickets to broadway's ``les miserables'' were dropped in august 1987, zorza said he was ``just trying to help out two friends.''
zorza was ordained in 1966, moved to the united states three years later and became an american citizen in 1976
authorities said zorza remained a member of the consolata fathers of somerset, n.j., but a priest there said the order ended its association with him more than a decade ago by mutual agreement
we just know what we heard last night,'' said the priest, who declined to give his name. ``we don't know what he's doing, or where he's doing it.''
the archdiocese of new york also doesn't know where zorza is, a spokesman said friday. zorza was assistant pastor at st. agnes church in 1983, but officials at the church hung up the phone when called for comment
zorza is charged with conspiracy to distribute and possess with intent to distribute heroin, cocaine and marijuana. the conspiracy charge carries a maximum penalty of life imprisonment
italy's defense minister assured secretary of state george p. shultz on friday that the government is considering seriously the possible transfer to italy of f-16 jets being evicted from spain
but defense minister valerio zanone did not commit italy to accepting the fighters. he said the entire nato alliance should be involved in the decision
shultz took up the issue of the f-16s with zanone during a stop in rome before heading for the middle east on sunday to continue efforts to spur arab-israeli peace talks
italy is considered the prime candidate to take the 72 fighter-bombers of the u.s. 401st tactical fighter wing, based in torrejon, spain. in january, washington bowed to a spanish demand to remove the planes within three years
in a communique issued after the talks, the defense ministry said zanone ``stressed the satisfactory progress of the study under way to identify all elements necessary to a carefully pondered decision, which will have to be made in concert with parliament.''
asked at a news conference whether an accord in principle had been reached on the f-16s, zanone replied, ``i wouldn't say an accord in principle. there is serious attention by the italian government to the problem.''
his statements did not go far beyond those made in february following talks in rome with defense secretary frank carlucci
zanone reiterated italy's position that the f-16s must remain in europe to protect nato's southern flank, but that a decision on where they should be relocated and how to finance the move must be decided by the entire western alliance
there is a predisposition by italy to study the possibility'' of accepting the f-16s, the minister told reporters
shultz did not meet with reporters after the meeting with zanone
state department spokesman charles redman said the meeting with zanone was ``not in any sense an effort to make commitments'' on the f-16s
zanone said he and shultz discussed the ``various possible'' sites in italy where the f-16s could be based, but he declined to identify them. italian media have identified possible sites as the bases of gioia del colle in southern puglia, decimomannu in sardinia, the present cruise missile base in comiso, sicily, and the u.s. base in aviana in northeastern italy
zanone, the lone cabinet minister from the tiny liberal party, noted that the issue will have to be faced by italy's new government. premier giovanni goria resigned three weeks ago, and fellow christian democrat ciriaco de mita is trying to form a new five-party coalition
some italian politicians, including former premier bettino craxi, a socialist, have voiced concerns about the possible relocation. the communists and other opposition groups are firmly opposed
shultz met earlier friday with president francesco cossiga and foreign minister giulio andreotti
speaking with reporters earlier on the plane taking him to rome, shultz was cautiously upbeat about his new middle east peace mission. his trip last month failed to bring an agreement
i think we have a chance to see some motion,'' he said of his shuttling to israel, jordan, syria, egypt and saudi arabia
shultz said he felt especially positive about the role of jordan's king hussein, describing him as a ``key player'' in the peace process
i hope we can make some headway,'' he said
so far only eygpt has endorsed the plan to have talks on palestinian self-rule begin on may 1
on saturday, shultz is to have a private audience with pope john paul ii. he also plans to attend the pope's easter mass on sunday before leaving for jerusalem
when it came to the crunch, eric erickson says he's proud to be a ``chocolate city man.''
erickson, 31, wrote a song to defend his birthplace in the ``chocolate wars'' between burlington, the home of nestle food corp., and hershey foods corp. of hershey, pa
the battle began when burlington adopted the name ``chocolate city usa'' during the debut of a chocolate festival in may 1987
nestle, the city's largest employer, embraced the idea. but hershey foods protested when burlington officials filed for trademark protection of the adopted name and a logo bearing a chocolate morsel. hershey foods claimed they bore too close a resemblance to its trademarks, including the name ``chocolate town usa'' and the hershey kiss
a word of warning, hershey _ and it's more than just a hunch. try and scare us with your `kiss of death' and you'll get the nestle's crunch,'' erickson sings
he also advises hershey: ``forget about the lawsuit _ you'll never make it stick. you'd be better off to get a glass of milk and have some nestle's quick.''
the song really makes you feel proud of this city,'' said jack berry, chocolate festival coordinator
hershey foods was closed friday and officials could not be reached for comment
a group of university of massachusetts professors has embraced ``squash power'' to help the land-grant university celebrate its 125th anniversary
the professors have stuffed a young hubbard squash into a foot-square plexiglass chamber so the fruit can expand only in a downward direction. now, the giant squash is growing ever larger in a campus greenhouse, compressing a set of springs connected to a set of load cells connected to a balance beam
and on charter day, april 29, the contraption will be wheeled out to the campus pond to demonstrate the power of the fruit by hoisting a tractor
the hubbard hijinks have historical precedent, said john w. denison, professor emeritus in the college of food and natural resources. the experiment was first performed at the institution in 1874 by its third president, col. william s. clark, a ``somewhat flamboyant botanist,'' according to denison
before it expired, clark's squash hoisted about 5,000 pounds worth of anvils, anchors, drainpipes, barrels of sand and ``whatever else he found lying around,'' denison said
we figure to do a bit better, maybe 30,000 pounds'' denison said wednesday. ``they've been really babying that vine over in the greenhouse. they even come in on weekends to feed it.''
elementary school principal gail thompson may think twice before betting with her pupils again
thompson challenged her doniphan elementary school pupils to read 10,000 books from october through march as part of the ``book it!'' national reading program. if she lost, she promised to spend four hours in a tub of oatmeal
the 200 youngsters met the goal, so the principal headed for the porridge thursday, clad in a 1920s style bathing outfit, checked hat and goggles
ohhh, this is awful,'' she said as she stuck her foot in the cereal
one of the youngsters was worried about the principal's ordeal
it's ok, honey,'' thompson told a pre-schooler. ``you don't have to feel sorry for me. it's just fun. i asked for it.''
the pupils also were given a special breakfast treat in honor of thompson's adventure. you guessed it, oatmeal
the reagan administation threatened a presidential veto of the newly minted congressional trade compromise friday unless major changes are made when lawmakers come back from their spring break
the administration says the president's hands would be tied unreasonably by provisions in the legislation calling for import curbs to retaliate for trade agreement violations
the compromise worked out by house and senate negotiators thursday night would transfer authority to retaliate from the president to the u.s. trade representative. but it would leave waiver authority if the president thought the costs of import curbs would outweigh the benefits
the measure also would impose restricitions on imports to punish toshiba corp. of japan and its toshiba machine co. subsidiary for the latter's role in the sale to the soviets of computerized equipment that helps make soviet submarines more difficult to detect
we still have grave reservations about several of the provisions, including plant closings, toshiba, presidential authority and some of the mandatory retaliatory provisions,'' spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters traveling with reagan to california for a 10-day vacation
the plant closing provision would require employers to provide their employees with 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs
lawmakers who drew up the compromise wrapped up most of their work before heading for the airports to start their spring break. but they left enough loose ends to cloud the picture
farm lawmakers were still wrangling over details, and a house-passed plan to require registration of foreign property ownership in the united states still had lawmakers deadlocked. they planned to tackle the issue again later
renewed white house veto threats should put the spotlight on senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen, d-texas, who is empowered under the rules to start action that could lead to a so-called superconference meeting of lawmakers to perform radical surgery
fitzwater said such a meeting already was in the works
the superconference will meet after recess, and if substantial changes aren't made by the superconference, the president's senior advisers will recommend a veto,'' fitzwater said
earlier, u.s trade representative clayton yeutter said congress ``jettisoned a lot of undesirable things'' in negotiations this week
the question is whether they jettisoned enough,'' he said. ``and we need a couple of days to assess that.'' he said there ``certainly are some provisions in there of dubious merit.''
some lawmakers already were indicating they saw room for revision
the bill is good strong market opening legislation,'' said sen. john c. danforth, r-mo., one of the conferees
i am convinced that the trade provisions which are the heart of the bill could be signed into law if they were standing alone,'' he said. ``but they are not standing alone. congress will have an opportunity in mid-april to consider any changes needed to meet remaining objections from the administration.''
the inventors of a flying machine to be used in an attempt to break the world distance record for human-powered flight said friday that strong winds may delay the endeavor for another three days
i think it's virtually impossible at this point to fly tomorrow ... but monday, tuesday it should be feasible,'' said steve k. bussulari, a massachusetts institute of technology aerospace expert heading the daedalus project
gale winds up to 45 mph are preventing the 70-pound plane from attempting the 74-mile flight from crete to the island of santorini, also known as thira
essentially, the airplane is ready to go anytime, and the pilot's ready to go. we're in a pattern waiting on the weather,'' john s. langford, the project director, told reporters
the flight will also update the 3,500-year-old legend of the inventor daedalus, who escaped from crete with his son, icarus, on wings he made from feathers and wax. icarus crashed into the sea and drowned after soaring so close to the sun that his wings melted, but daedalus flew safely across the aegean
the daedalus 88 aircraft will be pedaled in a five-hour flight that requires dead calm or a light southerly tailwind
five pilots _ four americans and a greek _ are taking turns on standby for 48 hours at a stretch and cycling up to 90 miles daily to stay in shape. there are four backup pilots in case something goes wrong
i feel a little disappointed i won't be going but i've been watching the weather and saw this delay coming,'' said greg zack, 26, a professional cyclist who was ready to fly friday or saturday
the three-year mit project already has produced one world record distance for human-powered flight of 37.2 miles. it was set by glenn tremml, piloting a daedalus prototype plane in circles around edwards air force base in california in january 1987
but the straight-line world record still stands at 22 miles set by bryan allen in 1979 flying across the english channel
with the right wind, daedalus 88 could probably go 100 miles, but we'll be satisfied with a touchdown on santorini,'' langford said
langford said the 36-member team will wait until mid-may if necessary to make the record flight
we've got funds for another six weeks and two backup planes that we'd also be willing to lose in the attempt,'' he said
the graphite epoxy and plastic aircraft with a wingspan of 112 feet could break up if the pilot crashes into the sea
greek navy vessels and a flotilla of inflatable crafts will escort the daedalus plane, which would fly just 15 feet above the waves
the government on friday apologized and offered compensation for hundreds of people killed and wounded when its troops scoured the city of kwangju to put down a 1980 civil revolt
it was the first official government apology for its handling of the citizens' uprising, the worst in modern south korean history
president roh tae-woo, who took office feb. 25 with promises of reform, pledged during his campaign to change the government's official account of the violence and offer financial compensation for victims
the government offers its sincere apology, not only to the victims of the turmoil, but also to all residents of kwangju and the general public,'' culture and information minister chung han-mo said in a statement friday
chung, the official government spokesman, also said the resistance was ``part of the democratization efforts of the students and citizens in kwangju'' in a concession demanded by city residents
his description sharply departed from the stand taken by the government of former president chun doo-hwan, which used the terms ``rebellion'' and ``rioters'' to describe what happened in kwangju
the city, 200 miles south of seoul, is the capital of opposition leader kim dae-jung's home province, south cholla
he was arrested in a government crackdown on opposition leaders may 17, 1980, when the former military-controlled government expanded martial law and moved to suppress political dissent
most pro-democracy demonstrations elsewhere in the country were quashed, but the struggle in kwangju led the government to move martial law troops into the city
kwangju citizens, armed with rifles and machine guns taken from government arsenals, drove out troops. however, reinforcements retook the city nine days later
by official count, 191 people were killed and more than 800 hurt. dissident sources put the casualty figure much higher
the government spokesman said friday that roh believed a satisfactory resolution of the kwangju issue was essential to promoting national reconciliation. others have said roh is trying to distance himself from the authoritarian chun government to prepare for national assembly elections at the end of the month
roh, a former general and schoolmate of chun, helped the former president gain power in 1980
the government spokesman said the administration would offer financial support and employment to bereaved families and wounded victims. the government also vowed to beautify a cemetery where many of the kwangju victims are buried
civic leaders in kwangju welcomed the government's offer of financial aid
but they have insisted that the government investigate the cause of the deaths and punish those responsible. the main opposition political group, the reunification democratic party, called the government measures a sham
government officials, however, have said an inquiry would only aggravate old wounds
members of pi kappa alpha fraternity are nearing their goal of winning a pool table from country music star larry gatlin by not drinking alcoholic beverages or using mind-altering drugs this week
we haven't messed up yet, and i don't think we're going to have any problem,'' said former pi kappa alpha president steve swanson of their saturday midnight deadline
gatlin, of nashville, set forth the conditions in a letter to swanson after learning the fraternity at tennessee tech was interested in the pool table he was trying to sell
gatlin received treatment in 1984 for drug and alcohol problems. since then, he has encouraged young people to avoid lifestyles that can lead to addiction
