a man accused of attacking one of two british soldiers who later were killed told police he was sorry the incident occurred, according to testimony friday
anthony gallagher, 17, appeared before belfast magistrates court charged with causing grievous bodily harm to cpl. david howes on march 19. he was ordered to remain in jail until his next court appearance april 22
howes and cpl. derek wood were beaten by a mob of mourners after their car encountered an irish republican army funeral procession in a predominantly roman catholic district of west belfast. they later were shot to death
a detective with the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, told the court that when police formally charged gallagher, he replied: ``i'm sorry it ever happened.''
gallagher is the fifth person charged in the incident
two men have been charged with murder, a third was charged with withholding information from police, and a fourth with trading a pair of bloodstained slacks with a man believed to have been involved in the murders
the outlawed, predominantly catholic ira has been fighting to oust the british from northern ireland and to reunite the province with the republic of ireland
the internal revenue service is promising quick relief for students who are due refunds because they were wrongly taxed on teaching or research stipends earned during graduate school
in general, any pre-1987 stipend that meets three tests spelled out by the agency in a 1975 ruling will be considered non-taxable, the irs said friday. students who apply for refunds of any additional tax will get prompt attention, the agency said
the irs announcement was aimed at clearing up confusion resulting from the fact that courts have issued conflicting decisions on the question. some court rulings have been considerably more stringent than the 1975 irs policy, and some irs district offices have chosen to use the court decisions as a guide
as a result, thousands of students have been billed for back taxes on their stipends. the irs says there is no concerted drive to audit the returns of graduate students, and says much of the blame for the students' problem is because many colleges reported their stipends as taxable income
a student who has paid additional taxes because a district irs office wrongly considered a stipend taxable should file an amended return (form 1040x) and ask for a refund, the irs said. those who have received a bill but have not yet paid the tax should file for an abatement
taxpayers should clearly indicate on the form that the claim is being filed for reconsideration of the teaching or research stipend issue under revenue ruling 75-280,'' the irs said
that ruling states that a stipend is non-taxable if:
_the student was a degree candidate at the time the stipend was earned
_the student performed research, teaching or other services that were required for a degree
_similar services were required of all candidates for the degree
if those tests are met, the irs said, the stipend will be considered non-taxable under the presumption that its primary purpose was to further the student's education or training
the rule applies only to stipends paid before 1987. a new law that took effect in 1987 specifically taxes such income
a woman says her sick infant and 6-year-old daughter were held as collateral in the philippines until her hotel bill was paid, and has turned her anger on the boston bank she says caused the trouble
maria luz deiulis, who failed in her bid to sue the hotel, has sued the bank of boston for $2 million, saying her anguish was caused by someone at the bank who bungled her credit card account
a suffolk superior court judge this week refused a request by the bank to dismiss the suit she filed last year. the bank says the suit is groundless and that deiulis brought all the trouble on herself by using a card she had asked be restricted so her boyfriend could not use it
deiulis, 39, of lynn, a filipino native, said her ordeal began when she returned to manila in november 1986 with two of her three children to see her ailing father
deiulis, her 6-month-old son and daughter checked into the royal palm hotel in manila for a week. she presented her bank of boston credit card and thought little of her $260 tab until shortly before she was to leave
they called my room at 11 o'clock at night and said the bank had voided my credit card,'' said deiulis
deiulis said she asked the hotel to check again but that the hotel responded by confiscating her credit card and calling police, who seized the family's passports
because it was the start of a three-day holiday in the philippines, deiulis said she was unable to go to a bank. as a result, the police ordered a security guard to watch them during the holiday
after the weekend, deiulis was escorted to a bank by police. she says police and hotel management said the children could not leave the hotel until the bill was paid and that it took most of the day to arrange to get the money
my baby son was sick, he had a fever and diarrhea,'' deiulis said. ``i was nervous all the time. i was horrified. i thought they might take the kids away from me forever, i thought they might take them away.''
deiulis said hotel officials released the children after she paid her bill and after she complained to the american embassy and ministry of tourism in manila
this is the craziest story,'' bank of boston spokesman wayne taylor said friday. ``it's absolutely crazy. it's the most groundless, frivolous suit. it's the most ridiculous thing in the world.''
taylor said deiulis contacted the bank before she left for the philippines and asked that her boyfriend's name be taken off the account. taylor said the bank gave her a choice of either notifying them in writing, or canceling the account and getting a new card. taylor said deiulis was unsure what to do and agreed to have the card ``restricted,'' meaning no one could use it
but deiulis said she had paid her credit card bill in full at the time and understood that she could continue to use it
deiulis said her attempt to sue the hotel was dismissed in the philippines
arman mamangon, an operator at the royal palm hotel for eight years, said in a telephone interview friday that he was unaware of the deiulis case. but he said that when customers fail to pay their bills, the hotel ``sometimes takes collateral like a passport, or maybe jewelry.''
mamangon laughed when asked if children were held as collateral. ``no, i never heard of that,'' he said
the wednesday night ladies house league says their bowling alley manager cares more about how many beers they knock down than pins
the league has been ousted from its 6 p.m. time slot in favor of a men's league _ who put more of a dent in a keg than the ladies
the women are out, the men are in because they can drink more than us, ... that's the bottom line,'' league official mary-lou allen said thursday. ``drinking should not be a prerequisite for bowling.''
jimmy walker, manager of fern hill golf and country club lanes in this detroit suburb, said he asked the 60 league members wednesday to switch to another time slot for their 30-week season beginning next fall strictly for business reasons
women's leagues water you do death,'' he said, bemoaning what he says is their preference for water over more costly beverages. ``that's why most places don't cater to women on the first (evening) shift. the bowling business is not strictly bowling.''
he said the men's league taking the women's place next fall will bring in $100 to $150 per night in addition to regular bowling costs. the women sometimes spent as little as $40 a night, he said
and some leagues are worth still more
what would you do if you owned the business?'' he asked. ``we've got an amvets league in here that does $250 to $275 a night, and they're all great guys.''
the league isn't sure what it will do, but carol blossey, outgoing president and a member of mothers against drunk driving, said she plans to file a complaint with her organization
i have a beer once in a while, but i can't bowl well if i'm drunk,'' said blossey, who carries a 167 average. ``i feel we're being discriminated against.''
the woodland park zoo says it no longer has a problem with people abandoning their rabbits after easter since word spread that zookeepers feed some of the unwanted pets to the lions
zoo spokesman hank klein said friday that in years past the zoo was overrun with rabbits. after easter passed, some people found that bunnies aren't as much fun in may as they were in march or april
abandoned rabbits damaged the zoo grounds and created other problems, klein said. domestic rabbits can't survive on their own and end up starving, getting run over by cars or eaten by owls and hawks
the zoo now has a pest control officer who traps and kills rabbits, adding them to the daily feed for lions, wolves and cougars
there are not too many people that want cute little thumper to end up in the jaws of a lion,'' klein said
it's not a good idea to surprise someone with a bunny,'' he said. ``we encourage people to think very carefully before giving any animal, especially as a surprise.''
a town marshal missing for a day after disappearing on a burglary call said friday he escaped after being held in a closet and car trunk by four men he thought were about to kill him
i knew i was done for anyway and i had nothing to lose,'' gary stokes said of his early friday escape in rural northeast mississippi. ``when they let me out of the trunk, i hit the ground running and i didn't look back.''
stokes, 35, disappeared about 12:55 a.m. thursday after calling for back-up units while investigating a possible attempted burglary at a store in this town of about 860 residents
police arriving at the store found his car with the engine still running, the lights on and his radio microphone hanging outside the door. his revolver and billfold were found nearby
about all i can tell you is that he is back and we are investigating.'' said tippah county sheriff leroy meeks said friday
sammy pickens, a highway patrol investigator, said the case was being treated ``as a felony ... an abduction, but we can't release any more information at this time.''
stokes, the town's only full-time policeman, said he was ``still nervous and kind of shook up. they had said several times they were going to kill me, and i believed them.''
he said he managed to escape when the men stopped their car near myrtle in adjacent union county ``because one of them had to go to the bathroom. i asked them if i could use the bathroom, too, and they agreed.''
stokes said he immediately ran down railroad tracks beside the highway and ducked into a wooded area before making his way to a house and calling police in nearby new albany
i had just about given up hope,'' he said. ``they were talking about robbing another store around holly springs and said before they got there, they would kill me.''
lawmen had used dogs as they searched for stokes in rural areas surrounding blue mountain all day thursday and well into the night
stokes said that while investigating what he believed was an attempted break-in at the store he confronted two men, drew his weapon and ordered them to stop
while i was chasing them, two others came up from behind and one of them hit me,'' he said. ``that caused my gun to discharge above their heads.''
he said the men drove him to a highway rest area about five miles away
one wanted to kill me right then,'' stokes said, but the others talked him out of it. ``they then put me in the trunk. i spent several hours in the trunk and all day in the closet of an abandoned house.''
he said the four put him back in the car trunk thursday night and drove to the myrtle area, where he escaped sometime before 3 a.m
stokes said he had seen the four men earlier in the week in another car. he said they were not from the blue mountain area
mary stokes, the officer's step-mother, said stokes appeared tired and shaken when he arrived home friday morning, and ``he's got a bad place on his face where they hit him
but i asked him if he would ever put the uniform on again and he told me he was going right back to work because he is needed.'' flap</head>
the naming of a plastic surgery consultant to the miss san diego pageant is drawing grimaces from state and national pageant officials, but stephen grifka doesn't understand what all the fuss is about
the culver city doctor said cosmetic surgery is a legitimate option for today's beauty queens
this is a competition,'' grifka said. ``and in order to get the competitive edge, they want to enhance themselves to the maximum amount. i can't change a couch into a chair. but i can certainly fluff up a pillow.''
dayna waitley, executive director of the miss san diego pageant, appointed grifka to the unpaid consulting position at the recommendation of a mutal friend
in a jan. 5 letter to grifka, waitley wrote that the expertise of the doctor, who specializes in nose jobs, scar removal and facelifts, could help contestants realize their full potential
the appointment brought a storm of criticism from other beauty pageant officials
that's the last kind of person who would ever be involved with the miss america pageant,'' leonard c. horn, chief executive officer of the miss america pageant, said in an interview in friday's los angeles times san diego edition
we have consultants on hair and evening gowns, but to have a consultant on plastic surgery seems a little strange,'' horn said
though horn branded the idea as ``laughable,'' plastic surgery is permitted under pageant rules. indeed, there were reports shortly after the 1982 contest that titlist debra sue maffett had undergone extensive cosmetic work
there is no chance in the world he would ever be associated with us,'' said robert arnhym, chief executive officer of the miss california pageant, which oversees the san diego pageant and 41 other contests throughout the state
no one in the state of california has ever encouraged our winners to have plastic surgery _ ever,'' arnhym said
grifka had no involvement in this year's pageant, which was held march 19, waitley said. she said she will ask the pageant's board of directors to review the arrangement because of the protest
for his part, grifka said he accepted the appointment with the best of intentions and has no desire to bring negative publicity to the pageant
these contests are not strictly a show of beauty,'' he said. ``if you attended a pageant you would be amazed at how talented these girls are.''
theatrical agent joe collins, the father of ``dynasty'' actress joan collins and novelist jackie collins, died friday at his home. he was 85
collins, who helped launch the careers of peter sellers, tom jones and roger moore and convinced joan collins to take her famous role as alexis in the popular tv series, suffered from a kidney infection, according to press association, britain's domestic news agency
although he came from a family of stage performers, collins said he did not consider show business a suitable profession for his daughters. ``too many pitfalls,'' he once said
he later came to feel differently: ``my children are healthy and have made their mark on the world. i think i can claim that almost every person in every land has had some form of entertainment, some pleasure brought their way by one member or another of my family.''
collins was born in south africa, where his parents, both from london, entertained. they returned to britain when collins was a year old and he was educated there
he began his show business career as office boy with moss empires theaters in london and later worked as an assistant theater manager in sheffield and liverpool
in 1931, he became a theatrical agent. the first artist he signed was dancer lew grade, now television producer lord grade, who became his partner. when grade left the collins and grade agency, collins continued alone
collins married his first wife, elsa, in 1932, and she gave birth to their daughter, joan, the next year. elsa died in 1962
collins did not encourage his daughter's early acting ambitions, but once she won a place at the royal academy of dramatic art, he supported her. he even set up a repertory company in southeastern england to help her career
he later persuaded her to take the role of alexis in ``dynasty'' even though a theatrical company was trying to hold her to a previous contract
collins said he was proud of his daughter jackie's success as an author but never read her books, which included ``hollywood wives'' and ``lucky.'' he declared the sexy novels were ``not my cup of tea.''
his own biography was titled ``a touch of collins.''
besides joan and jackie, collins is survived by his second wife, irene, and their daughter, natasha. services were scheduled for tuesday in london
rumors that a satanic cult planned to sacrifice a virgin reached a peak this week, leading people to keep hundreds of children home from school and inundate police with calls
despite the hysteria, police and school officials said extensive investigations didn't produce any evidence to support the rumors
pike county residents locked their doors and kept children home from school by the hundreds thursday, the day the rumors said was the intended date of human sacrifice
we have a 30 percent absenteeism in the district,'' mccomb assistant school superintendent leslie daniels said thursday. ``some of that is due to the weather; some of it is because it's the day before a holiday. but from the calls we've had, i believe much of it's from the rumors.''
there are about 3,700 students in the district
sheriff robert lawson has said in the past that there are 22 members of a satanic cult in pike county and that the group has probably sacrificed dogs, cats, goats and other animals in secluded areas
officials said the latest rumors led them to fear the public might act irrationally if someone was identified _ even erroneously _ as one of the cult members
as paranoid as this public is, some innocent person could get hurt,'' said lee barkdull, mccomb's acting director of public safety. ``i'm worried about mischief _ someone spray-painting something crazy and getting caught by others.''
since about march 24, barkdull's office has fielded dozens of calls from residents worried by reports that a cult planned human sacrifices and that several mccomb schoolchildren were on a list of potential victims
police believe the story spread quickly in schools, reaching a crisis level when parents got wind of it
students at gibson high school said teachers canceled tests thursday when classes began with small numbers of students. they also said rumors persisted that satan worshipers planned a midnight march through town, with a later sacrifice of a baby and a 13-year-old
the story is that good friday is their black sabbath, and they need a sacrifice,'' said 16-year-old tammy perry, a 10th-grader at gibson high school
i figure it's a bunch of kids playing practical jokes,'' said terry butrick of summit
i believe people worship satan. why not? people worship their car, why not satan?'' said butrick, who has two children in elementary school. ``but as far as me running around getting out the garlic and the silver bullets, nah.''
soviet tv reported friday that strikes have paralyzed most industry in stepanakert, the main city in a caucasus region that is at the center of an ethnic dispute
the nightly news program, ``vremya,'' said construction was at a standstill and delivery of goods to and from the city had been disrupted
public transport is virtually at a halt and many enterprises are idle on account of the failure to turn out to work,'' it said
reports by ``vremya'' and the official news agency tass appeared aimed at convincing armenians it is futile to press demands for annexation of the nagorno-karabakh region, which was made part of azerbaijan in 1923
about 75 percent of the 157,000 residents are ethnic armenians, most of whom are christian. azeris, the indigenous population of azerbaijan, are predominantly shiite moslem
farmers in nagorno-karabakh were shown on television hard at work with spring planting. the news reader said the akhtanak collective farm had appealed for a return to normal in stepanakert
cameras panned deserted building sites and quiet streets in the city while the narrator explained that most workers were staying home
stepanakert's industries have run up debts of ``several million rubles,'' the report said. no more specific figure was provided
most industrial activity stopped march 24 in protest of the communist party leadership's refusal to attach nagorno-karabakh to soviet armenia
activists in armenia and nagorno-karabakh began demonstrations in mid-february demanding that nagorno-karabakh, slightly smaller than delaware, be made part of armenia even though there is no common border. the kremlin refused and said protests were ``intolerable,'' although it announced a development program
the armenian claims incited riots feb. 28 in the azerbaijan city of sumgait. official reports said 32 people were killed and nearly 200 injured, and that about 400 were arrested for murder, rape, looting and other crimes
communist party officials said the nagorno-karabakh development plan would involve spending 400 million rubles _ $640 million at the official exchange rate _ to improve housing, education, armenian-language literature and broadcasts, and other elements of life in the region
complaints that nagorno-karabakh was losing its traditional armenian character were among points cited by activists in their demand for annexation
vremya'' said the development plan will not be carried out if the strike continues
the people of stepanakert have long been renowned for their good sense, their love of work, their skill,'' the news reader said. ``let them show all these qualities now in the present difficult situation.''
security forces were deployed in yerevan, the armenian capital, earlier in the week to guard against more disorder there, but it was not clear from the vremya footage whether similar measures were being taken in stepanakert
telephone calls to the region were not answered friday, even at such facilities as railroad stations and newspaper offices
in its only dispatch on the matter friday, tass outlined legal problems involved in addressing armenian demands for annexation. it said the legislatures of both republics would have to approve any change in status and the national supreme soviet would have the final say
washington _ (ap) _ the nation's unemployment rate fell to a new decade-low 5.6 percent in march even though there were 306,000 fewer americans at work than a month earlier, the government said friday
the drop from february's 5.7 percent rate was credited entirely to a 455,000 decrease in the number of people in the labor force _ those either holding jobs or seeking work _ raising inflationary alarms among some economists
it's just one month, but it indicates that wages are not high enough to coax second earners out of the home any more,'' said roger brinner, an analyst for data resources inc., an economic consulting firm in lexington, mass
if the labor force has stopped growing, then wage inflation may be right around the corner, not now but possibly in early 1989,'' brinner said. ``higher wages might coax more people out of the woodwork, but any increase in the standard of living will be temporary because prices will soon catch up.''
the number of americans in the labor force dropped from approximately 123.1 million to 122.6 million between february and march, as the percentage of the population age 16 and over holding or seeking jobs declined from an all-time record 66.3 percent to 66 percent
the government has been warning about a reduced rate of labor force expansion for several years, based on declining birth rates in the 1960s and early 1970s
and a big part of the full percentage point drop in a jobless rate that stood at 6.6 percent in march 1987 was the fact that the number of new jobs last year climbed by 3 million while the labor force grew by only 2 million
although women are continuing to enter the labor force in large numbers, the rate of their increase has slowed,'' labor statistics commissioner janet l. norwood told the joint economic committee of congress on friday. ``the dramatic surge of women in the labor force took place in the 1960s and 1970s.''
while the lower unemployment rates are raising fears of renewed inflation among some economists, there certainly was no evidence of it on the wage front last month
average wages in private industry rose just 2 cents an hour in march to $9.20, just 3 percent above what they were a year earlier. consumer prices, meanwhile, have risen 3.9 percent in the same period
the experience in the 1980s clearly shows that full employment and a falling inflation rate are not incompatible,'' said richard rahn, chief economist for the u.s. chamber of commerce. ``we have reached the lowest unemployment rate in a decade without stoking the fires of inflation.''
except for may 1979, when joblessness also was 5.6 percent, march's rate is actually the lowest it has been since august 1974
reagan administration officials were quick to pounce on the figures to bolster their opposition to union-sought provisions in a trade bill that would require companies to give workers 60 days advance notice of layoffs
sixty-four straight months of job creation and nearly 16 million new jobs is the product of a vibrant, innovative and entrepreneurial economy,'' said labor secretary ann mclaughlin. ``now is not the time to put on the brakes with anti-competitive, anti-growth federal mandates on business.''
despite the fewer number of americans at work, employer payrolls showed an increase f 262,000 new jobs in march, according to a separate survey by the department
ms. norwood explained that the payroll survey and the household survey from which the unemployment rate is calculated have moved in opposite directions before
over the long run, however, the two surveys generally show similar trends,'' she said, adding that the payroll survey is probably a better indicator of what actually occured in march
but the news on the payroll survey wasn't entirely good either. factory jobs, after rising an average 40,000 each month since last summer, fell by 1,000 in march, with small declines spread over 11 major industries
of the new payroll jobs, 85,000 were in business and health care services with another 80,000 in construction
in happier times, she planted flowers for the anniversary and directed tours of the small motel where martin luther king jr. died
but now, in the 20th year after his death, jacqueline smith huddles on a sidewalk, wraps herself in plastic to keep off the rain and tells anyone who'll listen how the slain civil rights leader would not like plans to make the lorraine motel a museum
miss smith, 37, lived and worked at the lorraine for 11 years and helped organize annual gatherings there on the anniversary of king's death
we would clean up and plant flowers, and how the crowd was handled was up to me,'' she said
but miss smith was evicted march 2 and has no official role in ceremonies set monday for the 20th anniversary of king's death
i feel sad,'' she said. ``i'll miss talking with the people as they go in the room.''
participants in memorial programs for the king anniversary plan a march through town, ending at the lorraine. after a wreath-laying ceremony there, a combination march and motorcade billed as a ``poor peoples' pilgrimage'' will be launched from the motel for a trek through mississippi, alabama and georgia
the lorraine, where king was staying while helping lead a memphis sanitation workers' strike, is to become a civil rights museum
for past anniversaries, visitors could go to the room where king stayed. over the years, motel employees built a makeshift shrine in the room
state officials closed the lorraine in january and put a chain-link fence around it, saying it was unsafe for habitation. miss smith stayed on
after her forced eviction, she set up housekeeping on the sidewalk
the motel is in a downtown district of warehouses and low-rent apartments, but developers have begun in recent years to upgrade property in the area in hopes of attracting middle-income renters
miss smith claims the $8.8 million museum will speed the gentrification of the neighborhood
dr. king would not want the poor people displaced,'' she said
the project for the lorraine museum, financed by the state and local governments, is largely due to the work of a citizens' group which raised $140,000 to buy the motel at a foreclosure auction. the museum is scheduled to open in 1991
d'army bailey, a memphis lawyer and a prime mover behind the project, said museum visitors will be surrounded by pictures and sounds of civil rights marches of the 1960s
the museum will take you back to those times and do all we can to recreate those feelings, the tensions of the moment,'' he said. ``when people come in and spend an hour or two and then walk out, i think and hope that what walks out is going to be affected and changed.''
bailey said it has taken almost 20 years for local government to realize that the lorraine should be preserved as an integral though painful part of memphis history
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis adopted a new populist stand friday in a drive to win blue collar support in wisconsin's primary while the democratic presidential candidates in a chorus called on attorney general edwin meese iii to resign
the four democrats kept up hectic schedules despite the passover and easter observances this weekend, mindful of the 81 delegates at stake tuesday in wisconsin
dukakis and jesse jackson each held farm rallies. jackson attracted more than 2,500 farmers and their families to his event on bud and faye lee's farm near amery, in northern wisconsin. jackson told the farmers they deserve fair prices for their products ``and workers deserve fair wages and the rich must pay fair taxes.'' he said people could afford to pay a little more for milk, bread and ice cream to make sure farmers got their due
sens. albert gore jr. of tennessee and paul simon of illinois joined dukakis and jackson in demanding that meese resign
as a member of the senate judiciary committee, today we are asking ed meese to resign,'' simon said at a breakfast speech in superior
it's time in this nation to restore respect for government, to establish rule of law,'' gore said in the same town
dukakis blamed meese's justice department for allowing the ``merger mania'' he said has cost a half million jobs
we've got an attorney general who couldn't tell the difference between antitrust and antifreeze, an antitrust division that hasn't been heard from in years,'' dukakis told a labor audience in racine. ``the japanese must be laughing at us all the way to the bank.''
the furor over meese's troubles erupted again friday when independent counsel james c. mckay announced there was no evidence ``developed to date'' to warrant a criminal indictment against the attorney general in connection with an iraq-jordan pipeline plan or his investment in telephone company stock. mckay said the probe was continuing
dukakis' speeches and a new television ad that started airing friday demonstrated the governor's shift to a more emotional approach drawing on the economic populism theme developed by rep. richard gephardt, who dropped out of the race monday
the human cost of seven years of republican indifference is staggering,'' dukakis says in the ad as laid-off workers, homeless people, unemployment lines and ``factory closed'' signs roll by the screen. ``who in this administration could look right into the eyes of the laid-off factory worker or the homeless family and say they've kept the promise of america? i say they've broken that promise.''
gephardt said on syndicated television program ``one on one'' that he didn't mind the heavy borrowing from his campaign. ``everybody has stolen it,'' he said. ``i willed it everybody when i pulled out and i hope they will use it. it is the issue of this campaign.''
gore, who has been outspoken in criticism of jackson this week, said again that jackson's race doesn't entitle him to kid-glove treatment
an end to bigotry does not mean some candidates are game for criticism and some are immune,'' gore said
in washington, house democratic leader tom foley said jackson will be subjected to increased scrutiny now that he is a front-runner. ``i think he would welcome that,'' foley said. ``the question that remains for the jackson campaign is whether he is electable in the fall.''
foley said decisions by himself and others to withhold an endorsement at this point should not be interpreted as a stop-jackson signal
there is a little bit of a sense that if you are neutral, you are getting in the way of jesse jackson,'' he said. ``that's unfair.''
colorado, with caucuses on monday night, was drawing some politcal attention this weekend, including on the dormant republican side
pat robertson, who has all but conceded the nomination to george bush, scheduled three days of activities in colorado including talks at four easter sunday services. he has said he is determined to go to the gop convention in august with a block of delegates to influence the party platform and bush's choice of a running mate
jackson and dukakis also planned some activities this weekend in colorado. but the democrats were focused mainly on wisconsin and the two industrial-state primaries that follow later this month: new york and pennsylvania
gore spokesman mark armour said the campaign has had fund-raising surge that will allow gore to conduct a $1 million-plus campaign for new york's april 19 primary without taking out any new loans
a prosecutor running for judge in racially troubled robeson county on friday asked the governor not to call a special legislative session to let a minority candidate enter the race after the slaying of a lumbee indian contender
district attorney joe freeman britt declared himself the democratic nominee for superior court judge. britt, who is white and would have faced julian pierce in the may 3 democratic primary, would automatically win the judgeship in november because there is no republican candidate
britt met privately for an hour with gov. jim martin a day after supporters of pierce asked the republican governor for the special session. britt had no comment afterward except to say, ``you will have to get your information from the governor's office.''
martin's chief of staff, phil kirk, said britt had met with the governor at martin's request and had spoken ``very firmly'' against a special session
he considers himself to be the nominee of the democratic party for the ... judgeship,'' kirk told reporters
martin said he remained undecided and would discuss the matter with advisers and legislators over the weekend. he said he hoped to make a decision early next week
pierce was shot to death last week in what authorities described at first as a probable assassination. on tuesday, they arrested a young man and said a second suspect committed suicide, and attributed pierce's murder to a domestic dispute
under state law, if a candidate dies more than 30 days after filing for a primary has closed, his opponent wins. pierce's supporters want the law amended to allow a replacement candidate
the judgeship is one of nine created last year in districts designed to enhance minorities' prospects for winning
britt's supporters suggested that britt was a minority candidate since blacks and indians make up 58 percent of the registered voters in robeson county, kirk said. but he said that argument ``doesn't hold water'' because the legislature intended for whites to be outnumbered in the new districts
that's why they were created that way, to give minorities an excellent chance to be elected,'' kirk said
the support price for 1988-crop honey will average 59.1 cents per pound, down 6 percent from last year's level, agriculture secretary richard e. lyng announced friday
actual honey support prices will vary between about 48 cents to 62 cents per pound, depending on the color or class of honey offered by producers, lyng said. the price supports will be carried out through loans on honey stored on or off the farm
under the 1985 farm law, honey supports are being gradually reduced. last year's average loan rate was 63 cents per pound and the 1986 rate was 64 cents
lyng also said the 1988 program will retain the ``marketing loan'' provision to help reduce inventories held as surplus by the department's commodity credit corp
in earlier years, producers could redeem their honey only by paying off the full amount of the ccc loan, plus interest. they had the option of not repaying the loan at all, allowing ccc to assume ownership of the honey which had been offered as collateral
consequently, because of large supplies and low market prices, ccc inventories of forfeited honey increased rapidly
but since the 1985 law, a honey producer can take out a loan and then repay it at the prevailing market rate. in effect, this allows the beekeeper to sell honey to the government at a specified price and then buy it back at a lower price
currently, producers who obtained price support loans averaging 63 cents per pound for 1987 honey can pay off the loans at 34 to 40 cents per pound, depending on quality
lyng said the lower buy-back rates ``will be established at levels that will minimize loan forfeitures, reduce honey stocks and storage costs, and maintain the competitiveness of domestic honey in u.s. and export markets.''
the seventh national conference on humor opened on april fool's day without so much as a gag, practical joke or even a hint of buffoonery
the 70-odd scholars gathered friday at purdue university to dissect the fragile body of humor. these humor anatomists specialize in the brain more than the funnybone
this is serious business,'' said purdue linguist victor raskin, the conference chairman
how serious? well, have you heard the one about, ``the effects of a silent or laughing confederate and the amplification or inhibition of facial reactions on cartoon funniness evaluation?''
ball state university researchers lambert deckers and daniel moore planned to deliver a paper on that topic during the three-day conference
you don't have to be funny while you're presenting a paper,'' raskin said
he knows the public is puzzled by the paradox of ``excrutiatingly boring'' research on a topic that is mirth itself
he learned that lesson the hard way, ducking ripe tomatoes and rotten eggs hurled by the media after the first conference in the 1970s at arizona state university
the media decided that the humor conference was supposed to be hilarious,'' he said ruefully. ``so there was a full page report in time magazine on how boring it was, complete with a couple of pictures of back-benchers dozing off during presentations
well, we learned our lesson,'' he said
at the five conferences that followed at arizona state, reporters were invited to cover sessions featuring humorists and dynamic public speakers, while the real work was carried out in back rooms, he said
the media on the whole have been very happy with those conferences ever since,'' he said
there is something funny going on here, though. the meeting is called the whim conference, that's for western humor and irony membership
and, for those not celebrating passover on friday night, the program guide promised seating for ``an indefinite number of people'' at a beer and pizza place down the block. on sunday night, a three-hour joke-telling contest was scheduled
but why do these academics _ linguists, psychologists, anthropologists and sociologists _ do it?
raskin's answer is basically, ``why not?''
it's an important natural phenomenon,'' he said. ``it's a human faculty, and we study all the other faculties. we study the mind, we study emotions, we study our health and behavior. and humor is part of all that.''
while a comedian knows which material works, the professors want to know why
you don't expect a gymnast or a figure skater to come up with a scientific explanation on their failures or successes,'' said raskin. ``that's what we are for. we're trying to figure out what makes humor work
i know of no reseachers who have any ambition to become stand-up comedians,'' he said. ``most of us are professors, and we use a lot of humor in the classroom. but that's a matter of survival. if you don't, the students doze off on you and this is reflected in your teacher evaluations and salary raises.''
sixteen americans will receive literary awards from the american academy and institute of arts and letters, the academy announced friday
in addition, the academy announced that blake morrison of london will receive the e.m. forster award, given to an english writer for a stay in the united states
nine of the 16 awards include $5,000 purses given to encourage writers in their creative work
those nine are william barrett of north tarrytown; david bottoms of marietta, ga.; rosellen brown of houston, texas; david cope of grandville, mich.; john clellon holmes of old saybrook, conn.; john mccormick of princeton, n.j.; james seay of chapel hill, n.c.; william weaver of arezzo, italy; and norman williams of north ferrisburgh, vt
holmes died wednesday of cancer in middletown, conn., and the prize money will go to his estate, the academy said. holmes had been told of winning the prize
the other seven are andrew hudgins of montgomery, ala.; kaye gibbons of raleigh, n.c.; edward hirsch of houston; thomas mcmahon of wellesley, mass.; andre dubus of haverhill, mass.; jonathan evan maslow of mobile, ala., and clement greenberg of new york city
the awards will be given may 18
the government sued the nation's second largest meatpacker friday on a claim that it cheated tens of thousands of workers out of millions of dollars in overtime pay at 10 packinghouses in kansas, iowa, nebraska, minnesota and idaho
in a suit filed in kansas city, kan., the labor department accused ibp corp. of ``repeatedly and willfully'' violating laws requiring employers to pay hourly workers one and one-half times the normal wage for work beyond 40 hours a week
the suit seeks what the government claims is unpaid overtime plus interest stretching back to april 1985 for between 20,000 and 70,000 current and former employees of the company
government officials refused to specify how much the sought damages might total, but one acknowledged that it will likely be in the tens of millions of dollars
attorneys for the united food and commercial workers union, which is trying to organize some of the plants and initiated the labor department's action, calculated the possible back pay awards at between $20 million and $43 million
the suit is based on allegations that ibp workers were required by the company to spend up to two hours a week putting on, taking off and cleaning safety equipment and maintaining knives without being paid for their labor
based on hourly wages in the industry averaging $6 an hour, and assuming each worker was denied about two hours of overtime a week, the union calculated that each worker may be owed as much as $3,744 in back pay
full-time employment at the 10 plants is slightly less than 9,000 according to company officials. however, meatpacking has one of the highest job turnover rates of any industry in the country _ estimated by some at as much as 80 percent annually
gary mickelson, an ibp spokesman, said the company is ``confident the courts will find our policies entirely acceptable and lawful.''
he said ibp follows the same wage practices with regard to maintaining safety equipment at its three unionized plants and its 11 non-union packinghouses. none of the unionized plants was mentioned in the suit
it's the same procedure industrywide,'' mickelson said. ``the unions have negotiated away what the labor department thinks we should be paying.''
we find this action ironic,'' he added. ``on one hand our company has been widely criticized as not doing enough to ensure the safety of our employees. now we're being sued for making sure our employees take the time to wear the equipment necessary to protect them on the job.''
last summer the labor department fined ibp $2.6 million for alleged job safety and record violations at its flagship packinghouse at dakota city, neb
the investigation leading up to that fine, which has been appealed by the company, was prompted by another complaint that the union filed with the government while engaged in a strike at the dakota city plant
the suit friday alleged the wage law violations occurred at ibp plants in emporia and holcomb, kan.; madison and west point, neb.; luverne, minn.; denison, storm lake, council bluffs and columbus junction, iowa; and boise, idaho
the city's no. 2 symphony orchestra is canceling the rest of its 1988 concert season because of money troubles, only months after chicago's ballet company disintegrated
the orchestra of illinois, a highly praised group observing its 10th anniversary this season, announced thursday it is canceling its remaining seven performances because of a $410,000 deficit in its $650,000 budget
the situation is very serious,'' linda g. moore, the orchestra's executive director, said in a chicago tribune interview. ``our cash-flow position has been bad for some time, and it has gotten to the point where we literally don't have enough money to pay our musicians.''
just four months earlier, the chicago city ballet, the city's only classical ballet troupe, collapsed following an internal dispute over artistic directorship that alienated its chief financial supporter
but the two groups' failures do not necessarily cast a pall over the performing arts in general, observers say
one organization's problems do not necessarily reflect the community,'' said matthew raphaelson, director of the chicago music alliance, a service organization comprising 15 orchestras and dozens of other music groups such as operas and chamber music companies
we have 86 member organizations ... and many of them are doing quite well,'' said raphaelson. ``many are having their best years.''
the city also has been supporting 28 performing companies, including the now-defunct chicago city ballet, said lisa tylke, executive director of the chicago dance arts coalition, another service organization
dancers who lost jobs at chicago city ballet have followed its former artistic director, daniel duell, in an attempt ``to rise from the ashes'' with a new classical troupe called ballet chicago, ms. tylke said
the troupe has given one fundraising performance in its own behalf and is practicing for another in may
gregory mansfield, spokesman for the illinois arts council, a state agency that poured $2.2 million into performing arts last year, said the failures of the orchestra and the ballet are the only ones he is aware of in the state this year
those failures may end up as springboards to healthier organizations, he said
the orchestra of illinois has a record of artistic excellence and could resolve its problems, he said. the orchestra's board has ordered outside experts to analyze its financial affairs to see what can be done, he said
the arts council feels that by stopping to re-evaluate, an arts organization can often emerge actually better,'' mansfield said. ``and there are hundreds of arts organizations in chicago that are doing quite well, and i'm speaking of performing arts.''
raphaelson said setbacks for performing groups seem to generate more fear than problems with business organizations
when it happens in the arts community, people seem to get more nervous than if it were soft drinks or crackers,'' he said
he speculated that the reason is that arts groups depend more on fund raising and benefactors, who may be unduly frightened by negative signs
the solution, obviously, (for arts advocates) is to be ever more outspoken in their support for the arts,'' he said. ``if that fear is the reality, the problem is not so much a problem in the industry as a problem of perception.''
the united states and spanish governments have agreed to eliminate duplicate coverage and taxation under the two countries' social security systems, social security commissioner dorcas r. hardy announced friday
many u.s. citizens working in spain for u.s employers now pay social security contributions to both countries for the same work, and the same applies to many spanish nationals working in the united states
elimination of the overlapping requirements was effective friday
similar agreements were already in effect with belgium, canada, italy, norway, sweden, switzerland, the united kingdom and west germany. agreements have been signed with france and the netherlands and are expected to become effective later this year
fifty-five percent of those questioned said attorney general edwin meese iii should resign his post, according to a u.s. news &amp; world report poll released friday
only 21 percent of the respondents said meese should stay in office, the magazine said
fifty percent of those who considered themselves politically conservative said meese should quit, while only 27 percent of all conservatives believed he should stay, the magazine said
forty-six percent of republicans said meese should go, compared with only 28 percent who said he should continue. sixty-one percent of all democrats and 54 percent of all independents should meese should quit
meese, who has been under criminal investigation for 11 months, has been under pressure in congress this week to quit since two top aides left the justice department. the aides said meese's continuing legal problems were hurting the department's operations and image
the nationwide telephone poll of 1,004 adults, conducted by the roper organization on wednesday and thursday, has a margin of error of plus or minus four percentage points
the air force on friday rewrote its contracts covering development of the new midgetman mobile nuclear missile, canceling almost $1 billion worth of work planned by six contractors
the service, in a brief statement, stressed it could not speak for the six contractors involved but estimated the cutbacks could affect the jobs of as many as 2,300 private-sector employees
the air force action became inevitable several months ago when defense secretary frank c. carlucci decided the pentagon could not afford to develop and deploy the single-warhead midgetman within the budget levels set by the white house and congress
the air force had recommended carlucci kill the program outright, but the defense secretary decided to request $200 million in fiscal 1989 to keep the program alive pending a final decision by the next president
the house armed services committee, a major proponent of the new weapon, has already voted to increase that figure to $500 million in fiscal 1989. even if that figure is approved, however, the air force said it would not have enough money to sustain the program on its original schedule, leaving no choice but to rewrite the seven major development contracts held by the six firms
in order for the program to adhere to its original schedule, the air force would have needed about $2.2 billion this year and another $2.2 billion in fiscal 1989. congress provided $700 million for the midgetman this fiscal year
the biggest loser as a result of friday's action was the rockwell international corp. its autonetics division had a $484.2 million prime development contract for the missile's guidance and control system that was slashed by $374 million to $110.2 million
the other losers included:
_boeing aerospace co., under contract to develop the missile's mobile launcher, cut $278 million to a new total of $313.6 million
_martin marietta corp. it had two contracts, one to provide support and assembly services and the other to develop the warhead's ``post-boost vehicle and shroud.'' the first contract was cut $47 million to a new total of $76.9 million, while the second was cut $100 million to a new total of $244.5 million
_aerojet nevada rocket operations, developer of the stage 2 booster for the missile, cut $77 million to a new total of $103.7
_hercules inc., developer of the stage 3 booster, cut $72 million to a new total of $97.7 million
_morton thiokol, developer of the stage 1 booster, cut $51 million to a new total of $74.9 million
when all the reductions are added, they total $999 million, the air force said
republican presidential candidate pat robertson is spending easter weekend in colorado trying to drum up support for his dormant campaign
he will be making an appearance, encouraging people to go vote'' in colorado's caucuses on monday night, robertson state campaign coordinator david nelson said friday
robertson has conceded that he has virtually no chance of winning the republican nomination. but he plans to stay in the race in hopes he can influence the gop platform that will be drawn up at the national convention
he wants to represent conservatives and christians in the formation of the platform so we can have a voice,'' nelson said
in colorado, nelson hopes robertson can win one-third to one-half of the state's 36 gop delegates
he said up to 10 phone bank operators are trying to persuade at least 10,000 people to show up for the caucuses. ``our goal would be to have 15,000,'' he said
the former television evangelist's only strong showings have come in caucus states, where organization and depth of support count
robertson's three-day schedule here includes talks to an estimated 5,000 people in four denver-area congregations on easter sunday
robertson summed up his version of the easter message this way during a rally in a virginia beach, va., church last weekend: ``...some of the press have been saying that in terms of my candidacy that it is dead. what they don't know about is the resurrection.''
nelson said robertson wouldn't mix church and politics in his talks, although robertson's support has been derived primarily from fundamentalist christians
i don't think it's proper to go into a church and say, `vote for me.' i believe pat respects the rules and regulations involving churches and politics. he will just talk about how important it is to be involved in the political process,'' he said
attorneys for inmates of the u.s. penitentiary at marion asked an appeals court friday to end the prison's 4{-year lockdown, arguing that inmates are suffering physical and psychological brutality
prisoners are chained to their beds, spread-eagle, sometimes for days at a time,'' attorney nancy horgan argued before a three-judge panel of the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals
u.s. district judge james foreman, who heard the original class-action lawsuit filed on behalf of marion inmates, refused last february to grant an injunction ending the lockdown
foreman's ruling followed a 1985 decision by u.s. magistrate kenneth meyers that tight security at the prison dubbed the ``new alcatraz'' did not constitute cruel and unusual punishment and was necessary to protect inmates and staff
the lockdown was imposed in october 1983, following a bloody week in which two guards and an inmate were killed in separate incidents
since then, virtually all 350 inmates at the maximum-security penitentiary remain locked in 7-by-8-foot cells for 23 hours a day, although prisoners in certain tiers are given an additional four hours outside their cell each week
family contact visits aren't allowed. meals are delivered through a slot and are eaten by prisoners while sitting on the floor or on a bed because cells have no chairs or tables
attorneys for the inmates argued friday that the lockdown has become a permanent condition of imprisonment, and that marion officials use a capricious, arbitrary system in assigning prisoners to tiers and doling out limited privileges
prison officials counter that the lockdown is necessary because the prison houses the most unmanageable inmates in the federal prison system
most of them come from the segregation units at other federal prisons,'' assistant u.s. attorney ralph friederich told the judges. ``it is a place for inmates who have demonstrated an inability to control their conduct at other institutions.''
marion was built in 1963. in 1979, it was designated by the federal bureau of prisons as the first level 6 prison _ the system's most secure. it remains the only level 6 institution
the roster of high-profile inmates who have been imprisoned there and several spectacular escape attempts have led to its comparison to alcatraz, the fortress island prison in san francisco bay that was closed 25 years ago
before friday's hearing, about 50 demonstrators marched outside the federal building in support of the inmates, carrying signs reading ``prison system built on lies.''
stephen wittman, a spokesman for the committee to end the marion lockdown, which helped organize the demonstration and has provided legal and financial support to the legal case, contended the penitentiary was being used to silence political prisoners
they keep them as long as (they) can and each time we draw attention to an individual, they transfer them,'' he said
equally important, they hold marion over the head of all prisoners in the system,'' wittman contended. ``they use the prospect of going to marion to intimidate them into behaving the way they want them to.''
a 5-year-old who had a fractured skull when he died in january had complained in november of being hit with a flat board as punishment and asked to leave his foster home, according to state records
rosa lee jones, 40, was charged wednesday with second-degree murder and aggravated child abuse in the jan. 8 death of albert smith. she has not yet been arraigned and was jailed in lieu of $50,000 bond
police say the boy's skull was fractured when he was struck with a board for refusing to kneel to say his prayers
over an eight-year period mrs. jones was a foster mother to 14 children. in 1986 and 1987 she asked the state for a break, saying at one point she was ``stressed out,'' records of the state department of health and rehabilitative services show
before licensing mrs. jones, a state worker had only one reservation, about the woman's membership in the fundamentalist holiness faith
mrs. jones' religion is obviously very important to her and she might border on being somewhat fanatical,'' licensing analyst salley caro wrote in her study, the tampa tribune reported friday
she may tend to be a little rigid in some areas because she is a devout member of a fundamentalist religion. however, i do not feel that she will be unreasonable in her expectations of the children.''
the first placement in february 1980, a 13-year-old girl, left seven months later after she complained of being whipped with a belt
after a warning about corporal punishment, which is against hrs rules, mrs. jones took 13 more children over the next seven years
mrs. jones nursed the sores of a neglected boy, adopted three foster children, and accepted as many as seven children in her home at once, including mentally impaired children
hrs workers reported no problems in annual reviews of her home, called ``the cleanest home that has ever been seen'' by one worker
by january 1986, mrs. jones told state workers she needed a break from foster parenting and asked that no more children be placed in her home, hrs records show. she had three adopted children and was caring for two foster children
two more were placed but by june 1987 the home was returned to its scheduled capacity of five
three months later, a caller reportedly said mrs. jones was abusing albert smith
the boy tearfully told social workers he had been spanked with a board or a belt. but no marks were found, making it more a discipline problem than abuse, said joseph tagliarini, hrs administrator for hillsborough county
albert's school bus driver told hrs workers the child had started crying when he got close to jones' home
mrs. jones denied she hit albert, but admitted she was ``stressed out'' and asked to have her foster home closed
social workers were working hard to keep albert and his little brother together. they had no other foster homes available when albert asked to leave in november, records show
mrs. jones agreed to care for the children a little longer
we try to preserve a (foster care) placement,'' said tagliarini. ``maybe sometimes we try to preserve too much.'' employees</head>
taking advantage of an appeals court ruling earlier this week, the army on friday ordered a resumption of random drug testing of civilian employees in certain critical jobs
the directive went out today,'' said paige eversole, an army spokeswoman at the pentagon. ``it orders resumption of the program effective immediately.''
the move had been expected since tuesday, when a federal appeals court struck down a preliminary injunction that had stopped the drug-testing program a month ago
a three-judge panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals said it was staying the injunction granted to employee unions while it considered the legal merits of the case
the employee unions filed suit to stop a program under which any civilian worker in a so-called ``critical'' job can be tested at random for evidence of drug use. about 9,400 army civilians are currently subject to the testing because they work in such fields as security, aviation and law enforcement
men and women on active military duty have long been subject to random drug testing. the extension of that testing to civilian workers, however, began only last year
on march 1, u.s. district judge thomas f. hogan ruled against the army and issued a preliminary injunction to stop the random testing of civilians, concluding that the practice amounted to an ``excessively intrusive'' search prohibited by the constitution
hogan said that random checks of employees in sensitive positions could not be justified by safety concerns, because the urine test used by the army did not indicate whether an employee was using drugs on the job
the suit challenging the army was brought by public employee unions representing civilian army employees at fort stewart, fla.; aberdeen proving ground, md.; and the sharp army depot in lathrop, calif
the unions have vowed to pursue their challenge. no date has been set as yet for the appeals court to hear arguments in the case
television reporters, angered by the live telecast of a soccer match during a journalists' strike, staged a retaliatory walkout friday that halted all newscasts by the state-controlled rai network
the national journalists union backed the 24-hour blackout of televised news, calling rai's behavior ``a severe attack against the right to strike.''
rai telecast the exhibition soccer match between the national teams of italy and yugoslavia on thursday night, reportedly bowing to pressure from sponsors who had invested about $300,000 in advertising at the yugoslav stadium
the telecast was without comment and viewers could hear only the crowd noise
ninety minutes of mute soccer on television,'' wrote the milan newspaper corriere della sera in a front-page story critical of rai's decision
italian press and television journalists have been striking on and off for weeks to protest a breakdown in negotiations for a new labor contract
italy's major newspapers will not print saturday because of the continuing strikes
top policymakers at the federal reserve, faced with a weakening economy, decided to push interest rates slightly lower in late january and early february, according to minutes released friday
the minutes of the february meeting of the federal open market committee confirmed comments federal reserve chairman alan greenspan made to congress on feb. 23 that the fed had eased its grip on credit in an effort to stimulate economic growth at the beginning of the year
partly in response to that easing move, a variety of interest rates, including mortgage rates, fell by more than one-half percentage point. major banks lowered their prime lending rate on feb. 2 to 8.5 percent, the lowest level for this benchmark interest rate since mid-1986
the minutes of the feb. 9-10 meeting said the slight easing move was taken because of concerns at the time about a slowdown in business activity
the fed had moved immediately following the oct. 19 collapse of the stock market to push interest rates lower in an effort to keep the economy out of a recession. but then in december had begun tightening slightly out of fears that too much money in the economy would threaten higher inflation later in 1988
the fed minutes said the central bank believed it had room to lower interest rates further because the dollar's value had stabilized on foreign exchange markets after falling sharply at the end of 1987
the minutes said the slight easing occurred in late january and early february, prior to the february meeting. at that meeting, fed officials decided to leave policy unchanged
the open market committee met again tuesday and officials said they believed that the central bank once again decided to make no changes to monetary policy in light of the fact that the economy has been showing surprising strength in recent months
the labor department reported friday that the civilian unemployment rate fell to an eight-year low of 5.6 percent in march, down from 5.7 percent in february
greenspan, in recent comments, has said he doubts the jobless rate can fall much farther without threatening a round of renewed inflation
because of these statements, many economists believe the fed will not ease further for the rest of the year unless the economy takes an unexpected turn for the worse
the committee minutes said that for the period before the march meeting, the central bank would seek to ``maintain the slightly reduced degree of pressure on (bank) reserve positions sought in recent days.''
the fed influences interest rates through its control over how much money banks have on hand. by increasing bank reserves, the fed increases the amount of money banks have to lend and thus drives down the cost of that money
the members were in broad agreement that any substantial change in policy, in either direction, was not warranted under prevailing economic and financial conditions,'' the minutes said
the fed decision was approved on an 11-0 vote. there is one vacancy on the fed board
the february meeting also sets monetary targets for the year and the committee voted unanimously for growth targets of 4 percent to 8 percent for two broader measures of the money supply known as m-2 and m-3. these targets were revealed by greenspan during his congressional testimony
m-2 actually grew only 4 percent in 1987, substantially below the low point of the fed's target of 5.5 percent growth for last year. that event had spurred some reagan administration officials to complain that the central bank was not doing enough to keep the 5-year-old economic recovery alive
however, after greenspan publicly complained about pressure from the administration, the critics, including beryl sprinkel, chairman of the president's council of economic advisers have been silent in recent weeks
nasa flight medals honoring the seven astronauts who died in the challenger explosion more than two years ago were given friday to their families
the presentations were made during a ceremony a day after hundreds of people gathered at a celebrity-packed tribute and fund-raiser for the challenger center for space education
june scobee, widow of challenger commander dick scobee, said it would have been a ``tremendous moment'' for the astronauts if they had lived to receive the flight medals, along with framed certificates acknowledging work in the space program
their proudest moment was to be known as one of you (nasa),'' mrs. scobee said, choking back tears
we want to thank you,'' she added
the dream is alive,'' mrs. scobee said, apparently in reference to the challenger center project. ``and it's becoming not only a dream, but a reality.''
conceived and developed by family members of the crew, the educational center will offer teachers and students the opportunity to learn about space by participating in simulated space flights and missions at the flagship center in washington, d.c., and at satellite learning centers around the country
some $2.5 million has been raised for the center since the challenger explosion jan. 28, 1986, when all seven astronauts died
daniel c. brandenstein, chief of the astronaut office at nasa's johnson space center, said the medals are given to those who have ``made significant contributions to the manned space program.''
those appearing thursday night were the fabulous thunderbirds, melba moore, pia zadora, brooke shields, actor michael york, the houston pops, and michael maguire and brandy brown, who are starring on broadway's ``les miserables.''
american adults are expected to reduce their cigarette consumption again this year after a 2 percent drop in 1987, the agriculture department said friday
domestic cigarette consumption is likely to decline this year because of further price hikes, continued anti-smoking activity and increased restrictions on where people can smoke,'' the department's economic research service said in a report
american adults consumed an average 3,201 cigarettes last year, down from 3,274 in 1986, according to the preliminary figures. that was the lowest since world war ii. the peak was 4,345 cigarettes per person in 1963
officials caution that the per capita figures measure the average ``disappearance'' of cigarettes among those 18 years and older, including smokers and non-smokers alike. it is used to show changes from one year to another and does not indicate actual use among the smoking population
a military school student was hunted down and held at gunpoint by neighbors convinced he had kidnapped a 4-year-old girl, officials said
kenneth widel jr., 21, was jailed on a kidnapping charge and released friday on $2,500 bail. he said the child was going to show him where an old girlfriend of his lived in a subdivision near orlando
widel, a senior at the citadel in south carolina, was tracked down wednesday night by neighbors who were alerted by a 5-year-old friend of the little girl. widel's car was spotted, and a neighbor stopped it and forced widel to step out. the girl ran home
if words could kill, that guy would be dead,'' said the girl's mother, carolyn john-nurse. ``when i was cussing him out, he said, `i'm sorry, ma'm. i'm sorry, ma'm. i was just getting ready to bring her back.'''
widel's attorney, dan perry, said widel told his mother he had six beers when he drove to hunter's creek to look for a woman he knew only as samantha. widel stopped to ask whether the little girl or her friend, rachel anne newhart, 5, knew samantha
the lawyer said the little girl told widel she knew where samantha lived and volunteered to show him. she got into widel's car, and the other girl ran off, perry said
after a while, according to widel, the little girl decided she wanted to go home. widel took her back, and a band of neighbors confronted him at gunpoint and accused him of being a child molester, perry said
it was a simple misunderstanding that i can understand,'' the lawyer said. ``he obviously exercised poor judgment. he's a good kid.''
deputies believed rachel, a youngster with ``exceptional'' presence of mind, sheriff's spokesman randy means said thursday. she told her mother widel yanked the little girl into the car
there is no reason to doubt the 5-year-old's story. it is pretty much corroborated by the other little girl and neighbors who were around,'' sheriff's spokesman jim solomons said. ``she apparently didn't get in the car willingly.''
widel told police he didn't know samantha's last name. solomons said no one named samantha has come forward to substantiate widel's story
widel, who is 45 days from receiving a degree in electrical engineering, was on full scholarship until recently, said officials at the citadel, who refused to give out any other information
widel's mother, carol widel of kissimmee, said her son lost his scholarship when his grades dropped
of his arrest, she said, ``this is so far out of the ordinary that i don't know what to think. ... i'm utterly dismayed. he has a lot to contribute to society.''
solomons said no neighbors would be charged. ``you can't condone it, but you can't condemn'' what they did, he said. ``it apparently was the right thing to do in this case. it's not illegal to have a firearm, and this guy stopped a first-degree felony.'' attacks; picks up 6th grar pvs, ``associated press ...</note>
iran said friday a new iraqi chemical bomb attack on kurdish villages killed 75 people and wounded more than 100. it also said it accepted a u.n. call for a halt in the deadly ``war of the cities.''
the iranians claim 5,000 civilians were killed and the same number wounded in gas attacks two weeks ago
the official islamic republic news agency, monitored in cyprus, reported that iran earlier fired fired seven missiles into kirkuk, iraq's northern oil capital and basra, a southern port city. iraq said many civilians were killed or wounded in kirkuk
no iraqi missile firings were reported. iraq said thursday it would suspend attacks on iranian cities for three days, beginning at midnight, while prime minister turgut ozal of turkey is visiting baghdad
turkey has good relations with both iran and iraq, which have been at war since september 1980, and ozal has tried to mediate
tehran radio said friday that u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar asked iran to stop attacking residential areas in iraq. the request came in a meeting in new york with iran's acting u.n. ambassador, mohammad ja'afar mahallati, said the radio, monitored by the british broadcasting corp
it quoted mahallati as saying: ``in line with our usual policy, iran accepts this request. however, true to its usual ways, iraq will renew these attacks. therefore, the u.n. secretary-general must not confine himself to a mere request.''
the statement appeared to represent a call for u.n. action to force iraq to end its attacks
associated press photographer greg english reported from kurdistan that iran's revolutionary guards were pushing westward into the strategic region of iraq as part of an offensive begun march 16
a dispatch from iran's islamic republic news agency said iranian jet fighters flew seven sorties against iraqi troop concentrations in the region friday, inflicting ``substantial casualties and losses.''
irna said iraqi warplanes dropped bombs containing nerve and mustard gases in the qara dagh region of northeast iraq on march 21-26
it quoted sources among iranian-backed kurdish guerrillas as identifying the villages affected as susiyan, doukan, balakha, jafaran and oliyan
there was no independent confirmation or comment from iraq
qara dagh is 15 miles west of the front in the kurdistan mountains
iran claims the thousands of casualties from chemical attacks were caused march 16-17 in three towns captured by iranian forces
western correspondents who visited one of the towns, halabja, last week reported seeing hundreds of bodies unmarked by bullet or shrapnel wounds. hundreds more iraqi kurds with severe burns and respiratory ailments, consistent with exposure to poison gas, have been seen in tehran hospitals
on thursday, iran claimed iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs on marivan in northwest iran, killing civilians
irna said missiles were fired friday at basra and at a ``military target'' in kirkuk ``in retaliation for iraqi missile attacks on iran's residential areas.''
iraq reported only one missile hitting kirkuk, 80 miles west of the battle zone in the kurdistan mountains. the official iraqi news agency said it exploded in a residential district, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including women and children.''
more than 250 missiles have been fired by both sides since the latest ``war of the cities'' began feb. 29, killing hundreds of civilians
in the kurdistan campaign, officers of iranian revolutionary guards said their forces had bottled up 5,000 iraqi soldiers around a hydroelectric dam on lake darbandikhan, 80 miles east of the kirkuk oil fields. the dam and power station provide most of the region's electricity and some power to baghdad
english, who was with western correspondents flown to the battle zone thursday, quoted revolutionary guards commander asgar ahmadi as saying his men were within five miles of the highway between the provincial capital of sulaymaniyah and baghdad, 160 miles to the southwest
ahmadi claimed sulaymaniyah was within range of iranian artillery
sulaymaniyah, which has a population of 100,000, is northwest of the darbandikhan region, where the iranians said several days ago they had captured 540 square miles of territory
the iranians claim to have killed or wounded 12,000 iraqis, captured more than 4,500 and destroyed more than 200 tanks and armored vehicles
english reported from the kurdish town of dojaila, captured on the second day of the offensive that he could hear artillery fire to the west and it was clear ``the iranians have made significant gains.''
here is a transcript of attorney general edwin meese iii's news conference friday
good afternoon
i indicated yesterday, when we were at the fbi, that i would meet with you in due course
and although my time is limited, i know that some of you, perhaps all of you, are on deadline
i did want to make myself available before the end of the week to take a few questions
before doing so, i would like to announce that early next week, we will be holding a press conference
terry eastland will let you know as to the details of that conference
and at that time, i will have with me certain individuals who will be filling key positions here in the department
now, let me also say that i have been gratified by the action and the statement issued earlier today by independent counsel james mckay
in addition to that, my attorney, nathan lewin, has also commented on it, and i would refer any questions you might have on that subject to those two statements and to mr. lewin
as i have said on many occasions, the purpose of an independent counsel is to review all allegations that may be outstanding and that all of us should await the determinations of the independent counsel
for that reason, i would certainly urge that there be no rush to judgment, but i am gratified by the statement that has been issued today
with that, i'll be glad to answer any questions. yes?
q. mr. attorney general, people in and out of the department have commented that the appearance of propriety is important as propriety itself. and therefore, that a law enforcement officer who is under investigation ought to step aside while that investigation is under way. can you tell us why you have not stepped aside, and what message that sends to other law enforcement officers who may find themselves in a similar position?
a. well, the purpose of the independent counsel process is to enable people to go on about their duties and, at the same time, to have an independent and fair evaluation of whatever allegations may be pending
that's the process, that is the way it should work, and that's the way it is working in this case
and therefore, there is no reason _ as a matter of fact, if a person has to step aside merely on the basis of some allegation, however false, then it would be easy for unscrupulous persons to make allegations and therefore literally cause people to step aside and move out of their offices
q. are mr. burns and mr. weld unscrupulous persons?
a. i beg your pardon?
q. are mr. burns and mr. weld unscrupulous persons?
a. are they unscrupulous persons? no
q. why did mr. burns and mr. weld resign?
a. well, they've already indicated that they are resigning to go back into private practice
let me say that there were some basic differences as to the effect that recent events have had on the department
and beyond that, i think their resignations are going to have to speak for themselves
q. were those recent events the investigations, sir?
a. i beg your pardon?
q. could you elaborate _
a. i say, there was a difference as to the impact that recent events had on the department
in part, they were the fact that there is an independent counsel investigation, yes
police charged a 31-year-old builder friday with conspiracy in the kidnapping of a lebanese businessman, who escaped unharmed two days earlier from a rural bungalow where he was held for 24 hours
the kidnappers demanded 5 million swiss francs ($3.7 million) as ransom for ramzi ata dalloul, scotland yard said. dalloul, 52, is head of rad projects and developments, a management consulting firm
dalloul's captors apparently did not know he had escaped and made ransom calls to the man's home after he was gone, police said
anti-terrorist detectives arrested a man who accompanied dalloul to his home in london's fashionable kensington district wednesday night. derek stanley bumbridge, 31, was charged friday with conspiring ``with persons unknown'' to kidnap dalloul and was to appear in court on saturday
scotland yard would not comment on media reports that the man was dalloul's only guard and helped in the escape
police said dalloul believed at least five men were involved, four britons and one who spoke arabic
he was seized tuesday night after his car was rammed on the way home from his office in london's west end, and driven for about 15 minutes before being bundled into the back of a white van and bound
dalloul was taken to a bungalow in tenterden, kent, about 40 miles southeast of london, where he was handcuffed while one man stood guard
the kidnappers telephoned dalloul's wife, saeda, late tuesday night demanding the ransom and she told scotland yard shortly afterward
on wednesday evening, the kidnappers again contacted mrs. dalloul, repeating their demand and explaining the method of payment, police said
forty-five minutes later, dalloul telephoned his wife to say he had escaped and was on his way home, police said. he turned up about two hours later
pope john paul ii, carrying a black wooden cross, led a torchlight procession at the colosseum friday night that symbolically retraced christ's walk to his crucifixion
tens of thousands of people gathered to watch the via crucis, the way of the cross ritual that ends the saddest day of the roman catholic year
john paul began the walk inside the great arena, where tradition says ancient romans threw christians to the lions. he proceeded up cobblestone steps and ended on the edge of the roman forum, once the meeting place of rome's leaders
thousands of people followed the service from behind barricades marking the pope's path, reading from prayer booklets illuminated by candlelight. many added their voices to the chorus that chanted the service
during the walk, john paul pressed the 5-foot cross, which weighed only a pound, to his forehead as he marked the 14 stations of the cross that represent the physical torment and mockery jesus endured as he walked to his death
the stations include the three times christ fell under the weight of the cross, the placing of the crown of thorns and whipping by jailers
john paul, wearing a white skullcap and gold-trimmed cape over a white cassock, was illuminated at the beginning of the procession by torches placed in the colosseum's arches
descriptions of the various stations were read in italian, french, english, german, spanish and portuguese and in the pope's native language, polish
vatican radio and italian state-run television carried the event live. the television said it was transmitted to 27 countries on five continents
earlier friday, the pontiff heard confessions from 11 pilgrims and tourists in st. peter's basilica in keeping with a good friday tradition he began in 1979, during his first easter week as pope
several hundred people were waiting when he appeared in the basilica shortly after noon and stepped into one of the hand-carved mahogany confessional booths
for 70 minutes, he heard confessions from, among others, an italian family of three, a 59-year-old contractor from the netherlands and his daughter, and a 22-year-old student from california
two small planes collided friday and crashed, killing one person and critically injuring another, authorities said. one plane landed safely with four people aboard
we were climbing out toward the ocean. ... then all of a sudden there was a tremendous explosion. the windshield blew out,'' said bob bruce, 38, of camarillo, pilot of plane that landed safely. ``i looked over and there was another airplane that looked like it was descending; on its way down.''
bruce's rented plane, a cessna sky hawk, was damaged but landed at camarillo airport. he suffered facial cuts when the windshield shattered, said ventura county sheriff's lt. lou mccombs
a cessna 172 crashed in a rural area 65 miles west of los angeles, said nona makinson, operations manager at camarillo airport. one man aboard that plane died and another was in extremely critical condition, said spokeswoman millie schofield of ventura county medical center
bruce, who has eight years of flying experience, said he was on a sightseeing flight over the ocean when the collision occurred. his passengers, including boys ages 4 and 5, were not hurt
the national transportation and safety board was investigating the crash
