sandinista soldiers and contra rebels on friday began observing a 60-day cease-fire designed to give both sides time to arrange a permanent peace in their 6{-year-old war
a spokesman for the defense ministry said there were no reports of violations of the truce, which began after midnight thursday
the cease-fire provision was contained in a peace agreement signed march 23 in the border outpost of sapoa, but details remained to be worked out
soldiers for both the leftist government and the u.s.-backed rebels had been observing a temporary truce since march 21 while negotiators hammered out the peace agreement
an associated press reporter in northern nicaragua reported no signs of battle friday
we want a truce,'' said a rebel leader known as comandante ernesto, one of a group of contra leaders huddled in front of a wooden shack in the village of la vigia. ``this cease-fire is the first step toward peace.''
nearby, sandinista troops meandered down winding dirt roads
the heaviest fighting of the war has been around la vigia, 120 miles northeast of managua, and other parts of the mountainous north
in washington, president reagan signed a $48 million non-lethal aid package for the contras, but it probably will be at least two weeks before the rebels begin receiving supplies under the new legislation
there certainly is an urgent need among the (rebels) for medical supplies, food, clothing, the basic commodities of life,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater. ``this bill is very welcome in that regard.''
u.s. aid to the contras ran out on feb. 29
there was no immediate comment from the sandinista government on the bill. most offices were closed for good friday observances in the predominantly roman catholic country
many nicaraguans marked the long easter weekend by taking vacations at beaches on the pacific coast. banks, government offices, stores and most restaurants were closed until monday
managua's three newspapers stopped publishing for the weekend
ortega charged thursday that the united states will try to undermine the nicaraguan peace process because negotiations ``debilitate the politics'' of the reagan administration
the (reagan) administration maintains in its thinking the decision to destroy ... the nicaraguan revolution and not to normalize relations with nicaragua,'' ortega said
on tuesday, ortega urged the united states to hold talks to normalize relations with his government
the peace agreement calls for contra rebels to gather in cease-fire zones during the first 15 days of april but left the conditions to be arranged in later talks
earlier this week, both sides held discussions on the cease-fire and agreed to set up two zones in the northern part of the country, two on the caribbean coast and one in the south
contra leader aristides sanchez said both sides had agreed not to pinpoint the exact locations
negotiations between the technical committees are set to begin at sapoa again tuesday to determine the size of the zones and operating rules for contras within the areas. still to be decided is how the contras will lay down their arms
under the peace agreement signed march 23, the sandinistas will grant freedom of expression and amnesty to political prisoners and will allow rebel leaders to take part in national talks
the contras, in turn, agreed to go to the cease-fire zones and accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization, such as the international red cross
on sunday, the sandinista government released 100 political prisoners from managua's zona franca prison as part of a three-stage amnesty agreement for the estimated 3,300 political prisoners
the sandinistas came to power in a revolution that ousted the pro-american, rightist regime of the late president anastasio somoza in july 1979. the united states supported the sandinistas initially, but in 1981 began financing the contras
protestants and roman catholics marched together through london, dublin and belfast on good friday and prayed for an end to sectarian violence
cardinal basil hume asked london marchers to pray for political leaders of britain, northern ireland and the irish republic who seek an end to the strife
today, as never before, healing is needed not only in grief-stricken ireland but here in the heart of london, since we are sadly but inevitably part of the problem,'' he said
the violence has always been the work of the few at the expense of the many who want nothing better than to live at peace with their neighbors.''
referring to the latest killings in northern ireland, hume said: ``for the sake of the future of our countries, there must be a renewed attempt to build a better society. this is no time to match violence with violence even in the face of real or perceived injustice.''
thirteen people have been killed in the province since march 6, when british soldiers killed three irish republican army guerrillas in gibraltar
the mainly catholic ira is fighting to drive the british out of northern ireland, where protestants are a majority, and unite the province with the irish republic
archbishop of canterbury robert runcie, spiritual leader of the church of england, sent a message of peace to the 200 people who marched silently from the catholic westminster cathedral to westminster abbey
i pray that the people of ireland and england will forgive each other for the hurts and wrongs done in the past and find in today's common action a deeper unity of spirit,'' he said
about 400 people marched through belfast and 1,000 in the center of dublin
northern ireland police said three people were arrested in belfast after stones and eggs were thrown at people marching from falls road, a catholic district, to shankill road, a protestant stronghold
the incident was over very quickly,'' a spokesman said
a. well, i doubt that it's very widely held, and i have had so many expressions to me personally to the contrary so that i think that the action i'm taking is in the best interests of the department, and i'm satisfied with that. yes?
