jesse jackson has maintained a slight advantage over massachusetts gov. michael dukakis among texas democratic convention delegates, who will pick 64 delegates to the party's national convention
presidential candidates have to compete twice for delegates from texas, once in the state's march 8 primary and again in a series of caucuses and conventions which begin that day. while the primary results governed allocation of 119 national delegates, another 64 were at stake through the caucuses
dukakis, who won the primary, was lagging behind jackson in state convention delegates in a nearly complete count issued by the party on thursday
of the 5,037 state delegates counted so far, jackson led with 1,722, dukakis had 1,666 and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 915. another 251 state convention delegates remain to be counted
houston may host the first of four scheduled debates between the 1988 presidential nominees this fall, but vice president george bush's campaign has not committed to participate in it
bush spokesman pete teeley said the vice president, the expected gop nominee, intends to debate the democratic nominee, but only on his terms and at a site chosen by the candidates, not the parties. but he said thursday it would be premature to discuss which cities bush, who calls houston home, would consider
since last july the democratic and republican national parties have heavily promoted the series of debates and are scouting potential sites
but donald ward, coordinator of the city's bid, said further delay in an announcement of debate sites may force houston to drop its effort to host the event. this includes the release of 2,500 local hotel rooms and the third floor of the george r. brown convention center which have been held since october in anticipation of the debate, he said
iowa democratic party leaders vowed friday to crush an attempt by political extremist lyndon larouche's supporters to use the party's mantle in the june primary, even if it means urging voters to go republican in some cases
to us, these people are political poison and we are going to beat them,'' said party spokesman phil roeder
they apparently feel this is fertile ground, but we are going to teach them a major lesson,'' said joe shanahan, who runs legislative elections for the party
their alarm grew out of the number of larouche supporters filing nomination papers to run in the june 8 primary for legislative and congressional seats. the party leaders said they identified 16 larouche backers who met friday's filing deadline
larouche supporters could win the democratic nomination in some legislative districts because no other democrats are running
if that happens, roeder said, ``we will encourage people to vote against them.''
groups and individuals are spending more money overall on independent campaigns for congressional candidates, but are spending less on negative ads, the federal election commission has found
a survey of 1985-86 election spending patterns revealed that independent expenditures for house and senate candidates was $9.3 million, up from $5.9 million in 1983-84
independent expenditures, in which a person or group buys advertising or otherwise campaigns for the candidate, are legal as long as the person making the expenditure does not coordinate with the candidate's campaign
in the 1986 congressional elections, independent expenditures against congressional candidates totalled $1.3 million, compared to $2.6 million in 1984
independent expenditures in favor of candidates totalled $8 million, up from $3.3 million spent in the last election
meese received other good news friday when solicitor general charles fried said he would remain at the justice department, even though fried reportedly urged meese to resign earlier in the week
i have concluded that while i am able to lead'' the solicitor general's office ``i should continue to do so,'' fried said. the new york times reported that fried had urged meese to quit wednesday but that meese had rejected the suggestion. fried's statement did not endorse meese
the independent counsel said that if at the end of his investigation there remains ``insufficient evidence to warrant a prosecution as to these or any other matters'' he will issue a report covering all the matters which have been under investigation
based on the evidence developed to date, he (mckay) does not intend to recommend that the grand jury return an indictment against meese as to the `aqaba pipeline' matter or as to matters relating to mr. meese's investments, including the so-called `baby bells' matter,'' mckay's statement said
if he issues a report without obtaining an indictment, mckay said he would ``refer all of those matters for review and action by the appropriate administrative authorities,'' an apparent reference to office of government ethics procedures
the ethics office has put its investigation on hold of meese's initial failure to disclose investments in the ``baby bell'' companies pending mckay's probe, said deputy director donald campbell
if that proceeding is revived, the office could move to have meese make a complete disclosure of those holdings, campbell said
nathan lewin, one of meese's lawyers representing him in the criminal investigation, criticized what he called ``speculation and uninformed judgments by others that have appeared in the media.''
today's announcement by the independent counsel should encourage everyone to continue abiding by the process,'' justice department spokesman terry eastland said. ``it is very important for the rule of law that we allow the process that the congress has ordained by enacting the independent counsel statute to continue to run its course.''
mckay has been investigating whether meese conspired with wallach and others to violate the foreign corrupt practices act in connection with an alleged scheme to pay the israeli government and the country's labor party to protect a proposed $1 billion oil pipeline from military attack by israel
four months after enlisting meese's assistance on a $1 billion iraqi pipeline project, wallach wrote the attorney general a memo saying that a portion of up to $700 million from the pipeline would be paid to the israeli labor party of then-israeli prime minister shimon peres. the pipeline was never built
wallach at the time was legal counsel to swiss oilman bruce rappaport, a partner in the project and a longtime close friend of peres
meese has contended he never read the portion of wallach's memo referring to labor party payments, rappaport says he never suggested any such plan and peres says he was never offered any money
mckay also has been investigating meese's ownership of stock in companies created by the breakup of at&amp;t when he was in a position to make policy affecting the telecommunications industry
meese as attorney general met with executives of four of the regional bell telephone companies at a time when he owned $14,000 worth of stock in the baby bells, raising conflict-of-interest questions
at the time, the bell companies were seeking a reversal of the justice department's position opposing the bells' expansion into new areas of business. meese ended up approving a reversal of the department's position early in 1987 in accordance with the companies' wishes
meese says he had intended to sell the stock in 1985 but was unable to do so because he had lost the stock certificates. on his financial disclosure forms for 1985 and 1986, meese listed the bell stocks as having been sold. the fact that he still owned them wasn't uncovered until last summer, when pressure from congress forced the attorney general to disclose the details of his financial holdings
in december, mckay's office issued a similar annnouncement stating there was insufficient evidence at that time to bring criminal charges against meese in connection with his efforts to help the scandal-plagued wedtech corp. get defense contracts
a storm spread snow up to 10 inches of snow from the southern rockies to the southern plains on friday, and heavy rain ahead of the storm raised a threat of flooding
snow fell over the southeastern third of colorado, the northeastern half of new mexico, the texas panhandle, the oklahoma panhandle and western kansas
there were reports of 10 inches of snow over sections of the texas panhandle and 6 inches of snow at ulysses, kan., the national weather service said
in oklahoma, the range was from 5 inches near boise city to 10 inches near guymon. amounts in colorado were mostly around 3 inches or less
the snow closed some highways in the texas and oklahoma panhandles
ahead of the snow, rain and thunderstorms extended from the remainder of kansas and oklahoma into eastern texas, producing marble-size hail in oklahoma. ground in the southern half of the plains was already saturated and flash flood watches were posted over northeastern and central oklahoma and the southeastern quarter of kansas
the caney river was expected to crest during the night at bartlesville, okla., at about 3 feet above flood stage. the neosho river was expected to crest about 4 feet above flood stage sunday evening at commerce, okla., and oswego, kan
showers extended across northeastern texas, the lower two-thirds of the mississippi valley, the ohio valley, the tennessee valley, eastern mississippi, alabama, western georgia, northern pennsylvania and southern new york state
elsewhere, rain continued over the northern oregon coast
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 26 degrees at yellowstone national park, wyo., to 85 degrees at kingsville, texas. the early morning low for the nation was zero at yellowstone national park
for saturday, rain and occasional thunderstorms were forecast from new jersey across pennsylvania, the ohio valley and the tennessee valley, from the northwestern half of georgia across the florida panhandle, alabama, mississippi and southeastern louisiana, and from iowa across missouri, northern arkansas, the east-central plains, illinois, southern wisconsin and lower michigan. scattered rain was forecast over the northern pacific coast
highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted over new england, the great lakes, the upper mississippi valley, the central plains, oklahoma, the texas panhandle and the southern rockies, as well as the pacific northwest; in the 80s over the florida peninsula, southern texas, central california and the desert southwest, and in the 60s and 70s over the remainder of the nation
the federal aviation administration on friday ordered a $632,200 civil fine for numerous safety violations against orion air, the cargo airline that is being sought out to fly passengers in case of a strike at eastern airlines
the civil penalty stemmed from violations of federal aviation regulations uncovered during an inspection of orion air's operations a year ago. the faa said the violations have since been corrected, although the agency is still reviewing whether to allow the airline to fly passengers
the north carolina-based cargo airline became the object of controversy in recent months after it entered into an agreement to fly passengers on eastern airlines' routes if eastern becomes the target of a strike by machinists and pilots
eastern's unions have charged that the tactic is a violation of labor law. earlier this week a federal judge ordered eastern to halt the training of non-union orion pilots under the contract with eastern, putting the future of eastern's plans with orion air into doubt
the faa said its fine stemmed from practices by orion air that involved operating some aircraft that did not meet federal airworthiness requirements and allowing pilots to fly too many hours in violation of federal duty-time limits
for example, the agency said, an orion air boeing 727 was found to have flown 1,193 flights while violating an airworthiness requirement involving the plane's mechanism that adjusts wing slats. slat position is critical in an aircraft's takeoff because it affects lift
in another example cited by the faa, some pilots of orion air were found to have flown slightly more than 100 hours during a single month. the faa requires that no pilot fly more than 100 hours during a 30-day period and most commercial passenger airlines schedule their pilots to no more than 70 to 75 hours per month
the faa said in a statement that orion air, which has its headquarters in raleigh, n.c., ``moved quickly to correct the deficiencies (discovered during the inspection) and is now in compliance with the (federal) regulations.''
a request that orion air be given a certificate to fly passengers is still pending before the agency, said faa spokesman fred farrar
few travelers likely have heard of orion air, which has 55 jet aircraft and serves such air freight companies as united parcel service, emery air freight and purolator
in an attempt to blunt the effects of a strike, eastern earlier this year disclosed that it was leasing 26 of its jets to orion air. eastern officials called the move ``insurance'' that would allow the cargo airline to fly passengers on eastern routes if pilots honor a possible strike by eastern's machinists
the faa acknowledged during congressional hearings in february that it found numerous safety violations at orion air during its inspection in april and march, 1987
at the time, orion officials acknowledged the violations, but said that the problems had been corrected
orion officials could not immediately be reached for comment on the civil penalties announced by the faa friday
gov. evan mecham stayed at his suburban ``government in exile'' friday as state senators prepared for the weighty decision of whether to remove the impeached governor from office
mecham, who has been giving speeches and making campaign trips, stepped out of the spotlight friday as his senate impeachment trial approached final arguments, and possibly a vote, on monday
there will be nothing over the weekend,'' said a secretary at mecham's office in suburban glendale. ``he is in the office just working on things here.''
at the senate building, which was officially closed for good friday, republican majority leader robert usdane was at his desk, poring over legal instructions and a trial memorandum from the prosecution
he insisted he has not made up his mind whether mecham is guilty or innocent
the first-term republican is charged with attempting to obstruct an investigation of an alleged death threat by one of his staffers and misusing $80,000 from a protocol fund by loaning it to his car dealership
i have to go back and look at the evidence again,'' usdane said. ``nothing hit me between the eyes, so i'm going to have to go back and see what's there.''
usdane said he found the second charge regarding the $80,000 loan ``heavier.''
there's more involvement by the governor. more people testified,'' he said, adding that testimony by mecham's former chief of staff, jim colter, contradicted the governor's
usdane said his greatest concern was that his senate colleagues not be swayed by phone calls from constituents urging them to vote one way or the other or face retribution at the ballot box
when it comes down to the bottom line, people will make a decision and not let what is going to happen to them politically change that decision,'' usdane said. ``at least that's what i hope.''
politics was evident this week when the 11 democratic senators voted as a bloc wednesday to dismiss the third impeachment count against mecham. democrats said they wanted to get the trial over in advance of the may 17 gubernatorial recall election. if he is removed from office, mecham will not be able to run
five republicans who have consistently voted on the governor's side joined the democrats to dismiss the count, which accused him of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
mecham also faces an april 21 criminal trial on felony charges of concealing the campaign loan
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate would be required to convict mecham, the first u.s. governor impeached in six decades. another two-thirds vote could bar him for life from holding elective office in arizona
clergyman carrying crosses led hundreds of people on a silent march through downtown durban friday to protest the white-led government's new restrictions on anti-apartheid groups
in a separate development, police reported that a white constable was fatally stabbed overnight by a group of blacks while on foot patrol in pinetown west, on the outskirts of durban. no details about the attack were released
nearly 1,000 people participated in the march at dawn. nineteen people wore gags to symbolize restrictions that banned the opposition newspaper new nation and major organizations opposed to apartheid, under which the black majority has no voice in national affairs
many voices which stand for justice are being silenced in our country, and we commit ourselves to ensure that those voices may be heard once again,'' said miriam cele of the dependents' conference, which assists the families of detainees
among those addressing the protesters at church services before and after the march was archie gumede, co-president of the united democratic front, south africa's largest anti-apartheid coalition and one of the groups banned from all activity in february
gumede was issued an individual restriction order limiting his political activities
other speakers at the services were roman catholic archbishop denis hurley and the rev. stanley mogoba, general secretary of the methodist church
after the march, women from the black sash civil rights organization planted crosses on the beach opposite regional army headquarters to protest monday's commando raid in botswana in which four people were killed
south africa said the victims were guerrillas of the outlawed african national congress, the main guerrilla group fighting apartheid. botswana says three of those killed were botswanan citizens
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
q. there are reports that first lady nancy reagan would like to see you go. what can you tell us about your relations with mrs. reagan?
a. i have always had a very good relationship with mrs. reagan and that still continues
q. you say you've had strong support in congress and yet everything we've heard in the public record except for maybe one or two senators who have supported you has been quite critical, especially among republicans who say that you are hurting the party and you are doing a disservice to the president. do you not feel that in a political election year, perhaps you should step, if not down, aside?
a. i can only tell you what people have told me, and as i say, they come from both sides of the aisle
q. are you troubled by what senator thurmond told you yesterday?
a. no, senator thurmond was very helpful and i'm very appreciative with my conversations with him
q. have any of these problems been caused by any mistakes of your own? and if so, what is wrong?
