here is the text of the statement issued friday by the office of independent counsel james c. mckay regarding the investigation of attorney general edwin meese iii:

james c. mckay, the independent counsel investigating attorney general edwin meese iii, in order to clarify the current status of this criminal investigation, announced today that, based on the evidence developed to date, he does not intend to recommend that the grand jury return an indictment against mr. meese as to the `aqaba pipeline'' matter or as to the matters relating to mr. meese's investments including the so-called ``baby bells'' matter
this announcement is being made because of recent media reports that an indictment is imminent
mr. mckay has previously made a similar announcement with respect to the wedtech matter
mr. mckay emphasized, however, that the grand jury's investigation is not yet complete as to these and other matters, and will continue at least through the end of april
if at the end of that period of time there remains insufficient evidence to warrant a prosecution as to these or any other matters, and if the grand jury and the office of independent counsel concur that further investigation is not warranted, the office of independent counsel will issue a report covering all the matters which have been under investigation
also, in that event, mr. mckay will refer all of those matters for review and action by the appropriate admnistrative authorities. annually</head>
a nasa scientist said friday he found new evidence supporting a controversial theory that millions of small, dark, water-bearing comets strike earth's atmosphere every year
other scientists remained skeptical, but physicist clayne yeates, of nasa's jet propulsion laboratory, said: ``i'm very convinced that what i'm seeing is real. ... these objects would not have been seen inadvertently during other searches. they're small, they're dark and they're moving fast.''
the theory was first proposed in 1986 by university of iowa physicist louis frank, who said friday he was met with ``total disbelief'' and ``lost a lot of friends'' because of it
i'm happy (about yeates' observations), but it's been a long two years,'' frank said by telephone from iowa city
a nasa news release called frank's hypothesis ``one of the decade's most controversial astronomical theories.''
frank proposed the theory after ultraviolet photographs of earth taken by the national aeronautics and space administration's dynamics explorer 1 spacecraft in 1981-86 revealed countless dark spots that appeared to be tiny holes in earth's atmosphere
frank theorized that about 10 million comets, essentially 30-foot-diameter fluffy snowballs with a dark coating, plunge into the atmosphere each year, forming holes then breaking up and vaporizing
he hypothesized that during earth's early history, billions of the tiny comets would have provided enough water to fill all the oceans
yeates said his observations on the 36-inch spacewatch telescope at kitt peak national observatory in arizona make him believe that at least a million such comets hit the atmosphere annually at a speed of 22,000 mph
the comets appeared as white streaks on enhanced telescope images, said yeates, who is deputy project scientist for the planned 1989 launch of the galileo space probe to jupiter
i'm a little skeptical,'' said astronomer anita cochran, of the university of texas at austin. ``he (yeates) may be seeing something, but to leap to 10-meter comets is a fairly large leap of imagination.''
frank said a soon-to-be-published study, in which atmospheric holes were recently observed by sweden's viking spacecraft, also supports his theory
university of michigan physicist and planetary scientist thomas donahue said: ``i'm not going to say this sounds like confirmation of frank's comets or not. but it certainly is exciting.''
about a year ago, donahue used 1977 data from the voyager 2 space probe to show that earth's atmosphere contained an excess of hydrogen atoms released from water vapor. he said the discovery could be consistent with frank's theory, but also could be explained if the hydrogen was freed from 10 million times fewer comets that were smaller, faster but much more active than those postulated by frank
the less abundant comets wouldn't provide enough water to fill the oceans, donahue said
i really am a bit skeptical'' of yeates' observations, said brian marsden, associate director for planetary sciences at the harvard-smithsonian center for astrophysics in cambridge, mass
if they (comets) are as numerous as he's talking about, then some of these should show up when the telescope is in more normal operation, and they haven','' marsden said
frank replied that only two specialized telescopes in the country, including spacewatch, are capable of observing the comets
cochran voiced the most common objection to frank's theory: if so many icy comets hit earth's atmosphere, they also should strike the moon, creating a lot of water vapor. yet the moon has very little water vapor
yeates said his observations are consistent with frank's theory that the comets orbit the sun in the same direction as earth, and that they are very dark, reflecting only 2 percent of the sunlight that hits them
despite the large number of such comets, there is so much space around earth that they would strike any single spacecraft only once every 100 million years, he said
a group of hungarian students has established an independent youth group intended as an alternative to the communist youth organization kisz, one of the students reported friday
the objective ... is to create a new autonomous and independent youth organization for the politically active ... reform-minded youth groups,'' said a statement issued by the group, according to miklos andrasi
andrasi, 25, a recent university graduate in economics, said by telephone from budapest that the group was formally established wednesday. he said it has 37 members so far and that it wants to work for a ``new hungary.''
andrasi said kisz has been losing influence among the country's youth. he said the new group, fidesz _ the alliance of young democrats _ would accept communist party members
the group hoped to talk to representatives of kisz soon about the possibility of cooperating, he said, but it rejects the idea of membership in both organizations
there have been increased calls in hungary for more pluralism and political reforms to accompany a strict austerity program that parliament adopted last september to help the country's stagnating economy
the group's statement said fidesz wanted hungary to have a mixed economy and democracy
s-charl, switzerland (ap) _ an avalanche engulfed a dutch skiing party on san lorenzo mountain friday, killing five people and injuring a sixth in the deadliest snowslide in the swiss alps in three years, police said
the deaths brought the skiing season's avalanche toll in switzerland to 19
the snowslide occurred at noontime and swept seven dutch skiers and a local mountain guide down the slope. the guide and one tourist freed themselves and alerted rescue helicopters by a walkie-talkie radio, police reported
search teams assisted by dogs recovered five bodies and rescued an injured woman who was flown to a zurich hospital
the skiers were at the 8,600-foot level of the nearly 10,000-foot mountain when they were struck by the avalanche. the swiss avalanche research institute on friday had warned of moderate snowslide danger above 6,600 feet
police did not release the names of the victims, but said the dutch group came to s-charl on sunday for a week of ski touring
it was the deadliest avalanche in switzerland since 11 people were killed near zermatt in march 1985. in graf 7, bgng ``he's great''</note>
democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson called friday for higher prices for farm products and said most consumers can afford to ``pay a few more pennies for a glass of milk or for a cone of ice cream or for a loaf of bread.''
a crowd nearly the size of the entire population of this town gathered on bud and faye lee's farm to hear jackson call for fair farm prices, a move designed to capture the votes of the 2,500-plus farmers who attended the rally
the fact is farmers deserve fair prices and workers deserve fair wages and the rich must pay fair taxes,'' jackson said on the dairy farm outside of amery, a town of 2,800. ``the reality is if urban people are working, they can pay a few more pennies for a glass of milk or for a cone of ice cream or for a loaf of bread.''
the preacher-turned-politician campaigned for another full day across wisconsin in preparation for tuesday's primary. jackson is locked in a tight race with massachusetts gov. michael dukakis here, according to pre-primary polls
from the lee farm, he headed to an indian reservation near green bay and to meet with union workers he stood with in a strike last year
farmers are a key part of the coalition that jackson hopes will give him another big-state victory, and the almost all-white crowd in amery suggested he is making some progress
he's great,'' said david dittman, a farmer from st. croix county, wis. ``he's the only one who has been standing up for the family farm.''
we don't have to invent a 30-second tv spot showing jesse jackson with the people: he's been with the people over the years,'' said texas agriculture commissioner jim hightower, on hand for the event
jackson, standing on a hay wagon in front of dark blue grain silos on the 600-acre dairy farm, returned to his religious roots in his first event on good friday
while so many farmers have been driven under in polk county, and though there is so much pain all around us representing the crucifixion ... there is a sense that the crucifixion is not going to last much longer, somehow we are going to roll the stone away and there is going to be renewal, resurrection, new hope ... as we the people come together,'' he said
jackson, saying he has stood with farmers for years, repeated his support for the liberal harkin-gephardt family farm legislation and said he backs higher milk price supports. he did not specify what increase he would support
jackson blamed middlemen in the food business and the government for the farm problems and for increasing food prices
the farmer did not take advantage of the consumer, it was conagra, cargill and the barracudas that ate up the farmers,'' he said, mentioning several large grain companies
the system has collapsed because you had good farmers and a poor president,'' jackson added
he accused the reagan administration of misrepresenting the situation with the dairy industry in order to cut spending on price supports _ as it did in january. at the same time, he said the administration was shutting down a free-cheese distribution program _ a major outlet for surplus milk products
jackson refered again to criticism of his lack of governmental experience
there is a lot of talk now days about experience. mine is in leadership. ... some officeholders are not leaders. and some leaders are not officeholders,'' he said
masked gunmen opened fire friday in a restaurant in a naples suburb, killing three people and wounding two, italian news reports said
the news agency agi said the gunmen belonged to a neopolitan gangs and there is a feud among rival underworld organizations
reports said the dead included two ex-convicts and a waitress who was serving lunch at their table when three or four men began shooting inside the the little rabbit restaurant
two other people described as ex-convicts were wounded, one seriously, in the attack in the torre del greco suburb, the agencies said
soviet and american scientists will conduct joint ecological studies of the bering sea and central pacific ocean this summer, the official tass news agency reported friday
it said the decision was made at a meeting of soviet and american scientists in the georgian city of batumi
the studies running from july and run through october will assess man's impact on the bodies of water, tass said, but gave no details
a bus collided with a car and plummeted into a ravine in an accident that killed 13 people and injured 42, the government newspaper reported friday
it quoted witnesses as saying the bus swerved to avoid a bulldozer parked beside the ivory coast's main highway thursday and met a car head-on
the newspaper said four people in the car were killed and a fifth was injured, and firemen removed nine bodies and 41 injured people from the bus
accidents are frequent on the highway linking abidjan, the country's capital and largest city, with the central city of bouake
an 80-year-old, three-masted square rigger that sank jan. 15 was raised from the murky boston harbor on friday by three giant cranes
the danish-built regina maris, believed to be the nation's last working square rigger of is size, had gone down in 30 feet of water at dockside, leaving only its masts protruding from the water
the deck broke the surface friday afternoon, eliciting a sigh of relief from salvagers who had slung cables around the hull of the historic, 114-foot barkentine
with a ship this age and it being a wooden ship, we were concerned that if it wasn't lifted uniformly ... we would pull one of the lifting cables through the ship, so it was important that we lifted it evenly,'' said jim frye, managing director of marina bay of quincy, owner of the vessel. ``it was a little dramatic, to say the least.''
debris cluttered the deck and hung from the rigging, but the regina maris did not appear damaged
the ship had been docked at marina bay for two years. it had been taken to boston marine workers for routine maintenance when it sank without explanation
the vessel will be put in dry dock, where an effort will be made to determine the cause of the sinking
frye said the proprietors planned to turn the vessel into a floating restaurant
he said the $50,000 operation to refloat the ship took six weeks of planning. one of the giant cranes had to be brought in from new jersey
field superintendent david kenny of cashman co., which raised the ship, said the regina maris weighed more than 100 tons and the cranes had a total lift capacity of 515 tons
the knot left everybody's stomach'' as the ship came up, he said
an israeli cabinet minister said his country had no intention of attacking medium-range missiles recently acquired by saudi arabia
in an interview to be broadcast saturday by the arabic service of radio france international, yitzhak navon said:
as a vice prime minister, i can state that israel has no intention of striking saudi arabia or any other country. and if it is confirmed that these missiles threaten israel, there are diplomatic means to counter such a threat. countries like syria, iraq and libya have missiles. israel has not threatened them or done anything else.''
a french script of the interview was obtained by the associated press
the washington post reported last month that the israeli air force had been conducting unusually intensive low-level bombing practice runs. it quoted u.s. intelligence officials as saying the runs could be in preparation for a pre-emptive strike at the missiles
president reagan warned israel a week ago against attacking the css-2 missiles the saudis purchased from china
it is believed the missiles have a range of 1,000 miles _ capable of reaching israel
navon is minister of education and culture and a member of foreign minister shimon peres' labor party. peres is deputy prime minister and navon is one of several vice prime ministers in the cabinet
a delegation from amnesty international, the london-based human rights organization, is in cuba on a fact-finding mission and has met with prison inmates, according to cuba's prensa latina news agency. in a dispatch monitored in mexico city, the agency said amnesty representatives arrived in cuba on march 24 and on thursday inspected the boniato prison in santiago de cuba, 430 miles southeast of havana. it said the visitors spoke with inmates
prensa latina said ian martin, director of the organization's department for the americas, heads the amnesty team. it quoted martin as saying the prison visit was ``very special, directly related to our work.'' the agency said the amnesty group also met convicts in other cuban prisons, but gave no details
the group also met with members of the government's judicial tribunals and officials of the federal prosecutor's office, prensa latina reported
it said the amnesty visit came at the invitation of vice president carlos gonzalez perez. the dispatch did not say how many people were in the amnesty group or give other details
hundreds of christmas stockings stuffed with cocaine paraphernalia were among $5 million worth of merchandise seized from a company, authorities said friday
company owner stephan pesce, 31, of massapequa was charged under a 1987 federal law making it illegal to sell or transport drug items across state lines and to foreign countries, said u.s. attorney andrew j. maloney of brooklyn
customs agents searched main street distributors inc. in hauppauge on thursday and carted off two truckloads of merchandise, maloney said. much of the drug paraphernalia was imported from taiwan or japan, he said
the christmas stockings, sealed with a picture of a smiling santa claus and a ``merry christmas'' greeting, contained a mirror, razor blade, a metal tube, a small glass container and a cocaine spoon, authorities said
pesce could receive up to three years in jail and up to $1 million in fines if convicted
twenty suspected kurdish guerrillas were killed in a shootout friday with security forces in southeastern turkey, the state radio said
it was the highest number of rebels slain in a single battle since the kurdish insurgency began in august 1984, it said
the radio said the guerrillas opened fire after they were surrounded by security forces and told to surrender. two soldiers were also killed in the fight, which took place near the village of kadirli in nusaybin township, the radio said
the report quoted the the regional governor's office as saying two other soldiers were wounded
in addition to the battle casualties, a major was killed and five soldiers were injured when the helicopter taking them to the zone crashed, according to the report. it did not say what might have caused the crash
most of the rebels in the area belong to an organization that seeks to establish a marxist kurdish state in southeastern and eastern turkey
more than 700 civilians and military personnel and 700 kurdish insurgents have been killed in violence related to the revolt since 1984
ethnic kurds make up about one-fifth of turkey's population of 52 million
two buses collided on a mountain road in central mexico friday, killing five people and injuring 25, highway police spokesman jose manuel fonseca reported
he said both drivers were among the dead in the accident that occurred at 5:45 a.m. 35 miles southwest of mexico city on the road to oaxaca
one bus was from the red star firm and the other from the cargo and passenger line, according to fonseca
fourteen people were killed and 26 injured in a bus accident thursday near valle de bravo in central mexico
