douglas edwards, who was the nation's first nightly tv anchorman, preceding walter cronkite in the job at cbs, had his last day at the network on friday after 46 years
friday's midday ``cbs newsbreak'' was his last television appearance for cbs
he concluded it with a personal statement: ``and so ends the chapter of almost 46 years as this reporter moves on along the journey. a deep bow of gratitude, love and respect to the men and women of cbs news and to the company for which they stand. to you out there, thank you for honoring me with your presence in my audience, and most of all for your voices, your most sweet voices. douglas edwards, cbs news new york.''
edwards' last radio broadcast was friday night. at its close, cbs news vice president joe dembo wished edwards ``goodbye and godspeed,'' and cbs evening news anchorman dan rather saluted him as ``one of the founding fathers'' of broadcast journalism
president reagan sent a congratulatory letter calling edwards a ``consummate professional.''
over the years, countless men and women have turned to you for the news, especially in time of crisis, and have felt reassured that they are `getting it straight' when they hear the the voice of douglas edwards. i can't think of any greater tribute to a journalist than that,'' said reagan's letter
edwards joined cbs radio in 1942, joining edward r. murrow's staff in london towards the end of world war ii. later, he served as paris bureau chief
when cbs launched its evening news show in 1948, then-cbs president frank stanton tapped edwards to anchor it and called it ``douglas edwards with the news.''
nbc followed with ``camel news caravan,'' and abc later launched a nightly news show with john daly
edwards stayed in the job for 14 years, until the show became the ``cbs evening news'' and cronkite took over as anchor
edwards, 70, plans to move to sarasota, fla. he will continue lecturing on broadcast journalism and start work on a book
talks between striking seamen and p and o european ferries broke down on good friday, the first day of the easter weekend, and no further talks were scheduled, government mediator dennis boyd said
p and o is one of the main ferry services across the english channel. at dover, where the line's seamen have been off the job for two months, about 3,800 frustrated tourists were stuck in a line of more than 100 buses, an equal number of cars and 500 trucks
p and o chairman peter ford issued a statement to those waiting at dover: ``i have nothing but apologies and regret for the people who have been disrupted. i remain convinced we will achieve a solution to this dispute, which i believe is being prolonged unnecessarily by people who are not trying to solve it.''
tourists who had ferry reservatons for calais faced delays of up to 12 hours and truck drivers could be waiting even longer, said paul youden of the dover harbor board. buses at the end of the line were given estimates of 24 hours
the strike has halted all p and o ferries in dover but other vessels were operating from the port. about 2,300 seamen are striking over the line's plans to cut 400 jobs and introduce new shifts
a ugandan rebel leader and voodoo priestess who anointed her troops with oils to protect them from bullets was turned over to united nations authorities after three months in prison, a kenyan government official said friday
alice lakwena, who fled to kenya after ugandan troops slaughtered her army, was turned over to the u.n. high commissioner for refugees, according to a high-ranking kenyan government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
new vision, the ugandan government newspaper, reported friday that ms. lakwena was seeking political asylum through the united nations
the kenya government jailed ms. lakwena and seven of her holy spirit movement followers in december on charges of entering the country illegally. kenya had said it would turn the rebel leader over to the ugandan government after she completed her a four-month sentence
but ms. lakwena appealed and the kenyan high court ruled feb. 11 that the minister in charge of immigration should decide on whether to return her to uganda. new vision said kenya had decided not to extradite ms. lakwena but did not give a source for its report
ms. lakwena, believed to be 28, was born to an anglican clergyman and his wife in northern uganda
she began her crusade against the government of president yoweri museveni in early 1987, claiming she was guided by a spirit demanding his ouster. she was known to followers as ``mama alice.''
she raised a battalion of followers numbering as many as 15,000 and told them she had magical powers to protect them. but government troops crushed her army, which fought with sticks and stones, late last year
there was no word on her jailed followers friday and no official kenyan statement on her release. the u.n. refugee office in nairobi was closed for good friday and calls to representatives' homes went unanswered
joe collins, a theatrical agent and the father of ``dynasty'' actress joan collins and novelist jackie collins, died friday. he was 85
collins began his show business career as office boy with moss empires theaters in london and later worked as an assistant theater manager in sheffield and liverpool
in 1931, he became a theatrical agent. the first artist he signed was dancer lew grade, now television producer lord grade, who became his partner. when grade left the collins and grade agency, collins continued alone
he helped launch the careers of peter sellers, tom jones and roger moore. collins also persuaded his daughter to take the role of alexis in ``dynasty'' even though a theatrical company was trying to hold her to a previous contract
his own biography was titled ``a touch of collins.''
police shut down an expressway outside philadelphia on friday in a search for a man who stabbed to death two women and wounded a couple working on an archeological dig at a construction site
police said they knew of no motive for the stabbings, which occurred in or near a house close to the schuylkill expressway, the state's most congested road and the major east-west thoroughfare through philadelphia
authorities withheld information on the dead women but identified the injured as glenn sheehan, 39, and his wife, ann jensen, 31, both hospitalized with multiple stab wounds
the shutdown of the expressway for nearly an hour forced a detour in which a tractor-trailer rammed into two cars and flipped over a barrier, injuring two people
police said they were looking for a man witnesses described as driving a pickup truck with massachusetts license plates
the top women officials of labor federations in seven cities issued a statement friday complaining that women on the job received unequal treatment and demanding a public debate on the issue
we call upon the media, economic and theoretical communities, leaders at all levels of the (communist) party and government ... and all men and women workers to air their own views and actively join in a discussion,'' the seven women said in the statement, published on the front page of the newspaper workers' daily
their statement, drafted at a meeting in beijing, was especially critical of what they said was a growing tendency to fire women once they have children
many enterprises also have done away with maternity leave and other ``women's benefits'' in order to cut costs now that companies are being held responsible for their own profits and losses
some people believe that when a woman becomes pregnant and has a child it is a private matter and becomes a burden for the enterprise,'' the statement said. ``but others believe women carry two heavy loads, of helping produce material goods for society and perpetutating the human race, and this contribution deserves social recognition and special protection.''
women were regarded as inferior in traditional china's rigid social hierarchy but are promised equal treatment in communist china's constitution
in reality, they hold few high government or party posts and have little social influence. most still bear the full burden of household chores and child-rearing while also working full-time in the fields or in factories
political and economic reforms, including decentralization of authority and emphasis on profit-and-loss, have eroded the few guarantees of access to higher education, jobs and political representation for women
official media have carried dozens of reports in the past year of women being denied jobs or fired because of their sex. a recent all-china federation of trade unions survey found that 64 percent of all workers being laid off in factory reorganizations were women
the statement by the seven labor leaders blamed the lingering influence of ``old thinking'' and the failure of enterprises to find practical solutions to problems faced by women workers with children
if these problems are not solved, not only will it harm the enthusiasm of women workers, but it will have impact on the progress of (economic) reform,'' said the seven, who head the women's sections of beijing, luoyang, wuhan, chongqing, nantong, handan and liuzhou municipal labor federations
democrat michael dukakis, looking for support among union voters, said friday the reagan administration has permitted a corporate ``merger mania'' that has cost a half-million workers their jobs and weakened america
dukakis injected a strain of populism into his presidential campaign as he spoke to labor audiences in wisconsin, where he is locked in what polls suggest is a close race with rival democrat jesse jackson
wall street pirates and corporate hit teams aren't the model for a new america,'' dukakis said
the massachusetts governor spoke to about 500 people crowded into the racine labor center, a meeting place for various union locals, where he criticized attorney general edwin meese iii and blamed the administration for what he described as a ``takeover epidemic'' among giant companies that enrich the corporate raiders and put workers out of their jobs
if we're serious about winning the battle for our economic future, we've got to get control of the merger and acquisition binge that's gobbling up capital, tearing corporations apart like erector sets, making millions of dollars for a few ... and leaving the average working men and women of america holding the bag,'' he said
dukakis' audience was mostly retired and active union members in racine, from auto, tractor and other manufacturing plants in a area where unemployment is reported to be more than 8 percent. later he was speaking to displaced workers in green bay and visiting a farm near wausau in northern wisconsin
dukakis' populist-tinged speech came as his campaign began a new television ad in wisconsin attacking the reagan administration and depicting farm foreclosures and homeless families
he is battling jackson _ whose own populist appeal has made him a close second to dukakis in the delegate race _ in next tuesday's wisconsin primary. after his loss to jackson in michigan, dukakis needs a victory in wisconsin. also running are sens. albert gore jr. of tennessee, who has been attacking big corporations in television ads in this state, and paul simon of illinois
under criticism from some democrats for a bland style, dukakis has unveiled new campaign speeches in an effort to sharpen his message, even as aides maintain he is not changing his style or approach in reaction to opponents
dukakis cited figures showing more than 12,000 corporations have changed hands in the last five years and that 15 takeover bids of $1 billion or more have been made in the past 12 weeks
and what have we got to show for it?'' he asked ``massive corporate debt. lower quality products. workers thrown into the streets. a less competitive america. and the profits these people make are unbelievable
altogether we've seen a half-million workers lose their jobs as a result of merger mania in recent years,'' he said, citing layoffs and plant closings in eau claire, la crosse, cudahy and milwaukee, wis
he blamed the administration's labor department and national labor relations board, saying they ``won't stand up for the american worker.'' and, he said, ``we've got an attorney general who couldn't tell the difference between antitrust and antifreeze, an antitrus division (of the justice department) that hasn't been heard from in years.''
dukakis said that because the administration has permitted ``this takeover epidemic ... the japanese must be laughing at us all the way to the bank.''
at a union hall in green bay, dukakis criticized meese, who has been under criminal investigation for 11 months
this guy in the justice department is spending so much time defending himself he can't do his job.''
suggesting reagan should fire meese, dukakis said: ``one of the jobs of a chief executive ... is not only you hire people but occasionally you fire them.''
meese came under heavy fire in congress this week after two of his top aides quit the justice department, saying meese's continuing legal problems were hurting department function and its image
but meese got a boost friday in washington when independent counsel james mckay announced he had found insufficient evidence to date to warrant indicting meese in connection with a $1 billion iraqi pipeline plan or a possible conflict of interest involving his telephone company stock
dukakis avoided mention of his democratic rivals but, taking questions from the audience at the green bay labor temple, said he viewed bush's claim to aspire to be ``the education president'' this way: ``with a large laugh.''
cutting and slashing student loans, destroying our commitment to education, i don't see it,'' dukakis said. ``what's he for? ... it'll be quite a conversion.''
he took a swipe at education secretary william j. bennett, saying: ``he's the exception to the rule that an education is good for you.''
dukakis met with leaders of the national farmers' union, a group representing family farmers, at a dairy farm near wausau. standing with farmers in front of a dairy barn after their meeting, dukakis said he backed ``reasonable price supports'' for milk as well as ``reasonable'' controls on supply _ but did not say what those levels would be
union president lee swenson said dukakis offered ``a very receptive ear'' to farm concerns
two jewish men imprisoned for armed attacks on arabs in the occupied land west bank were ordered freed friday in a passover holiday gesture by president chaim herzog
ira rappaport was pardoned with four months remaining on his sentence and yitzhak geniram still had 2{ months on his term, said ami gluska, a spokesman for herzog
this is really a holiday present,'' rappaport's wife, orit, told israel radio. ``we are very happy and every day ira spends with us is a present.''
gluska said the two had been pardoned in part because they expressed regret for their actions. ``there is a general trend to reduce sentences in the framework of the 40th year of the state,'' he said on israel radio. israel was founded in 1948
rappaport and geniram were convicted of belonging to a jewish terror ring that carried out attacks on arabs in the occupied west bank of the jordan river earlier in the 1980s. members of the group, called ``the jewish underground,'' were apprehended between april 1984 and december 1986
the new york-born rappaport was convicted of attaching a bomb in june 1980 to the car of a former mayor of nablus, bassam shakaa, who lost his legs in the explosion
rappaport was sentenced to four years in jail, but the court suspended 1{ years of the sentence, taking into account ``personal circumstances.''
rappaport came to israel in the 1970s and was a founder of shiloh, a jewish settlement in the west bank
geniram, a founder of the right-wing gush emunim settlement movement, was sentenced to four years in jail and three years on probation after being convicted of manslaughter and attempted manslaughter
the court ruled he loaned his car to attackers who killed three arab students at the hebron islamic college and wounded 30 in a july 1983 attack
he also was convicted of helping gather explosives for a june 1980 attack on arab mayors in the west bank and was involved in a plot to blow up moslem mosques on the holy temple mount in jerusalem
after nearly two decades in prison for the assassination of the rev. martin luther king jr., james earl ray says he would trade places with the hostages in lebanon
i'm primarily interested in getting out of jail. i'll take my chances over there,'' the 60-year-old alton native told the alton telegraph in a recent telephone interview
ray is being held in tennessee's brushy mountain state prison on a 99-year sentence for the april 4, 1968, slaying of king. ray pleaded guilty but maintains he did so only under pressure and is innocent
ray said he does not think about how he will be remembered
it's been a long time. after a while you get to think about other things,'' he said. ``i work in the laundry now. you don't get up and think about it everyday.''
the right-wing nationalist republican alliance won exactly half of the 60 legislative assembly seats in elections held on march 20, election officials announced friday
the central elections council said the alliance, known by its spanish acronym arena, won 30 seats but fell short of an absolute majority.f the elections council and a director of the governing christian democratic party, said the christian democrats won 23 seats and the conservative national conciliation party seven
arena earlier claimed the party won up to 35 seats. local media had projected the party would win 33-34 seats
in the new assembly, national conciliation legislators could form a voting bloc with the centrist christian democrats and make passage of legislation by either arena or the christian democrats difficult
samayoa said the results present an ``interesting situation because no party will predominate and will have to have negotiations.''
president jose napoleon duarte's christian democrats held 33 seats in the previous assembly and arena 13
arena founder roberto d'aubuisson said his party would petition the council to have the election results annulled. if that was rejected, arena would take its case to the supreme court, d'aubuisson said
alfredo cristiani, arena's president, had said on march 23 that the christian demcorats were manipulating the vote count to deprive his party of a parliamentary majority. ``we cannot let these shameless individuals steal our legislators,'' he said
in an interview on local television wednesday, cristiani said ``the people are being defrauded. this could explode at any moment, something difficult to stop (could) occur.''
d'aubuisson had said three days after the balloting, ``we don't want to promote violence. but we want to play clean and they won't let us.''
the national association for private enterprise had declared earlier it would call a general strike if the elections council did not report an arena victory
samayoa said friday arena would have to accept the final results and ``re-evaluate its positions.''
arena leaders withdrew from the vote-counting process tuesday night and removed their representative from the elections council
one representative from each of the three major political parties is allowed to sit on the elections panel. two votes are enough to approve any decision
francisco merino, the arena representative, withdrew tuesday and claimed the other panel members were trying to make a ``game of the vote tallies in order to change the results of the elections.''
in a recent interview with the associated press, samayoa rejected the allegations of fraud and said it ``only exists in the mind of those who have manipulated information about the results in their favor.''
while a computer count of votes for mayors in 262 municipalities was incomplete, samayoa said friday arena had won 178 of the races
japanese officials said friday they intend to continue seeking a compromise over u.s. demands for an end to their country's import quotas on u.s. beef and oranges
agriculture minister takashi sato said despite the breakdown of negotiations, his government would continue to discuss the issue through diplomatic channels. he also told reporters he was ready to return to washington when necessary. the minister was scheduled to leave saturday for tokyo
sato met briefly friday with allen wallis, u.s. undersecretary of state for economic affairs. their talk was described, however, as a courtesy call rather than resumption of the foodstuff negotiations with the office of the u.s. trade representative that ended in deadlock thursday night
u.s. officials said the next step will be next friday in geneva, where the united states will urge the council of gatt, the general agreement on tariffs and trade, to convene a panel to declare the japanese quotas illegal under international trading rules
u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter, who negotiated with sato, declared after the talks he was ``deeply disappointed that the japanese did not come forward with their proposal to liberalize trade on beef and citrus.'' japanese officials termed the u.s. demand for total elimination of the quotas covered by an expired four-year agreement unrealistic but declined to say whether they had offered a timetable for the elimination
a spring blizzard hit the texas and oklahoma panhandles on friday, stranding motorists and knocking out power in areas
as much as 6 inches of snow blanketed some areas and up to 20 inches were expected from the strong storm system that moved out of the southern rockies across northeastern new mexico, the national weather service said
they're going to have a white easter there,'' said weather service forecaster larry mooney in norman, okla., referring to a blizzard warning posted for the oklahoma panhandle
mary anne burdo, a highway patrol dispatcher at guymon, okla., where a foot of snow had fallen by late friday afternoon, said westernmost cimmaron county ``is completely shut down.''
we have a lot of stranded motorists in town and on the highways,'' said police dispatcher susie simmons in dalhart, in northwest texas. she said a lot of the travelers were on their way to ski resorts
i guess they can cross-country ski here,'' she said
at least two major highways were closed, u.s. 87 through dalhart and u.s. 287 north of stratford, because of blowing snow, the department of public safety said
winds of up to 30 mph caused power outages from west amarillo to dumas, authorities said
thunderstorms, some producing hail, also rumbled across texas and oklahoma friday
the weather service issued a flood and flash flood watch for much of southeast texas, including metropolitan houston, galveston, beaumont and port arthur
the defense minister on friday said a missing nuclear scientist, who allegedly gatherered information for the cia about purported plans by taiwan to make nuclear weapons, is in the united states
defense minister cheng wei-yuan said col. chang hsien-yi, former deputy director of the state-run nuclear energy research center, may have gone to america for a better job or because of ``his lack of confidence.'' he did not elaborate
we are not sure of the motive,'' cheng told the legislature
he said chang had telephoned and written friends in taiwan from the united states but he did not know where the scientist was staying
chang vanished in january and the government issued a warrant for his arrest. local newspapers claimed chang worked for the cia and left the country with information about a government nuclear weapons development program. they did not cite sources
taiwan's nationalist chinese government has said it does not have nuclear arms. the issue is sensitive because communist china has said production of atomic weapons in taiwan would be a justified cause for invading the island, which the communist leaders view as a renegade province
china has exploded its own nuclear devices
the american institute in taiwan, which handles diplomatic matters in the absence of official u.s.-taiwan relations, has said it does not know chang's whereabouts
a poll published friday indicated taiwanese are about evenly divided over whether the government should make nuclear bombs
the united evening news survey also indicated that most people in taiwan believe the country has the capability to make such weapons
it reported 35 percent of 767 people polled by telephone said taiwan should make nuclear weapons and 34 percent were opposed, with the rest undecided
about 58 percent believed taiwan has the ability to develop such weapons, it said
the poll was conducted last month and had a margin of error of 3.5 percentage points, according to united evening news. weeks</head>
if jesse jackson is elected president and ``did everything he said he wanted to do,'' the nation would be bankrupt in three weeks ``based on all the social programs we would be putting into effect,'' mayor edward i. koch said friday
however, because of party loyalty and because ``he'd be better'' than the likely gop nominee george bush, the democratic mayor said he would vote for jackson if the democrats nominate him at their convention in atlanta
i have said i would be stuck with whoever comes out of that convention,'' koch said
reacting to koch's remarks, jerry austin, manager of jackson's campaign for the democratic presidential nomination, said the mayor has ``solidified his position in the national exaggeration hall of fame.''
koch told reporters that ``i think this country would be ill-served to have jesse jackson'' in the white house
i think that in three weeks, based on all the social programs we would be putting into effect (under jackson), if you did everything he said he wanted to do, we'd be in bankruptcy. people know that's pie in the sky,'' koch said
koch added that ``he wants to disarm us'' and is ``on the wrong side of every issue i know of with two exceptions: drugs _ he's great in opposition to drugs _ and he's great in talking about the need for family responsibility and particularly as it relates to education.''
the mayor also said that jackson's standards are ``not my standards. so i have said that it's very bad to contemplate having jackson being president.''
stanley hill, co-chairman of jackson's new york campaign, said: ``it's obvious that mayor koch is being very divisive in the city. once again, it is not helping the city.''
while he termed the mayor's remarks unfortunate, hill added: ``i'm not going to even try to reach his level of negative campaigning.''
koch also said some people claim that criticism of jackson might be based on race, but he maintained that the black candidate's positions on the issues are just as open to comment as those of white candidates
he should be held accountable like any white candidate. not different. exactly the same,'' he said
but, the mayor said, if jackson is nominated, jackson would win koch's vote in the presidential election ``for two reasons: party loyalty _ and i have said i would be stuck with whoever comes out of that convention. and the other is: he'd be better than bush,'' the vice president, who is far ahead in this year's gop presidential race
a city bus went out of control while crossing a bridge and fell 24 feet into the frigid han river in seoul friday, killing at least 20 people and injuring 40, police said
the bus was carrying some 60 passengers, many of them students returning home from school, when the driver lost control after one of the front tires blew out, according to police
they said the death toll could rise as divers searched the partially submerged bus for more bodies
police assisted by passers-by rescued passengers who broke windows and climbed on top of the bus
britain and the soviet union have agreed to exchange information on nuclear safety, including the disclosure of nuclear accidents, the government's health and safety executive announced late friday
the agreement was initialed thursday by british officials and top soviet nuclear safety experts
a government spokeswoman, speaking anonymously in keeping with british government custom, said the agreement was wide-ranging and covered the exchange of information on operating, building, commissioning and decommissioning nuclear installations
the two countries agreed to exchange information on nuclear accidents and any major release of radioactive material, she said. the soviet union was criticized for its delay in reporting the april 1986 explosion and fire at the chernobyl nuclear plant, which killed 31 soviets and spread a cloud of radioactivity around the world
the four soviet officials met top officials at the energy department and toured the hinkley point magnox nuclear plant in southwest england during a four-day visit to britain. they have returned to moscow
veterans of britain's first ``ban the bomb'' movement 30 years ago, including former labor party leader michael foot, marched friday in front of thousands of demonstrators walking toward a nuclear facility
organizers said about 5,000 people participated in an anti-nuclear rally friday at hyde park in london. thousands of other protesters were expected to join the demonstrators on their 52-mile march that is to end monday with another rally at the aldermaston nuclear base in berkshire
the base houses the government's atomic weapons research center
organizers said some protestors at the hyde park rally were children of the demonstrators 30 years ago
foot said friday's protest was aimed at current problems. ``this has nothing to do with nostalgia,'' he said. ``this march is a sign that the campaign will go on until nuclear weapons are wiped off the face of the galaxy.''
a minister hired three men to kill his wife for $1,000 each, then shot himself to death as suspicion focused on him, authorities said friday in announcing the arrests of the alleged killers
the rev. charles sennett, 45, apparently borrowed the $3,000 from his girlfriend for the march 18 stabbing of elizabeth sennett, 45, at the couple's ransacked rural home, said colbert county sheriff buddy aldridge
kenneth eugene smith, 22, and john forrest parker, 19, both of florence, were charged with capital murder thursday, and billy gray williams, 21, also of florence, was charged with conspiracy to commit murder, aldridge said
they were being held without bail
sennett killed himself in front of his son's home march 25
we had interrogated him earlier in the day and ... told him he was a suspect and informed his family he was,'' said aldridge. ``we had set up a polygraph test for the following tuesday.''
the sheriff said sennett approached williams ``about hurting someone,'' and williams hired smith and parker to carry out the slaying
smith and parker ransacked the sennett home and took a videotape player and other items to make the crime look like a burglary, the sheriff said
the minister of the sheffield church of christ had told police he returned home to find his wife stabbed and unconscious on the floor, investigators said. she never regained consciousness and died that night in surgery
aldridge said sennett, in shooting himself to death, left a note saying ``he had never hurt his wife and that he had gotten in with some bad guys.''
the sheriff said that police have not pinpointed a motive in the killing but that minister had admitted having a girlfriend
the woman told police sennett borrowed $3,000 to ``pay on a note,'' the sheriff said, ``but he would not account to us what he had done with the money.'' the woman, whom authorities declined to identify, was not charged
the suspects told officers they threw the weapons used in the slaying _ a hunting knife, a fireplace poker and a cane _ into a pond outside the sennett home, aldridge said
jim jordan, who delighted radio audiences for decades as the well-meaning but bumbling fibber mcgee in the classic show ``fibber mcgee and molly,'' died friday. he was 91
jordan had been hospitalized for about a week after a fall at his home, said a family friend who declined to be identified
fibber mcgee and molly'' was on the air for the nbc radio network from 1935 to 1960 and was the top-rated show in the country for seven of those years
it was the source of such familiar routines as mcgee's overstuffed closet, which always unloaded mercilessly on jordan's character whenever it was opened. even mcgee's address, 79 wistful vista, became a place on the american cultural roadmap
even though he had become very frail, his mind and his humor were as fresh as ever,'' said lenore kingston, a vice president for pacific pioneer broadcasters. ``we all adored him.''
like the couple in the ``fibber mcgee and molly'' scripts, the stars of the show were married. jim and marian jordan came to radio out of vaudeville to formulate the comedy with writer don quinn
mrs. jordan died of cancer in 1961
u.n. mediator diego cordovez on friday held separate meetings with soviet special envoy nikolay kozyrev and u.s. diplomat robert peck in his efforts to secure an afghanistan peace settlement
the superpowers could sign as guarantors if an accord is reached
peck, a deputy assistant secretary of state, and kozyrev have been following the u.n.-sponsored indirect negotiations between afghanistan and pakistan since the latest round began march 2 and have routinely met with cordovez
pakistan acts on behalf of afghanistan's moslem guerrillas, who have fought to topple the pro-soviet government in kabul for more than eight years
peck declined to say what impact, if any, a proposal by secretary of state george p. shultz had on the talks
i'm not really able to talk about the details of the diplomacy at the present time,'' he told reporters at the geneva u.n. office where the talks are being held
shultz suggested thursday that moscow could keep arming marxist forces in afghanistan after an estimated 115,000 soviet troops withdraw, provided the united states can maintain supplies to the afghan guerrillas
washington said in the past it would not guarantee a settlement unless the soviet union agreed to stop supporting the afghan governmewnt at the same time the united states ended aid to the guerrillas
soviet officials rejected that as attempted interference in soviet-afghan relations and claimed america had raised a last-minute obstacle at the u.n. talks
but peck said: ``we're continuing to work very hard and we'll stay here until we get an agreement. we should be able to put something together.''
formal negotations are to resume monday, but u.n. officials have left open the possibility of continuing diplomatic contacts over the weekend
the soviets sent troops into afghanistan in december 1979 to help the government battle the rebels who were gaining control of many areas
zimbabwean forces joined mozambican soldiers in attacks that destroyed three major guerrilla bases in southern mozambique this month, the army announced friday
the national news agency, aim, said it was the first confirmation of zimbabwean participation in the 12-year-old civil war between marxist government forces and the mozambique national resistance, which the government says is south african-backed
zimbabwean forces have been in neighboring mozambique for several years, helping to guard the limpopo railway line which runs for over 300 miles from the border to the port of maputo
zimbabwean and mozambican railway workers are repairing the track, which will give zimbabwe a second outlet to the sea. the other line, to the port of beira, functions well, said aim. it also is guarded by zimbabweans
aim quoted a spokesman for the general staff of the mozambican armed forces as saying the joint force attacked the bases of chiconjo, maginge and nhahombe in gaza province during the second half of march, killing 260 bandits
there have been several reports of mozambican guerrillas raiding villages in zimbabwe since that country sent troops into mozambique. weeks</head> jackson comment. picks up 4th graf pvs bgng: reacting to ...</note>
if jesse jackson is elected president and ``did everything he said he wanted to do,'' the nation would be bankrupt in three weeks ``based on all the social programs we would be putting into effect,'' mayor edward i. koch said friday
however, because of party loyalty and because ``he'd be better'' than the likely gop nominee george bush, the democratic mayor said he would vote for jackson if the democrats nominate him at their convention in atlanta
i have said i would be stuck with whoever comes out of that convention,'' koch said
in green bay, wis., jackson told reporters he had not heard of koch's remarks. but when they were described to him he said, ``that's unfortunate. i should not dignify that statement.''
reacting to koch's remarks, jerry austin, manager of jackson's campaign for the democratic presidential nomination, said the mayor has ``solidified his position in the national exaggeration hall of fame.''
koch told reporters that ``i think this country would be ill-served to have jesse jackson'' in the white house
i think that in three weeks, based on all the social programs we would be putting into effect (under jackson), if you did everything he said he wanted to do, we'd be in bankruptcy. people know that's pie in the sky,'' koch said
koch added that ``he wants to disarm us'' and is ``on the wrong side of every issue i know of with two exceptions: drugs _ he's great in opposition to drugs _ and he's great in talking about the need for family responsibility and particularly as it relates to education.''
