campeau corp. won its 2-month-old battle for federated department stores inc. on friday, but rival retailer r. h. macy &amp; co. inc. will end up with two of federated's divisions in the southwest
campeau will acquire federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer and parent of up-scale bloomingdale's, for $73.50 a share, or $6.58 billion, campeau and federated said in a statement
the acquisition would be the fifth largest corporate takeover in u.s. history, and the largest deal not involving oil companies
macy came away with the bullock's and bullock's-wilshire division and the i. magnin chain, for which it will pay $1.1 billion, the statement said
macy agreed to terminate a merger agreement it reached with federated last month, the statement said
a definitive agreement signed by the three companies also calls for macy to be paid $60 million for its expenses in the takeover fight, the statement said
maureen milano, a spokeswoman for macy, said the company was pleased with the outcome
they felt that this is the most prudent decision for them,'' she said
campeau, a toronto-based real estate developer that also owns allied stores corp. in the united states, won federated following two meetings of the retailer's board this week
the deal ran along the lines of an agreement between macy and federated last month which gave macy the right to buy bullock's and magnin if the two companies' merger agreement fell through. the merger agreement was reached march 2 but federated reopened the bidding after campeau raised its offer last week
the purchase of the two divisions gives macy an expanded presence in california and the southwest. most of macy's nearly 100 department and specialty stores are in the eastern half of the country
allied president robert h. morosky, who would head the combined allied-federated operations, said campeau planned to sell off federated's supermarket, discount store and specialty store chains, as well as some of its department store chains. that would leave the company with the ``crown jewels'': rich's, lazarus, goldsmith's, burdines, bloomingdale's and abraham &amp; straus, he said
the canadian company previously agreed to sell the foley's and filene's department stores to may department stores co. if it won the fight for federated
after campeau bought allied in 1986, it sold off most of allied's store divisions to pay off debt, and ever since campeau launched its bid on jan. 25, analysts had predicted the same fate would befall federated
i'm sad about the fact that a fine department store like federated is being split up and decimated,'' said walter loeb, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm morgan stanley &amp; co
before friday's announcement, macy had offered to buy federated for $6.73 billion, while campeau bid $6.62 billion
campeau had offered wednesday to pay $74 a share in cash for federated's stock
macy offered thursday to pay $78.92 a share in cash for 80 percent of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares. it offered to pay $60 in cash or exchange five shares in the merged company, macy's-federated inc., for each remaining federated share. that would have produced a deal with an aggregate value of $75.14 a share
federated stock closed at $72.87{ a share thursday on the new york stock exchange. the stock market was closed for good friday
the fight for federated began jan. 25, when campeau offered $4.2 billion to buy the retailer, which rejected the offer as inadequate
campeau raised its bid, but federated spurned its advances until the end of february, when the retailer agreed to negotiate with campeau
but when the federated board was to meet to review that proposal, macy entered with its own bid
court battles ensued, and both suitors continued to raise their offers until the federated board called for ``final bids'' to be presented wednesday. background. no pickup.</note>
the leader of the august coup attempt that almost toppled the government of president corazon aquino escaped from his prison ship, the military announced saturday
a statement said col. gregorio ``gringo'' honasan escaped about 2:30 a.m. aboard two rubber boats along with 13 other people, including some of his guards
chief of staff gen. renato de villa ordered a massive search for the 39-year-old honasan and alerted subordinate commands nationwide to be on the lookout for him
honasan had been detained on a navy ship in manila bay since his arrest last december in a manila suburb
one military source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said officers close to honasan had been ordered to report to military chief of staff gen. renato de villa to discuss the case
the breakout followed rumors in the capital that honasan would attempt to escape
honasan, former chief of security at the defense ministry, played a key role in the feb. 22, 1986, mutiny which triggered the popular uprising that toppled president ferdinand marcos
but honasan became disillusioned with marcos' successor, president corazon aquino
on aug. 28, honasan led a force of 2,000 men who attacked the presidential palace and seized several media and military installations in the capital before they were driven off by pro-aquino forces
the coup attempt left 53 people dead and wounded hundreds, and mrs. aquino said it was aimed at killing her and her family
honasan's effort was the most serious of several major plots to unseat mrs. aquino's government
honasan has accused mrs. aquino of ``weak and inept'' leadership and says he tried to save the country from communism
the start of daylight-saving time this weekend has an effect so strange in indiana that many residents could use the extra hour to explain it to outsiders
while most indiana counties remain on eastern standard time, residents of 16 counties move their clocks forward an hour
eleven of those counties are in the central time zone, and move their clocks to be even with chicago's central daylight time and indianapolis' est
the five other counties are in the eastern zone and move their clocks up to eastern daylight time to keep pace with nearby louisville, ky., and cincinnati
the result is that some people in the same time zone have different times on their clocks, while people in different zones have the same time. this occurs among neighbors in a state less than 150 miles wide
indiana residents just call the two times ``fast'' and ``slow.''
it creates confusion for us until october,'' said barbara schuler, office manager at wsch radio in lawrenceburg. ``we make it a point to tell listeners if an event is on fast or slow time.''
she said the confusion hits hardest when family members are operating on different clocks, such as when a parent working in cincinnati has a child in a school using standard time
it's an absolute mess,'' said donna benning, a bookkeeper at an auto dealership in milan. ``the kids tell me to pick them up at 3 p.m. and i always show up an hour early.''
daylight-saving time was standardized by congress in 1966, but in 1972, indiana joined hawaii and arizona in exercising an option to exempt themselves
however, the legislature left some border counties near illinois and kentucky to go daylight-saving time. to update with report on internal justice department investigation.</note>
independent counsel james mckay said friday he has found insufficient evidence to date to warrant indicting attorney general edwin meese iii in connection with a $1 billion iraqi pipeline plan or a possible conflict of interest involving his telephone company stock
meese said he was ``gratified by the action and the statement'' of the independent counsel and that he would not step aside
it is certainly my intent to carry on my duties as long as the president wants me to,'' the embattled attorney general told a news conference
mckay said his report was an interim one and that his investigation was continuing
the grand jury's investigation is not yet complete as to'' the pipeline probe, the telephone stocks and ``other matters, and will continue at least through the end of april,'' mckay's statement said. a source close to mckay's investigation would not provide details of these matters, but said they were all felony cases
the grand jury is expected this month to hear testimony from meese, his wife, ursula, and u.s. circuit judge douglas h. ginsburg, former head of the justice department's anti-trust division that handled the breakup of american telephone &amp; telegraph co. while meese held telephone stock
even though mckay's announcement was an interim report, it was an enormous boost to meese, who has been reeling from bipartisan calls in congress for him to quit in the wake of the resignations tuesday of two of his top aides
mckay told a news conference that he decided to issue his statement on friday ``without any outside consultation.'' but he acknowledged that meese's attorney has asked several times for such a public statement, including ``quite recently.''
a source close to mckay said meese's attorneys ``have known of this decision for a period of time.'' the source said they argued mckay should tell the public as well because ``we know it and you know it.''
this source said of mckay, ``he's concerned about the fairness factor. ... he didn't want people speculating about what he would or would not do with respect to these matters.''
the source said mckay could be reappointed or retain his appointment to deal with any evidence that might surface after the grand jury is dismissed. mckay's staff is debating whether to say in his public report that he might have obtained an indictment but did not do so because he was uncertain of winning a conviction, the source said
several key figures in the criminal investigation of meese, including his longtime friend, e. robert wallach and meese's former financial manager, w. franklyn chinn, have refused to cooperate with mckay's inquiry. wallach and chinn are under indictment in the wedtech scandal
the aides who stepped down tuesday were concerned that meese's legal problems _ he has been under criminal investigation for nearly 11 months _ are hurting the justice department's operations and image
among those who resigned was assistant attorney general william weld, who oversaw all federal criminal investigations, and deputy attorney general arnold burns
meese had planned to announce replacements for burns, weld and departing associate attorney general stephen trott, but the announcement was called off at the last minute without explanation
the replacement for burns was expected to be arlin adams, a former u.s. circuit judge in philadelphia, department sources said. the replacement for wells is to be james knapp, a deputy in the justice department's tax division who formerly worked in the criminal division. the replacement for trott is to be francis keating, an assistant treasury secretary for enforcement
meese would not discuss in detail the reasons why the two top aides left, claiming his conversations with them were confidential
but he did say that ``there were some basic differences'' between burns, weld and the attorney general ``as to the effect that recent events had on the department ... in part they were the fact that there was an independent counsel investigation.''
meese told reporters that for him to resign would be ``incompatible with the actual state of affairs'' and he cited ``broad support'' from law enforcement officials, from within the administration ``at the highest level'' and from members of congress
the white house declined comment on mckay and meese's statements. and after president reagan arrived at his mountaintop ranch near santa barbara, deputy press secretary leslye arsht said only that ``the president was notified by phone in the air. we have no reaction. he has always said he has confidence in meese.''
in an interview taped for broadcast friday night on abc-tv's ``20@20'' program, meese said he did not feel he was hurting the president, but that if he thought he was, he would resign
if at any point, i felt that it was an embarrassment to the president, or an embarrassment to the department, i would not rigidly stand and stay here just for the purpose of staying here,'' meese told interviewer barbara walters
i've had people from literally all over the country calling me to say, `you owe it to the justice department, to the president, to hang in there. ... you owe it to stay, and not give in to the lynch mob.'''
asked who the lynch mob was, he said, ``certainly some aspects of the press.''
he said the justice department's problems were ``all of the false statements and false accusations on the outside. and i think it would be wrong if i, in effect, capitulated to what the president has called a lynch mob. i think that would be far worse. i think it's very important if we're gonna make government safe for public officials, that no person should be able to be hounded out of office by false accusations, by incessant media barrages, many of them based on distortions and falsehoods, or by political attacks.'' accident</head>
a 22-year-old irishwoman, critically injured in a st. patrick's day traffic accident during a trip here, is awake after 10 days in a coma and is exchanging smiles with visitors, officials and friends say
margaret hanley was listed in fair condition thursday, said anita robins, a spokeswoman at weiss memorial hospital
they're saying very little, except the doctor is saying she's becoming a little more alert,'' ms. robins said
gerry archbold, a director of the irish-american heritage center, said that when he visited miss hanley on tuesday, ``she was conscious and a smile came to her face. she recognizes voices, but she has a long way to go after this.''
an aspiring actress in dublin, miss hanley came to the united states in february to visit her jailed boyfriend and had planned to return home march 18. she was on her way to buy a bottle of milk march 17 when she was hit by a car
she was conscious in the ambulance and joked with attendants about not being able to dance for a while, but then lapsed into a coma
a broken leg created a blockage in blood vessels carrying oxygen to her brain, said miss dewitt. doctors didn't know how long the woman had a diminished supply of oxygen from the blood clot
there's hope she will recover fully, but it's too early to say,'' nursing supervisor dorothy dewitt said wednesday. ``the fact that she has been up and talking is a very, very good sign.''
another nursing supervisor, nancy durbin, said miss hanley attempts to talk, mouthing her words
the nurse said she does not know if the young woman has mentioned daniel stokes, an irish immigrant to america whom she met last year when he was back in ireland for a visit
stokes, 21, now is in cook county jail, charged with first-degree murder, residential burglary, armed robbery, home invasion and possession of a stolen vehicle. he is accused of killing his landlord and has pleaded innocent
archbold said the irish-american center helped ease the way for the woman's parents, stephen and ann hanley, who flew to this country when they learned of the accident. he attributed her improvement to the prayers of sympathizers
we prayed hard for her. there were special prayers during the palm sunday mass at the center,'' archbold said. ``just shortly after the mass was over, she started to regain consciousness.''
miss hanley's room has assumed a more cheerful atmosphere, filled with stuffed animals sent by well-wishers
a team of federal experts at an alaskan space communications center helped to rescue an ailing indian satellite that was out of control earlier this month, a u.s. official said thursday
larry heacock, director of satellite operations for the national oceanographic and atmospheric administration, said the indian satellite, called irs1a, was launched by a soviet rocket on march 17 and placed into an orbit of about 560 miles
satellite controllers in germany, he said, discovered that the irs1a was unable to focus a guidance sensor on the earth, a sighting it was to use for an accurate orientation. as a result, the craft was unstable and could not be controlled properly
heacock said the satellite passed over the noaa satellite communications station in fairbanks, alaska six times every 24 hours
the german space agency, which was operating the satellite for india, asked the noaa station to take and send data to irs1a
each time it went by, noaa took data and sent it to the german space agency,'' said heacock
using this data, the germans were able to properly orient irs1a
the satellite is now normal,'' said heacock
the irs1a is to be used by the indians to gather remote sensing data. it was placed in a near-polar orbit which enables it to scan the whole earth once every 22 days
heacock said the normal operation of the fairbanks noaa station is to collect signals from the noaa 9 and 10 weather satellites
for the indian satellite, the noaa engineers used a spare antenna, and india paid the agency about $200,000 for the work, heacock said
the noaa station earlier performed data collection for a french remote sensing satellite called spot
president reagan directed treasury secretary james a. baker iii on thursday to buy materials for u.s. coins from foreign countries when required by international agreement, despite a ``buy america'' provision enacted by congress
in a statement issued as he signed a reauthorization bill for the bureau of the mint, reagan noted that the legislation requires preference for u.s. producers and suppliers over those in any country that has its own protectionist measures governing procurement for coinage
this requirement, standing alone, conflicts with certain of our nation's international obligations,'' he said
under the general agreement on tariffs and trade, for example, the united states agreed to require the mint to give equal treatment to the products and supplies of other countries that are signatories of the agreement
some countries did not designate their mints as covered by this agreement, but may have designated other agencies that the united states elected not to have covered, the president said
thus, he said, the preference provided in the bill ``could be viewed by our trading partners as violating our obligations.''
canada did not designate its mint as covered by the agreement, but canada and the united states recently signed a free trade agreement which is now being considered by congress. the president said following the preference provided in the bill ``could also bring into question our obligations'' under the u.s.-canadian trade agreement
the president said it was fortunate that the bill would permit the secretary of the treasury to waive the buy america provision when he found that it would be inconsistent with the public interest or the cost would be unreasonable
the public interest of the united states includes adhering to our international obligations, and these obligations should be taken into account by the secretary of the treasury in making procurements'' affected by the bill, the president said
house advocates of granting banks broad new securities powers said thursday their efforts have been given a big boost by overwhelming passage of legislation in the senate
we're on the move,'' said rep. stephen neal, d-n.c., who plans to offer a bill mirroring the senate measure when the house banking committee meets next month to consider the issue
the senate voted 94-2 late wednesday to allow bank holding companies to underwrite and sell mortgage-backed securities, commercial paper and municipal revenue bonds
it would permit underwriting of corporate bonds and mutual funds six months after enactment by both houses of congress and signature by president reagan, who favors the bill
i think ... the vote in the senate shows a very broad-based, liberal-conservative, bipartisan base for this kind of change,'' neal said
but those pushing a more cautious approach say the senate action may have little effect, pointing out that a senate deregulation effort in 1984 died in the house for lack of support
four years ago the senate voted 89-4 for a bill that never came out of the house. i'm not sure what influence it has now,'' said rep. charles schumer, d-n.y. he said he believes provisions in the senate bill safeguarding federally insured deposits from the risk of securities activities are too weak
schumer is backing a bill drafted by house banking committee chairman fernand j. st germain, d-r.i. it would grant banks only a few securities powers _ commercial paper, mortgage revenue bonds and asset-backed securities _ and place more restrictions on banks
the senate bill substantially lifts limits on banks in place since 1933 when the glass-steagall act separated commercial from investment banking in the belief that bank involvement in securities helped fuel the speculative binge that ended in the 1929 stock market crash and the bank failures of the 1930s
proponents of change say developments in the financial system, particularly in the last decade, threaten the ability of banks to compete. securities firms, for instance, offer bank-like services such as commercial paper and money market mutual funds. they argue that sufficient safeguards can be put in place to prevent the abuses of the 1920s
the senate measure requires a separate vote in 1991 before bank holding companies could underwrite corporate stock, the most lucrative securities activity
rep. edward j. markey, d-mass., whose energy and commerce subcommittee on finance has partial jurisdiction over the issue, called passage of the senate bill a positive step, but said the house will devote its attention to ``developing strong and resilient firewalls'' between banking and securities activities
consumer groups on thursday praised provisions in the bill _ unrelated to securities _ aimed at benefiting bank customers
we're very excited,'' said peggy miller of the consumer federation of america
one section prohibits lenders from unilaterally changing the pay-back and other terms of home equity loans. it requires lenders to warn borrowers that they could lose their house if they fail to pay and imposes other disclosure requirements
another provision bars misleading savings and checking account advertisements and requires banks to disclose the interest rate, fees and other information
the bill would also require banks to prove they are meeting the needs of poor citizens and neighborhoods before getting permission to exercise the new powers
and, it directs banks to cooperate if state laws require them to mail material to customers inviting them to join state financial consumer organizations
nicaragua has given the world court an estimate of damage caused by the contra war as a first step in claiming reparations from the united states, a court spokesman said thursday
the spokesman, who spoke on condition he was not identified, did not give the number. sources at both the court and nicaraguan embassy cited world court rules that forbid disclosure of written material before hearings have been held in a case
during 1985 hearings on a complaint about u.s. aid for the nicaraguan rebels, known as contras, sandinista officials speaking privately put the damage at $250-$300 million
a 1986 ruling by the court, a u.n. agency formally named the international court of justice, ordered the united states to halt all support to the contras. the rebels began fighting in 1981, and last week reached a preliminary cease-fire agreement with the sandinistas
in the ruling, the 15-judge court also directed the parties to settle the issue of reparations for damage caused by the rebels. the decision came after more than two years of proceedings on the nicaraguan complaint
the reagan administration boycotted the final 17 months of proceedings, contending the court had no jurisdiction, and refused to discuss the issue with the sandinistas. the court began the award procedure this year at nicaragua's request
it is expected to take several years. the next step is the filing of written arguments by the united states, for which the court has set a july 28 deadline
sources familiar with the dispute said it was unlikely the u.s. government would be willing to enter the reparations argument after having rejected the court's jurisdiction in 1984. the court has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary adherence to its rulings
in a related development, nicaragua withdrew a request for an emergency ruling on its case accusing honduras of allowing the contras to have bases on honduran territory
that request was filed march 21, after the united states sent 3,200 troops to honduras in response to an alleged incursion by nicaraguan soldiers in pursuit of rebels
in it, nicaragua had asked the court to investigate alleged border crossings by honduran armed forces and requested that an international observer force monitor the border
nicaragua filed its action against honduras last year. it had been suspended on by request of both parties after five central american presidents signed a regional peace plan aug. 7
two police officers were sentenced thursday to hang for the killing of two reputed drug dealers
one of the officers, sgt. robert van der merwe, had testified that he carried out the slayings because his co-defendant, capt. jack la grange, told him the victims were helping the african national congress, the main anti-apartheid guerrilla movement
according to evidence presented during the three-week trial, la grange was hired by alleged drug dealer peter pillay to arrange the killing of two men said to be his rivals, bennie ogle and ernest molokoane
van der merwe testified that on sept. 28, 1987, while he was with la grange, he shot ogle and molokoane. ogle died and molokoane suffered five gunshot wounds but survived
van der merwe said that on oct. 4 he killed pillay, again at la grange's instructions
supreme court justice irving steyn, who presided over the non-jury trial, said it was possible van der merwe had been duped by la grange into killing ogle but ruled that the sergeant had no excuse for pillay's slaying
an execution date is pending. steyn said the two police officers could appeal their murder convictions for the death of ogle, but not for the killing of pillay
la grange, 40, had claimed he was being framed by superiors, while van der merwe, 30, contended that he thought he was taking part in an approved clandestine operation
van der merwe told the court that he knew of previous ``clandestine operations'' in which security police carried out missions to kill suspected anc operatives
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
a special police detail is using an obscure ordinance against walking in the bushes to arrest suspected homosexuals in a city park
an official of the american civil liberties union said thursday the tactic is discriminatory and probably illegal
police said they see it as a way to clear langford park of homosexuals who meet there. a city study concluded that the boardwalks that wind through the forested park have become a hangout for homosexuals and male prostitutes
plainclothes officers on the special detail walk the wooden boardwalks and wait for men to walk into the bushes and sheltered spots
the law against walking in the bushes is part of a catch-all loitering ordinance. it is not posted in the park
one 35-year-old man who did not want to be identified said he was sitting in an open area of the park listening to a radio when two uniformed officers demanded to see his identification and asked if he had ever been arrested
they wanted to know why he was in a city park 10 minutes from his home and if he was married, he said. ``they asked me if i was a homosexual. twice,'' the man said
he said the officers threatened to arrest him if they saw him ``walking aimlessly'' or spending more time there than they believed was proper
how do you walk with purpose in a park?'' ron ross, president of the local chapter of the aclu, asked thursday. ``police are using unposted laws and are creating their own criteria for arrest, like `walking aimlessly.'''
the innocent person doesn't have a chance,'' ross said, arguing that police have created a situation in which no single men are innocent
officers arrest suspected homosexuals on whatever charge they can when they are unable to prove the men are prostitutes, said police capt. duane mcgray
the tactic has been used for more than a year because it is difficult to make prostitution arrests, he said
robert stabile, 37, was picked up while strolling through the foliage last week. he was jailed on a charge of prohibited activity, although police could simply have issued him a notice to appear in court and let him go home
i wasn't doing anything. i was just walking,'' stabile complained. ``they said i was out there too long.''
the arrest report said a plainclothes officer on the special detail saw stabile ``walk into the bushes off of the park path. the subject walked throughout the wooded area. i then arrested him for prohibited activity in the park.''
stabile could serve 60 days in jail and pay up to a $500 fine if convicted
ross said the police practice is ``discriminatory, definitely discriminatory, especially in a city park that is supposed to be for the benefit of all citizens
it is outrageous to discriminate against a certain class of people _ rather, who they suspect to be members of a certain class of people,'' ross said
police attorney john ross, who is not related to the aclu president, said anyone who claims that the law is being selectively enforced has to prove it
the burden is on them to actually show that there are names and addresses of people we have not arrested,'' he said
the communist party said thursday it was to blame for hungary's economic woes and proposed reforms in party elections including secret ballots and multi-candidate slates
a draft policy statement published thursday by nepszabadsag, the hungarian communist party daily newspaper, said the party had failed to assess ``the impact of world economic changes on the hungarian economy,'' causing an economic crisis
the statement, a rare public admission of a mistake by a governing communist party, added: ``the central committee and its executive organs, the government and its institutions are responsible for all this.''
the draft is to serve as an outline of discussions at a national party conference opening may 20 to review the communists' role in the changing society
the party draft said hungarian leaders recognized ``belatedly'' that economic growth could not come without more economic and political changes
the statement advocated a new system of party elections to be implemented before the next congress in 1990
the practice of nominating more candidates should widen and secret elections be held at all levels,'' the draft said
a 1986 party resolution setting a two-term limit on some lesser party posts should be extended to cover regional party secretaries as well, the draft said
the document also noted the party ``should not assume the scope of tasks of the state and social organizations'' and pull back from daily administration
the policy statement did not say whether the conference would include a discussion on replacing janos kadar, the 75-year-old communist party leader who has held power since 1956
but an unsigned editorial in the economics weekly figyeloe said thursday that ``important decisions'' on personnel questions were expected at the conference
the party meeting must create a new political system capable of forging consensus among hungarians of different opinions and interests, figyeloe said
hungary borrowed heavily in the 1970s to build up heavy industry. now, its 10.6 million people are burdened with a gross hard-currency debt of $16 billion, the highest per capita in the soviet bloc
as part of a government austerity program that took effect jan. 1, hungary became the first east bloc country to impose personal income taxes. the government also said prices are to rise at least 15 percent this year
the austerity program is the work of prime minister karoly grosz, 57, who took over the government in july and is seen as a possible successor to kadar
the last party congress was held in march 1985. innocent</head>
a woman who concealed her husband's death for eight years and tended the corpse as if he were alive pleaded guilty thursday to two felony forgery charges related to the death
a former chicago-area dentist accused of assisting her in the forgery pleaded innocent
carole stevens, 42, of knoxville entered the plea in knox county circuit court. judge harry bulkeley placed her on two years' probation and sentenced her to 12 days in jail, for which she received credit for 12 days served
bulkeley also ordered mrs. stevens to undergo psychiatric treatment. she could have received up to five years in prison and a $10,000 fine
mrs. stevens was charged with fabricating a power of attorney for her dead husband in 1984 and using it to refinance a home mortgage
her alleged accomplice, richard g. kunce, 56, a former aurora dentist who was a guest in the stevens house, was charged with signing his name as a witness
in february, mrs. stevens and kunce pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of failing to report the 1979 death of carl l. stevens, a diabetic who authorities say died shortly after he joined a holistic health cult and stopped taking his daily insulin shots
mrs. stevens was placed on a year's probation on the misdemeanor charge. kunce has asked a judge to withdraw his guilty plea
stevens' withered corpse was found jan. 29 on a bed in the home, where officials said his widow, a registered nurse, had cared for the body daily for the past eight years, changing its clothes and moving it from room to room
mrs. stevens' children, ages 17 and 14, are in foster care receiving psychiatric treatment
in a separate case, mrs. stevenson on thursday admitted to child neglect for allowing her children to live with their father's mummified remains for eight years
she was granted permission to continue seeing her children under supervision pending a decision on whether she will retain custody
kunce also awaits a court appearance on a felony charge of cruelty to children for allegedly teaching the stevens children ``black magic and suicide'' and for allowing them to live in the same house with the corpse
if convicted on the cruelty charge, he could receive up to three years in prison and a $10,000 fine. extraneous words.</note>
two american balloonists on thursday called off their plans to circle the earth non-stop in two weeks or less, saying $100,000 worth of helium leaked out of one of their balloons
they said they hoped to try again next year
col. rowland smith, 50, said a patch in one balloon ripped wednesday as the two 360-foot-high balloons were being inflated at el plumerillo air base outside mendoza, 660 miles west of buenos aires
smith and project organizer john petrehn, of topeka, kan., said about $2.5 million had been spent in transportation, materials and personnel for the double-decker balloon flight
technically it's impossible to attempt to fly around the world'' this year, a disappointed smith said at a brief news conference. he said they hoped to try next year
petrehn, 52, is a businessman, while smith is a former vietnam war pilot and a kansas-based pilot for trans world airlines. the balloonists had hoped to do what no one else has: circle the earth around the 45-degree parallel in the southern hemisphere
they planned to follow the 45th parallel for about 17,545 miles, traveling southeast from mendoza, crossing the atlantic and indian oceans and new zealand's campbell island, then cross the pacific until chile, dropping over the andes to return to mendoza in nine to 14 days
they hoped to travel at speeds up to 60 knots an hour, following the prevailing eastern winds at altitudes of up to 30,000 feet in a pressurized radar-equipped polyethlene gondola three yards by two yards wide
the longest manned balloon flight was in 1981, when the double eagle v crossed the pacific for about 5,000 miles
the government on thursday banned all outdoor meetings for a year, except those involving sporting events or funerals
justice minister kobie coetsee announced the order under terms of the internal security act, which prohibits a wide range of activities. it takes effect friday and will be in force through march 31, 1989
under national emergency regulations already in effect, outdoor rallies are illegal unless approved by a magistrate or law and order minister adriaan vlok
it was not immediately clear if the latest order expanded government authority to restrict rallies
magistrates still will have the power to consider exceptions to the ban
the order appears aimed at nationwide municipal elections scheduled for all race groups in october. by restricting rallies to indoors, the government apparantly seeks to limit the size of crowds and reduce the potential for violence
it is the latest move in recent government crackdowns aimed at limiting political activity
last week, a judge, acting on a government request, banned an outdoor rally by the afrikaner resistance movement, a white-supremacist paramilitary organization. the group eventually met indoors
on feb. 24, the government banned 18 leading black anti-apartheid groups from participating in political activity
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
also thursday, minister of constitutional development chris heunis said residents of the small black township of oukasie, outside the northeastern city of brits, must be resettled in keeping with government policy
heunis said monday in parliament the government would not try to relocate the remaining 8,000 residents
he said thursday his statement was misinterpreted. he reiterated government policy that oukasie remained officially abolished and residents would be moved to lethlabile, a newly established township 15 miles away. but he said it would not be done by ``force.''
heunis abolished oukasie by decree in october 1986, but only about 5,000 residents moved to lethlabile. oukasie residents repeatedly have said they prefer their old homes and have no intention of moving
the government says the cost of upgrading oukasie would be ``astronomical.'' oukasie residents say the government wants them out because the township has expanded to within 250 yards of a white suburb in brits
the occupational safety and health administration should switch more inspectors to meatpacking plants because job injury rates there are the highest of any industry in the country, a house committee said thursday
the house government operations committee also called on osha to establish minimum training standards for packinghouse workers and consider setting standards on work loads and chain speeds in packinghouses
the committee concluded in a 45-page report that tens of thousands of meatpacking workers are being injured each year because they are ``regarded by some as disposable, someone who is used and then discarded.''
citing upton sinclair's 1906 novel ``the jungle'' on labor toil in chicago packinghouses, the committee said ``more than 80 years later ... meatpacking employees still work'' under the same conditions of slick floors and dangerous chain speeds that cause them to accidentally slash themselves and one another
terry mikelson, an osha spokesman, said the agency will take the committee's recommendations ``under consideration.''
we already devote special resources to meatpacking,'' he said, explaining that packinghouses are inspected three times more often than plants in other manufacturing industries. ``everybody recognizes that its a high-hazard industry and that employers need to do a better job.''
the report was based on three days of hearings conducted last year by the house panel's employment and housing subcommittee focusing on osha and ibp inc.'s flagship packinghouse at dakota city, neb
at the time of the first hearing, ibp and the united food and commercial workers union were engaged in a bitter lockout that turned into a strike involving 2,900 workers
the strike has since been settled, but not before the union succeeded in focusing both congressional and osha attention on safety conditions in the plant and the industry
last july, osha fined ibp $2.6 million _ then the biggest penalty ever levied by the agency _ for safety and record violations at the dakota city plant. the company has appealed the fine
part of the fine resulted from osha's determination that the company kept two sets of injury records at the plant, one for internal use and the other for the purview of osha inspectors when they visited
in testifying before the subcommittee, ibp chairman robert peterson denied that two sets of books were kept. later, peterson recanted that testimony, saying it was based on misunderstandings within the company
the committee concluded last week that peterson's explanation ``strained credibility'' but added that the panel lacked sufficient evidence to seek a perjury indictment of him
osha, meanwhile, announced last week that it would quit relying only on company-maintained injury records in deciding whether a plant should be inspected further
beginning this past monday, the agency's inspectors are to ``walk through'' the high-hazard areas of each plant after reviewing their safety logs
the committee, like officials in some other government agencies, concluded that exempting companies from inspections based on employer-maintained records encouraged companies to under-report injuries and illnesses
judges shouldn't be so quick to order couples in bitter divorces to share custody of their children, because the arrangement can do more harm than good to the youngsters, a researcher said thursday
far too often, said psychologist judith wallerstein, the courts are ``putting children in the middle of the battlefield.''
wallerstein, head of the center for the family in transition, helped conduct a study of joint custody arrangements, which have become increasingly popular in recent years
findings from the study were presented here wednesday at the annual meeting of the american orthopsychiatric association
researchers at the non-profit research and counseling center, located in corte madera, studied the children of 100 couples who went through bitter divorces and had custody arrangements decided by the courts. in about one-third of those cases, joint custody was ordered
researchers assessed the psychological health of the children by testing, interviews and talks with their parents, and found that children were psychologically worse off _ more depressed, withdrawn and uncommunicative _ if joint custody was imposed
the researchers also studied 93 children whose parents parted amicably and chose their own custody arrangements. again, about one-third of the cases involved joint custody
children in that group were not affected by custody arrangements, the study found
in all, 33 states have enacted legislation that permits courts to order joint custody, evidence of the growing trend in its favor, wallerstein said
it's very important for children of divorces to maintain a continuous relationship with both parents, but that doesn't have to be with the child going back and forth,'' wallerstein said thursday in an interview
what's important is the relationship'' between parent and child, she said. ``it is quality of relationship sustained over time.''
jeremy fogel, supervising judge for family court in santa clara county, said the study confirmed his observations. ``an equal time share will not solve the problems of a very conflicted relationship between parents,'' fogel said
a family law attorney in oakland, carole h. rochlin, said he fears some people may use the findings to argue against joint custody
we'd get back to the days where either one parent or the other has custody _ where we had these destructive custody fights,'' said rochlin. he heads a group called equal rights for fathers, which favors joint custody. one week</head>
the district of columbia school board, claiming budget shortfalls, voted thursday to furlough all employees for one to seven days
the board also voted to cut some summer school sessions, reduce purchases, and institute a hiring freeze because of a $15 million gap in the fiscal year 1988 supplemental budget, according to acting school superintendent alfred jenkins
furloughing all city school employees for up to seven days could save the school district $8.1 million in pay and other costs, jenkins said
i don't feel very good about it at all,'' jenkins said. ``i only know the reality is we just don't have the money. we have to make plans for any eventuality.''
jenkins said the school board did not decide whether the furloughs would take place on consecutive days, or whether they would be spread out between now and sept. 30, the end of the 1988 budget year
city council member hilda mason, who chairs the council's education and libraries panel, said she did not know whether the school district would run into accreditation problems if schools were closed
one possibility is that the furloughs would come during the summer, when most students aren't in school, while another scenario is that the temporary layoffs could be staggered in order to keep schools open, mason said
council chairman david clarke called the school board's decision ``the height of irresponsibility,'' and said that the council has approved a total of $37.7 million in additional school spending for fiscal years 1988 and 1989
the school board requested an additional $25.1 million in the 1988 budget supplement, but the council approved only $10 million of that request
including the supplemental increases, the 22,000-pupil school system will receive $579.5 million in the 1988 budget year
about 25 high school students and a teacher are being tested for aids after a 16-year-old jabbed them with a surgical instrument taken from a biology classroom, the principal said thursday
there is no indication that anyone was sick with anything, but it's better to be safe than sorry,'' said albert ferraro jr., principal at westerly high school
ferraro said the student, who was not identified, jabbed a teacher in the side and drew blood monday with a lancet, a two-edged, pointed device used to prick the skin for blood samples
about 25 students reported monday and tuesday that they had been poked as well, and a police officer who frisked the boy in the school office monday came in contact with the lancet in the teen-ager's pocket, ferraro said
the student was suspended for 10 days monday after the teacher, whom ferraro would not identify, filed assault charges
the teacher, police officer and students were given tetanus and hepatitis shots at westerly hospital on monday and tuesday, ferraro said
on wednesday, he said, the students began returning to the hospital, where their blood was being drawn and sent to the state department of health for the aids test. the results can take up to two weeks, a hospital spokeswoman said
ferraro said he recommended the testing after talking to the school doctor
the federal agency that regulates savings institutions said thursday that an internal investigation has found no criminal activity by a subsidiary agency that manages property from bankrupt s&amp;ls
however, the report by federal home loan bank board inspector general paul gibbons did reveal ``ineffective business practices'' by the federal asset disposition association
the investigation was requested in september by rep. james florio, d-n.j., after a critic of fada complained that he was being investigated by a private detective
william t. juliano, a mount laurel, n.j., developer who was threatening a lawsuit against fada, charged that the agency, through its law firm, hired a detective agency to probe his financial affairs
juliano, according to florio, reported that his office was broken into on sept. 14 and that eavesdropping equipment was found in the ceiling
gibbons, however, said new jersey state police had found no evidence of wiretapping at juliano's office and local police had closed their break-in investigation for lack of evidence
jon shure, a spokesman for florio, said the congressman had just received the report and had not had a chance to review it
but, he added, ``we are still pursuing our own look into fada. it is still very much a live issue. nothing would be in that report that would make us say, `ok we're not interested in fada anymore.'''
shure said there has been no result reported from a parallel investigation of the charges by the justice department. he said florio has asked congress' investigative arm, the general accounting office, to review the bank board report
karl hoyle, a bank board spokesman, said the report made no judgment about the propriety of hiring a private detective agency, whose investigators in questioning juliano identified themselves as representing a firm selling credit card
hoyle said the detective agency was hired without the knowledge of bank board officials and that the board subsequently directed that no investigators be hired without its permission
the bank board report also found no evidence to support allegations leveled by two others: pasquale verona, a fort myers, fla., real estate investor, and joe r. dobson, a austin, texas, developer
verona charged that fada officials offered him a bribe, in the form of a consulting fee, if he would back off from complaints he made to members of congress about the agency
dobson, according to florio, said his office was broken into and ransacked after he told fada officials he had secretly taped his conversations with them
members of congress, real estate investors and others have criticized fada for being too sluggish in selling property from bankrupt s&amp;ls, thus depriving the cash-short federal fund that insures s&amp;l deposits of money. they have said the agency is riddled with conflicts of interest and wastes money
among the poor business practices acknowledged by the bank board report were failure to return telephone calls to investors interested in buying property managed by fada and poor dissemination of bidding information
the house banking committee, meanwhile, has been preparing its own, broader report on fada, which according to an industry newsletter is being held up by the committee chairman, rep. fernand g. st germain, d-r.i
rick maurano, an aide to st germain, said the congressman was unavailable thursday evening to comment on the fada investigation. house banking committee aides did not return telephone calls on the subject
eleven men were charged after a 19-year-old woman told police she was raped repeatedly by a group of men who urged onlookers at a ranch to join in, authorities said thursday
some of the men watching illegal cockfights in a shed nearby heard the women's cries for help but did nothing; others joined in the assault saturday night, said ricardo carrillo, duval county assistant district attorney
some were holding her by the legs and by the arms, and some were covering her eyes and mouth,'' carrillo said
the woman told authorities that a group of men abducted her half a block from home and took her to a ranch north of town
authorities believe the woman, who has two children, was stripped naked and raped repeatedly for several hours in the back seat of a car, said carrillo
everybody's a little shocked and outraged by it,'' said assistant district attorney rodolfo v. gutierrez
seven men have been charged with sexual assault, three have been charged with sexual assault and kidnapping and one has been charged with kidnapping
officials say 20 to 30 men were at the ranch
a lot of people were present that did not participate, didn't assault her, but at the same time they didn't do anything to help her or do anything to stop the other people from assaulting her,'' gutierrez said
even though legally they may not be responsible, morally they didn't do anything to try and prevent this from happening or to stop it once it started.''
he said the woman knew some of her assailants but said some covered their faces while attacking her
some of them we've brought in have admitted it,'' carrillo said. ``some are not talking.''
carrillo said the woman was walking home from her uncle's house when several men abducted her and took her to the ranch
the woman reported four men later took her to another location, raped her again and dropped her off near her home early sunday, carrillo said
she was treated at humana hospital in corpus christi and released earlier this week, authorities said
people in the remote town of about 5,000 are frightened by the incident, said a 44-year-old woman who asked not to be identified because in the town ``everybody knows everybody.''
you expect something like this to happen in corpus or san antonio or dallas, but not in san diego,'' said the woman
all of the men charged are from san diego, officials said
ten suspects were arrested wednesday and thursday or turned themselves in. at least four were released on bail of $20,000 each
one man was not in custody thursday evening but was expected to turn himself in, gutierrez said, adding that there may be more arrests
an american attorney for gen. manuel antonio noriega said thursday he has advised the panamanian leader to be wary of possible attempts to kidnap him and bring him to trial on drug charges in the united states
neal sonnett of miami said he based his advice on history _ citing previous u.s. kidnappings of fugitives _ and the refusal recently of elliott abrams, assistant secretary of state, to rule out any option for removing noriega
the lawyer said a kidnapping attempt would not necessarily come while noriega is in panama. it could come as the general sought refuge in another country, he said
i don't know that the united states would send marshals, armed guards or troops to snatch him from panama,'' sonnett said
he said he would ``insist not just on a (u.s.) promise not to extradite but also on a guarantee of safe passage'' if noriega leaves panama
noriega, the military power behind the civilian government, has been indicted on drug and racketeering charges in miami and tampa
u.s. state department spokesman rudy boone on thursday refused to comment on sonnett's suggestion that kidnapping was a u.s. option
sonnett cited the u.s. decision in 1985 to force down a plane in sicily that was transporting four accused palestinian hijackers as ``an indication of the length to which the united states will go to secure a fugitive.''
a horse trainer thursday admitted taking part in a scheme to collect $81,000 in insurance by sending eight horses to their death over a cliff
bobby griffin, 45, of lufkin, texas, pleaded guilty along with leonard keith autterson, 48, of lakeside, calif., to conspiracy to defraud an insurance company
each faces up to five years in prison at sentencing may 23, but assistant u.s. attorney patrick coughlin said he will recommend probation. both men have agreed to testify at the trial of four co-defendants, coughlin said
the staged truck accident occurred in 1983 off interstate 8 near jacumba, about 70 miles east of san diego. seven horses died at the scene; the eighth horse was destroyed
coughlin said griffin was listed as the buyer of the horses because the alleged conspirators needed the name of someone in the horse business to make the accident look legitimate
i was supposed to get $10,000 to use my name as the contractor,'' griffin told u.s. district judge gordon thompson jr
they were supposed to be selling them to me and ship them to texas. i didn't put it together; i just agreed to it,'' said griffin. he said he did not get any of the money
autterson told thompson he was offered $7,500 by another co-defendant to drive the horses off a cliff
did you cause the accident?'' asked thompson
i drove the truck up to the cliff and made sure the horses were in it,'' he answered
political extremist lyndon larouche said thursday the defense at his conspiracy trial would show that vice president george bush condoned infiltration and harassment of larouche groups
vice president george bush is going to be dropped into this trial,'' larouche said without offering evidence to support this allegations. ``this is no longer a credit card case. this is the george bush-oliver north case.''
larouche is on trial on federal charges he conspired to obstruct a grand jury investigation into alleged credit card fraud by his 1984 presidential campaign
his remarks thursday were his first since defense lawyers gained access to government documents discussing alleged infiltration of larouche groups by fbi and cia operatives
according to trial testimony, the documents do not mention bush, but larouche said the vice president had to be aware of the alleged infiltration because he presided over an interagency panel that discussed intelligence matters
prosecutors contend intelligence operatives quoted in the documents lied in claiming to have been asked by the fbi and cia to infiltrate larouche groups
but larouche said the documents proved his contention that the reagan administration plotted to ruin him because he refused to support the president's contra-aid program
larouche said the defense also would prove that bush, contrary to his public statements, had a central role in the shipment of arms to iran and the diversion of the profits to the contra rebels in nicaragua
the people who are running the operations are accountable to him,'' said larouche, who espouses theories of world conspiracies and has accused prominent world leaders of being soviet agents
the vice president's office did not return telephone calls from the associated press
testimony in the trial of larouche, six aides and five larouche political organizations has been halted while a judge holds hearings on defense allegations that prosecutors withheld evidence of infiltration of larouche groups
the hearings are expected to continue at least through next week
bush's office and numerous federal agencies have been ordered to search their files for references to larouche, a candidate for the democratic presidential nomination. off-broadway</head>
sandra bernhard is a pouty priestess of pop culture, wickedly dissecting life and what passes for art and artifice at the end of the 1980s
in her show, ``without you i'm nothing,'' which opened thursday at off-broadway's orpheum theater, bernhard slouches and scowls through 90 minutes of brash comedy and rock music that is not only off-the-wall but occasionally beyond it
this outrageous woman, all lips, legs and long arms, is best known to late- night tv watchers for harassing david letterman. she's also remembered as the actress who stole ``king of comedy,'' martin scorsese's movie about a tv talk show host, from robert deniro and jerry lewis
with her new theater performance piece, bernard offers a string of unconventional, often very funny, observations about show business and the people who are consumed by it
it's a peculiar subculture which she celebrates and puts down at the same time. but then, as bernhard explains to the audience, her father was a proctologist and her mother an abstract artist, so that's just how she views the world
she seems to rap about anything that comes into her head, and the evening wanders from monologue to monologue. the performer, dressed in black pants and a denim jacket, is surrounded on stage by a small rock band. between conversations, bernhard breaks into song, much of it surprisingly effective. her repertoire ranges from such golden oldies as ``the lion sleeps tonight'' to material she wrote herself
bernard's targets in this show, which she co-authored with director john boskovich, range from broadway to cabaret to rock 'n' roll icons to fashion to her own childhood back in flint, mich., and later scottsdale, ariz
she tweaks the noses of many show biz personalities, some more famous than others. not many comedians would open their show with a parody of andrea marcovicci, a cabaret artist who is certainly not a household name in middle america
bernard also takes on more familiar performers _ joni mitchell comes in for a hilarious drubbing, for example _ and kayoes such diverse cultural phenomenon as esprit, the selling of fashion as affectation, and vanity fair, ``the least pretentious magazine in america.''
the material grows more serious, too. there's a wonderful sequence where bernhard fantasizes about being friends with stevie nicks of fleetwood mac and celebrates the women of rock 'n' roll
the actress is not on everybody's wavelength. bernhard doesn't travel in a straight line. she swoons, swerves, backtracks and then races ahead at 100 mph. but it's fun trying to keep up with her with her more fanciful observations. ``without you i'm nothing'' makes for a wild night ride of off-beat humor
britain said it would investigate thursday after a british newspaper said that kurt waldheim may have cooperated with u.s. and british intelligence in return for having incriminating evidence erased from his war record
john wakeham, a cabinet member and leader of the house of commons, told parliament the home office will conduct an inquiry into official military files that the times of london reported are missing from the public records office
the paper said the files may relate to the world war ii record of waldheim, a lieutenant in the german army who later became secretary-general of the united nations and now is president of austria
the times said that in one file on military activities in yugoslavia between may 1944 and the end of the war, an entire section listed in the index as ``allegations of murder of british prisoners of war'' was missing
waldheim served as an intelligence officer in the balkans and was posted at dubrovnik, yugoslavia, during that period
the times quoted robert herzstein, history professor at the university of south carolina, as saying several records of the british contribution to the u.n. war crimes commission also appeared to be missing from government records
britain ordered an inquiry earlier this year into the cases of six captured british commandos executed in 1944 after being handed over for interrogation to the german army unit in which waldheim served
the newspaper said it also has evidence that british wartime documents and foreign office papers which probably related to waldheim's wartime role had been suppressed
it said this suppression raised suspicions that waldheim may have collaborated with the americans and the british after the war ended in 1945 in return for having his german army record purged of incriminating evidence
the newspaper quoted herzstein as saying he believes waldheim passed on large amounts of information after the war to allied intelligence agents based at bad tolz, west germany, especially on the communist partisans in yugoslavia and guerrillas in greece
herzstein is due to publish a book next week that suggests waldheim worked for the americans after the war
a panel of historians has concluded waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to nazi atrocities in the balkans, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them. it said waldheim concealed his wartime past and tried to make it seem harmless once he could no longer hide it
the panel left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime. waldheim has denied any wrongdoing. hospital</head>
a judge said thursday he had no alternative when he sent a 4{-year-old boy to a state mental hospital
authorities said the child is apparently the youngest ever committed in maryland
there was a lack of any other resources under the circumstances,'' montgomery county juvenile court judge douglas moore said in a telephone interview from rockville. he said the boy was committed tuesday evening
the child was receiving individual attention at the springfield hospital center in sykesville, said mike golden, spokesman for the department of health and mental hygiene
the action stemmed from an investigation by the county department of social services into charges that the boy had been neglected, said j.c. shay, spokesman for the state department of human resources
this is an emergency placement, until we can find something better,'' shay said. ``the boy needs in-patient psychiatric care.''
officials could not remember any child that young ever before being committed in maryland, said dr. henry harbin, director of the state mental hygiene administration
winifred depalma, an attorney with the maryland disability law center, called the move ``mind-boggling.''
i have never heard of them committing a child that young,'' she said. ``they have no facilities for a child that age. there are some very emotionally disturbed youths in the adolescent unit. in no case should a 4-year-old child ever be committed there.''
