the suspense over who will end up with federated department stores inc. remained unbroken as the retailer's board put off deciding whether to remain betrothed to r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. or switch affections to campeau corp
the company's board of directors postponed the decision at least until friday after macy presented a new, $6.73 billion takeover offer thursday morning. campeau is offering $6.62 billion
general electric co. reached an agreement with rival bidder whirlpool corp., allowing it to proceed unopposed with a $507.6 million offer to acquire roper corp
ge spokesman george jamison said thursday the connecticut-based company's offer of $54 per share would be extended until 5 p.m. monday. whirlpool simultaneously announced it was terminating its $50-per-share offer
the battle to acquire roper, an appliance and lawn equipment manufacturer based in augusta, ga., began last november
the price of resorts international inc. stock slumped as donald trump, who holds 88 percent of the company's voting power, withdrew his bid to take the hotel-casino operator private and indicated he would block a higher, rival offer by entertainer merv griffin
resorts' class a stock fell by $1.62{ per share to $28.87{ thursday in trading on the american stock exchange
a supreme court justice has set aside an appeals court ruling that had cleared the way for the merger of the photofinishing operations of eastman kodak co. and fuqua industries inc
officials of the companies involved in the dispute disagreed thursday over whether the ruling by justice byron r. white would force the merger to be dissolved, at least temporarily
the deal created the nation's largest wholesale photofinishing operation
tropicana products inc. has obtained a court order barring a departed key engineer from divulging ``trade secrets and secret processes'' to rival minute maid
tropicana contends when engineer richard a. hamilton left last week he expressed an ``intense dislike of tropicana and stated he would `get' the company.''
hamilton began work monday with minute maid, a subsidary of coca-cola foods
nasa officials say two of the three ``more attractive sites'' for a $1 billion plant to build the next generation of space shuttle rocket boosters are on government property in mississippi
the third is near cape canaveral, fla., where shuttles are launched, nasa said thursday
nasa officials said they expect a site to be selected before requests are issued in june for proposals to build and operate the plant
wall street ``whiz kid'' david bloom has pleaded guilty to mail and securities fraud charges, admitting to an art work shopping spree funded with $10 million bilked from scores of investors
bloom, 23, faces five years in prison and fines up to double the amount lost by investors. he told a federal judge thursday he spent investors' money on ``art, automobiles, two homes and furnishings.''
house and senate negotiators reached tentative agreement on a sweeping trade bill designed to open foreign markets, but only after loading it with provisions that lawmakers said could invite a veto
repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies, tough trade sanctions against toshiba corp. of japan and millions of dollars in new subsidies designed to boost u.s. grain exports were tentatively included in the legislation approved thursday evening
the italian government has agreed to explore possible collaboration in building the ``super collider'' atom smasher planned by the energy department, energy secretary john herrington says
italy has not agreed to contribute to the cost of the $4.4 billion installation, but collaboration could still lead to savings, officials said thursday
italy has a distinguished history in advanced physics research going back to nuclear pioneer enrico fermi in the 1930s
the chairman of the senate banking committee has proposed creation of a regulatory committee to oversee the nation's financial markets in the wake of the october stock market crash
the bill, sponsored by sen. william proxmire, d-wis., is being pushed by former new jersey sen. nicholas brady, who headed a presidential task force that studied the crash
the bill creates an intermarket coordination committee composed of the chairmen of the federal reserve, securities and exchange commission and the commodity futures trading commission, officials said thursday
the teamsters union and the trucking industry have reached tentative agreement on a three-year national freight contract covering 200,000 drivers and warehouse workers
the new agreement, unless rejected by at least two-thirds of the affected union members, will replace a contract that expired at midnight thursday
terms of the accord were not disclosed thursday. including fringe and pension benefits, the industry had calculated its total labor costs to date at $23 an hour
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 9.94 to 1,988.06 thursday, finishing the week with a gain of 9.11 points
the dollar fell slightly against major currencies
bond prices were narrowly mixed as the yield on the benchmark 30-year treasury bond slipped to 8.74 percent
the contract for june delivery of live hogs plunged, and crude oil prices were mostly unchanged
oil trading has turned slow and lackluster with the approach of the holiday weekend
oil prices were mixed thursday in dull trading on the new york mercantile exchange. futures contracts for crude oil were unchanged to marginally higher, while heating oil contracts declined and gasoline was mixed
contracts for may delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, settled on the exchange at $17.08 per 42-gallon barrel, unchanged from wednesday's close
among refined products, the april contract for wholesale heating oil fell 0.45 cent a gallon to 48.15 cents. unleaded gasoline for april delivery edged up by 0.02 cent a gallon to 48.67 cents
there was no action; it was just dead,'' said chris mccormack, a futures broker for investment firm drexel burnham lambert inc
the mercantile exchange is closed friday in observance of the good friday holiday. mccormack noted that the bulk of the limited activity stemmed from traders balancing out their positions in advance of the weekend
market participants are looking ahead to an upcoming meeting of the pricing committee of the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries. the session is due to start on april 9 in vienna, austria. grows</head>
magdalena barut didn't need the money, but she was bored; tired of ``just chasing the chickens around the yard'' of the maui home she has lived in since 1954
so, on a whim, the 67-year-old barut applied for a job at mcdonald's, figuring she would be rejected because of her age
but not only has mcdonald's hired barut and other senior citizens like her, the nationwide hamburger chain also lets them pick their own shifts, gives them 20 hours of training for just one task _ barut learned to make french fries _ and in some cases drives them to and from work
i don't know i was worried about getting turned down,'' said barut, who has been promoted to running a cash register. ``i guess we just didn't figure how desperate they are for workers around here.''
mcdonalds _ which traditionally hires high school students for part-time, minimum-wage jobs _ is only one of the many companies facing a labor crunch in hawaii
businesses on the islands of oahu, kauai and maui and hawaii, especially those dependent on the ever-burgeoning tourist industry, are scrambling for workers as the state's unemployment rate falls to record lows and soon-to-open luxury resorts compete for the existing work force
the state department of labor and industrial relations reported a statewide unemployment rate of just 3.3 percent for february, the most recent data available
basically, everybody's got a job who wants one,'' according to a spokeswoman from the hawaii visitors bureau, who said the state's reputation could suffer if hotels, restaurants and other tourist-related businesses could not hire enough people to serve their guests
the aloha spirit is one of the prime attractions of hawaii,'' said the spokeswoman, who asked not to be named. ``if that begins to change because there are not enough people to fill all the jobs, we could have a serious problem.''
a report by the labor department's tourism and training council projected an average of 6,400 workers would be needed each year to meet job openings forecast for hawaii, kauai and maui counties through 1995. but the study found that after this year, only about 1,600 people _ or one-fourth the demand _ would enter the job market each year until then
those dim projections helped convince mcdonalds to turn to senior citizens to fill its employee gaps. other companies have taken more drastic measures
the westin maui hotel in kaanapali, in a joint venture with the state, helps ferry workers from the nearby island of molokai, where a declining pineapple industry led to a 5.8 percent unemployment rate in february. other businesses followed suit
maui had a low unemployment rate and molokai had a high one, so we decided to work together,'' said lindsey geyer, the director of human resources at the westin maui
although many are basking in the glow of the state's ``full employment,'' others say the prevalence of tourist-related jobs _ which account for about one third of the employment in the state _ means many residents earn less than they would in other industries. since hawaii's cost of living is about 26 percent higher than the national average, many people struggle to make ends meet
the islands may be paradise, but there also very expensive,'' said geyer. educators in the state are also concerned; they say that because of the proliferation of jobs, young people who would otherwise go to college are lured away to the work world
and economists say that full employment could trigger higher inflation, because when businesses compete for employees _ offering more pay and better fringe benefits _ the cost is ultimately passed on to the consumer
then, of course, there are the tourists
1987 was a record year for tourism in the state, with about 5.7 million people visiting the islands, 3.3 percent more than the year before, according to the visitors bureau
today's traveler and tomorrow's traveler want more service, and that's labor intensive,'' said dorothy bremner, employment analyst for the labor department's tourism and training council
an obvious cure _ enticing more people to work and live here _ could be painful
bringing people in presents plenty of other problems, and our infrastruture is already overloaded,'' bremner said. ``you'll find very few people interested in making it any more crowded here.''
a better solution, she says, is to upgrade the skills of the people who already live here, and make jobs in the tourist industry career opportunities rather than just average-wage occupations
the southeast economy continues to benefit from a depressed dollar, especially the region's manufacturing and agriculture sectors, according to the federal reserve bank of atlanta
regional manufacturing continues to expand, especially for textiles and paper,'' the atlanta fed said in a periodic report prepared for the latest meeting of the federal open market committee
the petroleum and coal extraction industries are reviving,'' the report said. ``although retailers' sales are not increasing much when compared to last year, inventories are not excessive and auto sales are improving'' in the atlanta district, which covers all or parts of six southeastern states
loan demand has turned up at commercial banks and tourism has posted healthy gains. the outlook for agriculture is positive thanks in part to government programs. although commercial construction continues at a low ebb, residential building is improving in some areas.''
the analysis was prepared for the ``beige book'' used by the fomc for its meeting tuesday. the committee meets about every six weeks to set the nation's monetary policy
nationally, the analysis said, ``reports confirm a moderate expansion. ... strength in the manufacturing sector and continued moderate growth in employment are sustaining the current expansion.''
the atlanta district covers all of georgia, florida and alabama, the eastern half of tennessee and the southern halves of mississippi and louisiana
the merger between the photofinishing operations of eastman kodak co. and fuqua industries inc. has had a rocky trip through the court system and the journey is not over yet
u.s. supreme court justice byron white on thursday set aside a lower court's decision to allow the merger to go through
it was unclear what effect this temporary ruling would have, since the merger was completed before white's ruling
fuqua president lawrence klamon said he didn't think it would change anything and kodak asked white to reconsider
this has no practical effect on the merger,'' klamon said from fuqua's headquarters in atlanta. ``it's a done deal. this is a moot point.''
the legal wrestling over the merger comes as a result of a lawsuit filed by a small wholesale photofinishing competitor, phototron corp. of san bernardino, calif., which claims the merger violates antitrust laws
in court documents, phototron claims that together kodak and fuqua's subsidiary, colorcraft corp., would control between 65 percent to 88 percent of the wholesale photofinishing market
this merger would require us to get into a closet with a gorilla,'' said joseph alioto, the san francisco attorney who is representing phototron
the company's lawsuit was filed in fort worth, texas, and a judge there on feb. 22 blocked the merger until he could hear the case and issue a ruling
kodak and fuqua, however, appealed that decision to the u.s. court of appeals in new orleans, where a three-judge panel on monday reversed that decision
those judges said phototron had no right to stop the merger and gave kodak and fuqua permission to merge
the two companies immediately combined operations the next day, forming a new company called qualex inc., which has 94 processing labs around the country and is based in durham, n.c., which had been the home of colorcraft
wholesale photofinishers primarily process film and print photographs for supermarkets, discount store chains and drug stores
white's decision to set aside the court of appeals ruling until tuesday when additional arguments on the case can be heard further muddles the situtation
alioto said the ruling means the merger will have to be dismantled
they acted too fast and now they have to face the consequences,'' he said. ``whatever was done has to be undone.''
but klamon, who is an attorney, said white's decision will have no practical effect on the merger. he explained it using an analogy of a car approaching a stop light
he said the federal judge in fort worth turned the light red as the kodak-colorcraft merger approached. the court of appeals turned the light green and the merger went on its way, klamon said
now, phototron has convinced the supreme court to turn the light red again, but it no longer matters because the merger has already passed through the intersection
klamon said he expects the high court to dismiss white's order on tuesday once it finds out that the merger has already proceeded
kodak spokesman paul allen said the company's attorneys are still reviewing the decision
regardless of the outcome of the supreme court fight, phototron's original lawsuit against kodak will continue in u.s. district court in fort worth and a decision there could still force the merger to unravel, alioto said
the head of cbs inc. says he has had no discussions about selling either the cbs television network or loews corp.'s stake in cbs and says neither one is for sale
laurence a. tisch, chief executive of cbs, told cbs employees in an unusual memorandum on thursday that he is committed to the long-term prospects of cbs and wants its television network to reclaim first place in the ratings
but he added, ``we know it will take several years _ not a few months _ to get there.''
in recent weeks, rumors have spread that tisch might be interested in selling the cbs television network while keeping the cbs radio and television stations
alternatively, there were rumors that tisch planned to engineer the sale of the 24.9 percent stake in cbs held by loews, a new york-based holding company with interests in tobacco, real estate and financial services that tisch also heads
tisch addressed both issues in the memo, saying neither the block of cbs stock held by loews nor the cbs network is for sale
let me go further. i have met with no one, had no conversation and have received no offer for the sale of loews' cbs stock or the cbs network. if you hear or read anything to the contrary, it is absolutely, totally and categorically untrue,'' he said
on wall street, cbs fell 62.5 cents a share to $156.37{ in trading on the new york stock exchange
speculation about tisch's plans has been fueled by the cbs network's steady decline in prime-time audience ratings. cbs is expected to finish in last place among the three major networks this season, and some analysts have questioned whether tisch has the patience to wait for a revival
but tisch said loews bought its stake in cbs because it felt ``this is a good investment in a premier company in a special business _ broadcasting.''
nothing has changed that belief. loews was not looking for a quick turnaround. that has never been the loews style,'' he said
since he became chief executive of cbs in the fall of 1986, cbs has sold its records, books and magazine divisions, amassing about $3 billion in cash
tisch said the sales have allowed cbs to focus on its basic business
he conceded he has offered ``some gloomy comments'' about the economic outlook and its potential effect of the broadcasting business
but he said those views have ``nothing to do with my deep personal interest in and my commitment to the long-term prospects of cbs.''
we are committed to build a schedule that makes us first again. with our eye on that long-term goal, we shouldn't be overly concerned about small setbacks,'' he wrote
british industrialist brian beazer says koppers co. is trying to confuse its employees and pittsburgh supporters over his $1.7 billion takeover offer. koppers says beazer is the one confused
koppers management has diverted attention to irrelevant subjects such as the role of our financial advisers ... but they have never responded to the key questions,'' beazer plc, the construction and building materials company, said thursday in newspaper advertisements
we have asked koppers management again and again to sit down and discuss our proposal,'' the ad said. ``instead, they have mounted a massive campaign of disinformation, creating panic and confusion among koppers employees and the pittsburgh community.''
koppers vice president j. roger beidler, responding to the ad at a news conference, said beazer has misconstrued koppers' profit margins and employment trends
koppers again criticized shearson lehman hutton inc. for being an equity partner with beazer in bns inc., the company formed to launch the $60-per-share takeover
the investment bank overstepped the traditional role to become a corporate raider, beidler said
shearson has said it is merely helping finance the tender offer
u.s. sen. john heinz, meanwhile, failed wednesday to amend a banking bill with language to bar another beazer backer, national westminster bank plc, from its role as an equity partner in bns, said richard bryers, an aide to heinz. but the senator won a promise from banking committee chairman william proxmire to hold hearings in april on the heinz measure as separate legislation, the aide said
at a news conference called by u.s. rep. doug walgren, d-pa., robert a. papariella, 38, said he resigned his job as a vice president of investments in shearson's pittsburgh office in protest of the firm's role in the koppers takeover attempt
papariella, repeating claims made by koppers and its allies, including heinz, said shearson stands to make $150 million or more in fees on the takeover
shearson spokesman michael o'neill said the figure is inaccurate, but he declined to offer a specific figure
beidler, meanwhile, said beazer was mistaken when he claimed recently he could improve koppers' profit margins in construction materials from 10 percent to the industry average of 20 percent
beidler said beazer misconstrued companywide margins for those of one segment. koppers' margins in sand and gravel exceed 20 percent, and margins in crushed stone are near 20 percent, he said
he's going to find very little room ... to achieve that kind of improvement,'' beidler said at a news conference. ``koppers has been running the business as well or better than most companies.''
beazer's ad tried to dispel fears expressed by koppers and its allies that a takeover could elmininate 1,100 pittsburgh-area jobs and sap the local economy of an estimated $232 million per year
all beazer companies have retained their local offices,'' the ad said. mentioning gifford-hill in dallas, squires in charlotte, n.c.; cohn communities in atlanta; phillips builders in nashville, tenn.; tidewater construction co. in norfolk, va.; and fk co. in farmington, n.m
the ad said employment at koppers has declined from 18,000 to 1,000, while employment at beazer has grown from 4,000 to 18,000 in the past five years
beidler said koppers eliminated about 9,700 jobs through asset sales and attrition but added about 6,000 through growth in its businesses. employment declined from 14,500 in 1983 to 10,700 in 1987, he said
beazer said koppers' efforts to find a white knight could lead to consequences worse that beazer's plan to sell the chemical businesses if it gains control
remember, it was `white knight' chevron that emptied the gulf building,'' beazer said
opponents of the beazer bid, including federal, state and local elected officials, say they don't want the landmark koppers building in pittsburgh to be emptied as gulf corp.'s headquarters were after t. boone pickens drove the oil company into a merger with chevron
every company we've acquired has improved its performance and profitability, with corresponding growth in opportunities and benefits for employees,'' beazer said. against pound</head>
the dollar was virtually motionless in foreign exchange trading in europe today as activity wound down to a bare minimum ahead of the easter weekend. the u.s. currency remained at a 6-year low against the pound
with most asian and european markets closed for good friday and with corporate clients standing on the sidelines, foreign exchange rooms that were open were mostly idle, traders said
the only european foreign exchange markets open today were those in luxembourg, france and italy, ``but they are all lying low,'' one trader in milan said. ``there is absolutely no direction at all
gold markets in london, zurich and hong kong were closed
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar closed at 124.10 yen, down 0.40 yen from thursday despite some light intervention by the bank of japan, dealers said. later in europe, the dollar was quoted at 124.05 yen
other dollar rates in europe at midmorning, compared with late thursday's rates, included: 1.6558 west german marks, up from 1.6555; 1.3613 swiss francs, down from 1.3635; 5.6250 french francs, up from 5.6130; 1.8630 dutch guilders, up from 1.8575; 1,228.00 italian lire, down from 1,229.50; and 1.2347 canadian dollars, up from 1.2339
the british pound was quoted at $1.8885 _ a six-year high for the second day in a row _ compared with $1.8878 thursday
the dollar and stock prices fell on tokyo markets today as trading decreased with the approach of the easter holidays in the united states and europe
the u.s. currency opened at 124.30 yen and traded between a narrow range of 124.05-124.50 yen. it finished the week at 124.10 yen, down 0.40 yen from thursday's close of 124.50 yen
there is not much happening,'' said peter tasker, head of research at kleinwort benson. ``the dollar is weak and unpopular,'' he said, and a ``poor supply and demand'' contributed to the currency's fall
the bank of japan intervened immediately after the foreign exchange opened for dealing to prop up the sagging currency, but tasker said the amount of dollars the central bank bought was very small
the intervention was a ritual, he added. the bank does not publicly comment on its activities
it's the easter holiday and people are not doing anything,'' added a dealer at a major american securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity
traders said they are anticipating a weak dollar in the new 1988 fiscal year that began today. ``the dollar will be wobbly,'' tasker said, ``but it probably will not fall below 120 yen.''
on the tokyo stock exchange, meanwhile, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues fell for a second consecutive day and lost 156.04 points, or 0.59 percent. it closed at 26,104.22 points
the loss was in ``reaction to an incredibly strong rise over the past week,'' tasker said, referring to the 1,000-point gain the nikkei averaged monday through wednesday. on thursday, the main market barometer lost 59.81 points
traders predicted the market would be quiet and show little direction during its half-day session saturday because of the easter weekend. measure</head>
government leaders and toshiba corp. executives today condemned a u.s. congressional move to punish the electronics giant for a subsidiary's sale of militarily sensitive machines to the soviet union
officials charged the united states was overstepping its boundaries by adding its own penalties to those already taken by japan
the government hinted it might bring the matter before the general agreement on tariffs and trade if the measure becomes law
the united states is seeking to unilaterally impose its own penalties in disregard of the independence of other countries,'' trade minister hajime tamura said in a statement to reporters. ``this is extremely regrettable.''
toshiba corp. president joichi aoi expressed regret, saying his company had been unaware of toshiba machine co.'s illegal sale to the soviets. he urged u.s. lawmakers to reconsider
congressional negotiators reached tentative agreement thursday night on a sweeping trade bill designed to open foreign markets. the measure would ban u.s. government purchases of toshiba equipment for three years and bar the import toshiba machine co. products for the same period
kyodo news service said toshiba corp. escaped the worst possible scenario in which it stood to lose its entire u.s. export market worth $2 billion a year. it said toshiba machine co. faces the loss of $136 million a year
the reagan administration has threatened to veto the bill because of the toshiba provisions and other measures
the japanese government determined last spring that toshiba machine co. sold to the soviets sophisticated machinery capable of silencing submarine propellers. the sales violated japan's own export laws and those of cocom, the western body that monitors such sales to communist nations
the u.s. congressional agreement ``runs counter to a basic principle of cocom that effective enforcement of export controls is entrusted to each participating country's autonomous responsibility,'' foreign minister sosuke uno said in a separate statement
he said the bill would, ``if adopted and implemented, violate the gatt provisions, which the government of japan cannot overlook.''
the columbia record, the capital city's afternoon newspaper for 91 years, ceases publication with today's edition
we will add 10,000 papers to the press run,'' acting managing editor bunny richardson said thursday. ``employees want them, people in the street want them and we've had people calling us who are not subscribers asking us where they can get a copy
there will be a lot of reminiscing in it from old record staffers. they have the same feeling that we have here now: the camaraderie, the feeling of family, the feistiness of a small newspaper.''
the demise of the record was announced jan. 20 by publisher ben r. morris, who said the readers and advertisers of the area can be served better by concentrating resources in a single daily newspaper, the state
there will be other news in the record other than its ceasing publication,'' ms. richardson said. ``we still have to put out a newspaper and that will keep us from feeling sad.''
the record staff will be merged with that of the state. both newspapers are owned by the knight-ridder newspaper group
the battle to acquire roper corp. appeared to be over with the announcement that whirlpool corp. was ending its bid, allowing general electric co. to proceed unopposed with a $507.6 million offer
a spokesman for ge said the fairfield, conn.-based company would extend its offer until 5 p.m. monday. but robert cook, chairman of augusta-based roper, indicated he expected the deal to go through quickly and smoothly
i'd say it's over,'' cook said. ``we had alrady told our stockholders to tender to ge two days ago.''
ge and whirlpool said early thursday that negotiations were continuing over their rival bids for roper, a manufacturer of appliances and lawn equipment
but the companies announced thursday night that whirlpool was terminating its $50-per-share offer for roper
ge is offering roper $54 per share
according to the ge announcement, ge will be free to acquire roper and its manufacturing capacity for kitchen ranges and lawn equipment. whirlpool obtains rights to the roper name for major appliances
ge will supply whirlpool with electric and gas ranges for the roper brand for at least two years under the agreement
also, whirlpool will relinquish its $37.50 per share option on 1.6 million roper shares upon the completion of ge's tender offer. and the companies agreed to various commercial relationships in which ge will sell to whirlpool certain industrial components and materials
the battle to acquire roper began last november, and led to a series of lawsuits charging, among other things, that roper and whirlpool engaged in activities designed to hinder ge's ability to bid competitively for the augusta company
thursday's agreement called for the withdrawal of all lawsuits upon the completion of ge's tender offer
for ge, the roper factories and roper's strong sears relationship makes this an important niche acquisition that will significantly strengthen our appliance business in an increasingly competitive global market,'' said roger w. schipke, ge senior vice president in charge of the company's appliance business
gaining the roper brand name was one of whirlpool's key strategic objectives in pursuing this acquisition,'' said david r. whitwam, chairman, president and chief executive officer of benton harbor, mich.-based whirlpool
with our complementary kitchenaid, whirlpool and roper brands, whirlpool plans to compete vigorously in all segments of the major home appliance market,'' whitwam said
the amicable settlement is beneficial to both parties, and is the foundation for a strong, expanded supplier relationship with whirlpool,'' ge's schipke said
officials reacted with regret and anger today after talks between agriculture minister takashi sato and u.s. officials failed to produce an agreement on japan's restricted imports of beef and citrus fruits
sato began three days of talks in washington on tuesday in hopes of renegotiating a four-year bilateral agreement setting quotas on u.s. beef and citrus exports to japan. no progress was made, and the accord expired thursday
shintaro abe, secretary-general of the governing liberal democratic party, told reporters, ``i am disappointed the talks ended with differences between the positions of the two countries still too great, but sato did his best.''
sato's delegation ``made efforts to explain the situation in japan, but could not regrettably come to an agreement,'' said a foreign ministry spokesman
in washington, u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter said the united states requested an emergency meeting next week of the general agreement on tarrifs and trade, where it will ask that a panel be formed to review u.s. complaints. gatt is an international body for settling trade disputes
sato is scheduled to return sunday to japan, according to an agriculture ministry official who spoke on condition of anonymity
mitsugu horiuchi, chairman of the powerful central union of agricultural cooperatives, issued a strong statement accusing the united states of refusing to hear out japan
though the situation making it impossible for japan to liberalize its market for imported beef and citrus fruits was repeatedly expressed during the talks, the united states government refused to listen and continued to one-sidedly push for total liberalization or a decision by gatt,'' the statement said
horuchi said his organization would continue to urge the government to maintain beef and citrus quotas, saying ``this is the concensus of japan's 5.5 million farmers.''
japan has insisted in past talks with the united states that a liberalized market for beef and citrus imports would have a detrimental effect on domestic producers and lead to unemployment
but the united states has demanded japan remove its quotas and has refused to negotiate unless japan proposed a timetable for liberalization, something japan has yet to do
william d. slattery, a 16-year veteran of twa, has been hired by northwest airlines to head the minnesota-based carrier's flight, maintenance, cargo and ground handling operations
slattery, 45, replaces benjamin griggs jr., who was promoted earlier this week to executive vice president of nwa inc., the parent company of northwest, the carrier announced thursday
slattery, who will carry the title of vice president of operations, also will handle the duties of tom koors, the executive vice president of customer services who resigned last week, the company said
slattery's most immediate challenge is to reconcile the policies and practices of former northwest and republic airlines flight and maintenance operations
northwest merged with republic in august 1986. the combined airline has continued to operate internally as two airlines, although marketing, financial and accounting functions have been merged
slattery's appointment is the latest in a series of changes designed to bring the airline's operating functions under a single responsibility, said steven rothmeier, northwest chairman and chief executive officer
slattery also will be faced with helping to reach contracts with pilots and the international association of machinists, the union that represents 20,000 mechanics, baggage handlers, reservations agents and transportation agents
slattery is perhaps best know for getting braniff inc. off the ground again in march 1984 after its bankruptcy and reorganization in 1982. slattery was president of braniff for less than a year when he resigned amid speculation that braniff chairman jay pritzker was undermining his authority
slattery, who began his airline career as a sales representative for trans world airlines inc., became vice president of twa's international division before leaving for braniff
e.f. hutton &amp; co. says it will plead guilty to up to three felony counts and pay a fine for money laundering _ some which was conducted for organized crime figures _ at its providence branch
the company revealed details of a pending agreement with the u.s. justice department and the u.s. attorney's office in rhode island in a mandatory quarterly report to the securities and exchange commission
federal authorities have been investigating allegations that hutton, which was acquired last year by shearson lehman brothers inc., failed to report cash transactions over $10,000 conducted by its providence branch as required by law
u.s. attorney lincoln c. almond said some of the $1.2 million in transactions involved were for organized crime figures, while others were for ``legitimate'' businessmen trying to hide income from the irs
almond revealed a week ago his office and the justice department's new england organized crime strike force were negotiating a guilty plea in the case
almond and john voorhees, attorney in charge of the strike force's providence office, declined to comment on the sec report, which was filed on wednesday
companies are required to report to the sec any activities that could affect their status as licensed investment dealers
under sec rules, a felony conviction could result in the total suspension of business. but a spokesman for shearson lehman hutton inc. in new york said thursday the company expects to receive waivers from the sec that will allow it to continue operating
in its sec report, hutton said the investigation will result in criminal charges, as opposed to civil penalties that could be imposed under federal law
the company said it will plead guilty to ``no more than three'' felony counts'' and that the allegations ``will result in a fine being imposed in an amount yet to be determined.''
most of the illegal transactions involved stephen fusco, a hutton broker who died of cancer in december 1985. fusco allegedly helped customers break large sums of money into amounts less than $10,000 that were then deposited into their accounts. the scheme is known as structuring
most of the abuses ``took place during 1982 and 1983, and none occurred later than august 1984,'' the company told the sec
michael o'neill, a spokesman for shearson lehman hutton, said thursday that the company does not expect any ``adverse impact on the business.''
last october, the sec found that hutton had violated provisions of the sec law and rules relating to financial record keeeping and reporting of currency transactions
as a result of the findings, hutton was censured and directed to report to the sec on policies and procedures regarding the receipt of cash deposits and to adopt surveillance procedures to monitor deposits of multiple bank checks. election</head>
a dissident movement within the united auto workers will have another chance to elect one of its members to the uaw's powerful executive board in a new regional election ordered by a federal judge
candidate jerry tucker lost a june 1986, election against incumbent region 5 director kenneth worley by two-tenths of a vote and protested that the election was tainted by discrepancies
on wednesday, u.s. district judge richard suhrheinrich in detroit ordered a new election in the eight-state region, which covers 80,000 active and laid-off workers in 68 local unions in missouri, kansas, oklahoma, arkansas, louisiana, texas, colorado and new mexico
tucker and worley again will compete in the election, which could be held in 60 to 90 days. a third candidate also reportedly may enter the race
as director of region 5, the winner will sit with other regional directors and top union officers on the uaw's core decision-making body
the dissident faction, which calls itself new directions, seeks more participation by the rank-and-file in decisions affecting the 1 million-member union and want more open debate about the uaw's general direction and philosophy
tucker said he is most disturbed by the reluctance of union leaders, including uaw president owen bieber, to allow the democratic participation by the rank-and-file as provided under the union's constitution
suhrheinrich also ordered new elections for the region's approximately 300 convention delegates. the uaw can appeal the order, but it cannot by law halt the election, set up by the department of labor, which had brought the case
uaw officials who asked not to be identified said the union would appeal if it believed the decision set a precedent that was harmful to the uaw
the labor department brought three suits against the uaw, charging 27 illegal delegates voted in the election, worley illegally used union money for his campaign and tucker was fired illegally in may 1986 after announcing his candidacy
worley did not return phone calls from the associated press on thursday
chrysler corp. says it will offer a $750 rebate or discount loan financing on its slow-selling new eagle premier, while general motors corp. said it was extending its buyer incentive program on certain buick and oldsmobile models
chrysler's new rebate program takes effect today and will continue indefinitely. the rebate or annual rates of 8.8 percent on loans of up to 72 months may be applied to purchases or leases of the canadian-built car
eagle is a brand-new nameplate and customers are still unsure what it stands for,'' chris cedergren, analyst with j.d. power and associates in suburban los angeles, said thursday
new models, when they are introduced in a market full of incentives, need incentives on them now to draw attention,'' he added. otherwise, buyers ignore the new cars and look for models bearing sale tags, he said
premier needed a level playing field. it has a chance to compete now because it has incentives on it,'' cedergren said
william hoglund, a gm vice president and executive in charge of its buick-oldsmobile-cadillac group, made similar comments earlier this week about gm's new buick regal
despite pricing that gm considered low for a new model, regal's sales were disappointing until early march, when gm offered option-package discounts of up to $900 on the car, hoglund said
on thursday, buick and oldsmobile extended incentives scheduled to expire april 15 until may 11, following a similar step by chevrolet earlier this week
buick extended rebates ranging from $400 to $750 on four models and option-package discounts on six models including regal. oldsmobile extended similar rebates on four models and option discounts on six models
as of march 20, chrysler had sold only 5,086 premier models since the car's introduction late last year, including 4,894 during 1988. cedergren said chrysler had expected premier to take off slowly
however, he said, the car is reaching its target audience of well-to-do young buyers who otherwise wouldn't buy chrysler products, most of which are aimed at buyers interested in prices that are usually lower than gm and ford motor co
it's not pirating sales away from other chrysler models,'' cedergren said
on the gm products, buick rebates include $400 on skylark and $750 on century, lesabre and electra-park avenue. cars must be delivered by may 11. rebates may be used as down payments or taken in cash
oldsmobile rebates include $400 on calais and cutlass calais and $750 on cutlass ciera, delta 88 and ninety-eight
option-package discounts are available on all rebate models as well as buick regal and skyhawk and oldsmobile cutlass supreme and toronado. secrets</head>
tropicana products inc. has obtained a court order in an attempt to ensure that minute maid, its top citrus-juice competitor, doesn't learn trade secrets from an engineer who switched companies
in court documents tropicana claims richard a. hamilton left last week after 3{-years employment, expressing an ``intense dislike of tropicana'' and vowing to ``get'' the company
hamilton began work monday with minute maid, a subsidary of coca-cola foods, alice brink, a spokeswoman at coca-cola foods in houston, said thursday. a judge on tuesday granted tropicana's request to bar hamilton from divulging ``trade secrets or secret processes.''
we take this matter very seriously ... it was intended to make sure (coca-cola) cannot get our proprietary secrets,'' said steven b. gold, tropicana vice president and general counsel
tropicana is considered top in the rapidly growing market for ready-to-serve citrus juices, with minute maid second
it would cause ``last and irreparable harm to tropicana,'' if hamilton were to disclose what he knows to minute maid _ ``which is attempting to develop a commercial pasteurized orange juice product,'' tropicana said in its court papers
tropicana officials maintain hamilton told them he was joining ardmore farms, a small, non-competitive juice processor in deland
tropicana said its concern was ``heightened when shortly after leaving tropicana, (it) discovered that, contrary to his earlier representations, hamilton had in fact accepted a position with coca-cola.''
before he quit tropicana, hamilton told company officials that minute maid representatives had contacted him by telephone at home and at work ``in an attempt to obtain confidential information concerning tropicana's processes,'' court documents contend
but ms. brink said any attempt to get proprietary information are ``definitely against our policy.''
the company told hamilton in writing not to divulge ``anything which would breach the confidentiality agreement he signed with tropicana. we ask our employees to sign a similar agreement,'' she said
last month, seagram co. ltd. agreed to buy tropicana from its parent, beatrice u.s. food corp. for $1.2 billion
general motors corp. has decided its high-tech teamwork and technology exhibit was such a hit in new york in january that it is taking the show on the road
the exhibit is scheduled to stop in april 26-27 in chicago, may 9-10 in los angeles, may 23-24 in dallas, june 6-7 in atlanta, and june 13-17 in warren, mich
at the exhibit, autoworkers, executives and engineers demonstrated new products, technology and production techniques, including a working design studio
we made the point with the new york show that we do have new products and new technology, and we are making great strides,'' said jim crellin, gm's chief spokesman
the show also featured concept cars, offering glimpses of the automotive future, including the cadillac voyage. the sleek voyage is a four-wheel-drive luxury car with a keyless infrared entry system and rear-view television
the teamwork and technology exhibit was held for three days at new york's waldorf-astoria hotel. parts of the show have been displayed in various cities, but most or all of the display will be reassembled for the new tour
