a sharp decline in the size of the american labor force last month sent the civilian unemployment rate to 5.6 percent, its lowest level since 1979, the government said today
construction spending fell 0.3 percent in february, held back by weakness in the residential sector, the commerce department said in another report
the third consecutive monthly decline in construction spending reflected the adverse effects of the new tax law and high vacancy rates for apartments and office buildings
while the number of people at work in march dropped by 306,000, those either holding jobs or looking for them fell by 445,000, the labor department reported
the 0.1 percentage point drop from february's 5.7 percent jobless rate reflected a decrease of 137,000 _ to 6.8 million _ in the number of workers listed as unemployed
janet l. norwood, the commissioner of labor statistics, said a slowdown in the expansion of the labor force is beginning to be reflected in unemployment rates, which had, until last month, been dropping more on the basis of job growth
on thursday, the financial markets gave a mixed performance in quiet pre-holiday trading, with stock prices modestly higher, the dollar losing some ground and interest rates holding steady
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 9.94 to 1,988.06, finishing the week with a gain of 9.11 points. six issues increased in value for every five that fell on the new york stock exchange
in foreign exchange, the dollar headed narrowly lower against all key currencies while the rising pound continued to take center stage in trading
the dollar hit its lowest level against the pound since january 1982 in london. it cost $1.8878 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.8790 late wednesday. later, in new york, one pound cost $1.8874, up from $1.8780
in the credit markets, bond prices and interest rates were narrowly mixed, although the treausury's bellwether 30-year issue managed to end the week with a gain of [ point, or $1.25 per $1,000 face amount. the bond's yield, which moves inversely to its price, slipped to 8.74 percent from 8.76 percent
analysts said traders were reluctant to carry big positions thursday ahead of the easter and passover holiday weekend, especially with the unemployment report due
both the stock and bond markets will be closed today. many currency dealers did not plan to trade today, while others said they would work only half a day. credit</head>
the internal revenue service said today that american corporations' tax payments to the delvalle government of panama will qualify for the u.s. foreign tax credit
the announcement cleared the way for u.s. firms that operate in panama to pay taxes into a special account at the federal reserve bank of new york without jeopardizing the tax credit. the credit is designed to avoid taxation of the same dollar of income by the united states and a foreign country
the action cuts off a source of cash to the financially strapped regime of manuel antonio noriega in panama. the reagan administration has expressed concern that a recent infusion of cash, some of it from u.s. corporate tax payments, may have temporarily strengthened the hold of noriega
the united states recognizes eric arturo delvalle as president. delvalle issued a decree on march 25 directing that income taxes due the government of panama be paid only to a new york federal reserve bank. details. no pickup.</note>
french publisher hachette s.a. said it is increasing its tender offer for grolier inc. to $24 a share, or $444 million
paris-based hachette's original offer of $21 a share was rejected by grolier, a publisher of encyclopedias headquartered in danbury, conn
grolier had no comment on the increased bid, which as announced after the market closed on thursday. hachette's latest offer is due to expire at midnight edt april 14
in new york stock exchange trading thursday, grolier closed at $24.37{ a share, down 62{ cents
andrew j. reinhart, grolier's president and chief operating officer, said the company will consult with its investment adviser, first boston corp., according to today's editions of the wall street journal
grolier has said it would pursue talks with other interested parties to negotiate a sale for a ``satisfactory'' price
separately, hachette said in a statement that the federal trade commission and the justice department terminated the waiting period under federal antitrust law for hachette's initial offer. decision will be announced, picks up 7th graf, for the ...</note>
the board of federated department stores inc. resumed its deliberations today on whether to continue the retailer's alliance with r.h. macy &amp; co. or agree to a buyout by campeau corp
the board was meeting in new york, but federated spokesman jim sluzewski said he had no details about the talks or when an announcement would be made
sluzewski said the board would meet ``as late as they need to.''
the board was believed to be considering a $6.73 billion takeover offer from macy and a $6.62 billion bid from campeau. however, it was possible that higher offers also were on the table
the directors had been expected to reach a decision on which offer to back following an all-day meeting wednesday. however, they agreed to continue their talks after macy submitted a higher bid on thursday
wall street analysts said that even if a decision were announced today, they did not expect the 2-month-old battle for the nation's fifth-largest retailer to end soon
macy's has a slight edge, but i don't think that it's over,'' walter loeb, a retail industry analyst with morgan stanley &amp; co., said thursday. ``there'll be more discussions and more legal wrangling.''
for the first time since it announced its cash-and-stock bid a month ago, macy placed a value on the stock end of its bid and also offered shareholders the option of taking all cash for their shares, federated said in a statement
macy offered $78.92 a share in cash for 80 percent of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares, and said it would pay $60 in cash or exchange five shares in the merged company, macy's-federated inc., for each remaining federated share. that would give the deal an aggregate value of $75.14 a share
macy's latest offer superseded a $6.61 billion bid presented at wednesday's meeting
in its latest bid, campeau said it would pay $74 a share for approximately 80 percent of federated's shares, and the same amount for the remaining 20 percent after a merger, federated said
wall street analysts had said macy would be forced to put a value on the securities portion of its offer to compete with campeau. many investors, including arbitragers who hold a sizable portion of federated stock, had been leaning toward the certainty of campeau's all-cash offer
federated had reached a merger agreement with macy on march 2 but reopened the bidding after campeau raised its offer last week
investors pushed up the price of federated stock thursday, but it held below either of the latest offers, rising $2.62{ a share to $72.87{ on the new york stock exchange
before the meeting, campeau had taken its bid directly to federated's stockholders, in a two-step, all-cash tender offer totaling $6.53 billion
macy was offering $5.4 billion in cash plus stock in the new company. analysts valued that offer at $6.3 billion overall
the fight for federated began jan. 25, when campeau offered $4.2 billion to buy the retailer, which rejected the offer as inadequate
campeau raised its bid, but federated spurned the canadian company's advances until the end of february, when the retailer agreed to negotiate with campeau
but as the federated board was to meet to review that proposal, the macy bid surfaced, and on march 2, federated and macy announced they had reached a merger agreement
court battles over federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense ensued, and both suitors continued to raise their offers until the federated board called for ``final bids'' to be presented wednesday
if federated's board endorses the latest macy bid, the battle will return to court, where the poison pill would again be an issue
the pill would make a takeover attempt more expensive by allowing the retailer's shareholders to buy more company stock at a discount, unless federated's management supported the bid
federated's divisions include bloomingdale's, burdine's, filene's, foley's, lazarus and rich's department stores
macy owns nearly 100 department and specialty stores
campeau, which started in real estate development in canada, moved into the u.s. retail market at the end of 1986 by acquiring allied stores corp
texas railroad commissioner kent hance says he will meet the president of the opec cartel in london monday to discuss the world energy situation and need for stable petroleum prices
hance said he also will urge that the railroad commission gain observer status at opec meetings and that crude oil prices be stabilized in the range of $18 to $24 per barrel
the president of opec, minister rilwanu lukman of nigeria, will participate in the meeting to discuss ``the world energy situation and options for the stabilization of oil prices,'' hance said
he said he has been working through diplomatic channels since last fall to achieve observer status for the commission at meetings of the organization of petroleum exporting countries
a line of communication with opec is of importance to texas and the nation,'' hance said thursday. ``at the present time, the opec cartel sets the price, and we have no input.''
the designation means that non-opec members can attend meetings but can't vote. opec ministers can exclude observers from their meetings as they choose
oil cartel founders used the railroad commission as their model when opec was formed in 1960 because ``texas is one of the largest non-opec producers in the world,'' hance said
lukman scheduled a meeting of opec`s pricing committee for april 9 in vienna
texas railroad commission was established in 1891 to prevent abuses and discrimination in freight and passenger tariffs on railroads, but its powers were later broadened to include regulation of oil and gas production. also running on general news wires</note>
a sharp decline in the size of the american labor force last month sent the civilian unemployment rate to a decade-low 5.6 percent, the government said today
while the number of people at work in march dropped by 306,000, those either holding jobs or looking for them fell by 445,000. the 0.1 percentage point drop from february's 5.7 percent jobless rate reflected a decrease of 137,000 _ to 6.8 million _ in the number of workers listed as unemployed
the 5.6 percent, seasonally-adjusted, rate is the lowest since may 1979 and has not been lower since 1974, the labor department reported
janet l. norwood, the commissioner of labor statistics, said a slowdown in the expansion of the labor force is beginning to be reflected in unemployment rates, which had, until last month, been dropping more on the basis of job growth
the birthrate decline in the 1960s and the early 1970s has resulted in fewer young people reaching labor force-age in the 1980s,'' she said
while the number of americans at work has grown by 3 million over the last year, ``the labor force has increased by less than 2 million,'' she told the the congressional joint economic committee
even though the unemployment rate has fallen a full percentage point from march 1987, the latest government data indicate that the job boom may be coming to an end
the number of so-called ``discouraged workers'' _ people who have given up the search for a job out of the belief they cannot find one and are not included in the labor force or jobless rate calculations _ rose by 115,000 in the first three months of 1988 to 1,027,000 after falling by more than 200,000 last year
two-thirds of the increase in discouraged workers was adult men, historically the primary family breadwinners
factory employment, which had soared through the last half of 1987, was stagnant for the second month in a row
at 19,417,000 people, manufacturers actually had 1,000 fewer people on their payrolls than in february. factory employment, however, is still more than 420,000 above where it was a year ago
job increases in machinery and printing and publishing were offset by small declines in 11 other manufacturing industries, ms. norwood said
despite what appears to be an end to the manufacturing rebound, total payroll employment grew by 260,000 last month, according to a labor department employer survey
the unemployment rate calculations are based on a sampling of the nation's households
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater hailed the report, saying, ``we are very pleased. jobs are still the best barometer of the economy.''
health care and business services provided 85,000 of the new jobs, with construction adding 80,000 more. the growth in construction jobs plus a jump of 10,000 people on real-estate agency payrolls affirm earlier indications of a resurging housing market
things are not so well in banking and on wall street, however, with employment dropping by 5,000 last month. it was the second straight monthly decline
retail trworkers in january and february
the jobless rate for whites fell from 4.8 percent to 4.7 percent while rising from 12.6 percent to 12.8 percent for blacks. the rate for hispanics dropped from 8.3 percent to 8.2 percent
joblessness among men was unchanged at 4.9 percent but dropped among women from 5.2 percent to 4.8 percent
the rate for teenagers rose from 15.4 percent to 16.5 percent. black teens saw their rate drop from 38.3 percent to 36.9 percent
an alternate unemployment calculation, including the 1.7 million members of the armed services stationed in the united states, also fell 0.1 percentage point to 5.5 percent
here are the major business events and economic events scheduled for the coming week (some dates are tentative):

