market watchers expect soybean futures to open with a bang monday, following a pair of government reports that indicate supplies could become extremely tight later this year
and they says a quick, strong rally is the only thing that could encourage more soybean planting and perhaps lessen the crunch
corn-and-soybean growers have until april 15 to decide whether to opt for the security of corn price-support payments _ and the accompanying requirement that they idle 20 percent of their land _ or take their chances on the open market
higher futures prices for new-crop soybeans would induce more farmers to choose the latter course and grow soybeans on those acres that would otherwise lie idle, analysts said
market-watchers were predicting three months ago that prices for 1988 soybeans could climb as high as $7 a bushel, the highest level in four years
thursday's agriculture department reports on spring planting intentions and u.s. grain stocks reaffirmed that view
the general mentality of the market has been an expectation of over $7 beans on november futures, probably $7.20, which would result in $7 cash in most parts of the country,'' said david bartholomew, an assistant vice president of merrill lynch futures inc
but after thursday's reports ``$7 almost sounds conservative,'' he said. ``i think they're going to set prices higher after seeing these figures.''
cathy leow, assistant vice president of thomson mckinnon securities inc., predicted a sharp rise in soybean futures prices on monday and said the november contract could reach $7.30 a bushel by april 15. november beans settled thursday at $6.71 a bushel on the chicago board of trade, which closed out a work week shortened by the observance of good friday
we may go 30 to 60 cents higher from these levels, with 60 being the upper limit,'' she said
but, she added, ``i don't think you need to get quite as high as $7.30 basis november'' to encourage more soybean planting
the planting intentions report, based on surveys conducted in march, said farmers planned to plant 58 million acres of soybeans, up 1 percent from last year but still the second lowest acreage since 1976 and below the average pre-report estimate of about 59 million acres
the market has been rallying all year in an effort to get additional supplies for next year and boost farmer plantings,'' ms. leow said. ``this report shows the market hasn't done its job and prices have to move higher.''
the soybean stocks report was even more surprising. the usda reported soybean stocks at 1.15 billion bushels, down 14 percent from march 1, 1987. the market had expected the number to be about 30 million bushels higher
the relatively low number suggests soybean stocks on aug. 31, the end of the current marketing year, will also be lower than had been expected, ms. leow said
when you combine the less-than-expected acreage with a smaller-than-expected carryout, you're looking at a very, very tight supply situation for next year,'' she said
if weather is even marginally below average, supplies are going to be extremely tight. i think the market will want to do something about that.''
thursday's reports on corn and cotton planting intentions also were seen as bullish for futures prices. the wheat numbers were construed as neutral for futures prices
here are some commodity price trends during the past week:
