the veterans administration said friday it was raising its maximum interest rate for federally backed va home mortgages by one-half percentage point to 10 percent
the va said it was making the change, which will take effect sunday, to reflect recent increases in interest rates in financial markets
in the past 12 months, the va rate has been changed seven times, fluctuating between 9.5 percent and 11 percent. the last change was feb. 1, when the rate was lowered a full percentage point from 10.5 percent to 9.5 percent
the federal home loan mortgage corp. said friday that the national average for 30-year conventional mortgages, those without government guarantees, rose above 10 percent for the first time since late january. the national average rate was 10.05 percent, up from 9.99 percent the previous week
the va said that effective sunday a variety of other mortgage rates will also rise by one-half percentage point. graduated payment mortgages will increase to 10.25 percent, home improvement loans will rise to 11.5 percent and loans for mobile homes will increase to 12.5 percent
the va rates apply to new loans, not existing ones. va mortgages peaked at 17.5 percent in september 1981 before beginning a decline whih reached a low for this decade of 8.5 percent in early 1987
a bill to let states regulate exports of raw logs cut on state lands gained key support friday from several northwest lawmakers, including the chairman of the house panel with jurisdiction over the measure
log exports are creating a crisis for northwest mills,'' said rep. peter defazio, d-ore., who introduced the measure almost a year ago
defazio said the new support, especially that of washington democratic rep. don bonker, ``shows a growing determination in the northwest to get serious about log exports.''
the measure is pending before the house foreign affairs committee's subcommittee on international economic policy and trade, which bonker chairs
log exports benefit certain parts of the industry, but processing those logs at home would provide thousands of jobs and a stronger domestic economy,'' bonker said in endorsing the bill. ``i think we're foolish if we don't maximize the economic benefits which come from our natural resources.''
other new co-sponsors of the bill include democrats al swift of washington and les aucoin of oregon and republican rod chandler of washington
defazio said he was ``confident'' action would be taken on his measure as soon as congress deal with the omnibus trade bill. congress is expected to vote on the trade bill shortly after it returns from its easter break
oregon, alaska and califfrnia had restricted exports of unprocessed logs harvested on state lands until a 1984 u.s. supreme court decision struck down the alaska ban
the court ruled that congress had not specifically delegated such authority to the states
defazio's bill would grant the states such authority, strictly limiting it to logs harvested from state owned or administered land
about 80 percent of the logs cut on washington state lands and about half of those harvested on oregon lands in 1987 were shipped without being processed
raw log exports from the northwest totaled roughly 3 billion board feet in 1987
defazio said that the u.s. forest service estimated that 27,000 jobs are created from every 1 billion board feet of timber milled
last year, that translated into 81,000 jobs _ unfortunately, those jobs are all oversees,'' said defazio
in addition, some northwest mill owners earlier this year blamed a layoffs at their facilities on a shortage of logs resulting from exports to japan, south korea and other asian countries
northwest timber industry groups are generally split over the measure depending on whether their members are log exporters or they have milling and processing operations
among those who support the measure are the western forest industries association of portland, the northwest timber association of eugene and northwest independent forest manufacturers headquartered in tacoma
opponents include the pacific rim traders association, whose members include weyerhaeuser, georgia pacific corp., international paper and publicly-owned ports in portland, astoria, newport and coos bay
the measure has also drawn support from several northwest and national environmental groups, including the national audubon society and the washington environmental council
west coast shrimpers staged an informal strike on the first day of their season friday to protest low prices resulting from abundant supplies of last year's catch
the boats are not out right now and this is opening day, so it appears we have a strike situation until they get the price worked out,'' said oregon department of fish and wildlife shrimp biologist neil richmond. ``it's real interesting, because there is not an organized association, but you're not real popular if you got out now. you'd be a strike breaker.''
richmond said shrimp fishermen were staying in port up and down the west coast while they haggle with packers over a price
shrimpers were asking for at least 50 cents a pound, while processors were offering only 40 cents, said scott adams, plant manager at hallmark fisheries, the largest processor on the oregon coast
last year's price averaged 68 cents a pound, with a high of 80 cents in may brought on by strong demand
adams said a huge inventory of last year's catch was driving down wholesale prices from $4.75 a pound last summer to a current level of $3.60 a pound
just about every processor on the coast has shrimp left from last year,'' he said
between 1 million and 2 million pounds remained in cold storage from last year's oregon catch of 45 million pounds, the third highest on record, according to the oregon department of fish and wildlife
processors may begin selling their stocks at $2.99 a pound to clear current inventories and any dockside price higher than 40 cents a pound would make inventory reductions difficult, adams said
you can't afford to buy a product if you can't make any money,'' adams said. ``i understand the fishermen and i'd like to see them get what they got last year, but we can't afford it.''
adams said processors probably would sit back and wait to see what happens with the market value and shrimping conditions
in astoria, point adams packing co. general manager tom libby said the current price of 40 cents a pound wasn't enough to entice fishermen to sea
i don't know of anyone who is holding out at that price locally,'' he said
in newport, state biologist marc saelens said it wasn't unusual for the shrimp fleet to stay in port the first few days of the season as the price was negotiated. the season runs through october
richmond said shrimp should be at least as abundant as last year, resulting in an increased effort by shrimpers, once the price is worked out. to at least seven cases of illness; also moved on general news wires.</note>
the food and drug administration warned consumers friday not to use nutrien and vitalite powdered drink mixes because they may be contaminated with salmonella bacteria
both products are nutritional supplements marketed as powdered drink mixes by sunrider international of torrance, calif
the fda reported there have been at least seven cases of illness associated with the products
it said sunrider has agreed to begin a nationwide recall, but has not supplied the agency with specific distribution information
the warning applies to all sizes and flavors of vitalite diet drink mixes and all flavors of nutrien drink mixes
the fda said sunrider markets its products nationally through more than 37,000 independent distributors _ generally individuals who sell them door-to-door or among friends
the full product name for nutrien is ``nutrien whole food concentrate.'' it is sold in flavors such as pina colada, mandarin orange, ambrosial almond, brisky lemon and positively plain, the fda said. the vitalite weight management product is marketed as a meal substituting for a conventional breakfast, lunch or dinner
salmonella bacteria ca cause nausea, fever, headache, diarrhea and vomiting in healthy adults. it can be fatal to infants and to elderly or debilitated individuals, the fda said
the agency said tests detected salmonella in a soybean powder extract used in the sunrider products and in some samples of finished products. promotion</head>
mcdonald's corp., general motors corp. and sears, roebuck &amp; co., the largest u.s. companies in their respective fields, linked hands friday not in monopoly, but in monopoly
in what has been called one of the biggest giveaway promotions ever, the three corporate giants are offering oldsmobiles, children's clothing, cash and food to winners in a game based on monopoly
business analysts said the campaign, based on mcdonald's successful 1986 monopoly promotion, will allow gm to pitch the 1988 oldsmobile cutlass supreme to young adult customers of mcdonald's. it also will help sears promote a line of children's clothing developed last year in conjunction with mcdonald's
company officials declined to say how much the promotion would be worth, but a report in an automotive trade magazine several months ago said it would be a joint venture of at least $100 million. the copyright story in the jan. 25 issue of automative news described the mcdonald's-gm link, but did not mention sears
i can confirm that we're part of it,'' a spokesman for chicago-based sears said when advance word of the promotion leaked out
mcdonald's is based in oak brook, a chicago suburb
mcdonald's customers who play the game will be given paper facsimiles of the monopoly game board, and can collect cards representing various monopoly properties at any mcdonald's restaurant
automotive news reported that detroit-based gm would contribute 500 oldmobile cutlass supremes as prizes in the game, as well as cash prizes
the new york times reported that sears was expected to contribute prizes from its sears mckids children clothing, a line decorated with pictures of mcdonald's cartoon characters
the joint effort ``is not suprising in the sense that we think of those three as large mass-marketing organizations,'' said sidney j. levy, chairman of the marketing department at northwestern university's j.l. kellogg school of management
they are all-american names sharing an interest in a very large public,'' levy said. ``mcdonald's, nevertheless, seems to represent a little more working-class, a little more teen-age, a little more casual idea than i would associate with oldsmobile or even sears, because i had the impression that sears was trying to upgrade.''
the game began friday at mcdonald's restaurants nationwide. grafs to update with ibm changing again to say it makes patent licenses generally available; picks up 9th graf, clone makers ....</note>
a year old on saturday, ibm's new line of personal computers will soon have some unwelcome company. big blue's rivals are about to send in the clones
the imminent arrival of compatible computers has given the world's largest computer company the difficult choice of whether to fight them all the way or give them room to grow
the question penetrates to the heart of international business machines corp., and many observers believe it has sparked a debate within the company
being the only company making a personal system-2 for the past year has allowed ibm to run up healthy profit margins, recoup some of its investment and reassert control over corporate accounts
but some customers have been reluctant to buy a personal system-2 until they know whether it will catch on as a standard. and it may not catch on as a standard if ibm is the only company making it
some big corporate customers, wanting a second source for the ps-2, have been urging ibm to license other companies to make compatible machines
there seems to be confusion even with ibm on its willingness to issue patent licenses to potential ps-2 clone makers
one spokesman said friday, ``i don't see why we would ever want to do that. ... that would be just the same as giving them the store.'' later, another said that in fact, ibm makes licenses available to anyone under reasonable terms and conditions. but clone makers still have to avoid infringing on ibm's copyrights on the ps-2
clone makers forced down prices and stole market share when they knocked off ibm's first line of personal computers. but they also helped ibm by expanding the overall market, of which ibm got a healthy chunk
in any case, the moment of truth is approaching quickly
tandy corp. has called an april 21 meeting for ``the unveiling of a revolutionary invention of major significance.'' a well-traveled rumor is that it will be a ps-2 clone
chips and technologies inc. and adaptec inc. have created sets of chips that will allow clone makers to build ps-2 look-alikes. they demonstrated a working model this past week
even compaq computer corp. of houston, which makes premium pcs based on the old standard, admitted last year it is hedging its bets by working in the back shop on a ps-2 compatible
alone in the market, ibm shipped 1.5 million of its new computer line through the end of january
the sales boosted ibm's share of the worldwide personal computer market to 13 percent last year in terms of units sold, up from 12.2 percent in 1986 and not far from the peak of 13.9 percent in 1985, estimates dataquest inc. of san jose, calif
the ps-2 has gotten some negative press lately, including an article in the wall street journal that compared its mysterious micro channel architecture to the overblown secret ingredient in a can of cleanser
most computer analysts say the micro channel architecture is more than an audacious marketing gambit. it only seems that way now because software developers have not had time to develop any important programs that take advantage of its power, said dataquest analyst peter teige
by 1990 or 1991, i personally believe the old pc bus (data pathway) will be considered very archaic,'' said john xenakis, a consultant and writer based in framingham, mass
the emergence of ps-2 clones does not entirely depend on ibm. theoretically, computers developed independently could be compatible with the ps-2 without infringing on any ibm copyrights or patents, the company says
but without ibm's blessing, many customers would be reluctant to buy clones for fear that they would not be fully compatible or would be at risk of a legal challenge
in short, ibm can squelch the clones if it chooses to do so. even if the compatibles turn out to be perfectly legal, the costs of a protracted lawsuit by ibm could wipe out some small companies
ibm could simultaneously stimulate and control the ps-2 market by selectively selling sets of chips or issuing licenses to clone makers, said john mccarthy, a director at forrester research inc. in cambridge, mass. but he doubts ibm will do so
it's kind of a circling-the-wagons mentality,'' mccarthy said
other observers are more willing to believe that ibm will take it easy on the cloners. chips and technologies, in san jose, calif., says its own discussions with ibm about licensing have been ``positive and non-adversarial.''
dataquest's teige said ibm could recoup its investment in the ps-2 through royalties and license fees from clones, while continuing to introduce new models that would keep it a step ahead of the compatibles
i don't think they want to monopolize the market,'' teige said
customers' desire for ps-2 clones is partly psychological, said john xenakis, a consultant and writer in framingham, mass
what would kind of give me personally a green light to buy the ibm is if everybody's cloning it and it'll become an industry standard and i won't become stuck with a lemon,'' he said. ``i do believe that ibm understands that strategy.''
ibm will issue licenses selectively, predicted bill langenes, an analyst with creative strategies international in santa clara, calif
ironically, ibm's original personal computer in 1981 helped legitimize computing on the desktop, a revolution in the office that is eating into ibm's traditional mainframe and minicomputer business
ibm contends there is still plenty for big machines to do, but clearly they are a shrinking portion of the total market
the pc may ultimately be ibm's undoing. they've created the monster that's going to eat the parent,'' mccarthy said
corning glass works, which had previously reached an agreement to buy a tennessee clinical testing firm, bowed out of a bidding war friday with smithkline beckman for the company
the pharmaceutical giant smithkline's latest offer for international clinical laboratories inc. was $37 per share, or nearly $400 million, for all the outstanding shares. corning's last offer had been $35 a share
corning said it had purchased 3 million shares of the approximately 10 million outstanding shares of icl stock at their original offer of $26 per share. corning has agreed to sell those shares to smithkline at $37 per share
icl is a fine company, but our management and board made a firm and final decision about icl's potential value to corning,'' james r. houghton, corning's chairman and chief executive officer, said in a prepared statement
smithkline's $37 per share offer expires at midnight edt on april 20
our offer to acquire icl is in concert with our corporate strategy of leadership in health care and life sciences. clinical laboratory services is one of our key businesses, growing fast in both sales and earnings,'' henry wendt, smithkline chairman and chief executive officer, said in a press release
icl, based in nashville, runs 13 major clinical testing laboratories mainly in the south and west. icl had sales of $205.5 million for the fiscal year ending aug. 31, 1987, compared with $168.7 million a year earlier
through a subsidiary, king of prussia-based smithkline bioscience laboratories inc., smithkline is the country's largest provider of clinical testing services
on march 8, icl agreed to be acquired by corning for about $260 million or $26 a share. before the deal could be consumated, however, smithkline offered $32 a share
corning challenged the offer with a $35 per share bid on monday and smithkline countered hours later with the $37 offer
the agreement announced friday between smithkline and corning also resolves possible claims between the two parties, corning said
in a pair of new economic reports, the government says the nation's unemployment rate fell in march and construction spending slipped in february
the financial markets' reaction to the reports won't be apparent for a few days, however, because the u.s. stock and bond markets were closed friday to mark the start of the easter and passover holidays
some light trading was reported in the foreign exchange markets, where the dollar fell in the united states after steadying in europe
the unemployment rate fell to 5.6 percent from 5.7 percent in february even though there were 360,000 fewer americans at work than a month earlier, the labor department said
the unemployment rate is at the lowest level since it was 5.6 percent in may 1979
the rate decline was credited entirely to a 455,000 decrease in those in the labor force _ which includes those either holding jobs or seeking work
employer payrolls rose by 262,000 new jobs in march, according to a separate government survey
factory jobs, which have risen an average 40,000 each month since last summer, fell by 1,000 in march. of the new payroll jobs, 85,000 were in business and health care services with another 80,000 in construction
the 0.3 percent decline in construction spending in february reflected weakness in the housing sector
the commerce department said that construction spending declined to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $391.5 billion in february following a 2.8 percent drop in january
in addition, the department revised the december figure to show a small decline of $100 million instead of a 0.4 percent increase
the february decline pushed construction spending 2.5 percent below where it was a year earlier. analysts are forecasting further cutbacks in 1988 because of high vacancy rates in apartments and office buildings
residential construction fell by 1.1 percent in february to an annual rate of $188.1 billion, while non-residential construction posted a 1.2 percent increase to an annual rate of $92 billion
public construction edged up 0.4 percent in february to an annual rate of $74.7 billion
the italian government has agreed to explore possible collaboration in building the ``super collider'' atom smasher planned by the energy department, energy secretary john herrington said thursday
the agreement does not represent a commitment to contribute to the cost of the $4.4 billion installation, but department officials said collaborative projects could lead to concrete cost savings even if no cash were given
the united states and italy already collaborate in some energy research. a joint statement issued thursday by herrington and gianni ravaglia, deputy minister of industry, commerce and handicrafts, at the conclusion of the annual review of the work said the two men had ``endorsed the need to explore ways of achieving joint undertakings'' to support the super collider
the administration is asking congress for $363 million to begin construction in the fiscal year beginning oct. 1., but there is considerable resistance to the high overall cost. some members have asked herrington to produce evidence that other countries will contribute, or committments by them, to back up his assertions that a quarter to a half the project cost could come from other countries
a site for the machine, a 53-miles (85 km) around underground tunnel, is expected to be chosen in november. sites in north carolina, texas, arizona, michigan, illinois, colorado and tennessee are being considered
george j. bradley, principal deputy assistant secretary for international affairs and energy emergencies, told reporters that smaller sums being mentioned in congress would not convince potential foreign contributors that the united states was committed to the collider
asked specifically about discussions about allocating $200 million for the project, he said, ``it's not enough.''
if other countries are convinced the united states is going ahead, they will undertake ``complementary program'' that might include other types of less expensive high-energy accelerators. but without a u.s. super collider, they might decide that they need to collaborate on building one themselves _ and they need to make such decisions in the coming year or so, bradley said
thus, he said, $200 million is not enough because ``the key here is schedule slippage'' _ such a sum would delay the u.s. project somewhat, and foreign countries would be forced to make decisions without knowledge of u.s. intentions
he declined to specify a particular sum other than the $363 million as ``enough.''
to explore the secrets of matter and energy, the super collider would whirl beams of protons into each other at collision energies 20 times higher than the most powerful machines today
italy's help might be particularly welcome, bradley said, because that country is the only one so far to build superconducting magnets with a field strength anywhere near the strength the super collider beam-bending magnets would use, about 6.6 tesla or roughly 66,000 times the strength of the earth's magnetic field. the italian magnets are used at an accelerator near hamburg, west germany
the most powerful u.s. magnets are about 4.4 tesla. scientists have said they see no reason they can't build more powerful ones, but the $363 million budget request includes about $32 million for magnet research
if the italians are willing to transfer that technology, you don't have to spend'' that money, bradley said
italy's manufacturing capacity is only 500 magnets every three years, while the super collider will require 10,000 magents estimated to cost $100,000 each _ a $1 billion expenditure
if a magnet agreement were reached with italy, u.s. firms, and italian firm or a joint venture might build a manufacturing plant in the united states, bradley said. similar collaborations are being discussed with several countries, he said
i can assure you it's not pie in the sky,'' bradley said
italy has a long tradition in advanced physics research, going back to nuclear pioneer enrico fermi in the 1930s and extending today to carlo rubbia, professor of physics at harvard university in cambridge, mass. and director-general of cern (centre d'etudes de recherches nucleaires), the multi-national european high-energy physics reserach center near geneva, switzerland
the stock market spent the first three months of 1988 healing some of the wounds it suffered last fall
but as the end of the quarter arrived on thursday, it was still suffering from the after-effects of the crunch that culminated on black monday oct. 19
by maintaining a moderate but steady pace of growth, the economy has done its part so far to reassure investors that the crash wasn't an immediate harbinger of a recession or something worse
yet many frightened analysts and investors seem reluctant to put much credence in the favorable news, reasoning that the market last fall foresaw something that hasn't yet become visible to the naked eye
if the economy isn't going to slide immediately into a recession, the pessimists argue, then it might be heating up so much that the federal reserve will be forced to tighten credit, inducing a business slump later on
the confusion that reigns in the marketplace is illustrated by the two worst-performing stock groups in the first quarter through march 23, as calculated by standard &amp; poor's corp
gold mining stocks suffered the biggest decline, falling 8.9 percent, presumably reflecting a drop in inflationary expectations
but savings and loan holding companies, down 7.5 percent, seemed to be signaling expectations of rising interest rates prompted by increased inflationary pressures
still, analysts at some of wall street's biggest brokerage firms describe the touchy, cautious mood of investors as a significant plus for the market outlook over the next few months at least
we doubt if a medium-term top in the market will be made amid alternating worries about a too strong or too weak economy,'' maintains phil roth, a technical analyst at shearson lehman hutton inc
these worries keep buying power on the sidelines and enhance the market's technical position. it is more likely that a real top will be made when investors are actively buying stock despite real fundamental worries.''
at merrill lynch, chief market analyst robert farrell contends, ``we think the market has shown unusual underlying strength in light of the trauma of last october
most of the flaws and concern seem to be part of the wall of worry that strong advances need to keep going.''
the market made some grudging progress in the past week, which was cut to four sessions by the good friday holiday. the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 9.11 to 1,988.06, closing out the first quarter with a net gain of 49.23 points
other readings for the week showed the nyse's composite index up 0.02 at 146.60; the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market up 2.10 at 374.64, and the american stock exchange market value index up 1.77 at 296.43
volume on the big board averaged 146.80 million shares a day, against 157.26 million the week before
edward yardeni, economist prudential-bache securities, has been a vocal optimist lately, arguing that steady growth is possible for the next several years
he contends that the markets, in particular the bond market, now exert a powerful degree of discipline over economic conditions
economywide recessions are unlikely to occur in the future,'' he argues. ``rolling recessions that are limited to certain industries and sectors of the country are more likely to occur
market forces will keep the economy from booming. so it won't develop the excesses which typically set the stage for an economywide recession
global competitive pressures are intense and will keep a lid on wage and price inflation. such a scenario should be bullish for both stocks and bonds.''
u.s. sugar beet growers plan to increase their plantings, a move the sweetener users association said on thursday may reduce imports again
the u.s. department of agriculture reports that a survey in march indicated that sugar beet growers intend to plant 1.29 million acres, an increase of 1.6 percent
if sugarcane growers in florida, hawaii, louisiana and texas follow suit, higher domestic sugar production would force the fifth consecutive reduction in u.s. sugar import quotas,'' the association said in a statement
calculation of quotas is mandated by existing u.s. law
tom hammer, the president of the association, added:
this is bad news for many of our caribbean, latin american, asian and african trading partners who have seen their sugar sales drop from from 2.2 billion dollars to just under 400 million since 1981.''
the dominican republic has the biggest import quota, followed by the philippines
last december president ronald reagan's administration reduced the quota to 750,000 tons, compared with 5 million tons in 1981. the action was the fifth reduction in a row and brought imports to the lowest point in 113 years. there were strong protests from the governments of sugar-exporting countries
unless the legislation is changed, the trends will continue,'' u.s. agriculture secretary richard e. lyng predicted then
lyng said in january that the administration would like to kill the sugar program as enacted by congress. it keeps prices high in the united states for the benefit of domestic farmers, at the expense of countries which traditionally export it to the united states
legislators from urban areas have put forward a plan to cut the u.s. price and increase imports, saying price support for u.s. sugar benefits only 10,000 growers and costs u.s. consumers $3 billion a year. they have had little response from other membes of congress sympathetic to farm interests
last month the agriculture department raised its estimate of world production for the 1987-8 season by 1 percent to 101.9 million metric tons, 900,000 tons less than than last season's crop
the sweetener users association said u.s. sugar beet farmers last year indicated that they planned a 1.3 percent increase in acreage but actually planted 3.1 percent more, resulting in a record u.s. output of nearly 4 million tons
partly because of the high price of beet and cane sugar, sweeteners made from corn and other products have been taking a larger share of the u.s. market. consumption of sugar has been declimning
the world bank approved a $400 million loan package thursday to financially troubled argentina and its banks
funds from the 15-year low interest loan will be released in two stages. the first half will become available immediately, with the release of the final $200 million contingent on the success of argentina's economic recovery
the world bank said it made the loan to encourage deposits and confidence in the argentine banking system, improve the distribution of credit and reduce its cost
this action comes after a $317 million loan from the international monetary fund two weeks ago. the imf loan, which was also conditional on reductions in the government deficit, was designed to trigger a release of funds by private banks
argentina is the third world's third largest debtor, after brazil and mexico, with a total debt estimated at $50 billion, of which $3.5 billion is owed to the imf
argentina's situation is complicated by inflation that reached 175 percent last year and appears headed in the same direction for 1988
dravo corp. says negotiations to sell its waste-to-energy business to westinghouse electric corp. have been halted
the move will ``enable both companies to explore alternative options to achieving their respective objectives,'' said thomas j. ward, dravo's acting chief executive officer
the business ultimately could go to westinghouse, ward said, but the sale ``is now more likely to involve one of the potential buyers who expressed interest prior to the reaching of the preliminary agreement with westinghouse.''
dravo officials also said the company has executed a letter of intent to sell its interests in geothermal energy production in california to a joint venture organization formed by bonneville pacific corp. of san jose, calif., and calpine corp. of salt lake city
included in the planned sale are dravo's geothermal power generation facility and a contract for the future supply of power from a planned second unit, the company said thursday
terms of the sale were not disclosed
the sale of our stake in geothermal operations complements the divestiture actions now under way involving dravo's other engineering and construction businesses,'' ward said
donald kingsborough, chairman and founder of worlds of wonder inc., agreed to leave the debt-saddled toy maker as part of its bankruptcy terms, the company announced thursday
the agreement involves banks and unsecured creditors and has bankruptcy court approval, wow said
the new management team includes president and chief operating officer angelo pezzani and stephen j. hopkins as chief executive officer. hopkins is executive vice president of nightingale &amp; associates inc., a new canaan, conn.-based management consulting company
kingsborough, who said earlier in march that he had no intention of stepping down, has not disclosed his plans. the company said he would be available to assist the new chief executive officer
with the bank's support and toy specialists on the management team, i believe that worlds of wonder inc. is entering a new era which will inspire retailer and vendor confidence and active participation,'' he said in a press release
now the company can get on with what it does best _ creating and marketing innovative toys with exceptional play value,'' he said
wow said the new arrangements call for a business and operating plan to be presented to the banks and unsecured creditors for approval, with financing then being negotiated
the high-tech toy manufacturer owes creditors about $260 million and has missed $3.6 million in interest payments to bondholders. it lost $186.9 million in the quarter ending dec. 31, and the stock has plunged from $29 a share after it went public in june 1986 to $1.31\, up 12{ cents thursday in over-the-counter trading
kingsborough, 41, a former executive with atari corp., founded wow in march 1985 and turned it into one of the fastest-growing startup companies ever on the strength of enormous success with the teddy ruxpin talking bear and the game lazer tag. it fell victim to overexpansion and slumping sales and filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection last december
